<title>May_1993: Guns, Guns</title>
<h1>Guns, Guns</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 1993 08:54:32 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#240">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#240">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#240">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#240">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0241.html">Susan Harrington: "Re: sdas and guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0239.html">Woody Baker: "questions"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0243.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Guns, Guns"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am one American who is horrified by the national obsession with guns.<br>
While I understand the historical background of this (the revolution and<br>
resulting constitutional guarantee of the right to "bear arms") and the<br>
need to tame the frontier, I support any efforts to curb the uncontrolled<br>
availabity of firearms.  Somehow it's become associated with virility<br>
and masculinity (and certainly supported by the public media).  And then<br>
of course there are the unconscionable efforts of the National Rifle<br>
Association, which doesn't see any difference between prohibiting<br>
weapons designed for warfare and those meant for hunting.  We must admit<br>
that most guns were designed to kill people, not animals.  To them, any<br>
attempt to differentiate seems a threat to any use of guns at all.  I<br>
suppose it's similar to the idea that any attempt to register cars and<br>
license their drivers is a threat to car ownership.  However, appeals to<br>
reason don't seem to make much difference with this group, which I'm<br>
tempted to say is mostly redneck anyway.  Even the police are pleading<br>
for a change in policy.<br>
<p>
Of course the more guns there are, the more there becomes a legitimate<br>
reason for additional guns for self-protection.  Just what it will take<br>
to change these attitudes is hard to say.  The level of carnage already<br>
is appalling.  How much worse does it have to get?  I suppose some Adventists<br>
would say it's reason to move to the country (not to say there aren't<br>
any guns out here!).<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
