<title>May_1993: Doctor/nurse/preacher/teacher/dentist/lawyer</title>
<h1>Doctor/nurse/preacher/teacher/dentist/lawyer</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 1993 09:14:24 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#221">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#221">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#221">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#221">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0222.html">Bruce Holm: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0220.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Bible and Homosexuality (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tom is right, lawyer wasn't on the original list of "Approved<br>
Occupations" (neither was politician!).  It probably became acceptable<br>
in the '60s and '70s.  Dentist was added in the '40s or so when LLU<br>
added this program.  Most of our colleges started with a small student<br>
body (a few hundred), and of course a small number of offerings.  In the<br>
19th century, most colleges and the new universities didn't have large<br>
offerings.  Many of our overseas colleges are still this<br>
way--concentrating on ministerial training with a few others thrown in.<br>
I suspect that is the way things began in the U.S. as well.  <br>
<p>
Bull and Lockhart (I hesistate to call "Seeking a Sanctuary" a<br>
must-read, but it's very good) point out that SDA occupational choice is<br>
often related to those occupations and professions with little or no<br>
Sabbath problems.  For example, you can be a doctor and work (at least<br>
to some degree) on Sabbath in good conscience, but you can't be a<br>
librarian and do the same (not many SDA librarians working outside the<br>
church).  <br>
<p>
However, again in the '60s and on, because of increasing demand of SDA<br>
students for more occupational options, the North American SDA colleges<br>
and universities have vastly expanded their offerings--architect,<br>
engineer, social worker, physical therapist, and on and on.  However,<br>
this expansion (necessary though it may be) has put the entire "system"<br>
at financial risk.  There simply aren't enough students to go around<br>
among all the schools, some of which have remained small and some of<br>
which have grown both in numbers of students and programs.  Few have<br>
adequate numbers of students to support the programs they have.  Andrews<br>
is under the gun with its accrediting association on this very issue.<br>
This is also a significant problem elsewhere.  Under the current<br>
circumstances, there seems little future for those institutions under<br>
1,000 students (the number generally accepted in higher education as the<br>
minimum to even be able to support the necessary support services).<br>
<p>
Like gun control, what the crisis it will take to resolve this issue<br>
remains to be seen because the church (for political and sentimental<br>
reasons) seems unwilling or incapable of making the kinds of dramatic<br>
changes that are probably called for.<br>
<p>
Fred correctly points out the technology program at Andrews.  He did not<br>
point out two attendant problems.  One is, as noted above, there simply<br>
aren't enough students in these programs to cover the instructional<br>
costs in many cases, and so the programs lose money, which has to be<br>
found elsewhere in the institution.  There is a barely-concealed civil<br>
war here at the present on that very issue.  The other is a lack of<br>
academic compatability between some of these and other programs.<br>
However, let me hasten to point out that I personally have great<br>
admiration and respect for those who clean our buildings, run the<br>
computing center, fix my car, and supervise construction of my house.<br>
It takes all types (doing a good job in their area) to make the world go<br>
'round, and we academics certainly shouldn't look down on those who work<br>
with their hands (or vise versa).<br>
<p>
On an unrelated topic, my ear has no difficulty at all distinguishing<br>
between acoustic music and synthesized sound, and hardly think one can<br>
compare a synthesizer with a fine pipe organ.  Perhaps someday that will<br>
be true, but certainly isn't at present any more than a fine playback<br>
system replaces the live concert.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
