<title>May_1993: Re: The White Lie</title>
<h1>Re: The White Lie</h1>
Bill Nickless (<i>nickless@mcs.anl.gov</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 1993 10:19:55 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#242">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#242">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#242">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#242">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0243.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Guns, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0241.html">Susan Harrington: "Re: sdas and guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Lets broaden the scope a bit more then. According to this concept, it is </i><br>
<i>&gt; wrong for me to attack sin without having at least tried it out myself. </i><br>
<i>&gt; Not having tried it out for myself puts me in a position of merely repeating</i><br>
<i>&gt; the prejudices and biases of others. !!!!!</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Thats like saying I shouldn't tell people not to drink, unless I've had a few</i><br>
<i>&gt; first can can personally relate from first hand experience what drinking was</i><br>
<i>&gt; like !</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; *_NOT_* so.</i><br>
<p>
Let me repeat myself.  To attack a book or other publication without at least<br>
starting to read it yourself puts you in a position where you're merely<br>
repeating the prejudices and biases of others.<br>
<p>
All I'm saying is that you should *admit* it.  Not that you can't attack it.<br>
Not that you can't condemn it.  All I'm saying is that until you read<br>
something, you can't condemn it from personal experience.<br>
<p>
Let's contrast that with alcohol consumption.  There are observable things<br>
that I can point to that keep me from drinking.  Like some of my relatives,<br>
who exhibit strong addictive behavior to alcohol and other vices.  I can<br>
condemn drinking on that basis because I've observed the pain they have<br>
endured and the destruction that drinking caused.<br>
<p>
And you can condemn a book based on the reaction that people have.  "By their<br>
fruits ye shall know them."  If reading something causes people that you know<br>
to lose their relationship with Christ, you can say so.  (As you do later on<br>
about The White Lie.)<br>
<p>
If you respect the experience and wisdom of someone, and they condemn the book<br>
for whatever reason, that's alright as well.  But remember: your understanding<br>
of why the book is condemned is necessarily filtered by the other person's<br>
biases and prejudices.  You lose the ability to put the words of the book into<br>
whatever context it might mean to you.  You are simply repeating what someone<br>
else says, without adding your own experience or understanding to the<br>
situation.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If I know something is wrong because God's testimony tells me or if it</i><br>
<i>&gt; goes against God's revealed truth then there is absolutely _no_ need for me</i><br>
<i>&gt; to be aquainted and familiar with it, in order to condemn it. In fact I</i><br>
<i>&gt; should avoid all association with it, because it know it to be evil.</i><br>
<p>
We should avoid all association with that which we know to be evil.  Amen.  In<br>
fact, we should avoid all association with that which is questionable, and<br>
doesn't lead us directly to a closer walk with God.<br>
<p>
How do you know if something is wrong?  What if a book claims to lead you to a<br>
better understanding of Gods' Truth?  How do you know what God's testimony is,<br>
or how does God revel truth to you about a book or publication that has been<br>
written only in the last 6 months or 6 years?  Are you putting someone besides<br>
God in a position to tell you what truth is?  If so, who is that person?  <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; So do you suggest we must all go out and read Kelloggs book "The Living</i><br>
<i>&gt; Temple" before we can condemn it ? That just like saying that I should</i><br>
<i>&gt; go to a seance before I can condemn spiritism. No way.</i><br>
<p>
I disagree with your connection, but I'll let that slide.  Once again: if you<br>
condemn the book, you should also provide the basis for that condmenation.<br>
Someone had to have read the book in order to form an opinion about it.  Who<br>
was that person, what was their purpose for reading it, and how much can I<br>
trust their wisdom?<br>
<p>
I don't go to seances because I trust the testimony of multiple people who<br>
have.  I compare the claims of the mediums against the Bible, and find them in<br>
disagreement.  I trust the Bible.  So I don't go.  I challenge you to perform<br>
a similar analysis with your condemnation of "The Living Temple."<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Same goes for the White lie, mind you I have read the book, when I was young</i><br>
<i>&gt; and naive, It offically was handed out at church to all the church members,</i><br>
<i>&gt; I read it and I know what it says, and I know that this very book is what</i><br>
<i>&gt; EGW wrote about when she said that just before the end of time, opposition</i><br>
<i>&gt; would arise to the Testimonies, and that those who would leave God's</i><br>
<i>&gt; truth and receive the mark of the beast would first loose their confidence</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the Testiminies. This single book in its time probably did the</i><br>
<i>&gt; most in unsettling the faith and causing many to leave the church than</i><br>
<i>&gt; all other factors at the time.</i><br>
<p>
Thank you for a clear review of the White Lie.  I now know why you condemn it,<br>
and what basis you have to do so.  That is all that I'm asking for.<br>
<p>
--Bill Nickless<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
