<title>May_1993: FW: Bible and Homosexuality</title>
<h1>FW: Bible and Homosexuality</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 93 12:18:32 PDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#228">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#228">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#228">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#228">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0229.html">Steven Timm: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0227.html">Ted Ashton: "Re: Censored Newsgroups @ WWC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0229.html">Steven Timm: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Maurice Ashton writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;What I am concerned about is the evangelical zeal which some use to</i><br>
<i>&gt;promote homosexuality as a way of life. When homosexuality becomes an</i><br>
<i>&gt;excuse for selfish gratification, then it becomes wrong. In that sense</i><br>
<i>&gt;it is just as wrong as someone who uses marriage as an excuse for</i><br>
<i>&gt;selfish gratification.</i><br>
<p>
If there are other behavioral science/human relations people on the net, they<br>
might confirm or refute my belief:<br>
<p>
For millennia, homosexuals have been "oppressed".  It is not difficult for<br>
someone with a teachable mind to imagine the options open to people who<br>
find themselves in more hostile times than the present.  At first, they were<br>
unquestionably "sinners", burned, drowned or done away with in other<br>
creative ways.  Then enlightened thought described them as "sick",<br>
"unfortunates who just couldn't help themselves", but who turn into <br>
sinners once<br>
they think themselves to be "well" - especially as "well" as anyone else.<br>
These two views have continued till now.  However, within the last few years a<br>
new view has emerged, mainly among homosexuals themselves, and even<br>
more recently, their family and friends (people who've had a personal<br>
relationship with them).  This third view is that they are _humans_ first, thus<br>
deserving of human rights.  Moreover, judgment of any "mental sickness" in<br>
homosexuals should be done taking into account the options society gives<br>
them - what are their "alternatives"?<br>
<p>
Society has regulated their place, in work, housing, and familial status.<br>
The church has regulated their place in membership and mission.  Finding no<br>
"city of refuge" among 'believers', it is likely that they lose hope and even<br>
become bitter.  In thinking that the Church speaks for God, and that <br>
even God has<br>
no place for them in His kingdom - given various interpretations of scripture,<br>
many will chose to take their own lives swiftly, or slowly through <br>
harmful lifestyles.<br>
Let the believers turn around and point the finger (act of worship to <br>
self's own<br>
righteousness) at those lifestyles (symptoms of lost hope, and self <br>
worship) and<br>
the scene is RIPE for confusion and rejection between both parties.  This is<br>
extremely important in discussing what some call "the gay community" or "the<br>
gay lifestyle".<br>
<p>
NOW put yourself in the place of a parent of a homosexual person.  You have<br>
"believer" friends, who are outspoken about the 'evil' homosexuality is.<br>
They recite proof-text as support for the way they treat your child, <br>
and propose<br>
that their view is the only view which is from God.  You see some of them form<br>
citizen alliances and raise huge sums of money to combat the "homosexual<br>
problem" while others watch in silence.  You speak to the vocal, but they don't<br>
hear you for the noise which the proof-text and phobia make in their heads.<br>
The silent don't hear you either, for the fear of being different, or <br>
losing their<br>
souls (by knowing and speaking out for 'sinners').  Meanwhile, your whole<br>
town has ruled that your child, solely because of who s/he is, will not be<br>
protected by the police when people throw rocks at their home or try to<br>
beat their brains out.  There will be no job security for this child, <br>
and forget<br>
about all the lessons you taught her/him about telling the truth, cause we<br>
prefer you to lie, than make us uncomfortable in our prejudice.<br>
<p>
A counselor friend of mine who among other things, counsels gay and lesbian<br>
youth, told me of a member of his discussion group.  The youth's parents<br>
recently disowned him, kicking him out of his home for being (I assume)<br>
an "avowed" (someone who doesn't have self pity or shame) gay.  The youth<br>
and his parents are Seventh-day Adventist.  I don't know if the youth is still<br>
"Seventh-day Adventist".  I can see that is would be difficult to remain so.<br>
This kind of stuff is happening everyday, thousands of times in hundreds of<br>
"believing" circles.<br>
<p>
The point is, our words and actions do not exist in a vacuum.  As Christ said<br>
that His words go out and do not return void, so do our own.  What type of<br>
return are we casting out on the sea of life?  I believe that Christ is calling<br>
believers to stop and think, what are we really doing with the homosexual,<br>
and even their loved ones?  When the proof text have all been said, we still<br>
must address the practical = real people, real lives, and a real God.<br>
<p>
Some say we are of Moses, or Paul, but few say we are of Christ.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
