<title>May_1993: Re: The White Lie</title>
<h1>Re: The White Lie</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 93 12:28:25 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#212">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#212">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#212">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#212">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0213.html">Len Archer : "Tang Beng's friend Caleb"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0211.html">Marcus Stringer: "Competition"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0171.html">Harvey Brenneise: "The White Lie"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I must agree with Harvey Brenneise: to attack a book or other publication</i><br>
<i>&gt; without at least starting to read it yourself puts you in a postition where</i><br>
<i>&gt; you're merely repeating the prejudices and biases of others.  (Forgive me if I</i><br>
<i>&gt; misunderstand your position....)  On the other hand, we need not recommend</i><br>
<i>&gt; that "all SDAs" "get and read Kellogg's book" because not "all SDAs" have an</i><br>
<i>&gt; interest in that time and place in church history.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Lets broaden the scope a bit more then. According to this concept, it is <br>
wrong for me to attack sin without having at least tried it out myself. <br>
Not having tried it out for myself puts me in a position of merely repeating<br>
the prejudices and biases of others. !!!!!<br>
<p>
Thats like saying I shouldn't tell people not to drink, unless I've had a few<br>
first can can personally relate from first hand experience what drinking was<br>
like !<br>
<p>
*_NOT_* so.<br>
<p>
If I know something is wrong because God's testimony tells me or if it<br>
goes against God's revealed truth then there is absolutely _no_ need for me to<br>
be aquainted and familiar with it, in order to condemn it. In fact I should<br>
avoid all association with it, because it know it to be evil.<br>
<p>
<p>
That's exactly what Satan told Eve, he said "don't believe God's word, He's <br>
biased look I've tried the fruit for myself and its ok. Try it for yourself<br>
and you'll see what I mean". And Eve did just follow this counsel and<br>
wow ! Satan was right, she didn't die. See God was wrong all along !!!!!<br>
So she took that same story to Adam, and you know what Satan still brings<br>
us this same story and we keep on falling again and again into the same<br>
trap, and he knows and can't believe that we can be so stupid as to keep<br>
falling for the same line.<br>
<p>
No Way, Eve should not even been near the tree, and that goes for all<br>
of us, why should we need to drink of polluted fountains to know that <br>
the water tastes bad ? Why should we go listen to the arguments of<br>
the serpent when we have been warned of the dangers of wandering too<br>
close to the tree of knowledge of good and evil !!<br>
<p>
The understanding of God's truth is sufficient, I don't need to wallow in<br>
the mud to know its dirt. I don't need to go out and read every worldly and<br>
satanic publication to better appreciate their arguments to know they're bad. <br>
<p>
So do you suggest we must all go out and read Kelloggs book "The Living<br>
Temple" before we can condemn it ? That just like saying that I should<br>
go to a seance before I can condemn spiritism. No way.<br>
<p>
Same goes for the White lie, mind you I have read the book, when I was young<br>
and naive, It offically was handed out at church to all the church members,<br>
I read it and I know what it says, and I know that this very book is what<br>
EGW wrote about when she said that just before the end of time, opposition<br>
would arise to the Testimonies, and that those who would leave God's<br>
truth and receive the mark of the beast would first loose their confidence<br>
in the Testiminies. This single book in its time probably did the<br>
most in unsettling the faith and causing many to leave the church than<br>
all other factors at the time.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
