<title>May_1993: Re: organs and synthesizers</title>
<h1>Re: organs and synthesizers</h1>
Dan Hamstra (<i>hamstra@andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 93 18:33:32 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#248">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#248">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#248">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#248">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0249.html">Susan Harrington: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0247.html">Dan Hamstra: "Stockpiling weapons"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0214.html">Steven Timm: "organs and synthesizers"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;My</i><br>
<i>&gt;source is an organ professor here at Morehead State, who joined our</i><br>
<i>&gt;church last year and moved in his Yamaha Electone and now provides us</i><br>
<i>&gt;with the most beautiful music on Sabbaths!</i><br>
<p>
Is this a synthesizer with three(?) keyboards (manuals in organ parlance)<br>
and a full set of pedals?  If so, I can attest that the versatility of this<br>
machine is certainly well beyond that of your typical Conn or Allen<br>
electronic organ.  It is also not your typical synthesizer.  We had such a<br>
machine here at Andrews for a concert about three years ago.  It was rented<br>
(I believe Yamaha reduced / underwrote the price due to our educational<br>
status) for the performance of a 20th century piece for electronic<br>
keyboards and orchestra, Adams "Fearful Symmetries" if I recall correctly. <br>
I was a technical consultant (I knew how to hook up wires) to the orchestra<br>
conductor and had occasion to connect and disconnect this "organ" on a<br>
number of occasions during the month or so that it was here.  It seemed to<br>
have most of the functionality of an organ but with the added advantage of<br>
being a MIDI capable synthesizer.  I don't recall all of it's features and<br>
never really knew its price, but I would encourage anyone looking at the<br>
purchase of an electronic organ to at least explore this avenue.<br>
<p>
dan hamstra<br>
hamstra@andrews.edu<br>
