<title>May_1993: Re: Guns, Guns</title>
<h1>Re: Guns, Guns</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 1993 19:18:34 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#243">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#243">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#243">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#243">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0244.html">Steven Timm: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0242.html">Bill Nickless: "Re: The White Lie"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0240.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Guns, Guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0261.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Guns, Guns"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Hello SDAnetters:</i><br>
<p>
Hi!<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What is it with the American obsession with guns?  </i><br>
<p>
It's much more of an issue in the press than it is in reality...<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Did any of you see the Nightline program last week, where Ted</i><br>
<i>&gt; interviewed some folk on this subject?</i><br>
<p>
Mr. Koppel is more evenhanded on the subject than most in the U.S.<br>
media, but still not exactly impartial.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If I am not mistaken, the statistics indicate that in</i><br>
<i>&gt; the USA, tens of thousands of people die every year as a result of</i><br>
<i>&gt; hand gun violence, whereas in Canada, Japan and Britain, less than</i><br>
<i>&gt; 70, (yes 7-0-) die a year.  </i><br>
<p>
This has been true since long before gun control was instituted in<br>
the UK or Canada...they choose other methods of killing (and committing<br>
suicide, which accounts for more than half those numbers).  Canada and<br>
the UK historically had lower violence rates than did the U.S., and they<br>
still do, although *not* by the wide margin that they once did, and *that*<br>
is something to be concerned with: their violence-crime rates are rising<br>
faster than U.S. rates.<br>
<p>
If you subtract gun-related homicide in the U.S. in lower-class economic<br>
urban neighborhoods, and the portion of drug-trade-related violence in<br>
the rest of the country, you would see something interesting: the overall<br>
homicide rate that remains is equal to, or slightly lower than, Canada's<br>
rate. (Just in case you might have thought that socioeconomic conditions<br>
of someone somewhere else had no bearing on your own life...we should<br>
justifiably be concerned with more than others physical and spiritual<br>
health alone.)<br>
<p>
The problem is one of violence (sin), and that problem should not be lost<br>
sight of in fixating on the tools used toward that end.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Yet most Americans can see nothing unusual or catastrophic about those</i><br>
figures.<br>
<p>
I think most Americans do see the problem...they just disagree on the way to<br>
fix the problem.  Some solutions will definitely make things worse, some<br>
will help; the problem being how to choose which one(s) to use.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Is human life worth so little to us that we argue about our right to</i><br>
bear arms?  <br>
<p>
When government (FBI and other) studies indicate that there are somewhere<br>
between 400K and 1million with-gun defenses from criminal assault each year,<br>
more than 99% of which involve no firearm discharge, there may be some<br>
reason to continue the discussion.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; many more die at the hands of relatives or friends or</i><br>
<i>&gt; by accident than by the drive-by shootings and violent crime we often</i><br>
<i>&gt; use as an excuse for our need to protect ourselves.</i><br>
<p>
The correct usage is "by acquaintences", which has been incorrectly changed<br>
to "relatives and friends". The term "loved one" is often used to describe<br>
incidents which did not by any stretch of the imagination fall into that<br>
relationship.  But it sounds better in the news.<br>
<p>
Criminal assault by pure stangers is fairly rare, comparatively speaking, and<br>
*most* criminal assault is done by someone against someone they know, whether<br>
that person is a competing drug dealer, or the local shopkeeper who just<br>
happens to be more convenient to visit than the local bank.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Maybe there is something else that I don't  understand being an</i><br>
<i>&gt; immigrant of only 12 years.</i><br>
<p>
Most of us don't completely understand the issue, either, so don't<br>
feel bad.<br>
<p>
The problem is sin. Period.  The issue is how best to deal with it.<br>
<p>
[SDAnet is never going to solve the problem of gun control in society <br>
at large, nor should we waste bandwidth reciting the same arguments that<br>
are repeated elsewhere.  If there are specific SDA-related issues here,<br>
such as why did Koresh go off the deep end, or how should one be a <br>
pastor in Big Shotgun Gap, VA where there have been several shootings<br>
within the congregation, fine, let's discuss.  Otherwise, I think <br>
this discussion is repeating itself.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
