<!-- inreplyto="9305241918.AA01508@netmail.microsoft.com" -->
<title>May_1993: Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality</title>
<h1>Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 1993 19:57:29 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#229">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#229">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#229">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#229">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0230.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Bible and Homosexuality (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0228.html">Marcus Stringer: "FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0228.html">Marcus Stringer: "FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0249.html">Susan Harrington: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It seems that in the current "I'm recovering, you're co-dependent" world<br>
of the SDA church, we are losing an important distinction.  Most of those<br>
who have argued against the standard church position on homosexuality have<br>
used the argument "We shouldn't condemn people."  I agree that Christ did <br>
not come to condemn and neither should we.  But whether we condemn someone<br>
or not has nothing to do with whether what they are doing is a sin.  <br>
Nowadays we are so loath to judge that we convince ourselves that there<br>
really are no rights and no wrongs.  "It all depends on the situation"<br>
"I was born that way, it's my nature."  SO WHAT?!  We have inborn tendencies<br>
to all sorts of sin, stealing, lying, cheating, you name it.  God sent not <br>
his son into the world to condemn the world, but that the world through Him<br>
might be saved.<br>
<p>
Those who say that homosexuality should be accepted because it is Biblically<br>
OK, where do you draw the line?  Is there any behavior at all that is <br>
unacceptable in the way you read the Bible?  Is the prohibition against<br>
bestiality similarly "culturally conditioned?"  (It's in the same<br>
chapter).<br>
If someone is oriented towards sadism is this acceptable?  What about<br>
pedophilia?  necrophilia?  It seems to me that for each of these an<br>
"orientation" could similarly be manufactured, "rights" declared, and <br>
the next step is of course affirmative action for this "oppressed minority."<br>
<p>
I do not advocate reacting towards homosexuals with either fear or <br>
condemnation, although you may sense that there is some fear in my post.<br>
It's just that I honestly do not see how one can interpret the Bible to <br>
allow homosexuality and still have any meaning or authority to it at all.<br>
If we believe Genesis 1 where man and woman are a singular image of God,<br>
the logical conclusion is that procreation is a way that we as humans share <br>
with God in the act of creation, and perversions of that border on blasphemy.<br>
(Of course, this too is a slippery slope, as I have mentioned before.)<br>
<p>
Those who would favor "rights" for homosexuals with the church, do you <br>
ever envision the day when homosexuals will teach in our church schools?<br>
If so, then we enter the area where civil liberties conflict with religious<br>
liberties.  Already this is happening at Carnegie Mellon, where there are<br>
strong rules against gay-bashing, to the point of restricting freedom of<br>
speech.  Where will their rights stop and mine begin?  Do "normal<br>
individuals" plaster the campus restrooms with graffiti saying<br>
where and when anonymous sexual encounters may be had?  <br>
<p>
Some say that the oppression came and forced the gays underground to the<br>
various risky behaviors that they take.  It seems to me that this may <br>
be revisionist history.  <br>
<p>
I know this post may be tough, but I should say that my head is not so far<br>
in the sand that I haven't noticed that there are real people in SDA schools<br>
dealing with their own homosexuality and that of others.   This is an issue<br>
that until now has been unspeakable, and we need to get a dialogue going.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
