<title>May_1993: Order in  Chaos</title>
<h1>Order in  Chaos</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 1993 20:01:53 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#223">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#223">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#223">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#223">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0224.html">Raylene Dyson: "Re: sdas and guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0222.html">Bruce Holm: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I recommend reading the article in Dialogue by SDAnet's own Dave Thomas<br>
about chaos as an organizing principle of nature.  It provides<br>
interesting insights on this topic.  I also picked up interesting insights<br>
from a colloquium speaker here at Fermilab recently, who has spent<br>
much time recently trying to model the central nervous system with <br>
nonlinear dynamics.  <br>
<p>
One of the pieces of evidence he put forth is that a normal healthy<br>
human heartbeat cycle is chaotic, in other words, the amount of time<br>
between beats varies slightly from beat to beat in an unpredictable way.<br>
When EKG's of heart patients a few hours from death are studied, the <br>
heart beat is much more regular.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
