<title>May_1993: Lead Us [Not] Into Temptation   part 1</title>
<h1>Lead Us [Not] Into Temptation   part 1</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 24 May 1993 22:48:11 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#231">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#231">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#231">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#231">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0232.html">Tony Dyson: "Electronic music"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0230.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Bible and Homosexuality (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
After watching the David Koresh TV movie last night, I was once again <br>
reminded of my sensitivity to violent movies such as that one by a string <br>
of various nightmares.  Yet the pitched gun battle which ended that movie<br>
is probably tame by today's television standards.  Probably many SDAnet<br>
readers, and many children much younger than myself, could sit through<br>
that movie and not be moved at all afterwards, or have any aftereffects.<br>
Since I grew up in a home without TV, seeing it now can have a much different<br>
effect on me than most other people.<br>
<p>
I propose an axiom:  "Temptation is in the eye of the temptee."<br>
<p>
If this is true, then there are serious consequences.  For instance,<br>
a typical liberal ax to grind is the claim that moderation in alcoholic<br>
beverages, not abstinence is the rule.  Nationwide 1 in 10 who tries alcohol<br>
will become an alcoholic.  But from SDA families and those of similar<br>
background the percentage is much higher.  So here again the danger is <br>
much higher not due to any intrinsic difference in the act, but due to <br>
differences in the actor.<br>
<p>
Again, it is the same way with sports and competition.  The activity is the <br>
same, but the danger is different for those with different experience.<br>
(Here, though, I would say that SDA's are no worse than the general public.)<br>
<p>
In the Bible, there are cases where people were ordered by God to dishonor<br>
father and mother, kill people, commit adultery, steal, lie, and make<br>
graven images.  So if we are looking for excuses to do something, they <br>
can be found.  The question "what's wrong with ...." is a rhetorical question<br>
which always expects the answer "nothing".  And perhaps it is not always<br>
wrong to use the methods of the world, only dangerous in the sense that<br>
they can easily sidetrack us from God.<br>
<p>
"Lead Us Not Into Temptation" was the motto of Hadleyburg in Mark Twain's<br>
story "The Man Who Corrupted Hadleyburg."  But Hadleyburg could just as<br>
well be replaced by any SDA colony.  There certainly is a great effort to <br>
shield the occupants of these colonies from temptation.  Now that I look <br>
back on this effort, I don't think I am the worse for the shielding.<br>
Perhaps I am a "weak brother" who doesn't feel free to do all the things<br>
in which my "liberated" friends indulge.  But there's nothing in the <br>
Bible that says it is wrong to be weak, in fact it is encouraged by Paul.<br>
As long as people can be trained to make their own decisions whilst being <br>
shielded from temptation, this can be a good thing.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
