<title>May_1993: Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality</title>
<h1>Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality</h1>
Susan Harrington (<i>sue@cuc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 25 May 93 09:55:36 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#249">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#249">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#249">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#249">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0250.html">John Ash - CS: "Re: Ambush in Waco"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0248.html">Dan Hamstra: "Re: organs and synthesizers"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0228.html">Marcus Stringer: "FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0253.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<p>
	Those who say that homosexuality should be accepted because it is <br>
	Biblically OK, where do you draw the line? <br>
<p>
I'm having difficulty understanding why we are saying homosexuality is OK<br>
or is not OK.  I believe that if I am a homosexual or not is a personal<br>
issue that I work out with the Holy One.  I do not make this decision<br>
based on whether 9 out of 10 SDAnetters say it is OK or not.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm writes:<br>
	Is there any behavior at all that is unacceptable in the way you read<br>
	the Bible?...bestiality? ...sadism? ...pedophilia?...necrophilia?<br>
<p>
The behaviors you have listed as analogous to homosexuality all contain an<br>
element not present in homosexuality.  They are all involved with the <br>
powerful have power over the less powerful and using it.  Homosexuality is<br>
not about having power over anyone else.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<p>
 	It's just that I honestly do not see how one can interpret the Bible to <br>
	allow homosexuality and still have any meaning or authority to it at <br>
	all.<br>
<p>
Does this mean that since we all perhaps interpret the Bible differently<br>
that it has no meaning for us?  If I interpret the Bible to say that God<br>
surely understands, accepts, and blesses people who are homosexual does that<br>
affect you ability to interpret the scriptures for yourself.  You belief<br>
about the Bible and homosexuality has little impact (or hopefully it does)<br>
on my belief and relationship with the Divine One.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm writes:<br>
 <br>
	Those who would favor "rights" for homosexuals with the church, do you <br>
	ever envision the day when homosexuals will teach in our church schools?<br>
	If so, then we enter the area where civil liberties conflict with <br>
	religious liberties.   Where will their rights stop and mine begin? <br>
	<br>
Yes, I favor competent persons having the freedom to teach in "our" church<br>
schools.  The sexual orientation of the person has little to do with their<br>
abilities in the classrooms.  Since we have much more evidence that<br>
heterosexual men sexually abuse young women should we declare that no<br>
men can teach in "our" church schools?  <br>
<p>
Can you please explain how it is a religious liberty to determine that<br>
lesbian and gay people are sinners?  How is a person's sexual orientation<br>
a right that infringes on your rights?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<p>
	Do "normal individuals" plaster the campus restrooms with graffiti <br>
	saying where and when anonymous sexual encounters may be had? <br>
<p>
I'm not sure who you are calling "normal" but many items of graffiti written<br>
by heterosexuals have been within my view during my lifetime. <br>
<p>
<p>
 Yes, as a matter of fact they do.   <br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm writes.   <br>
<p>
	This is an issue that until now has been unspeakable, and we need <br>
	to get a dialogue going.<br>
<p>
Here's to a continued conversation.  I, however, would feel more comfortable<br>
if we would speak about this issue as a personal one rather than a theoretical<br>
one.  <br>
<p>
I marched in the recent march in Washington, D.C. for the rights of lesbian<br>
and gay persons on Sunday, May 24, 1993.  The day before the march I was<br>
walking downtown on the Mall between the Capitol and the Lincoln with my<br>
partner.  We encountered many lesbian and gay persons during our walk.  Some<br>
of them had their arms around each other or were holding hands.  My initial<br>
reaction was "why do they have to flaunt their relationships?" and I voiced<br>
this opinion to Sandoval.  We both realized that we were walking hand in<br>
hand talking about this.  We then became aware of the seemingly little<br>
aspects of a relationship that are denied to persons who are other than<br>
heterosexual.  We feel most comfortable walking hand in hand or arm in arm.  How<br>
maddening it must be to have to deny oneself these parts of a relationship<br>
for fear one will encounter someone expressing their "religious liberty" and<br>
feeling authorized by God to punish the sinners (e.g. the lesbian who was<br>
shot in Washington, D.C. a couple of months ago because she rebuffed a<br>
heterosexual "come-on").<br>
<p>
Sue Harrington<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
