<title>May_1993: Electronic music</title>
<h1>Electronic music</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>25 May 1993 10:09:25 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#232">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#232">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#232">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#232">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0233.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Church organs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0231.html">Steven Timm: "Lead Us [Not] Into Temptation   part 1"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SYNTHESIZER VS ORGAN<br>
<p>
First let me say that an electronic organ is a particular type of synthesizer.<br>
The differences between an instrument that would be classified as an "organ"<br>
and an "electronic keyboard" are these:<br>
<p>
1.	An organ has its own amplification system, and if it does use external<br>
	power amplifiers for extra volume, those are usually under the control<br>
	of the organist and are not used by or controlled by anything else.<br>
<p>
	An electronic keyboard, or "synthesizer", generally has either no <br>
	amplification system, or a very low-powered one for monitoring<br>
	purposes only. That is, just enough for the keyboard player to hear<br>
	him/herself. Further amplification can be either with an external<br>
	instrument amplifier, or through the house sound system if it is<br>
	capable of amplifying the full frequency range. (Many church systems<br>
	are not.)<br>
<p>
2.	In the tradition of acoustic organs, electronic organs allow the<br>
	organist to layer sounds, adding different timbres together to create<br>
	the desired effect. This is a simple process, and organs are usually<br>
	designed so that this can be done "real time".<br>
<p>
	Synthesizers generally have a range of preset sounds of which the<br>
	musician can select one or a few, depending on the complexity of<br>
	the instrument. Any tailoring of the sound needs to be done prior<br>
	to the performance, and the resulting sound stored in memory. It is<br>
	virtually impossible to do much of this in real time. This is<br>
	analogous to the organist selecting the stops to be used, done one<br>
	step at a time, usually during practice, not performance. An<br>
	accomplished organist, however, can select stops on the run, while<br>
	this is not practical with a synthesizer.<br>
<p>
3.	Different organs have a similar sound for the various stops, allowing<br>
	an organist to move from one installation to another with a minimum<br>
	of adjustment.<br>
<p>
	Synthesizers, however, vary tremendously, and a musician unfamiliar<br>
	with a particular keyboard can find it difficult to locate the<br>
	desired sounds.<br>
<p>
4.	Many electronic organs are designed for one purpose: to produce organ-<br>
	like sounds as best they can. They are optimized for this, and some<br>
	do an OK job of it, although clearly an electronic instrument can<br>
	never sound the same as a pipe organ with its myriad of tonal colors,<br>
	mechanical aspects, and the presence obtained from a large array of<br>
	sound sources.<br>
<p>
	Synthesizers are usually designed for use by contemporary musicians,<br>
	and are often used instead of string sections, tuned percussion,<br>
	horn sections or pianos. Few have a range of organ sounds, although<br>
	most have two or three to choose from - generally a Hammond sound,<br>
	a "cathedral" diapason sound (attempting the pipe organ), and a <br>
	"small church organ" sound.<br>
<p>
5.	Organs have a pedal board and two or more manuals. A synthesizer<br>
	has only one keyboard and no pedals.<br>
<p>
I have simplified things here, of course; there are many hybrid-type <br>
instruments around these days, and the modern "home organ" is kind of <br>
fifty-fifty. The Electone Lola referred to may fit this hybrid category,<br>
unless it is more than about eight years old, in which case it is more<br>
of an electronic organ.<br>
<p>
As far as sound goes, there is no electronic instrument which can duplicate<br>
its acoustic counterpart. Synthesizer manufacturers continue to spend large<br>
amounts of research money to achieve this aim, and they're getting closer.<br>
But even if an electronic piano were to sound exactly like an acoustic<br>
piano (impossible!), the experience of playing it would still be lacking,<br>
and it would still rely on amplification to produce any sound at all.<br>
<p>
Having said that, a good-quality synthesizer with acceptable key action<br>
and a decent set of factory sampled sounds is quite an asset in many<br>
situations. It can substitute for a wide range of instruments, and do<br>
that quite well. It is portable, and subject to the availability of<br>
suitable amplification can be used anywhere. It doesn't go out of tune.<br>
It can be used for many forms of music, from straight piano through<br>
brass band to contemporary. It is affordable.<br>
<p>
Now for my conclusions.<br>
<p>
A synthesizer is not well suited for use in a church. It can not easily<br>
fill the role of an organ, and a person needs to be a little more<br>
"technically oriented" to use it to its full potential. The exception<br>
would be if your church uses piano far more than organ, in which case<br>
the appropriate synthesizer may well do the job if portability and<br>
price are a consideration.<br>
<p>
WHOOPS - please, PLEASE let me rephrase the above! A synthesizer is not<br>
well suited to replace the organ in a church. !!!!!  Steve, if you are<br>
still reading here maybe you could fix that properly for me????<br>
<p>
At the same time, many traditional SDAs have a "thing" against synthesizers.<br>
This is similar to the situation a couple of decades ago, when guitars were<br>
frowned upon because they were used in rock music. As far as the actual<br>
hardware is concerned, there is no difference between an electronic organ<br>
and a synthesizer. Both create or reproduce sounds electronically. There is<br>
nothing "wrong" with a synthesizer, unless it sounds terrible!<br>
<p>
Synthesizers can be used to good effect in Sabbath Schools, with or instead<br>
of the piano, at camp meetings, in many kinds of bands, and I have even<br>
heard one played with an organ. (Organ/harpsichord duet! Sounded good, too.)<br>
<p>
One final note of caution: a synthesizer is totally dependent on its <br>
amplification. It is unrealistic to expect to plug a synthesizer into a<br>
speech-only sound system and have it sound reasonable. If your church<br>
has a speech-only sound system and you plan to use a synthesizer, you<br>
will need to either upgrade your amplifiers and speakers (!) or purchase<br>
a capable amplifier along with the keyboard. This is a *necessary part*<br>
of the synthesizer purchase, and should be included in any cost estimates.<br>
<p>
Any questions - drop me an e-line! <br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
