<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0277.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: Guns, Guns"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve:<br>
<p>
Sorry about this, but I couldn't let Harvey's post go by<br>
unanswered.<br>
<p>
For anyone starting this, unless you're really interested<br>
in this topic, you might want to skip over it; it's long.<br>
<p>
That said, I'd like to make it clear that I'm, at this point,<br>
a member either of the NRA or of any gun-control orgainization.<br>
I am, however, concerned with the issues that Harvey raises, and<br>
have been studying them for some time.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; From: brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu (Harvey Brenneise)</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I am one American who is horrified by the national obsession with guns.</i><br>
<i>&gt; While I understand the historical background of this (the revolution and</i><br>
<i>&gt; resulting constitutional guarantee of the right to "bear arms") and the</i><br>
<i>&gt; need to tame the frontier, I support any efforts to curb the uncontrolled</i><br>
<i>&gt; availabity of firearms.  </i><br>
<p>
I was with you up to this point.<br>
<p>
 1. With more than 20,000 gun-control laws on the books in the U.S., <br>
    one might have some trouble claiming that firearms availability<br>
    is "uncontrolled". (That the control being exercised is imperfect<br>
    is another thing entirely.)<br>
<p>
 2. Nowhere in the U.S. are minors, convicted felons or those judged<br>
    mentally incompetant allowed to purchase firearms. Interstate <br>
    mail-order sales of firearms are prohibited. One may not (legally)<br>
    travel to an adjoining state to purchase firearms. Various states,<br>
    counties and cities often have restrictions in addition to the above<br>
    federal laws. (And criminals ignore all of the above...unless you can<br>
    either form a law that affects the criminals, or change their hearts,<br>
    you will be wasting your time.)<br>
<p>
 3. LBJ once said that the test of the usefulness of a law is not "who<br>
    will it help", but "who will it hurt". A law that restricts the<br>
    law-abiding, while not affecting the lawbreaker is of limited utility,<br>
    at best. If it causes an increase of suffering to the law-abiding, then<br>
    it is almost certainly a bad law.  We have *lots* of the latter.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Somehow it's become associated with virility</i><br>
<i>&gt; and masculinity (and certainly supported by the public media).</i><br>
<p>
I know a number of women who would be vastly amused by this. None of them<br>
particularly masculine.<br>
<p>
The broadcast media, in particular television and movies that glorify violence,<br>
have little or nothing to do with reality...although there is strong evidence<br>
that they are a major factor in the increase in all types of violence in<br>
our culture. (The most striking evidence for this that I've seen was a study<br>
profiling the rise in all sorts of violence in South Africa that followed the<br>
introduction of television there beginning in the 1950's.)<br>
<p>
Of course, the tv and movie studios deny that they could possibly have any<br>
effect on people's behavior, and scream loudly about violating the First<br>
Amendment if they are called to task about it.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; And then of course there are the unconscionable efforts of the National</i><br>
<i>&gt; Rifle Association, which doesn't see any difference between prohibiting</i><br>
<i>&gt; weapons designed for warfare and those meant for hunting.</i><br>
<p>
This would be something to worry about if it were true.  Unfortunately,<br>
it isn't. (But one would know this if one had bothered to ask the NRA<br>
about its position on the issue, rather than relying on NRA's opponents<br>
for one's information.)  Actually, it's not necessary to rely on the NRA's<br>
word, either, there are unbiased sources of information available, such<br>
as the FBI's periodic Uniform Crime Reports, and other objective<br>
commentators on the issues. (Being suspicious of both camps, I spent time<br>
looking for more-objective information...and it's available.)<br>
<p>
Here were two opposing groups, claiming opposite viewpoints on the same<br>
subject.  It wasn't likely that both were right, so I started looking into<br>
the issue myself. I hate being lied to, and I was most definitely concerned<br>
with the level of violence in the U.S.<br>
<p>
As I studied the issue, I found that groups like HCI and the Center to<br>
Prevent Handgun Violence and others consistently got easily-verified objective<br>
facts wrong. (And had made the same mistakes for years, not correcting<br>
themselves.)  Sorry, I don't like being treated in that fashion, not even for<br>
a "good cause".  When someone says (or implies) that the ends justifies the <br>
means, I'm gathering my things to leave. Not that the NRA is perfect, but<br>
they're correct a lot more of the time, and I've actually observed them making<br>
corrections to errors they've published.<br>
<p>
Weapons designed for warfare (real "assault rifles", not what the media<br>
wrongly label as such) are not the issue, since they have been strictly<br>
controlled since 1934, and additional controls were added in 1986. No<br>
matter what some would have you believe, all the legally-owned full-auto<br>
firearms owned in the U.S. since 1934 have been involved in a grand total<br>
of *one* murder.<br>
<p>
An assault rifle, btw, must conform to a few characteristics:<br>
<p>
	1. Use of a medium-power cartridge.<br>
	2. Medium size and weight.<br>
	3. Offer select-fire (both semiauto and full-auto operation).<br>
<p>
That last requirement means that what the evening news usually calls "assault<br>
weapons", and claims that they need to be controlled or banned, aren't.<br>
<p>
What they are indistinguishable from (except cosmetically) are any number of<br>
varmint and small-game rifles.  Looks can't kill, although this is exactly<br>
what some newscasters seem to want to make you believe. Most of the rifles in<br>
question would not be permitted in many states to be used for hunting anything<br>
larger than game smaller than deer.<br>
<p>
The California Attorney General's office, who has the job of enforcing the<br>
laws of California, including its' recent "assault weapon" ban, has after<br>
study concluded that the law is not only essentially unenforceable, because<br>
of the lack of precision in the definitions used to frame the law, but that<br>
it won't even have any noticeable effect on crime, since the firearms banned<br>
have almost no presence in gun-related crime. (They make up about 3% of<br>
firearms owned in CA, and are implicated in less than 1.5% of gun-related<br>
crimes, according to a study done by the LAPD.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; We must admit that most guns were designed to kill people, not animals.  </i><br>
<p>
If we admit this, we would be wrong.<br>
<p>
The vast majority of firearms sold were originally designed for hunting,<br>
not military or self-defense use.  Of the remaining minority, a large portion<br>
is designed for (and essentially useless for anything else) target shooting.<br>
<p>
Even looking at handguns, unless you believe that the proper job of a police<br>
officer is to kill people, most have been designed for law-enforcement use.<br>
<p>
The bow and arrow was designed to kill...but what are most of them used for?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; To them, any attempt to differentiate seems a threat to any use of guns at all.  </i><br>
<p>
If you were dealing with an opponent who's stated goal was to completely do<br>
away with...um...all religious books, might you not be a little resistent to going<br>
along with "reasonable" restrictions on other books proposed by your opponent?<br>
(Imagine that said opponent had a history of lying about relevent issues.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I suppose it's similar to the idea that any attempt to register cars and</i><br>
<i>&gt; license their drivers is a threat to car ownership.  </i><br>
<p>
Well, it might be, but only if there was a significant movement advocation the<br>
complete banning of all motor vehicles.  Which wouldn't be unreasonable, since<br>
mv deaths total more than double the number of murders in the country.<br>
<p>
(But vehicle registration and licensing are primarily ways for a state to<br>
conduct "revenue enhancement", as they phrase it here in California, not a means<br>
to control vehicle use/ownership.) You need neither be licensed nor register<br>
a motor vehicle to legally possess and use it, unless you intend to use it on<br>
public roads.<br>
<p>
The effect of licensing and registration on highway safety is not all that<br>
certain, btw, unless your state is a *lot* tougher on periodic testing and<br>
relicensing than mine. And most aren't.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; However, appeals to reason don't seem to make much difference with this</i><br>
<i>&gt; group, which I'm tempted to say is mostly redneck anyway.</i><br>
<p>
I'm glad to see you use "tempted" there, Harvey. If you're talking about<br>
NRA members, their membership tends to be somewhat better-educated and<br>
employed than the rest of the national population. Their opponents would<br>
have you belive otherwise.  For that matter, most farmers that I know are<br>
neither uneducated nor uncultured, though they'd likely be classed as<br>
"rednecks". The term is unworthy of use, being, to my mind, no better than<br>
similar terms like "nigger", "slope", "chink" or "bohunk".<br>
<p>
Some others, more excitable, might be tempted to brand you a bigot, but I<br>
don't think you are, having read many posts from you here on the net.<br>
<p>
I do, however, suspect that you've been given bad information on at least<br>
some aspects of this issue, probably for all the best of reasons, but still<br>
bad information.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Even the police are pleading for a change in policy.</i><br>
<p>
Depends on which "police" you're talking about.<br>
<p>
Some organizations of police chiefs (a mostly appointive office) are calling<br>
for more gun controls. Organizations, such as Dewey Stokes' FOP, are primarily<br>
political in nature, with all that entails.<br>
<p>
At the same time, polls among rank-and-file officers (those folks who actually<br>
work out on the street) overwhelmingly indicate that they have little enthusiasm<br>
for more gun-control laws.  They, being out where things happen, understand how<br>
little good gun-control laws are likely to produce. (Polls I've seen were<br>
conducted for, and published in, publications catering to the business, such as<br>
"Law Enforcement" magazine.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Of course the more guns there are, the more there becomes a legitimate</i><br>
<i>&gt; reason for additional guns for self-protection.  </i><br>
<p>
This explains why those places with the lowest levels of legal gun ownership<br>
are such excellent communities to live in.  Let's see: Washington D.C., Detroit,<br>
Chicago, New York City...<br>
<p>
Something's wrong here.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Just what it will take to change these attitudes is hard to say.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; The level of carnage already is appalling.  How much worse does</i><br>
<i>&gt; it have to get?  </i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I suppose some Adventists would say it's reason to move to the country</i><br>
<i>&gt; (not to say there aren't any guns out here!).</i><br>
<p>
Hate to make things worse, but legal gun ownership is *much* higher in<br>
rural areas than in the major cities where the vast majority of with-gun<br>
crimes are committed.<br>
<p>
Maybe there's something important, other than the tool, that's the <br>
relevant factor. Maybe the problem is *sin*, manifested in this case <br>
as violent behavior.<br>
<p>
Like I said, I don't belong to the NRA. But I see things in the gun-misuse<br>
and gun-control issues that should concern us all (and completely ignoring<br>
the guns themselves).<br>
<p>
Do I think that everyone should have guns? No.<br>
<p>
Do I think that *most* people need guns? No. <br>
<p>
Do I think that people should be able to make their own *informed* choice <br>
regarding them? Absolutely.<br>
<p>
It would be lovely if everyone would voluntarily give up committing <br>
violent acts of all kinds.<br>
<p>
Do I expect that it will happen? No. Sigh.<br>
<p>
Gun control laws in the U.S. have historical roots in post-Civil War efforts<br>
to "control" the poor and black populations. I think that gun-control may <br>
well be a tripwire indicator pointing to the loss of other freedoms, including<br>
religious freedom, freedom to choose how one's children should be educated,<br>
and more. Sometimes I worry that I'm paranoid, other times I'm worried that<br>
I'm not paranoid enough.<br>
<p>
When all is said and done, while I can't "put my trust in prices", I at least<br>
can put my trust in Someone else.  There's really nowhere else to go.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
