<i>&gt; From: Raylene Dyson &lt;CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; So tell us about the Insight article especially pertinent to the discussion</i><br>
<i>&gt; of relying on guns or angelic hosts? Some of us don't have ready access to</i><br>
<i>&gt; such publications!</i><br>
<p>
I like "Insight"...to bad it doesn't include "Radarscope" from the old<br>
Youth's Instructor days. Oh, well.<br>
<p>
The May 22, 1993 issue of Insight has an article by Jeff Riedesel<br>
recounting a frightening experience that he and his wife had.<br>
<p>
They were parked near the beach in southern California one Friday night,<br>
when seven drunk men arrived in two cars.<br>
<p>
It appears that besides being drunk, they were angry, and thought that<br>
Jeff had done something to one of their relatives, and were intending<br>
to get even. Physically.<br>
<p>
Jeff and his wife tried to ignore what was going on, until one of the <br>
group outside tried to break into the motor home (caravan?).<br>
<p>
At this point, Jeff took out a small revolver that the had and, opening<br>
the door, confronted the man.<br>
<p>
Oops. Threaten a group of drunks, and you can bet they'll threaten<br>
back.  (They produced what appeared to be "a short shotgun and a long<br>
pistol".)<br>
<p>
His wife had a better notion of what ought to be done...she prayed.<br>
<p>
And at that time the ones outside calmed down, and shortly got back<br>
in their cars and drove off.<br>
<p>
Jeff had got his priorities scrambled, not to mention coming close<br>
to violating California law (the drunks had not done more than make<br>
verbal threats and had not entered the motor home), and getting one <br>
or more people killed. <br>
<p>
He was fortunate enough to have the opportunity to relearn the need<br>
to rely on God's protection and grace.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
