<title>May_1993: Re: The White Lie (fwd)</title>
<h1>Re: The White Lie (fwd)</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 25 May 93 15:37:12 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#265">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#265">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#265">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#265">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0266.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0264.html">Alan Fargusson: "ATF raid at Waco"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I really don't see that much connection between the two cases.  In any</i><br>
<i>&gt; case, there's only one Book that I would recommend that ALL SDAs should</i><br>
<i>&gt; read.  The controversy over "The Living Temple" was more a political</i><br>
<i>&gt; power struggle in the church (viz. between the preachers/church leaders</i><br>
<i>&gt; and the medical work, specifically Kellogg) than it was over theology.</i><br>
<p>
Huh ? The living temple was an exposition of pure New Age Theology,<br>
Pantheism. The issue was whether such spiritistic matter should<br>
be published at all, let alone by the remnant church. The issue turned<br>
into a power struggle only when Kellogg and his cohorts realised that it<br>
was EGW against them, and EGW was impeding them attaining their objectives . <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I have not read the book, but historians report that the charges of</i><br>
<i>&gt; pantheism were overplayed.  It is hardly controversial today, and would</i><br>
<p>
EGW didn't seem to think that the panthesism issue was of little <br>
consequence. I would question the accuracy of these later reports<br>
since they weren't there at the time. EGW made it very clear the<br>
main issue was theological, an apostacy is always somehow based on <br>
theological issues. An apostacy of the 1st magnitude it was. Read<br>
EGWs comments regarding the occasion if you like.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
