<title>May_1993: Re:  FW:  female homosexuality in the bible?</title>
<h1>Re:  FW:  female homosexuality in the bible?</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 25 May 93 16:21:50 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#258">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#258">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#258">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#258">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0259.html">Susan Harrington: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0257.html">Floyd Poenitz: "RE: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0238.html">Marcus Stringer: "FW:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0263.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  FW:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tang Ben seeks more clarification:<br>
<p>
When I ask "How, exactly are we to love the sinner but hate the sin?",<br>
I'm asking for suggestions for practical application.  What exact activities<br>
will be evident in the people of God, which will show that they "love" the<br>
sinner but "hate" the sin?  Love is not an ignorant response, one must be<br>
informed in order for true love to take root.  It must be informed, not <br>
only in<br>
scripture, but in the human experience and needs.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Well, my own opinion is that if they are out of a job, we should help them</i><br>
<i>&gt;find one, not because they are homosexual, but because they are people</i><br>
<i>&gt;in need of work.</i><br>
<p>
I couldn't have asked for a better response.  : )  Tang, many people aren't<br>
getting the job _from the start_.  Not because they are people who don't<br>
need it, or they can't do the job, but **because** they are homosexual.<br>
Now, how will those who "believe" assist them?  Is "Godly love" too<br>
concerned with more important things than to address this human need?<br>
If you think a job and house are luxury, think about the peace of knowing<br>
that no one will seek you out to harm you, just because of who you are?<br>
It's kind of basic isn't it?<br>
<p>
I don't deny that the spirit of Satan's way and character can be found in both<br>
gay activism and the religious right anti-gay movement.  Yet I propose that<br>
the spirit of the enemy is more than militancy.  The opposite of love is not<br>
hate, but   &gt;_indifference_&lt; or as some might say, being 'luke-warm'.<br>
The church wants to keep clean, comfortable, and content.  So the position<br>
of some "believers" seems to be worse than lukewarm, they will speak<br>
scripture to support their belief in homosexuality = bad, but will not <br>
lift a finger<br>
to lighten the burdens of those weighted down.<br>
<p>
Again, regarding Jude 1:7, what type of sexual liaisons are these impurities?<br>
What is the perception of the people, what do they associate these liaisons<br>
with? What is the actual liaison as to what we know today?  Do we know less<br>
than they about these things?  Has knowledge increased _everywhere_ else<br>
SAVE in this instance?<br>
<p>
I don't want this to sound like you or any other "netters" must condone<br>
homosexuals their "orientation" or their relations, force is not the <br>
way of Christ,<br>
only love - informed love.<br>
<p>
Marcus@microsoft.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
