<title>May_1993: Guns, 2nd amendment and Koresh</title>
<h1>Guns, 2nd amendment and Koresh</h1>
Russell Yonkers (<i>ryonkers@mis.mi04.zds.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 25 May 93 16:27:29 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#251">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#251">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#251">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#251">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0252.html">Tony Dyson: "EGW and Scripture"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0250.html">John Ash - CS: "Re: Ambush in Waco"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
There are two different issues involved with the discusion of the <br>
Waco incident and gun usage and ownership.  First Koresh was most<br>
likely doing many things that he should not have been doing.  The<br>
BATF went in on gun issues because that is all they could go in under<br>
but I am sure that they justified it with knowledge of other activities<br>
in the compound that were outside of their jurisdiction (in their minds).<br>
They could have handled it in any of a number of better ways that would<br>
have not endded in the large loss of life and the significant bad <br>
press that they recieved through it along with the fact that there<br>
are several weighty constitutional issues that are laid wide open.<br>
<p>
The second issue is gun ownership itself.  Some SDA's and some <br>
christians of other denominations as well feel that it is wrong<br>
for one person to shoot another for ANY reason including self defense<br>
or defense of ones country.  That is fine and thier desicison.  Some <br>
in our church do not hold that belief, and until it is made part of the<br>
doctrine of the church that we are pure pascifists we need to respect the<br>
rights of others to non-pure pascifistic beliefs.  I for one would take<br>
up a gun to defend myself my family my property or my country but that<br>
is my choice (and I feel that I can defend it from the bible but the<br>
people of the other opinion say the same so be it) <br>
<p>
As far as the issue of the 2nd amendment and the attempt to limit <br>
ownership of weapons to hunting perposes there is a significant <br>
misunderstanding of what the 2nd amendment was for.  The country was<br>
originally designed for very limited federal powers.  The 2nd amendment<br>
was added to allow us to protect ourselves from our own government.<br>
This can be substantially verified when you read the writtings of our<br>
founding fathers on the issue.  Thus the 2nd amendment is dealing with <br>
weapons that are used for defense not hunting.  This primarily came out of<br>
the laws of Britan at the time that denied the right to bear arms by the <br>
colinests to try to prevent a revolution.  I feel that the laws that <br>
limit gun ownership are a drastic violation of the 2nd amendment. There<br>
should only be limitations put on to convicted felons which have been in<br>
place forever to my knowledge (or at least close to forever).  <br>
<p>
I do understand that this is a very deep and difficult issue and hope that<br>
people think it out FOR THEMSELVES as I did.  It took me a long time <br>
and a lot of soul searching before I came to my conclusions.<br>
<pre>
-- 
*************************************************************************
*Russell Yonkers           *  It is only when I can say something that  *
*ryonkers@mis.mi04.zds.com *  may offend someone else that I have true  *
*Zenith Data Systems       *  freedom of speech!                        *
*************************************************************************
* My opinions are completly my own and governed by copyright and the    *
* sensibilities of a right-minded conservative.                         *
*************************************************************************
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
