<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I just saw the NBC made-for-TV movie about the events that led up to the raid</i><br>
<i>&gt; on the Mt. Carmel complex.  The Seventh-day Adventist church was never </i><br>
<i>&gt; mentioned by name, and oblique references were few.  The details seem </i><br>
<i>&gt; to match most of the other things we have heard.  Lots of shooting, lots</i><br>
<i>&gt; of preaching before the shooting. </i><br>
<p>
<p>
   I also watched that movie (something I rarely do).  There were things <br>
that disturbed me while I looked on... things the movie-makers were subtly <br>
suggesting.  One of the most disturbing things was hearing "Koresh" saying <br>
things _I_BELIEVE_ (world is coming to an end; what are we doing about it; <br>
shouldn't just sit back), along with the other fanatical things which are <br>
way off base.  <br>
<p>
   There is danger in mixing truth with error in such cases.  Poison is <br>
only deadly when mixed with healthy food.  It seems that the media (esp.<br>
TV) is terribly good at giving the good along with the deadly.  It seems <br>
that people who watched that "dramatization" would be desensitized to the <br>
gospel message.  Now if someone mentions quotes from the Bible or that s/he <br>
thinks the world is coming to an end, the response will laughter and scorn... <br>
"You're going off the deep end... gonna end up toasted like those wackos on <br>
Mt. Carmel." <br>
 <br>
   Also, I do believe that things were NOT quite like the way they were<br>
portrayed on TV.  They basically reflected everything the media has been<br>
saying.  Some of it's probably right... but I think it's the government's<br>
version of the story.<br>
<p>
--John Ash (jash@eecs.wsu.edu) <br>
KB7ONG  <br>
