<title>May_1993: Homosexuality...</title>
<h1>Homosexuality...</h1>
David Klein - EECS (<i>dklein@tribble</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 25 May 93 22:25:27 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#269">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#269">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#269">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#269">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0270.html">Steven Timm: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0268.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  FW:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0253.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0259.html">Susan Harrington: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Just a few thoughts on homosexuals and the church:<br>
<p>
How many of you netters have been hit upon repeatedly by a gay person?<br>
While working at Microsoft as a CO-OP student, I was.  And I still<br>
shudder to think about it.  Was it sexual harassment?  Yes!  Was anything<br>
done about it?  No.  I was laughted at for being hit on.  What happens<br>
if that happens in the church?  In our schools?<br>
<p>
Lest I be damned for waving a red shirt here, I have friends who are<br>
gay and who are lesbian.  And I care a great deal for them.  They<br>
have never tried to proposition or convince me that their persuasion<br>
was right.  And I haven't told them that they are going to hell.  If<br>
there is any justice, I think all three of them will make it into<br>
heaven, but that is not my call.<br>
<p>
I do not have a problem with gay or lesbians being in my church or<br>
teaching my children, should I get married and raise a family.<br>
However, if I found that they were actively pushing their sexual<br>
orientation, then I would have a problem with what they were doing.<br>
<p>
I guess what I'm trying to say is this:  If you are gay or straight<br>
doesn't matter to me.  What matters is that you display common<br>
decency in your sex related conduct.  I don't go around hitting on <br>
women.  (You can ask my girl-friend for verification of that.  It took<br>
me the longest time to get up the courage to ask her out.  ;-))  Just<br>
don't expect it as a gay right that you can go hitting on men if you<br>
are a man or women if you are a woman.  Fair?<br>
<p>
What do you think?  Next time you sit down at the potluck table, look<br>
at the people around you and ask yourself if it really would bother<br>
you to find out that one or two of them were gay.  I hope it doesn't,<br>
because if you don't know yet, I doubt they are any more sinner then<br>
you are.<br>
<p>
David<br>
<pre>
-- 
David J. Klein - dklein@eecs.wsu.edu
Electrical Engineering - Computer Science
Washington State University - Pullman
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
