<title>May_1993: Re: Bible and Homosexuality (fwd)</title>
<h1>Re: Bible and Homosexuality (fwd)</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 26 May 93 00:09:25 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#255">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#255">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#255">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#255">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0256.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Southern College's Organ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0254.html">Steve Hix: "Re: sdas and guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Harver Breneise quoted Gary Phillips as saying:<br>
<i>&gt; I come by these positions honorably: I have a degree in religious studies</i><br>
<i>&gt; and some additional seminary coursework. And I can read Greek, which is</i><br>
<i>&gt; often a claim that our detractors cannot make!</i><br>
<p>
Well folks, that just goes to show you how useless some of these degrees and<br>
seminary studies are. I don't mean to be rude, but really, a lot of stuff<br>
coming out of some of these seminaries just goes to show that the people in<br>
them either don't believe the bible, or don't read it, or both.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Terry, this is entirely correct. Not only is homosexuality a very tiny</i><br>
<i>&gt; issue in the bible, there are instances where gay relationships appear to</i><br>
<i>&gt; be accepted. Much of the furor over this issue among fundamentalist</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christians derives from mistranslation of a few specific verses. It's</i><br>
<p>
Would you believe it? The gay pastor my friend was communicating with said<br>
that David and Johnathan and Ruth and Naomi were homosexuals! I was entirely<br>
dumbfounded by this. It was so ridiculous that i was amazed that anyone<br>
could ever come up with this idea and actually believe it. I mean, if one<br>
believes this, one can believe just about anything, and make the bible say<br>
all sorts of things that it doesn't even hint at.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Don't let anyone use Sodom and Gomorrah as an argument, the issue there</i><br>
<i>&gt; had nothing to do with sex and everything to do with hospitality toward</i><br>
<i>&gt; strangers.</i><br>
<p>
Well, what about this then?:<br>
<p>
Jude 1:7 Even as Sodom and Gomorrha, and the cities about them in<br>
like manner, giving themselves over to fornication, and going<br>
after strange flesh, are set forth for an example, suffering the<br>
vengeance of eternal fire. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Jude 1:7 In a similar way, Sodom and Gomorrah and the surrounding<br>
towns gave themselves up to sexual immorality and perversion.<br>
They serve as an example of those who suffer the punishment of<br>
eternal fire. (NIV)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Likewise, the words used by Paul in his epistles that are</i><br>
<i>&gt; usually translated as "homosexual" or "effeminate" could just as easily</i><br>
<i>&gt; be translated as "coward" or "weakling." Quotes from Leviticus are the</i><br>
<i>&gt; most worthless of all: unless the person relying on Leviticus is also</i><br>
<i>&gt; willing to condemn wearing of mixed fiber garments, wet dreams, women who</i><br>
<i>&gt; wear red, and eating of shellfish or shrimp.</i><br>
<p>
This person, despite all his greek and degrees, is obviously grasping at<br>
straws and trying to change what the bible says because he doesn't want to<br>
change his life.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<p>
email:  beng.tang@f622.n600.z6.fidonet.org<br>
