<i>&gt;&gt; I think the preceding statement does justify the canceling of this</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; newsgroup, in that WWC is trying to get rid of newsgroups which</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; contradict the beliefs of SDA's.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I'm glad that the library I work for does not cancel subscriptions for</i><br>
<i>&gt; the reason given above.  As I've thought about this, I don't think</i><br>
<i>&gt; subscribing to newsgroups on a network is that different from</i><br>
<i>&gt; periodicals in the library.  The job of selection is a positive one in</i><br>
<i>&gt; which one chooses that which contributes to the institutional mission.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Pronography and items of prurient interest do not, so are not selected.</i><br>
<i>&gt; This is different than censorship.  Our library subscribes to journals</i><br>
<i>&gt; which contradict SDA beliefs.  We could hardly be a university and not</i><br>
<i>&gt; do so.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Harvey Brenneise</i><br>
<i>&gt; Head Reference Librarian</i><br>
<i>&gt; Andrews University</i><br>
<i>&gt; (brneise@andrews.edu)</i><br>
<p>
<p>
Sorry Harvey, I sent Steve three copies of the message and thought that<br>
I had changed this line in one of them.  What I meant to say is that I<br>
think this is why the university thought they justified themselves in<br>
canceling this newsgroup.  I totally agree with you that it is important<br>
also agree that newsgroups are similar to magazine subscriptions and<br>
should be chosen accordingly.  for a university to enable its students<br>
to become better educated.  Just thought I would clarify this point.<br>
<p>
Now going, I sent a message which I think was not posted.  It involved<br>
what I thought about the newsgroups.  I can't remember exactly what I<br>
said, but it went somewhat along the lines of what Harvey mentioned above.<br>
There are several newsgroups in the alt groups which do have value in them<br>
such as alt.internet.services, alt.politics.*, etc.  However, to read<br>
these groups currently I have to go elsewhere since we do not currently<br>
subscribe to these at Andrews.  It is a little more of a hassle to get<br>
to these newsgroups, but I have no real difficulty with it.  What I<br>
think though is that any of our universities (or whoever is in charge of the<br>
newsgroups) look at the validity of several of the alt newsgroups.  The only<br>
problem I see with this is that the alt newsgroups tend to disappear as<br>
quickly as they appear and they also tend to be umoderated, which is why<br>
it is harder to judge the content of the newsgroups.<br>
<p>
It's getting late here and I need my sleep.  I hope the above makes sense<br>
since I'm writing this so late at night.<br>
