<title>May_1993: What is love?</title>
<h1>What is love?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 26 May 1993 01:24:41 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#267">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#267">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#267">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#267">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0268.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  FW:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0266.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The approach I took of saying "There has to be right and wrongs" when <br>
addressing homosexuality is foreign to many people.  In fact, it's not my <br>
favorite approach, either, because I sound like Rush Limbaugh when I make<br>
those kind of arguments.  I suspect that some of our readers would be <br>
more comfortable with the approach of relationship theology.<br>
<p>
Relationship theology says, "My goal in life is to love God supremely<br>
and my neighbor as myself."  I think none would argue that we can love <br>
any neighbor as ourself, regardless of sex.  It is the question:  "What<br>
does this love entail?" where we may part ways.  <br>
<p>
Is there an additional committment that sexual love adds to a love<br>
relationship that is not there otherwise?  Is it necessary to participate<br>
in sex with someone in order to display love (or to seek love)?  <br>
Should sexual love be restricted to one person, a few (polygamy is permitted<br>
in the Bible, after all) or unrestricted?  I do not doubt that members<br>
of the same sex can live together and have committed and devoted<br>
relationships,<br>
but it is not obvious that sexual intimacy between them is either necessary<br>
or beneficial to achieving this goal.  I bring the hypothesis to this<br>
discussion that the Bible has something to say about these questions. <br>
Others claim it is between themselves and the Holy One.  If the<br>
understanding gap<br>
is to be bridged, we shall have to find a way to test the hypotheses.<br>
  I think we may take <br>
it as a principle that if we are to call something a sin, it should <br>
not be due to an arbitrary definition, there should be real and obvious<br>
detriment that occurs to our relationships with God and fellow humans.<br>
<p>
Consider the homosexual relationships of which you are aware (I must admit<br>
I am aware of precious few and those of which I am aware are not good ones.)<br>
Ask yourself what is the fruit of these actions.  A man moves out on his<br>
wife and children, leaving them without support, to live with his gay lover.<br>
Is this between him and the Holy One?!  I think not. <br>
<p>
As I expressed at the beginning of this thread, I am not comfortable with <br>
either scriptural interpretation of the various texts that are commonly<br>
used to talk about the Bible and homosexuality.  It is difficult to keep the <br>
texts which ban homosexuality without also keeping the texts which are used<br>
to hold women in the Stone Age.  If we continue down the logical path of <br>
that interpretation we arrive at the position of Paul VI and the Catholic<br>
church.<br>
<p>
On the other hand, if we say for some reason that these texts do not apply,<br>
then the Bible has precious little to say about human relationships at all.<br>
I do not have an answer to this problem.  Although I have expounded the first<br>
position I realize it may be untenable.  I have not seen any good study<br>
on this topic.<br>
<p>
On one side it seems we have the black lie that says "Homosexuals are <br>
Bad People.  You shouldn't get near one or touch one.  And if you men<br>
show affection to another man, you are a Queer and we will never let <br>
you forget it."  <br>
( I think this attitude exacerbates the need of men to seek affection <br>
from other men, but I could be wrong.)<br>
<p>
On the other side we have the white lie that says "the homosexual<br>
relationship is perfectly natural and if you don't think so, you<br>
are a Homophobe and we don't have to listen to you."<br>
<p>
Oftentimes I've got a great "colorful alternative" to insert between<br>
black and white lie.  This time I don't.  But I wonder:<br>
<p>
In some cases (probably not a majority) homosexuality could be an <br>
"acting out" behavior of rebellion against strict standards that forbade it.<br>
If instead of looking for the root emotional cause of the rebellion<br>
we simply condone the behavior which is a symptom of the rebellion,<br>
we do the person a disservice, at least I think so.<br>
<p>
I have spoken before of a student (several years younger than myself)<br>
in South Africa, whom I counsel by mail.  In the past seven years she<br>
has been part of ANC, MDM, ECC, Adventist, agnostic, Catholic, and now<br>
lesbian.  I still give her as much moral support as I ever did, encouraging<br>
her to pursue her studies and her quest for truth.  I still show faith <br>
in her that she is acting in accord with her best moral judgment.<br>
But I do not condone her lesbian behavior (even though I expected it <br>
would eventually happen).  I don't think she expected me to condone it.<br>
(In fact, she held off telling me about it for several months after it <br>
started happening.)  I believe that it is possible for me to show her<br>
love, give her support, and try to understand the motivations for her <br>
behavior without abandoning my own moral standard, and I think she respects<br>
me for that.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
