<title>May_1993: Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality</title>
<h1>Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 26 May 1993 01:50:33 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#270">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#270">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#270">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#270">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0271.html">Alvin Vitangcol: "Re: Censored Newsgroups @ WWC"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0269.html">David Klein - EECS: "Homosexuality..."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0228.html">Marcus Stringer: "FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;&gt;We have inborn tendencies to all sorts of sin, stealing, lying, cheating,</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;you name it.  God sent not his son into the world to condemn the world,</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;but that the world through Him might be saved.</i><br>
<i>&gt;[MARCUS S.]</i><br>
<i>&gt;This statement seems to simplify homosexuality to the point of being</i><br>
<i>&gt;a case of selfishness and self-seeking equal to "stealing, lying, and </i><br>
<i>&gt;cheating."</i><br>
<i>&gt;Are you ready to qualify your thoughts and biases?  What are the underlying</i><br>
<i>&gt;issues in stealing, lying, and cheating?  Are the traits of</i><br>
selfishness, &gt;telling untruths to cover oneself found in the homosexual<br>
identity itself?<br>
My point:  1)  If indeed homosexuality is an inborn trait, this does not<br>
a priori make it right.  Tendencies to other sins are also inborn.<br>
2)  Christ can save from any inborn or acquired tendency to sin.<br>
My bias:  I believe that any homosexual act violates the 7th commandment,<br>
"thou shalt not commit adultery."<br>
Now for some questions I can answer...<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Maybe getting back to basics isn't bad, a basics which goes beyond</i><br>
<i>&gt;"Adam and Eve".  WHAT ARE RELATIONSHIPS?  </i><br>
Relationships define identity.  We learn who we are by relating to <br>
other people.<br>
<i>&gt;ARE THEY A GIFT FROM GOD?  </i><br>
In general, yes.<br>
<i>&gt;ARE THEY SUPPOSED TO DRAW US TO A BETTER</i><br>
<i>&gt;UNDERSTANDING *OF* AND RELATIONSHIP *WITH* GOD?  </i><br>
Yes<br>
<i>&gt;CAN THE GOD-GIVEN POWER OF CHOICE AND UNDERSTANDING BE EXPRESSED</i><br>
<i>&gt;IN THESE RELATIONSHIPS?  </i><br>
Yes<br>
<i>&gt;ARE THEY REFLECTIONS OF THE</i><br>
<i>&gt;COVENANT LOVE-RELATIONSHIP GOD HAS WITH HUMANS?  </i><br>
Yes<br>
We might begin to find answers by addressing these questions.<br>
<p>
Now the question which to my knowledge has no data to support the <br>
affirmative, although I am open to suggestions:<br>
Can a relationship which includes homosexual intercourse reflect<br>
the image of God as relationships ought to?<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;Marcus -&gt;  How ARE homosexual students treated on our Adventist college</i><br>
<i>&gt;campuses by faculty/staff/students?</i><br>
<p>
In my day those that were caught got kicked out. (early 80's)  But only <br>
one got caught at AU that I heard of, and none were caught during<br>
my days in academy.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
