<title>May_1993: EGW and Scripture</title>
<h1>EGW and Scripture</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>26 May 1993 08:54:32 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#252">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#252">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#252">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#252">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0253.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: FW: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0251.html">Russell Yonkers: "Guns, 2nd amendment and Koresh"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Thanks for your reply to my question, Ron. In fact, it was an<br>
inquiring question rather than a leading question, so your<br>
assumptions about my own personal position are not correct.<br>
<p>
If you want to know my regular position on this topic, you need<br>
to read what I wrote to "Dan" on bit.listserv.christia a few<br>
months back. In fact, it was that conversation that prompted me<br>
to do some more reading on the inspiration/revelation thing. One<br>
argument I came across, and which sounded reasonable, is that<br>
there are no "degrees of inspiration". (I had heard this before,<br>
but never checked it out carefully). So either EGW was "inspired"<br>
(interpret that how you will) or she wasn't.<br>
<p>
So I am currently asking myself these questions: do I see the <br>
inspiration of EGW any differently to the inspiration of the<br>
prophets of old? If so, why? Why do I respect the authority of,<br>
say, Jeremiah's prophetic writings more than those of Ellen White?<br>
If the type of inspiration is similar from one prophet to another,<br>
what differences can there be between the canonical and non-canonical<br>
literary prophets? Plus a whole lot of related things.<br>
<p>
My preliminary findings are few and far between at this stage, hence<br>
my question. I'm trying to find out what others think and why, <br>
particularly those who take a similar stance to me! (Like Ron.)<br>
One thing I would say is this: people are far more prepared to<br>
contextualize Scripture than they are Ellen White. This is despite<br>
the fact that sociological changes in this century alone are <br>
probably equally profound as those between the time of Christ and<br>
the nineteenth century. Well, maybe not quite, but you get my drift!<br>
Hence I have become accustomed to making cultural allowances for<br>
Paul and Peter, but not for Ellen White. Many fundamentalist SDAs I <br>
know have quoted EGW far more than the Bible; after all, her writings<br>
are quite substantial and, combined with their high quote coefficient,<br>
this gives a large quote potential.<br>
<p>
Maybe I will conclude that there is a lot more in common between EGW<br>
and canonical prophets than I have cared to admit in the past. And<br>
that if I use the same hermeneutic to study her writings as I apply<br>
to the Scripture, I may benefit equally from them. I don't know!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
