<i>&gt;Consider the homosexual relationships of which you are aware (I must admit</i><br>
<i>&gt;I am aware of precious few and those of which I am aware are not good ones.)</i><br>
<i>&gt;Ask yourself what is the fruit of these actions.  A man moves out on his</i><br>
<i>&gt;wife and children, leaving them without support, to live with his gay lover.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Is this between him and the Holy One?!  I think not.</i><br>
<p>
"The man moving out on his wife" seems be an increasingly rare one.<br>
Some say they married in hopes to "change" themselves, others say that<br>
it was a necessary "cover".  I think of marriage in a much higher state <br>
than to<br>
be used for such things.  If people have been driven to do things like this,<br>
then the things or societal beliefs which drive them are wrong (formal and<br>
sometimes relational separation of husband/father and wife/children) and not<br>
of **Christ**.<br>
<p>
I along with many others, do not say that the Bible is irrelevant in <br>
the area of<br>
human relations.  To the contrary, the Bible has beautiful EVERLASTING<br>
__principles__ for human relationships.  The problem is not a silence on<br>
this matter, but a RAPING of the Bible by those who for centuries, have<br>
interpreted it to fit their bigotry and prejudice.  It is only fitting <br>
that these last<br>
days, have many "called out" people speaking out for the "healing" of the<br>
scriptures which we've raped.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
