David,<br>
<p>
I suspect that, a woman faces this behavior more than once in a month.<br>
This doesn't make it any better at all.  I don't know the logistics of your<br>
situation, but a firm "no", then report to a supervisor, and on up the ladder<br>
should have had the situation under control in a hurry.  Acceptance<br>
should not be a license for harassment.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I do not have a problem with gay or lesbians being in my church or</i><br>
<i>&gt;teaching my children, should I get married and raise a family.</i><br>
<i>&gt;However, if I found that they were actively pushing their sexual</i><br>
<i>&gt;orientation, then I would have a problem with what they were doing.</i><br>
<p>
This standard should be understood for teachers or preachers in general.<br>
But think about it?  You have school events where teacher/staff bring their<br>
"families"...  Teacher shows up in church with partner every Sabbath,<br>
they use the same car, go to the same home, invite members to that home<br>
for Sabbath dinner?  Maybe there's a "singles ministry" at church and<br>
people wonder why they don't attend?  How does one, NOT push ones<br>
sexual orientation in these cases?  They are not out waving flags or<br>
shouting.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Just don't expect it as a gay right that you can go hitting on men if you</i><br>
<i>&gt;are a man or women if you are a woman.  Fair?</i><br>
<p>
This shouldn't be a right or winked at as a "boys will be boys" as with the<br>
infamous "Spurs posse" case here in the USA.<br>
<p>
Your opinion is a bit more open than most.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
