<title>May_1993: Biases</title>
<h1>Biases</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 26 May 1993 21:57:50 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#280">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#280">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#280">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#280">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0281.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Pigs and the FLU"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0279.html">David Plaisted: "Branch Davidians"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0275.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: What is love?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Marcus called on me to be willing to admit my biases.  I did so.<br>
Now I think it is only fair that those who say the Bible supports<br>
homosexual behavior, including him, admit their biases.  I will not<br>
presume to say (yet) what they may be but it is clear that they do exist.<br>
<p>
Marcus, what are the principles of Biblical interpretation that lead you<br>
to believe that I am "Raping" the bible when I say that it says homosexuality<br>
is wrong.  It seems that you must begin with the hypothesis that <br>
1) homosexuality is ok and 2) the Bible must be interpreted not <br>
to contradict this.  Certainly you have presented no evidence to bolster<br>
either of these points.  Do you think that all that has to be done is to <br>
explain away the few texts that are usually used, and then say "because it <br>
is not prohibited, it is OK?"<br>
<p>
Part of the reason I feel the way I do is that I know of no case personally<br>
where a gay person really is happy and gay.  If the proponents were pointing<br>
to happy families with dad and dad and two kids or mom and mom and kids<br>
it would be different.  All the personal cases I know and all the statistics<br>
I hear suggest that homosexuality is a high-risk behavior in which <br>
monogamy is rare.  For that matter, if the bible allows homosexuality,<br>
why worry about monogamy, because polygamy is known and permitted in the Bible?<br>
<p>
I will agree with Marcus on one point and that is that there should be <br>
a division between the church's responses to homosexual people and <br>
whatever our theology is.  We are called first to love. "Love first, <br>
ask questions later" as it were.  From all my experiences (limited though<br>
they are) homosexual behavior is a divisive force in relationships,<br>
destroying them wherever it appears.  Christians are called to rise above<br>
our beliefs, and our reactions to this behavior and be ready to show the <br>
love of Christ to whomever.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
