<title>May_1993: RE: SDAs and homosexuality.</title>
<h1>RE: SDAs and homosexuality.</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 May 93 10:26:09 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#289">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#289">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#289">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#289">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0290.html">Bruce Holm: "Homosexuality and the Bible"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0288.html">Woody Baker: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0296.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "RE: SDAs and homosexuality."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Noe,<br>
<p>
I'll have to read messages from other "netters", but at least I have <br>
not argued<br>
against heterosexuality.  And if it seems that I have, arguing against<br>
heterosexuality was not my intention.<br>
<p>
Noe, the Adventist message was founded on the Sabbath, the Sanctuary,<br>
and Second Coming.  The main point of these should be Christ, and not the<br>
event or place, in and of itself.  Marriage, a symbol of a covenant <br>
should not be<br>
separated from the true meaning it was meant to reflect - God covenanting,<br>
committing Himself to humans, ultimately in the form of Jesus.  Homosexuality<br>
need not obliterate the meaning and importance of marriage between a husband<br>
and wife.<br>
<p>
I'm an Adventist, grew up in an Adventist home, but the belief that <br>
homosexuality<br>
_in and of itself_, being the work of Satan to destroy heterosexuality, <br>
is not a part<br>
of my belief.  Neither is a person's ethnicity, or physical disability <br>
being God's<br>
manifest displeasure on that person or the person's parents.  Nor is the view<br>
that the earth is the center of the Universe, a part of what I believe. <br>
 So neither<br>
you nor I can speak for ALL Adventists.<br>
<p>
As I've said to others on the net, granted that homosexuality is a sin, we as<br>
professed followers of Christ are a part of this world.  If people are <br>
being killed,<br>
fired, or made homeless because of their homosexuality, and we remain silent,<br>
we commit sin.  To we who know to do good AND DO IT NOT, to us it is sin.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Homosexuality is, in my view, not defendable from Scripture, and</i><br>
<i>&gt;expositors have to take great liberties with God's Word in their attempts</i><br>
<i>&gt;to defend what God plainly calls sin.</i><br>
<p>
This is good, it is your view which you are entitled to.  But you/we are NOT<br>
entitled to make a club out of scripture, to beat over people's head *without*<br>
you/us knowing the full reality of the situation, _That_ is what I'm saying to<br>
SDAnet.  As far as taking "great liberties", great liberties were taken <br>
in ending<br>
the tradition of enslaving, segregating, and discriminating against my<br>
foreparents &gt;as some supported it from the Bible&lt;.  And there is the furor now,<br>
and violence (act/word) as there was then.  I interpret your phrase <br>
"taking great<br>
liberties" to mean that I take liberty the invitation to prayerfully <br>
"dig in" in search<br>
of the "hidden pearls" in scripture (in context), free from pre-imposed <br>
prejudiced<br>
opinion.  If so, then I'm guilty, praise God!  I recommend again, that <br>
people read<br>
the introduction to "The Great Controversy" which talks about <br>
inspiration of the<br>
Bible the role between the human and divine.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;God's Word interprets itself as we compare Scripture with Scripture.  </i><br>
It's very<br>
<i>&gt;uplifting for us to dwell on God's great love for humanity (John </i><br>
3:16), but we must<br>
<i>&gt;never lose sight of God's justice, for it is because God is just that </i><br>
our dear Savior<br>
<i>&gt;Jesus Christ had to receive the penalty that we deserved in order to </i><br>
bring salvation<br>
<i>&gt;to us.  The magnitude of sin is seen in the torture endured by the </i><br>
spotless Son of God.<br>
<p>
As I've said before, Text - Context = Pretext.  The Son of God came eating and<br>
drinking with publicans and "sinners" too.  God's justice is <br>
everlasting, and it takes<br>
into consideration, the WHOLE picture, which we cannot, or will to not see.<br>
Thanks be to Christ, who endured bashing, "demonization", and death for ALL,<br>
and who is returning in terrible justice against the same.<br>
                                            ^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
Marcuss@microsoft.com<br>
