<title>May_1993: Homosexuality and the Bible</title>
<h1>Homosexuality and the Bible</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 May 93 14:44:03 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#290">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#290">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#290">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#290">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0291.html">Harvey Brenneise: "New journal: Adventist Today"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0289.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: SDAs and homosexuality."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In reading through the postings of those who defend homosexuality, I have to ask<br>
some questions...<br>
<p>
The underlying question is this...is homosexuality a sin in God's eyes (not<br>
yours, God's)?  This would have to be based and determined from His word, the<br>
Bible.  If it can be determined that it is sin, then the defense of this<br>
perversion is not possible.  (Just to clerify, I speak of the practice, not the<br>
person involved).<br>
<p>
There are cases in the Bible where God had homosexuals destroyed due to their<br>
sins.  It is worth noting that they were killed specifically because of this and<br>
other sexual perversions and they were killed right away, as opposed to letting<br>
them live out their lives to a normal age.  I have to ask why judge them now and<br>
kill them versus waiting for natural death?  Because He did not want to let this<br>
"diesease" spread in the community.  To back this up, just read the chapter in<br>
Patriarchs and Prophets on Sodom and Gamorah.<br>
<p>
Even if there was only ONE story in the Bible where this perversion was spelled<br>
out, judged on the spot, and executed because of the perversion, would that not<br>
be enough reason to call it abominable to the Lord and flee from this practice??<br>
 Or do we simply try to rationalize it away by saying that God really wasn't<br>
killing them for that reason, or thoses individuals were a unique case and not<br>
applicable to today?<br>
<p>
I believe there is ample evidence that homosexuality is a perversion and<br>
therefore a sin, in the Bible.  If you want to pursue some references, I can<br>
research them for you.<br>
<p>
Then there is the writings of EGW.  Do we throw those out as well, for the sake<br>
of condoning this perversion?<br>
<p>
If we can agree that this is indeed a sin, then we can proceed, otherwise we<br>
have no starting point in common in which to discuss this.  For me this whole<br>
issue is not whether I like it or not, BUT does God like it or not?  If we can't<br>
agree on that, then how can we talk about how to treat these people?<br>
<p>
So then the question comes up...what do we do with these people?  How do we<br>
treat them?<br>
<p>
If it is a sin, then we can treat these people as we would anyone else (you, me,<br>
everybody).  We are all sinners.  Marcus asked how to hate the sin and not the<br>
sinner?  How would you do that if it were your son who had done something very<br>
wrong (in your eyes)?  Maybe he robbed a bank, killed someone, gotten hooked on<br>
cocaine.  Do you tell him "hey, its ok with me that you did these things"?  Do<br>
you kick him out of the house and tell him you never want to see him again in<br>
your life?  No, you still love him and treat him as a human being deserving of<br>
such.  But you let him know that the behavior is unacceptible.  For those who<br>
you are not in charge of, you can still communicate that you don't accept the<br>
behavior but will support them in their struggle.  We should not discriminate<br>
against them any more than we do others with sin problems in their lives.<br>
<p>
I dont think Christ would ignore or shun the homosexual as far as interacting<br>
with them.  When they were ready to stone the women, Jesus said he who is not<br>
guilty of sin may cast the first stone.  When all had left, he told the woman to<br>
go and SIN NO MORE.  He loved her and stood up for her BUT then let her know<br>
that her behavior was not right and to stop it.<br>
<p>
The homosexual lifestyle is a private choice as is any other choice of a sinful<br>
lifestyle (such as a heterosexual relationship living together out of wedlock).<br>
 But it loses its privateness when teachers or others start promoting it (as<br>
they will do) in the classroom or elsewhere.  I would not want my kid's teachers<br>
telling directly or indirectly that their lifestyle is an "alternative" that is<br>
ok.  In my mind it is not ok (from what I read is God's perspective).  Sin is<br>
private as long as it only affects those who chose to sin.  It is no longer<br>
private when it involves others who don't consent or are unsuspecting, such as<br>
kids.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Bruce G. Holm               503-685-1350      email:  bruceh@wv.mentorg.com
Mentor Graphics Corp.       503-685-7000
8005 SW Boeckman Rd.
Wilsonville, OR 97070-7777     Disclaimer:  Opinions expressed are my own!
</pre>
