<title>May_1993: Communicating at cross purposes:</title>
<h1>Communicating at cross purposes:</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 May 1993 20:08:07 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#292">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#292">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#292">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#292">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0293.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: ATF raid at Waco"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0291.html">Harvey Brenneise: "New journal: Adventist Today"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Well, it seems that all the various arguments have been given on both <br>
sides of the homosexuality issue and now the only thing left is to <br>
repeat them louder.  Before we do that, let's step back and analyze.<br>
We have here a situation of diametrically opposed arguments, but also <br>
a situation of two totally different purposes.<br>
<p>
Most on the anti side, including myself, have been attempting to answer<br>
the question "Is homosexuality right or wrong?" and answering it "yes,<br>
it is wrong."<br>
<p>
If I read the posts of Marcus, I see a different concern.  He is pointing<br>
to a population of people who have been mistreated by the church and <br>
by society as a whole, and asking, "How ought we to love these people?"<br>
<p>
To first order, these issues are decoupled.  It is difficult to argue<br>
about both of them at the same time, and what has been happening is<br>
that someone like me will say "yes we have to do something for these <br>
people BUT HOMOSEXUALITY IS WRONG AND WE MUST HATE THE SIN".  In other words,<br>
only paying passing attention to Marcus' point whilst reiterating mine again.<br>
Marcus is saying something like "I think it's ok, BUT THESE PEOPLE HAVE <br>
BEEN OPPRESSED FOR YEARS WHAT ARE WE GOING TO DO ABOUT IT?"<br>
<p>
Is there room for cooperation in outreach to the homosexual person who <br>
most probably feels alienated from the church?  Can someone who approves<br>
of that behavior and someone who disapproves, like myself, find common<br>
ground?  It's difficult when some say that the first step in outreach to <br>
gay men and lesbians is to lead them to cherish their homosexuality as <br>
a good and integral part of their being.  But if there is common ground<br>
to be found, it is here:  why not teach them general Biblical principles<br>
of building new relationships and healing broken ones.  It takes <br>
a willingness of both sides to put truth on the line, to abandon any<br>
preconceptions about what the Bible may say or ought to say, and commit<br>
to live as Jesus would.  If such a community of people with fully healed<br>
relationships could be constructed, then God's will for homosexuals would<br>
be obvious by which direction the healing took.  Deciding whether or <br>
not homosexuals ought to be "fixed" then becomes God's decision and not <br>
ours.  <br>
<p>
Then we could pursue the parallel and exciting discussion of what <br>
hermeneutics could lead one to conclude that homosexuality is acceptable<br>
in the Bible.  Also to be addressed are the two meta-issues:  What <br>
authority should the teachings of the Bible have in the life of the<br>
Christian, and under what circumstances can emotional reactions lead <br>
people to discard doctrines to which they give mental assent.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
