<title>May_1993: Re: More thoughts on homosexuality</title>
<h1>Re: More thoughts on homosexuality</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 May 93 21:06:28 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#304">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#304">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#304">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#304">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0305.html">Steven Timm: "Bible interpretation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0303.html">Steven Timm: "RE: Biases and Perversion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On May 19,  8:34pm, Ray Mialki wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: More thoughts on homosexuality</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Some posters talked about seperating the sin from the sinner.  That is</i><br>
<i>&gt; really wishy washy, and I don't think God looks at it that way.  A</i><br>
<i>&gt; person who steals is a thief.  A person who kills is a murderer.  A</i><br>
<i>&gt; person who does not speak the truth is a liar.  A person who has sex</i><br>
<i>&gt; with members of his own sex is a homosexual.</i><br>
<p>
Yes, but Christ separated the two.  He mingled with and interacted with the<br>
sinners, the prostitutes.  While helping and loving them as people, He did not<br>
condone their actions.  To the woman about to be stoned, He told her to go and<br>
sin no more.<br>
<p>
My point in suggesting that the sin be separated from the sinner is in our<br>
dealing with them.  We accept homosexuals as humans deserving of respect but we<br>
don't condone their lifestyle.  We help them thru the problem, but only if they<br>
see it is wrong and want our help.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; When Christ comes in judgment, these people will be destroyed.  God is</i><br>
<i>&gt; holding these objects of his wrath until then.  (Read Romans 9)  When a</i><br>
<i>&gt; thief is put in jail, the PERSON is put in jail, not his actions.</i><br>
<p>
True.  But my comments were only meant to help us know how to deal with the<br>
person.  I am willing to help someone as long as they understand that by my<br>
actions, I am helping them as a person and not condoning the choices they have<br>
made.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; As a Church, we must learn to accept the homosexual, and his behaviour,</i><br>
<i>&gt; but without approving of it.  Then when they are led to Christ, over</i><br>
<i>&gt; time, as they renew and transform their minds, they will change.  And it</i><br>
<i>&gt; does take time, and they will sometimes fall.  But that is what the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Church is for, to bring them back.</i><br>
<p>
A very well stated point.  I agree.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
