<title>May_1993: RE: SDAs and homosexuality.</title>
<h1>RE: SDAs and homosexuality.</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 May 93 23:37:16 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#314">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#314">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#314">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#314">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0315.html">Tony Dyson: "International Date Line"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0313.html">Woody Baker: "RE: Gun, Guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Noe wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;In other words, the God-ordained matrimony between a man and a woman is</i><br>
<i>&gt;"spiritualized" into just a "covenant" into which homosexuals may also</i><br>
<i>&gt;enter.  It doesn't matter if it's man with man, woman with woman,</i><br>
<i>&gt;whatever... anything goes...</i><br>
<p>
It *seems* we might be near a red herring.<br>
<p>
&lt;Calmly asking rhetorical question&gt;<br>
<p>
Nowhere in this "discussion" have I supported anything *near* doing away with<br>
heterosexuality, original marriage, or family.  I _have_ supported the <br>
need to know<br>
and tell the whole story about homosexual humans who are born from the<br>
married man and woman, who are part of a sibling group.  This includes knowing<br>
and telling the whole story (context) as it is found in scripture.  In <br>
this, I have not<br>
proposed that "whatever... anything goes..."  I wonder if the belief <br>
that heterosexuals<br>
can "turn into" homosexuals what many with the traditional view believe?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;As I took pains to point out in my original post, I do not believe that</i><br>
<i>&gt;homosexuality _in and of itself_ is any greater or lesser of a sin than any</i><br>
<i>&gt;other sexually-immoral behavior.  Such immorality, whether hetero or homo,</i><br>
<i>&gt;is serving Satan's purposes in eroding God's plan for strong family units</i><br>
<i>&gt;centered around the faithful, committed marriage of a man to a woman.</i><br>
<p>
I'm sorry for overlooking the special detail you placed in being clear in your<br>
last post.  I'll try to be more careful.  Nevertheless, I say again, <br>
this is your opinion.<br>
I respect your opinion. Other people might and do have other opinions.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;A person's ethnicity or physical disability does not constitute willful</i><br>
<i>&gt;and deliberate sinning against God's revealed Word.  Homosexual behavior</i><br>
<i>&gt;does.</i><br>
<p>
Please read The Desire of Ages, "The Light of Life" chapter.  This issue is<br>
beautifully uncovered.  Being of African American descent, I can attest <br>
that many<br>
"Christian" people argued against ending the institution of slavery <br>
because it was<br>
interpreted that our skin color and culture is a result of a curse God <br>
placed on Canaan,<br>
the son of Ham, for Ham's act of looking upon the body of a naked and <br>
drunk Noah.<br>
(Gen 9: 18-27)  It was Ham's deed or "sin" which supposedly brought the curse,<br>
later interpreted to support the enslavement of Africans.  There were other<br>
Christians who believed otherwise, but many payed with their lives and <br>
the lives of<br>
their families.  Most noteworthy are the Quakers.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;The earth ***is*** the center of the Universe, figuratively speaking, in</i><br>
<i>&gt;terms of where the great controversy is being played out.  And yes, the</i><br>
<i>&gt;great controversy still pits the sophistries of Satan, of which I</i><br>
<i>&gt;believe homosexuality is a part, and the truth and justice of Jesus Christ.</i><br>
<p>
The first half of this point I agree with you, the second half I do <br>
not.  But we both<br>
have a right to our opinions... the issue is not our opinions, but the <br>
ways in which<br>
they are acted out, and the effect they have on people.<br>
<p>
In your previous post you said:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;"Adventists believe that Satan has been actively seeking to obliterate the</i><br>
<i>&gt;meaning and importance of the Sabbath institution.  We also believe he has</i><br>
<i>&gt;been seeking to do the same to the heaven-ordained union between husband</i><br>
<i>&gt;and wife."</i><br>
<p>
Saying "Most Adventist believe... or the Majority believe" makes more room<br>
for reality.  An English or communications professor would assume "Adventists<br>
believe" is a non-verbal way of saying "all Adventists".  (Me, of all <br>
people talking<br>
about English - SC's Jan Haluska would be speechless) Interesting <br>
enough, I'm in<br>
the majority (rare occasion) about Satan's battle against the Sabbath and<br>
heterosexual marriage.  Yet I part ways when we try to include <br>
homosexuality: "the<br>
state of being physically, mental, emotional, and spiritual attraction <br>
to a person of<br>
the same gender" as a tool in breaking these institutions down, at <br>
least heterosexual<br>
marriage.  Satan has also battled to keep the spirit of fear and <br>
prejudice alive and<br>
well so that homosexuals have been turned away from the Gate which is Christ.<br>
Yet a growing number of them are as persistent as the Samaritan woman who<br>
contended with Christ granting that the bread of life was only to the <br>
children, even the<br>
"dogs" get to eat the crumbs from the children's table.<br>
<p>
I'm sorry if it seems that I'm not allowing you to express your view of <br>
Scripture<br>
as you see it.  Again I say, when the dust of recited scripture settles <br>
no mater<br>
who is reciting it, we all must return and deal practically in a real <br>
life, real human,<br>
and real God way.  My words have not changed, they are as from the beginning.<br>
And if you read my previous posts, you'll see where I discuss the issue,<br>
"granting" that _opinions_ of which I don't subscribe are indeed _fact_.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;No, you interpret it incorrectly.  What I meant by taking great liberties</i><br>
<i>&gt;is to regard plain facts of Scripture as "pre-imposed prejudiced opinion"</i><br>
<i>&gt;because they don't square with what ***you*** believe.</i><br>
<p>
Ah, then we disagree.  The "plain facts" I've alluded to are not "plain<br>
facts" to you and the feeling is mutual.  You are only experiencing what<br>
thousands of others have experienced for centuries.  At least I have<br>
experienced it for a few years.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;And finally, Marcuss, you seem to feel that my previous post was a direct</i><br>
<i>&gt;response to you when it was not.  I had no particular person or post in</i><br>
<i>&gt;mind when I wrote it; neither did I even have your name in mind at all at</i><br>
<i>&gt;any point as I composed it.  However, apparently it had an impact....</i><br>
<p>
As a member of SDAnet, you were speaking to Marcus Stringer albeit,<br>
indirectly.  In context, within the last few weeks, there have been precious<br>
few who have posted *as I have*, from a non-traditional perspective.<br>
So you were speaking _to_ me as well, unless you were trying to speak<br>
_around_ me.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
