<!-- body="start" -->
Note that I put moralists in quotes.  And later mentioned reference to Christ.<br>
It was a suggest that such acts of morality are not "moral" at all, considering<br>
the whole picture.  When I take things out of context and use them as fact,<br>
ignoring other principles involved, then I'm worthy of quotes too and should<br>
be identified as a "moralist".<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I take it you are excluding yourself from the "moralists"?  If a moralist is</i><br>
<i>&gt;someone who has morals, then I guess I am a moralist.  But yet I don't </i><br>
"go into<br>
<i>&gt;the night" and point fingers.</i><br>
<p>
I too am a moralist, especially the Personage and principles which found true<br>
morality (see my above comment).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Are you suggesting that Christ and the principles of His character are </i><br>
no where<br>
<i>&gt;to be found?  Have you read the Gospels lately?  Maybe I misunderstood your</i><br>
<i>&gt;statement.</i><br>
<p>
No, and I share your joy that the Gospels help us see and know Christ <br>
better and<br>
thus we know the Father better.  I might have been confusing in my <br>
wording - sorry.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;What human rights are homosexuals being denied?  You seem to like to tell us</i><br>
<i>&gt;about how mistreated they are, but the ones that I have seen around here, they</i><br>
<i>&gt;don't seem to be in too bad a shape.  I am not suggesting that some </i><br>
are not, but<br>
<i>&gt;what percentage are we talking about here?  How far should we go in </i><br>
fighting for<br>
<i>&gt;their rights over someone else's rights.  Many people have their rights</i><br>
<i>&gt;violated.  That doesn't make it right.  But why single out the homosexuals?</i><br>
<i>&gt;Lets be fighting against all violated human rights.  I get the feeling from</i><br>
<i>&gt;many of them interviewed on TV that they think they deserve a special </i><br>
status in<br>
<i>&gt;society.</i><br>
<p>
As I've done on other issues before now, I've supported speaking out for the<br>
rights as individuals, and the need for the "Church" to do the same.  <br>
Therefore, I have<br>
not "singled out" homosexuals.  Let there be a discussion about women, ethnic<br>
or racial minorities, the poor, the homeless, broken family relations, <br>
and I'll speak<br>
out, as we all should.<br>
<p>
For the informing of anyone uninformed:<br>
=================================<br>
(1) In the State of Oregon, including all political subdivisions and<br>
government units, minority status shall not apply to homosexuality;<br>
therefore, affirmative action, quaotas, special class or special<br>
classification such as "sexual orientation," "domestic partnerships" or<br>
similar designations shall not be established on the basis of homosexuality.<br>
<p>
(2) Children, students and employees shall not be advised, instructed or<br>
taught by any government agency, department or political unit in the<br>
State of Oregon that homosexuality is the legal or social equivalent of<br>
race, color, religion, gender, age or national origin; nor shall public<br>
funds be expended in a manner that has the purpose or effect of promoting<br>
or expressing approval of homosexuality.<br>
&lt;More deleted&gt;<br>
=============================<br>
Society does treat some people special (positively speaking).  If some people<br>
have their way, as this case shows, it definitely wont be the homosexuals.<br>
Not unlike the citizen alliances formed to oppose the civil rights movement of<br>
the 1950's and 60's, many present day citizens alliances have formed to<br>
oppose the *inclusion* of homosexual people into those basic <br>
civil/human rights.<br>
<p>
"Homosexuality is that mark of Cain, of a godless soulless culture which is<br>
sick to the core."<br>
<p>
"The teaching of the youth to appreciate the value ... of the <br>
community, derives its<br>
strongest inner power from the truths of Christianity.... For this <br>
reason it will always<br>
be my special duty to safeguard the right and free development of the Christian<br>
school and the Christian fundamentals of all education."<br>
<p>
The first statement comes from a Fascist pamphlet published in Nazi Germany;<br>
the second was made by Adolf Hitler in a 1933 edict on the education of German<br>
young people.  Historians say that in the name of Christ and moral <br>
purity, Hitler later<br>
had people who were suspected of homosexuality either shot without trial or<br>
exterminated in concentration camp gas chambers.  If you've listened to <br>
testimonies<br>
of Jews who survived the death camps, they will say that the above <br>
statement sounds<br>
frighteningly close to that which proceeded the holocaust half a century ago.<br>
<p>
This is probably what some if not all homosexuals think of when they <br>
experience<br>
scripture, and "moral" crusades out to change their orientation, legal <br>
limitation of their<br>
human rights.  Again, my position is, we might want to read more <br>
carefully the scriptures<br>
we use against others.  The Jews kept silent, and few were around to <br>
speak up for them<br>
when it was their turn.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
