<title>May_1993: Questions from the net.atheists</title>
<h1>Questions from the net.atheists</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 28 May 1993 15:41:21 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#306">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#306">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#306">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#306">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0307.html">Steven Timm: "Cognitive Dissonance"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0305.html">Steven Timm: "Bible interpretation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0316.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Questions from the net.atheists"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have received many questions in response to my questionnaire about<br>
questions that Christians have never answered correctly.  <br>
I enclose them here, for you all to chew on over the weekend.  <br>
I will hold up the regular SDAnet over the weekend to allow a <br>
"cooling off" period as it were.  Anyone who sent me a post since<br>
1 AM this morning won't see it until Monday.<br>
<p>
Rather than trying to answer all the questions broadside, try to pick<br>
out two or three and give thoughtful answers.  We need questions like this<br>
to keep us honest.  Time was when SDAnet had resident atheists of our own.<br>
No longer.  (at least none that admit it).<br>
<p>
(And please don't include this whole post when replying.  SCT)<br>
<p>
Questions begin here<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
*From: Hein Ragas &lt;heinr@sci.kun.nl&gt;<br>
<p>
Hello. I am a net.atheist, for your information. (Actually, a<br>
net.free.thinker!)<br>
There are several questions that I frequently ask Christians, and they fail<br>
to give me an answer that satisfies me.<br>
I hope you could answer them for me.<br>
<p>
1) _Why_ do you believe in god?<br>
2) If god is so just, good, and loving, and if god wants to save us so bad, why<br>
   doesn't he show himself to all the people in the world at once? That's <br>
   the sure way to get everybody converted.<br>
3) Some christians say: 'The only way you can get saved, is to accept the lord<br>
   jesus as your saviour.' Ergo, actions do not count. Is a god, that allows<br>
   people to kill eachother off, but still allows them in heaven, not a<br>
   bastard? Don't you feel you are worshipping a bastard?<br>
<p>
<p>
*From: b.liddicott@ic.ac.uk<br>
<p>
X-Philosophical-Position: Strong Atheist.<br>
<p>
*Why* did Jesus have to die for our sins?  <br>
Why can't goD just forgive us when we repent? <br>
<p>
<p>
*From: apodaca@ucsu.Colorado.EDU<br>
<p>
If a Christian believes that the Bible is the absolute word of god,<br>
how can s/he pick and choose passages to believe and follow and<br>
passages to ignore without being hypocritical?<br>
<p>
i.e. how can a Christian use the Leviticus passage which forbids male<br>
homosexuality to justify discrimination against homosexuals, and<br>
at the same time, ignore the Leviticus passages which deal with<br>
personal hygene and clothing?<br>
<p>
<p>
*From: (James J. Lippard) &lt;LIPPARD@CCIT.ARIZONA.EDU&gt;<br>
<p>
What is the purpose of the crucifixion?  That is, how is it that God's<br>
sacrificing himself incarnate pays for the sins of humanity?  To whom<br>
is this sacrifice "owed"?  Why can't God just say "OK, you're all forgiven"<br>
without the sacrifice?<br>
<p>
If salvation is by faith and not by works, why does everything Jesus says<br>
about salvation in the synoptic gospels seem to indicate otherwise?<br>
<p>
What is one clear, specific, detailed prophecy of the Messiah in the<br>
Hebrew scriptures which was clearly fulfilled by the historical Jesus,<br>
and in such a way that the fulfillment was itself remarkable?  (i.e.,<br>
could not have been intentionally been fulfilled by a prospective Messiah<br>
claimant)<br>
<p>
What happens to those who don't hear about Christianity during their lifetime?<br>
If they go to hell, that seems unfair.  If they don't go to hell, then<br>
missionaries are sending people to hell by telling them about Christianity<br>
and giving them a chance to reject it.<br>
<p>
Why didn't God just create heaven, with all of the people who he knew in<br>
advance would go there in it, instead of creating the earth and sending<br>
many people to hell?<br>
<p>
<p>
I am a "recovering Catholic;"  that is to say, I have almost purged all of the<br>
detrimental teachings of that particular sect from my brain.  I spent a year<br>
in the seminary, on my way to becoming a priest (or so I thought).  I give you<br>
this background to let you know that my search for God (long since abandoned)<br>
is no fly by night, passing concern.  <br>
<p>
Here's the question that no Christian can answer.  How do you know God's will?<br>
 Let's assume you need to make a very important decision, and in Christian<br>
fervor pray over the matter in order to discover God's will.  You pray, and<br>
some sign or another (which you of course interpret as a sign, using your<br>
mind) comes to you.  You then decide what to do.  Note those words *YOU*<br>
*Decide* what to do.  <br>
<p>
If one wants to pass off the responsibility for making a decision to what one<br>
perceives as God and his will, that is your right.  However, ultimately<br>
knowing what to do is up to the thinking individual, even *if* you deign to<br>
call the decision God's will.<br>
<p>
P.S.  I knew a guy who, after making numerous mistakes at work and generally<br>
being a slougher, was passed over for a promotion.  "Oh well," he said with a<br>
clear conscience, "that must be God's will for me."  What a disgusting way to<br>
avoid responsibility.<br>
<p>
<p>
*From: jcopelan@nyx.cs.du.edu (The One and Only)<br>
<p>
OK, what is God and how do you come to know this??<br>
<p>
<p>
*From: solovay@netcom.com (Andrew Solovay)<br>
<p>
My A1 question:<br>
<p>
How can anyone, in a finite lifetime, commit crimes/sins which merit<br>
*infinite* punishment? I could (in principle) understand if, say, all<br>
my "sins" worked out to 1E15 years of torture, or something like that;<br>
but sooner or later it'd all be paid off, right?<br>
<p>
 <br>
Andrew Solovay<br>
<p>
<p>
1) If god is infinite (or everywhere), I must be part of god. And, if god<br>
is perfect and infinite, I am part of a perfect being. Ergo, I am <br>
perfect. How can I be a sinner?<br>
<p>
2) If god is able to do whatever he wants, why did he need to kill his<br>
own son and not just forgive us all?<br>
<p>
3) If god know it all, where is the freedom of choice when things are<br>
already established?<br>
<p>
4) If god can do anything he wants, why did he create men?<br>
<p>
5) Anyway, why did god create men?<br>
<p>
6) Why did god create all the other planers, galaxies, etc?<br>
<p>
7) Why didn't god stop the Nazis and saved all the people who died in the<br>
Holocaust?<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
*From: lanph872@crow.csrv.uidaho.edu (Rob Lanphier)<br>
<p>
Well, how about the tired old thread "Messianic Jews and Christians",<br>
which deals with Christian accountability to the Old Testament, in terms<br>
of Matthew 5:17-20.  It seems like any time anyone points out the flaws in<br>
the OT, some Christian will proclaim that the OT doesn't apply in the "New<br>
Convenant".  Yet Matthew 5:17-20 is quite clear.  Explain.  <br>
<p>
Rob Lanphier<br>
<p>
<p>
*From: Esa Perki| &lt;EPERKIO@cc.Helsinki.FI&gt;<br>
<p>
1.)  Why should one believe in gods?  (Request for evidence incl.)<br>
2.)  Why does your "God" wish to be worshipped?<br>
3.)  What has he/she/it done to deserve my respect?<br>
4.)  What is his/her/its motivation?<br>
5.)  If you believe in a god who knows the future, how do<br>
     you explain away the contradictions that naturally arise?<br>
6.)  Explain the concept of Trinity without resorting to the use of<br>
     the word "mystery" or its synonyms.<br>
7.)  Explain the idea of "redemption" and tell just why was it <br>
     even necessary.  <br>
8.)  What is "sin"?<br>
9.)  [Various biblical trivia]<br>
10.)  What does the phrase "God is love" mean?<br>
<p>
The above were ones that popped immediately into my mind.  <br>
Hope it helped.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
 <br>
Here is one:<br>
 <br>
The fundamental difference between many atheists and theists is not so<br>
much what we believe but what we accept as reliable ways of knowing.<br>
It does not seem to be possible to prove the existence of a god or gods<br>
on the basis of empirical evidence or logical argument, or at least all<br>
such attempts to date are widely judged by both philosophers and<br>
theologians to have failed.  Faith (belief in the absence of empirical<br>
evidence or logical proof) is held by most to be the proper basis for<br>
religious belief, but it is not felt to be a reliable way of knowing in<br>
any other areas of inquiry.  For example, in a court of law, we don't<br>
believe one man's complaint just because we have faith in him; proof is<br>
required to win a case.  If faith is not reliable in some areas of<br>
inquiry, why should we accept it as reliable in another: the question<br>
of the existence of supernatural beings?  Isn't it rather that the sole<br>
basis of religious belief is the desire to believe, or rather make<br>
believe?<br>
 <br>
David Nye<br>
<p>
*From: nrp@st-andrews.ac.uk (Norman R. Paterson)<br>
<p>
Q1.  Define what you mean by "God".<br>
(I generally find everyone has a different definition, even within a given<br>
religion.  This makes it difficult to discuss god.  I find that the only time<br>
people agree what "god" is, they are agreeing to a definition so vague as to<br>
be worthless.)<br>
<p>
Q2.  Resolve the paradox of omniscience and free will.<br>
(The only solutions I have seen to this are fudged.)<br>
<p>
Q3.  How do you explain the fact that if you had been born in, say, India,<br>
	you would have been as committed to Hinduism<br>
	as you are now committed to Christianity.<br>
(Substitute region &amp; religion of choice.  You can always find incompatible<br>
religions, so it's not good enough to say that "all religions are<br>
essentially the same.")<br>
<p>
Q4.  If your god told you to buy a rifle and shoot children, would you do it?<br>
(Don't say it doesn't happen.  It did in the Old Testament, and it<br>
happens nowadays.<br>
Or don't you think that David Koresh really believed what he said?  A<br>
straight yes or no<br>
is required.)<br>
<p>
Q5.  How do you tell if someone is a "True Christian?"<br>
(Is there ANY way of telling?  If not, how do you know whether David<br>
Koresh was one<br>
or not?  Be specific.  Apply the test to Joan of Arc, Mother Teresa,<br>
Adolf Hitler (he<br>
thought he was - see the FAQ), the Bishop of Durham (UK), Mormons,<br>
Muslims etc.)<br>
<p>
Let's see how these do for starters.<br>
<p>
-Norman<br>
<p>
Ohh, what the heck.  Here's one:<br>
<p>
Is something good because God commands it, or does God command it<br>
because it is good?  (ie., can God really be the ultimate source of<br>
morality?)<br>
<p>
<p>
*From: (Quowong P. Liu) &lt;qpliu@phoenix.Princeton.EDU&gt;<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
How important is the idea that Jesus will return?<br>
If many people get the idea that it is close at hand,<br>
some those people might make the world a nastier<br>
place to be, as in the case of the cult in Texas.<br>
At the present, there does not seem to be any sign<br>
that the major Christian sects think that any<br>
return of Jesus will occur any time soon.  If any<br>
sects do consider that the return of Jesus is<br>
important, when and how do they envision it<br>
happening?<br>
<p>
*From: Jeffrey Clark &lt;J.Clark@edn.gu.edu.au&gt;<br>
<p>
Steve here's a couple:<br>
<p>
How come, if you don't know the mind of God, can you be so sure that some of<br>
these self-professed Christians, who carry out atrocities in the name of<br>
God, are not carrying out God's will as God means *them* too?<br>
<p>
Why is the genealogy of Jesus traced back to David via Joseph, when Jesus is<br>
supposed to be immaculately conceived?<br>
<p>
Why does the Bible ("God's Word") get so many basic facts wrong, like bats<br>
are birds, rabbits are cud-chewers, whales are big fish etc?<br>
<p>
What makes your denomination right and all the others wrong, and why<br>
christianity and not Islam or Shintoism or Hinduism etc?<br>
<p>
Why is the Bible written only to males? (Mostly I get denials, but it's<br>
patently obvious if you read it)<br>
<p>
If some parts of the Bible are fallacious or allegorical (I normally get<br>
them to admit this bit), then which bits do you take as guidelines for life<br>
and how do you know they are not fallacious?<br>
<p>
What parts of the observable world would not be explainable without an<br>
existant God? (I normally use this to dazzle Christians with what we do know<br>
as human beings about how the world works, I've even met some that didn't<br>
understand the water cycle)<br>
<p>
How come different denominations seem to be geographically poradic (ie why<br>
is it only the people around you who have access to the TRUTH)?<br>
<p>
This will do for now, but really there are hundreds more. For basically the<br>
incontinuity of the world-view held by most Christians is so blatently<br>
obvious that I find it easy to ask questions that touches on something they<br>
have not thought about. The questions can change for each denomination,<br>
mainly because denominations normally spring from some disagreement about<br>
some particular fallacious aspect of the previous church and therefore the<br>
concentration on certain issues for each church has allowed them to fix up<br>
some of the errors in that fallacy whilst just accepting blindly other<br>
fallacies they don't consider to be particularly important. Basically it's<br>
like trying to tape up a leaky bucket which is still being filled with<br>
knowledge (care of scientific enquiry) and is still decaying due to age. But<br>
some people just can't throw away the old bucket and get a new one!<br>
<p>
Jeff.<br>
<p>
<p>
*From: jmunch@hertz.elee.calpoly.edu (John Munch)<br>
<p>
Why did god make sex feel so good, and then allow various religions<br>
to label sex as sin?<br>
