<title>May_1993: Re Homosexuality and the Bible</title>
<h1>Re Homosexuality and the Bible</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 31 May 1993 10:46:35 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#309">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#309">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#309">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#309">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0310.html">Steven Timm: "Historically Correct Meets Politically Correct"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0308.html">Steven Timm: "Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Wow!! I leave the computer for a few days and SDAnet explodes with an<br>
argument about homosexuality. The usual viewpoints have come to the surface.<br>
<p>
1. Homosexuality is wrong. it has to be punished.<br>
<p>
2. We need to give support to homosexuals reaffirming our love for them<br>
   because they deserve it since Christ died for them as well.<br>
<p>
3. We somehow must accomodate homosexuals because they cannot do <br>
   anything about it.<br>
<p>
I won't go over the arguments as we know what the texts are. We have<br>
quoted the few texts ad nausium dragging our own meanings out of them. I simply<br>
want to say this. For too long we have concentrated on the disciplinary<br>
side of people behaviour, rather than the redemptive side.<br>
<p>
I knew a minister here in Australia who although married, fought homosexual<br>
tendencies and urges all his life. He was caught and disciplined. He came<br>
back to church and made a continued effort through the remainder of his<br>
life to bring people into the church. At the time of his dismissal from<br>
the ministry the argument raged through the church. There were those<br>
who wanted him to stop attending church. Fortunately good sense prevailed<br>
and a caring Christian was able to continue to serve his church in a lay<br>
capacity.<br>
<p>
I taught with a young male teacher who was a homosexual. He too was caught<br>
and disciplined. He was dismissed from the teaching work force, his parents<br>
rejected him and a couple of year later, he died of AIDS. I did not know<br>
him well. His dimissal took place only a couple of weeks after my arrival<br>
at the school. I did not know till a couple of year later that he was<br>
homosexual. I met him from time to time in my professional capacity and<br>
I am sorry that I did not do more to affirm him as a Christian. His<br>
death from AIDS did not surprise me. By that time I was teaching in<br>
a different part of the country. I can only hope that those who ministered<br>
to him in his final illness were loving caring Christians.<br>
<p>
My heart goes out to those people who are disciplined by the church.<br>
Sometimes, I think we cure warts by chopping off arms and legs. We <br>
need to develop techniques for affirming the worth of people no<br>
matter what they have done.<br>
<p>
Christ affirmed prostitutes, adulterers, cheats, murderers, and thieves<br>
during his ministry, not in their sin, but because he sensed in each a<br>
person of value, someone worth dying for. His response was "Come unto Me."<br>
His greatest indictments are against those who are hypocrites, those who <br>
lead others astray, and those who have knowledge but do not pass it on.<br>
<p>
I ma heterosexual and love it, but I know that in my heart is pride,<br>
jealousy, hypocracy and so on. With sins like that on my slate, I want to<br>
do something to ease the path of other Christians no matter what their<br>
sins are.<br>
<p>
When we have learned to love those we love the least, then we will<br>
have developed a true Christian love.<br>
<p>
Christian Regards<br>
Maurice Ashton<br>
mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au<br>
   .-_|\<br>
  /     \<br>
  \.--._/<br>
       V<br>
