<title>May_1993: Historically Correct Meets Politically Correct</title>
<h1>Historically Correct Meets Politically Correct</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 31 May 1993 22:23:35 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#310">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#310">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#310">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#310">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0311.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Fidonet mailing"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0309.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Re Homosexuality and the Bible"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
(And the result is many kilojoules of heat but no light)<br>
<p>
The discussion on homosexuality has been interesting but I think there<br>
has been precious little actual communication that actually went on.<br>
We may never reach consensus before the Second Coming, but I think <br>
it ought to be possible to at least understand why communication has been<br>
difficult on this issue, and at least be able to address the concerns <br>
of both sides.  Note that it is much easier to react than to communicate.<br>
<p>
Issue 1:  What is opinion and what is the word of the LORD and what <br>
is experimental fact?<br>
Marcus suggests that the core of the scriptural argument against<br>
homosexuality is some people's opinion of the texts which can also be <br>
read a different way.  I have suggested that his interpretation of<br>
when homosexuality starts and its intrinsic moral value is opinion and <br>
not established fact.  The two starting sets of hypotheses are completely<br>
differently, yet both sides of the argument (and here I include myself)<br>
have proceeded in the argument as if our hypotheses ought to be taken<br>
for granted by the opposite side, and proceeded to make arguments<br>
based on them.  If the audience does not accept the underlying hypotheses,<br>
why should we expect anyone to listen to the arguments?<br>
<p>
Issue 2:  Irrespective of whether homosexuality is or is not a sin,<br>
how ought the church to respond to those who claim this orientation?<br>
<p>
Those who have a burden for this community generally say that this issue<br>
ought to be addressed first.  Some netters point out, though, that <br>
Jesus said "Go, and sin no more."  Thus the moral implications are dragged<br>
into the discussion, and the two issues are mangled together.  It's not<br>
helped by those who say that the first step is affirming these people<br>
in their homosexuality.  Since there are also politically correct people<br>
that say that is wrong to give deaf people operations to help them hear<br>
"you are destroying a valid community with its own active culture and <br>
methods of communication", I am not surprised.  But I think in the short<br>
run if any consensus is to be reached, issue 1 and 2 must be decoupled.<br>
<p>
Perhaps one of the few things we can agree on is that the current church<br>
record in this area is dismal.  Colin Cook cost us a great deal of <br>
credibility.  I don't suppose the trademark suit endeared the church <br>
leadership to the Kinship gay "SDA" organization, either.  Yet it <br>
is not an overstatement to say that the scriptural interpretation used<br>
by this group is difficult for some Adventists to recognize as an Adventist<br>
interpretation of any sort.  <br>
<p>
Issue 3:  Relationship theology:<br>
Can the covenant relationship, image of God, be reproduced in a sexual<br>
relationship between two members of the same sex?<br>
<p>
It is not clear to me that either side thinks this question matters.<br>
Certainly many times God's image is not expressed in heterosexual union.<br>
It's also not clear why monogamy should matter to those whose morals<br>
allow homosexuality.<br>
This issue can be resolved, however, with experimental data.<br>
<p>
Issue 4:  What makes many people, Christian and not, fear homosexuals<br>
and are these fears founded.<br>
<p>
<p>
If we can attack the issues,  there can at least be communication.<br>
We may never agree, but at least we'll know why we don't.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
