<title>May_1993: Cognitive Dissonance</title>
<h1>Cognitive Dissonance</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 31 May 1993 22:45:00 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#307">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#307">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#307">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#307">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0308.html">Steven Timm: "Notes on the day of Pentecost"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0306.html">Steven Timm: "Questions from the net.atheists"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Or, the grass is always greener over the septic tank<br>
<p>
I don't remember the percentage of people that leave the SDA church over<br>
some conflict with some person, but it is large.  I suspect that even <br>
this figure is underreported, because some of the people who have left<br>
over doctrinal disagreements have come to these disagreements during<br>
conflict with people or organization of the church, which may have had<br>
nothing to do with the doctrine.<br>
<p>
I call to mind the experience of my SDA/ANC/agnostic/catholic/lesbian<br>
friend mentioned here previously.  Her discontent with the church began<br>
not with any doctrine, but with a reactionary pastor who wanted to keep <br>
blacks and women in their place in South Africa.  She first said that<br>
she assented mentally to the doctrines of the SDA church (else she wouldn't<br>
have been baptized at age 12 or whatever) but within 2 weeks of that time<br>
she said that she was doubting the existence of God altogether.<br>
<p>
She has now convinced herself that the Catholic church is much more friendly<br>
to the women's cause and the gay rights cause both.  (I think it's probably<br>
about a tie between Catholic and SDA in both of these categories).  This<br>
is what I mean by "grass is greener over the septic tank."  SDAnet<br>
subscribers who have been around for awhile saw one of our readers switch<br>
from Mormon-basher to Mormon, due mainly to cognitive dissonance.  We were <br>
also treated with a stellar picture about how LDS women have it  so good.<br>
<p>
What does this tell us?  It points out that if the written words of a<br>
doctrine fail to match up to the practice of the doctrine, people notice.<br>
This is a gut-level emotional reaction, which is the opposite of the <br>
initial reaction that comes with conviction of truth.  There can be a <br>
positive side for this, because it is frequently such a reaction that<br>
leads people to search out the SDA church.<br>
<p>
Thoughts?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
