<title>May_1993: Notes on the day of Pentecost</title>
<h1>Notes on the day of Pentecost</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 31 May 1993 23:00:45 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#308">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#308">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#308">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#308">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0309.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Re Homosexuality and the Bible"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0307.html">Steven Timm: "Cognitive Dissonance"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Since my organ teacher plays at two different churches (Episcopal<br>
and Catholic) I have had the opportunity to observe her on several<br>
occasions, and see a service while I am there.  I always leave these<br>
sessions with interesting ideas (to me at least):<br>
<p>
1)  There's precious little difference between Episcopals and Catholics.<br>
Still enough to make the Catholics call the Episcopals damnable heretics, <br>
(Episcopals break the wafer of bread as they consecrate it) but not much <br>
else.  I believe the word "Protestant" was struck from the title <br>
"Protestant Episcopal" some time ago.  (check me on this?)<br>
<p>
2)  Both find ways to involve young people as integral parts of the service.<br>
With all the crosses, candles, and whatnot to lug around, several acolytes<br>
and crucifers are needed.  In the Episcopal tradition, acolytes can be girls<br>
as well as boys, and a news item indicated that Catholics are thinking <br>
about allowing this, too.  What would an SDA service look like with two<br>
young people serving communion on either side of the pastor?  Couldn't hurt?<br>
Or is it pagan by definition because the Catholics do it?<br>
<p>
3)  You never have a first elder stumbling through an impromptu prayer<br>
because the order of prayer is always predetermined.  <br>
<p>
4)  On the con side, singing the same liturgy every week would get slightly<br>
boring.  But you do have to be on your toes to follow it all at first.<br>
There's no sitting back and sleeping for 40 minutes, participation is <br>
required every step of the way except during the 10-15 minute sermon.<br>
<p>
So how did the SDA form of worship become mostly like the Baptist liturgy?<br>
Baptists weren't prominent in the early SDA church, were they?<br>
Both denominations are so-called "spiritual experience" denominations<br>
which place large emphasis on preaching as opposed to corporate worship<br>
(and expect their ministers to uphold high moral standard).  That's<br>
all I can think.<br>
<p>
Is the SDA church service today more devoted to conveying information<br>
or to worship of God?  Are these mutually exclusive?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
