<title>Apr_1992: Let me see if I have this correct</title>
<h1>Let me see if I have this correct</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 16 Apr 1992 00:37:40 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#26">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#26">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#26">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#26">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Pharisees' Guide"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Evangelism in Russia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0033.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Scott Mattes writes:<br>
<i>&gt;  I am reading The Great Contraversy and wanted to see if my impressions</i><br>
<i>&gt;on what EGW is saying are 'correct'.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  1) There is no eternal punishment for the wicked.  So what happens to</i><br>
<i>&gt;them?</i><br>
<p>
The punishment of the wicked is eternal in effect but not in duration.<br>
The wicked burn up, and die, and that's it.  They cease to exist for<br>
all of eternity.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  2) After death there is no consciousness.  Where are our spirits after</i><br>
<i>&gt;we die?</i><br>
You need to understand the definition of spirit used here, quite different<br>
from the LDS definition or the mainstream Protestant definition.  <br>
What happens to the spirit is found in Ecclesiastes 12:7.<br>
Then shall the dust return to the earth as it was; and the spirit<br>
shall return to God who gave it.<br>
In the narrow sense of spirit it refers to the breath of life, the quantity<br>
of being alive.  We do not view the spirit as having a consciousness<br>
separate from the body.  Some writings of EGW refer to the spirit also <br>
as comprising our distinctive traits of character.  Think of it sort of <br>
as God's backup, and at the resurrection he restores our existence <br>
from the backup.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  3) I find it interesting that EGW acknowledges that we will be judged</i><br>
<i>&gt;by our works.</i><br>
Through selective quoting of EGW you can prove any position from legalism<br>
to antinomianism.  Can you give me a page reference so I can check the <br>
specific reference you refer to?  A judgment by works is indeed referred<br>
to in EGW and the Bible but no one would pass that judgement save for <br>
the grace and forgiveness of Christ.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  4) I also noticed a interesting contradition.  On page 491-2 she</i><br>
<i>&gt;quotes Gen 3:4-5 as satan's deception, yet in v 22 of the same chapter</i><br>
<i>&gt;God says exactly what satan said in v 5.  I assume that what she meant</i><br>
<i>&gt;was that the 'will not surely die' was the deception.</i><br>
<p>
That's correct:  the "ye shall not surely die" was the main part of <br>
the deception.  But we should also point out that while knowing good and <br>
evil is a small part of being like God, there are many other parts<br>
to which Adam and Eve did not attain by eating the fruit.  <br>
<p>
As for the easter bunny, he won't be over at my house on Sunday.<br>
I do think mainstream Christianity owes him an apology, however, for trying<br>
to steal his holiday.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
