<title>Apr_1992: Re: Pharisees' Guide</title>
<h1>Re: Pharisees' Guide</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 15 Apr 1992 23:40:54 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#27">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#27">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#27">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#27">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Eric Snyder: "After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Steven Timm: "Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0024.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Pharisees' Guide"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0029.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Pharisees' Guide"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Nancy's mention of Pharisees brings to mind a Jewish tradition I once <br>
heard.  It seems that the Pharisees believed that if one Sabbath was<br>
kept perfectly in Israel, the Messiah would come.  Has anyone else <br>
ever run across this tradition?<br>
<p>
More importantly, are 7th-Day Adventists guilty of the same thing at times?<br>
Is the fact that Christ has not yet come used as a guilt generator to spur<br>
church members into activity or giving money?  So often we hear that <br>
it is the fault of we, the members, that Christ hasn't come yet, and so <br>
we ought to support Radio Station X or Global Strategy Y, so the gospel <br>
can be preached and Christ can come.  <br>
<p>
Along the same line, we hear the I.K.I.I.E.G.W.S.* statement "When the <br>
character of Christ is fully reproduced in His people, then He will come <br>
to claim them as his own."  <br>
<p>
*I Know It's In EGW Somewhere<br>
<p>
I believe that statement and I believe that a loving and commandment-keeping<br>
people will be God's final and best witness in the last days.  I believe<br>
we have a long ways to go.   <br>
<p>
What I have trouble with is the idea that we can control God by our actions.<br>
There exist reasons why Christ has chosen not to come.  There exist no <br>
barriers that would stop Him from coming at any second He chose.<br>
Instead of pulling the blame on ourselves for it, or pushing it at others,<br>
we need to view God as the God who is in control and ready to help us<br>
finish the work that needs to be done.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
