<title>Apr_1992: Re: Evangelism in Russia</title>
<h1>Re: Evangelism in Russia</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 16 Apr 92 11:13:18 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#25">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#25">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#25">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#25">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Steven Timm: "Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Pharisees' Guide"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0012.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Evangelism in Russia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
	When we talk about non-active laymembers we generally do so without<br>
considering the reasons why they are not active. We like to simply put people <br>
and things in easy to manage boxes and just blame the members. However I don't <br>
think the problem can be set aside so easily. I have found that the reason<br>
why many members are inactive is not just they're own fault. Some times the<br>
leadership itself stifles action on part of the laymembers because they are<br>
afraid of loosing personal control. Othertimes the laymembers are reluctant<br>
to participate because they have never been encouraged and trained in how<br>
to work for Jesus. Most of the times however it is because the congregation<br>
has lost the fire and sense of mission due to too much compromise with the<br>
world, they can no longer see what Adventism has to offer the world and so <br>
there is no point in converting "already saved" christians from other <br>
denominations.<br>
<p>
	It is that most terrible of all scourges to afflict the church lately<br>
"the independant ministration" of each and every member which the church needs<br>
today. Maybe instead of looking at each other and blaming the other one<br>
for the problem we should be looking at ourselves and wondering whether we are<br>
the stumbling block in the way of permitting members to get up and do the work<br>
as God leads each and every one of us. God leads individuals personally and He <br>
will guide us too if we permit Him. God's leading is not limitted to the <br>
directions of any single person or organisation but promised to each of us <br>
personally.<br>
<p>
	Sometimes is seems that the only acceptable work for Jesus is that <br>
carried out the way I want it to under my direction. This simply is the <br>
way that prohibits God from working. In all my experience no matter how <br>
"active" a church may appear to be, it is only in those places where the <br>
leadership actually listens to God's word when He says that those who would<br>
be first must be the servant of all and not lord it over the lesser ones, and<br>
instead of placing themselves in positions of authority put themselves in <br>
positions of servitude that God's work is leaping forward.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
