<title>Apr_1992: Andrews University CAST brouhaha</title>
<h1>Andrews University CAST brouhaha</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  6 Apr 1992 10:19:15 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#3">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#3">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#3">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#3">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0004.html">Steven Timm: "Re: South African Votes &amp; SDA Race Relations"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0002.html">Paul Gates: "Re: SDA Race Relations"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To my surprise and amusement, I saw posted on the bulletin board at my church<br>
a letter "to whom it may concern" from W. Richard Lesher, president of <br>
Andrews University.<br>
<p>
Apparently there has been a major outcry against the artwork found in the <br>
student directory of Andrews University, the CAST.  Lesher described this<br>
as artwork containing religious themes, which some people have interpreted<br>
as an endorsement of Catholic theology.<br>
<p>
Lesher in his letter commends the editor for trying to portray a religious <br>
theme at all, and apologizes for the fact that the CAST sponsor was out of <br>
the country when the CAST went to press.  He conveys the students feeling <br>
that no specific theological message was meant by the artwork, that the<br>
editors were simply trying to emphasize that Andrews University is a <br>
religious institution.<br>
<p>
The fact that such a letter appears six months after the CAST comes out<br>
is a little surprising, usually such rumours travel around the globe much <br>
faster.  And again, whilst defending himself, Lesher has exposed the<br>
controversy to a much larger audience.<br>
<p>
The fact that none of our many correspondents at Andrews University has seen <br>
fit to mention this tempest in a salt shaker can give us some idea of the<br>
relative unimportance of this issue to daily life.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
