<title>Apr_1992: Re: South African Votes &amp; SDA Race Relations</title>
<h1>Re: South African Votes &amp; SDA Race Relations</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>20676LKC%MSU.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 07 Apr 92 13:34 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#4">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#4">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#4">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#4">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Steven Timm: "Good news and happy things"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Steven Timm: "Andrews University CAST brouhaha"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Just in response to your comment on interracial marriages, I have had</i><br>
<i>&gt; quite a few such couples as I have pastored in SDA churches. The problem</i><br>
<i>&gt; seems to be that some African Americans as well as whites will not accept</i><br>
<i>&gt; them. I knew of such a couple at Benton Harbor, MI. The white SDA church</i><br>
<i>&gt; would not accept them and perhaps might not have been willing to have</i><br>
<i>&gt; their membership in the church, not sure about that, the black church</i><br>
<i>&gt; really did not accept them either but did tolerate them. This was back in</i><br>
<i>&gt; the 70s. The other thing is that their children had a rough time being</i><br>
<i>&gt; accepted by their peers. Do you think this has changed here in the 90s?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &lt;&lt;Paul Gates&gt;&gt;</i><br>
 <br>
Well, pastor, it just so happens that I am originally from that area myself.<br>
I attended Edith B. Garrett SDA church school, which is attached to the white<br>
SDA church you speak of.  I also remember the episode you refer to - I<br>
attended church school and academy with the young White woman involved.<br>
Unfortunately it appears that not much has changed.  It is still very<br>
difficult for an interracially mixed couple to find a place, and they, more<br>
often than not, usually end up in an African American regional church.<br>
 <br>
In considering the race issue in the church both here and in South Africa, I<br>
am reminded of Dr. M.L. King's LETTER FROM BIRMINGHAM JAIL of April 16, 1963<br>
in which he addresses White moderate church members - "Things are different<br>
now. So often the contemporary church is a weak, ineffectual voice with an<br>
uncertain sound.  So often it is an archdefender of the status quo ...  But<br>
the judgment of God is upon the church as never before.  If today's church<br>
does not recapture the sacrificial spirit of the early church, it will lose<br>
its authenticity, forfeit the loyalty of millions, and be dismissed as an<br>
irrelevant social club with no meaning for the twentieth century ...<br>
   Perhaps I have once again been too optimistic.  Is organized religion too<br>
inextricably bound to the status quo to save our nation and the world?<br>
Perhaps I must turn my faith to the inner spiritual church, the church within<br>
the church, as the true 'ekklesia' and the hope of the world.  But again I am<br>
thankful to God that some noble souls from the ranks of organized religion<br>
have broken loose from the paralyzing chains of conformity and joined us as ac<br>
tive partners in the struggle for freedom.  They have left their secure<br>
congregations and walked the streets of Albany, Georgia, with us.  They have<br>
gone down the highways of the South on tortuous rides for freedom.  Yes, they<br>
have gone to jail with us.  Some have been dismissed from their churches, have<br>
lost the support of their bishops and fellow ministers.  But they have acted<br>
in the faith that right defeated is stronger than evil triumphant.  Their<br>
witness has been the spiritual salt that has preserved the true meaning of the<br>
gospel in these trouble times.  They have carved a tunnel of hope through the<br>
dark mountain of disappointment."<br>
 <br>
Those last few sentences, in particular, could apply quite readily to those<br>
church members in South Africa.  I admit this exerpt from Dr. King's letter<br>
adequately and eloquently sums up my attitudes about my struggle as an African<br>
American female to realize equality in America and, even more so, in the SDA<br>
church.<br>
 <br>
Just a further word of advice and encouragement, especially to those in South<br>
Africa.  Dr. King in his letter also addresses the concept of time, and a<br>
misconception about time where racial matters are concerned - "Actually, time<br>
itself is neutral, it can be used either destructively or constructively.<br>
More and more I feel that the people of ill will have used time more<br>
effectively than have the people of good will.  We will have to repent in this<br>
generation not merely for the hateful words and actions of bad people but for<br>
the APPALLING SILENCE OF THE GOOD PEOPLE.  Human progress never rolls in on<br>
wheels of inevitability; it comes through the tireless efforts of men [and<br>
women] willing to be co-workers with God, and without this hard work, time<br>
itself becomes an ally of the forces of social stagnation.  We must use time<br>
creatively, in the knowledge that the TIME IS ALWAYS RIPE TO DO RIGHT.  NOW IS<br>
THE TIME TO MAKE REAL THE PROMISE OF DEMOCRACY AND TRANSFORM OUR PENDING<br>
NATIONAL ELEGY INTO A CREATIVE PSALM OF BROTHERHOOD.  NOW IS THE TIME TO LIFT<br>
OUR NATIONAL POLICY FROM THE QUICKSAND OF RACIAL INJUSTICE TO THE SOLID ROCK<br>
OF HUMAN DIGNITY."  Emphasis my own.<br>
 <br>
Linda<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
