<title>Apr_1992: Evangelism in Russia</title>
<h1>Evangelism in Russia</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 11 Apr 92 21:21:03 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#12">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#12">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#12">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#12">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0013.html">Steven Timm: "Simplicity"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Just questions"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0005.html">Steven Timm: "Good news and happy things"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0016.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Evangelism in Russia"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
FYI<br>
<p>
Pastor Mark Finley is currently holding evangelistic meetings in Moscow.  In<br>
fact, the auditorium he is using is inside the Kremlin.  The attendance is<br>
about 13,000 for each day.  He is repeating the service three times in order<br>
to accomodate all who wish to attend.<br>
Not long ago a Protestant evangelist offered a free booklet to Russian listenersRequests came in for several million.<br>
Considering the expense of such a response, SDAs paid something like $3000 to a<br>
Moscow newspaper to print Steps to Christ--I believe--in several issues.  Next<br>
step: Pravda offered to print another book free.  This, as you may realize,<br>
happened several months back.<br>
<p>
When China closed about 1950, there were about 30,000 SDAs.  The figure last<br>
year was about 85,000.  When we visited China in 1986 one SDA pastor told about<br>
baptizing more people in one day than his pastor father had baptized in a life=<br>
time.  Almost all evangelism is done by laypersons, since there are very few<br>
pastors--most are quite old.  Some Chinese young people are being permitted<br>
our of the country to study for the ministry.  <br>
<p>
It would seem that in these places not having pastors simply puts the respon-<br>
sibility where it belongs: on the church members.  Maybe we have something to<br>
learn?<br>
<p>
Nancy Vyhmeister<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
