<title>Apr_1992: Simplicity</title>
<h1>Simplicity</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 12 Apr 1992 12:06:18 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#13">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#13">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#13">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#13">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Just questions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Evangelism in Russia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0015.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Challenge"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am faced next month with planning another one of our "Prime Time" programs<br>
for our youth here, our topic is "outreach."  Most likely we will come up <br>
with our usual mix of skits, slide shows, and speakers to convey some kind<br>
of message to these young people about why they should and how they can <br>
reach out to their friends.<br>
<p>
But this led me back to thinking about the days when I was that age<br>
(mid to late 1970's).  I remember how my dad would take me and a bunch <br>
of other kids and we would just go through the neighborhood passing out<br>
tracts.  Every fall we used to go Ingathering, for week after week.  <br>
Thing is, we liked doing it.  It was fun.  Nobody had to preach at us that<br>
we had to do it or that it was important, it was just "let's go."<br>
<p>
I have to confess I haven't done much ingathering lately, or passing out<br>
tracts.  And while I know there is much more to sharing your faith than that,<br>
these used to be the easy ways to do it.  Are we just too sophisticated now?<br>
Give me a handful of tracts and the Holy Spirit against the best thought-out<br>
strategy for evangelism there is, and the Holy Spirit will win every time.<br>
<p>
Of course, the Holy Spirit can bless the complicated as well as the simple.<br>
And we would be in a far worse state if we had neither the Holy Spirit nor<br>
a good strategy. <br>
<p>
Nancy Vyhmeister wonders out loud why we observe the greatest success in <br>
areas where there are fewer pastors.  I think it is not fair to say that<br>
pastors handicap the church or draw it back.  Pastors are not so much <br>
a handicap as they are a crutch, giving us the feeling that we are paying <br>
someone else to do the work of sharing.  Those pastors who enable their<br>
congregations to share on their own are the ones who enjoy the most<br>
success.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
