<title>Apr_1992: Challenge</title>
<h1>Challenge</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 13 Apr 92 10:04:02 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#15">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#15">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#15">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#15">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Evangelism in Russia"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Just questions"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0013.html">Steven Timm: "Simplicity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0020.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Challenge"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Timm's posting is challenging to all of us.  What would happen if...<br>
If we took the challenge of Matthew 28:19, 20 and Acts 1:8 seriously???<br>
<p>
On the other hand, a witness needs something to tell.  I think of the<br>
witness of the Samaritan woman--most effective.  And simple.  "Come,"<br>
she said, "see a man that told me everything I've done in life."  She<br>
had not acquired much theological baggage in the encounter with Jesus.<br>
She simply told what had happened to her.  Likewise, the demon-possessed<br>
Gadarenes, whose legion of devils had sent the pigs flying down the cliffs<br>
into the Sea of Galilee.  Jesus sent them to witness without even a set of<br>
Bible studies or the benefit of a series of meetings.  What could they<br>
tell?  I used to be devil possessed.  Now I am free!  Jesus did it!<br>
<p>
Perhaps we have a problem in that we don't have a great story to tell.<br>
If people around me see that because I am a Christian I am more truthful,<br>
more loyal, more caring, I've got the beginning of witness.   Trouble<br>
might be that there is no visible difference....  <br>
<p>
I don't say this because I have "arrived."  No, I am a pilgrim, on the<br>
way, always becoming.  But the pilgrimage is exciting, if not exactly<br>
easy.  <br>
<p>
Yours for more witnesses,<br>
<p>
Nancy Vyhmeister<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
