<title>Apr_1992: Re: Evangelism in Russia</title>
<h1>Re: Evangelism in Russia</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 13 Apr 92 07:05:06 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#16">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#16">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#16">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#16">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "LAYMEN AND WOMEN!"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0015.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Challenge"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0012.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Evangelism in Russia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0017.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "LAYMEN AND WOMEN!"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; . . .</i><br>
<i>&gt; time.  Almost all evangelism is done by laypersons, since there are very few</i><br>
<i>&gt; . . . .</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; It would seem that in these places not having pastors simply puts the respon-</i><br>
<i>&gt; sibility where it belongs: on the church members.  Maybe we have something to</i><br>
<i>&gt; learn?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Nancy Vyhmeister</i><br>
<p>
Amen!  Amen!<br>
I've seen it happen over here.  Since I've told the story a few times on<br>
SDAnet I'll not go into it again.  Simply that a church I was closely<br>
acquainted with went from the doldrums to rapidly growing when the<br>
laymen got tired of waiting for the pastor to take the lead and took<br>
charge themselves.<br>
<p>
So, absolutely, its the best thing that can happen to a church when<br>
the laymen gecome active.  Now of course, the pastor can assume a vital<br>
role in activating the laymen.  Either way, whether by lay leadership<br>
and/or pastoral leadership, activated laymen make a tremendously big<br>
difference.  Given the choice -- activated laymen vs an active pastor,<br>
I'll go for the church with the involved laymen.  Any day.  And I mean<br>
no reflection on pastors when I say that.<br>
<p>
Thanks Nancy for your story!<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
