Nancy writes:<br>
<p>
On the other hand, a witness needs something to tell.<br>
[text deleted]<br>
Perhaps we have a problem in that we don't have a great story to tell.<br>
<p>
Yours for more witnesses,<br>
<p>
Nancy Vyhmeister<br>
________________<br>
<p>
May I say that as Christians, we have the greatest story to tell.<br>
Often, a difficulty is that some feel that if they don't have a<br>
personal experience to express, then they don't have anything<br>
to say.  That is sad.  We can tell about the woman at the well,<br>
about a demon-possessed man named Legion, about Moses and the<br>
prophets; and we can tell about a God named Jesus.<br>
<p>
Take a look at Luke 16:27-31.  Lazarus wanted someone with a<br>
great story to tell (returning from the dead) to go witness to<br>
his five brothers.  Abraham replied, "They have Moses and the<br>
prophets; let them hear them....If they hear not Moses and the<br>
prophets, neither will they be persuaded, if one rise from the<br>
dead."<br>
<p>
Yours also for more witnesses,<br>
<p>
Dan Blake<br>
dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com<br>
