<title>Apr_1992: Re: Simplicity</title>
<h1>Re: Simplicity</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>15 Apr 92 10:44:51 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#21">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#21">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#21">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#21">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Scott Mattes: "Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0020.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Challenge"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0013.html">Steven Timm: "Simplicity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve, I do not think we are more sophisicated. We have just found more<br>
cost effective ways of doing things. The ministry as well as a lot of<br>
other professions have changed in the last 35 years for example.<br>
<p>
In the last 2 weeks we have given the Spiritual Gifts evaluation in both<br>
of our churches. It has been very revealing not only to the pastor but to<br>
the congregations. Our next step is to help the people to develop their<br>
gifts and apply them to ministry.<br>
<p>
2 others things we are doing is : begin small group meetings weekly in<br>
strategic homes. The other thing is refining a survey that I used in<br>
Michigan. --- asking some of the traditional questions but also gathering<br>
info on what people would like to see in a church -- the type of<br>
ministries they would like to see and support. Then after that info is<br>
tabulated -- designing those ministries as we can use them. Print a<br>
brochure explaining our services and going back to those same people and<br>
inviting them to our services. We will begin small  -- like just<br>
contacting the neighbors in the area of our churches.<br>
<p>
I like what the Kettering, Ohio church is doing. Their church is a focal<br>
point for community activities. The New Hope church in Burtonsville, MD is<br>
doing the same type of thing.<br>
<p>
I want to eventually develop a program in both of our churches where we<br>
will have multiple seminars, workshops going on at the same time. We will<br>
have Bible oriented seminars but also for example, seminars and workshops<br>
on small engine repair, CPR classes, Parenting, and a "whole slew" of<br>
other things. This includes support groups for families of suicides, Grief<br>
Control, Singles and Single parents.  What has happened before is we also<br>
get non adventist volunteers who volunteer to teach some of the classes<br>
and/or they have expertise in other areas and can teach classes or<br>
seminars as well as our church members. I also know of junior age youth<br>
who can participate and teach for instance "kite making" etc and get all<br>
of their "peer" friends to VBS.<br>
<p>
This kind of a program, Steve will work and will break down a lot of pre-<br>
conceived ideas about Adventism and will get people from the community<br>
involved. Most people are curious about what Adventists believe and why. A<br>
wonderful opportunity to share the Gospel -- I said the Gospel -- not so<br>
much the Sabbath important as it is, but reveal the Lord of the Sabbath!<br>
<p>
Incidently Steve, I have a new visitor registration form that we are using<br>
in both of our churches on Sabbath. It gives us a lot more information<br>
than just their name and from what city. We are going to use those names<br>
to share literature, etc rather than the traditional "broadcasting" of<br>
literature. Why waste precious time giving literature to people who aren't<br>
interested in the first place when you can share with people who were<br>
interested enough to come and visit your church?<br>
<p>
The above are a few of the ideas that are fresh on my mind this AM. What<br>
do you think?  Perhaps you can understand now why I am saying that if a<br>
congregation are "do nothings" I am going to move on eventually to a<br>
congregation than has or will get the vision. Of course I realize a lot of<br>
responsibility rests on my shoulders to challenge the people.<br>
<p>
Paul<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
