<title>Apr_1992: Let me see if I have this correct</title>
<h1>Let me see if I have this correct</h1>
Scott Mattes (<i>COTRSSM@sea04vm.navsea.navy.mil</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 15 Apr 92 11:34:31 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#22">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#22">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#22">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#22">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Farewell to SDAnet"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Simplicity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
  I am reading The Great Contraversy and wanted to see if my impressions<br>
on what EGW is saying are 'correct'.<br>
<p>
  1) There is no eternal punishment for the wicked.  So what happens to<br>
them?<br>
<p>
  2) After death there is no consciousness.  Where are our spirits after<br>
we die?<br>
<p>
  3) I find it interesting that EGW acknowledges that we will be judged<br>
by our works.<br>
<p>
  4) I also noticed a interesting contradition.  On page 491-2 she<br>
quotes Gen 3:4-5 as satan's deception, yet in v 22 of the same chapter<br>
God says exactly what satan said in v 5.  I assume that what she meant<br>
was that the 'will not surely die' was the deception.<br>
<p>
  Next week I go back to riding the bus daily so will have more time to<br>
delve into this and other books.<br>
<p>
  Unofficial poll: how many are having the easter bunny over on Sunday?<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
