<title>Apr_1992: Farewell to SDAnet</title>
<h1>Farewell to SDAnet</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 15 Apr 1992 07:59 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#23">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#23">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#23">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#23">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Pharisees' Guide"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Scott Mattes: "Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dear SDAnetters,<br>
<p>
I have been a subscriber to SDAnet for a year now and have <br>
enjoyed the  discussions and interchange.  At times I have <br>
been an active participant  and at other times a silent <br>
listener.  My program at the University of  Utah will be <br>
finished very soon now and May 23 I will participate in  <br>
Commencement exercises and receive my hard-earned Ph.D.  The <br>
next 30 days will be exceedingly busy for me, but also an <br>
exciting time for me.  So far I have made trips to Columbus, <br>
Ohio and Houston, Texas for job  interviews.  The next three <br>
weeks I will visit Mobile, Alabama; Milwaukee,  Wisconsin; <br>
St. Paul, Minnesota, and perhaps Ann Arbor, Michigan.  <br>
Hopefully I will land my first career position among these <br>
prospects.<br>
<p>
I have been greatly blessed spiritually through SDAnet and <br>
want to thank each one of you for your participation.  I also <br>
want to thank those who have on occasion sent me personal <br>
messages.  This past year has been a period of spiritual <br>
growth and renewal for me and I thank each one of you who may <br>
have had played a role in this.<br>
<p>
As some of you know (and it may have been obvious to others), <br>
I have also struggled with deep doubts about my SDA faith.  I <br>
was born and raised a 4th-generation Adventist, but I left <br>
the church in my early twenties.  As the result of a severe <br>
car accident in 1980, I was rebaptized into the church <br>
through the loving efforts of my orthopedic surgeon (who <br>
happens to be related to the Vyhmeister's at Andrews <br>
University).  I was happy and active in the SDA church until <br>
I suffered a terrible misfortune at the  hands of an SDA <br>
employer which left me bankrupt and unable to be gainfully  <br>
employed.  I lost everything I owned including my home, my <br>
health, and a reason to live.  Mercifully, God spared my life <br>
after I made a serious suicide attempt in 1983 following this <br>
agonizing experience.  Finally, I moved on with my life and <br>
started graduate school and earned a masters degree in <br>
computer science.  Then I moved to Utah to pursue my Ph.D.  <br>
But my life in the SDA church was never to be the same again.<br>
<p>
I never really understood and may never totally understand <br>
why I had to suffer so much at the hands of the SDA church.  <br>
Until recently, I doubted that any good would ever come out <br>
of it.  Now I can testify that good did come from this <br>
disaster for me personally.  This disaster may have been the <br>
only way for me to be open to believe in God's true church.  <br>
Last summer I had the privilege of studying with two <br>
beautiful young ladies who were serving full-time missions <br>
for the LDS church.  They put their education on hold to <br>
serve their church at their own expense.  During the ensuing <br>
six months, I studied diligently, thirsty for truth and <br>
hungry for the true love of Christ in my life.  On November <br>
14, 1991, I was baptized into The Church of Jesus Christ of <br>
Latter-Day Saints<br>
<p>
I have found peace and great spiritual truths which give my <br>
life real meaning now.  I am not a guinea pig down here on <br>
this sinful earth, a victim of the war in heaven.  Rather I <br>
am a child of my Heavenly Father who cares deeply about my <br>
eternal progress and my sojourn on this earth.  My life on <br>
this earth is an opportunity for growth--to become more like <br>
my Father in Heaven-physically, spiritually, and mentally.  <br>
The sacrifice of Jesus Christ has made it possible for me to <br>
return to my Heavenly Father and live once again in His holy <br>
presence.  For this, I am most grateful.<br>
<p>
If any of you have any comments or questions, I encourage you <br>
to respond to me personally.  I will have this email account<br>
for one more month.<br>
<p>
<p>
Cheryl Berthelsen<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
