<title>Apr_1992: After Death - Soul/Spirit</title>
<h1>After Death - Soul/Spirit</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 16 Apr 1992 14:06:00 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#28">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#28">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#28">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#28">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Pharisees' Guide"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Pharisees' Guide"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0032.html">Dave: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[The words of Eric Snyder]<br>
       If my study on this is correct, the SDA position is basically<br>
     the same as the Jehovah's Witnesses.  That after death, there is<br>
     no immaterial part that survives.  Only after the Resurrection,<br>
     will the entire person be brought back.  At that time, the wicked<br>
     will be Annialated.  The righteous will be given eternal life.<br>
[The end effect is quite the same for SDA and JW.  However, the setting of <br>
eschatology in which it occurs is quite different.  SDA beliefs were <br>
certainly known to Charles Russell, founder of JW's, and it is likely <br>
he borrowed this idea.  SCT]<br>
<p>
 <br>
       I have to admit.  I have thought a lot about this issue and have<br>
     come to some conclusions.  Our Church, would not teach annialationism.<br>
     As far as there being a Soul/Spirit that survives death, I believe the<br>
     honest SDA or Evangelical would need to admit that there are<br>
     Scriptures supporting both positions.  What about the Luke 16 parable<br>
     about Lazurus and the Rich man.  Yes I realize that it was a parable,<br>
     but would Jesus use an untruthful example to teach ?  Also, Paul states<br>
     that to be absent from the body is to be with the Lord.  Do you not get<br>
     a sense that Paul considers his body like a "shell"?  I have also spent<br>
     time discussing the Luke 23:43 passage with the Jehovah's Witnesses.<br>
     The difference is the placement of the comma, of which I believe in the<br>
     original Greek was not present.  If the comma is before the word today<br>
     than, Jesus is telling the thief that even though he is about to die,<br>
     the thief will see Jesus that day in a much better place called paradise.<br>
     On the other hand, if you place the comma "after" the word "today", it<br>
     means that Jesus is emphasizing His point by stating that he is telling<br>
     the thief on that day.<br>
         There are many other passages that I believe that could be used to<br>
     argue both sides.....I am certainly open to discuss this with anyone<br>
     further......<br>
 <br>
     Eric Snyder<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
