<title>Apr_1992: More Good News and Happy Things</title>
<h1>More Good News and Happy Things</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 16 Apr 1992 14:32:26 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: More Good News and Happy Things"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Pharisees' Guide"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0031.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: More Good News and Happy Things"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I continue the series of good trends I see happening in the church.<br>
I focus on the phenomenon of Seventh-day Adventists becoming more<br>
well-recognized in the world at large, and giving of themselves in the <br>
process.  There are many we could name.<br>
<p>
In the realm of politics, we have seen an Adventist prime minister<br>
in Uganda (so what if he came to power in a revolution) Dr. Kisekka.<br>
In Jamaica there have been several cabinet ministers who were SDA.<br>
There is an Adventist president of the quasi-independent Pacific <br>
island of Palau.  As more SDA's become involved in politics and working <br>
for justice, we are in a sense returning to the spirit of the early <br>
movement, which was strongly anti-slavery, non-combatant, and<br>
pro-temperance, as well as strong fighters for religious liberty.<br>
<p>
In the performing arts, SDA's now inhabit all venues from jazz to CCM <br>
to classical.  Herbert Blomstedt of the San Francisco symphony<br>
has led other SDA professional musicians to set their sights higher.<br>
Take 6 has won several Grammy awards in the gospel/jazz arena.<br>
And while names like Patty Cabrera, Bret Barry, Tom Prasada-Rao,<br>
and Ann Trubey aren't household words in the Christian music industry as yet,<br>
they are out there and selling enough records to live, with wider<br>
distribution than (practicing) SDA artists have had before.  Of course<br>
we shouldn't forget Clifton Davis who makes a career both as a singer<br>
and as an actor.<br>
<p>
In the health area members of our church are also gaining recognition,<br>
and none more so than Dr. Ben Carson of Johns Hopkins Univ., the<br>
pediatric neurosurgeon.  His books have a wide circulation in mainstream<br>
and Christian bookstores alike.<br>
<p>
I'm excited enough that Adventists are starting to come out of the salt<br>
shaker and spread out to the world, that I won't dwell on our tendency<br>
to hero-worship anyone within our church that becomes famous.  We won't<br>
stress that so many churches asked Ben Carson to speak that it was hurting<br>
his work and his department now demands a $1000 speaking fee whenever<br>
he gives a talk.  People coming out of their shells is the beginning of <br>
an alive and vibrant post-institutional Adventism, and it's something we<br>
will need a lot more of in future.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
