<title>Apr_1992: Home schooling and the Moores</title>
<h1>Home schooling and the Moores</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 17 Apr 1992 12:22:31 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#36">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#36">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#36">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#36">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: More Good News and Happy Things"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0039.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Home schooling and the Moores"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have not read Dr. Moore's book on home schooling, so I am out of step in <br>
questioning the utility of his work.  I retract my statement.<br>
<p>
If there is any problem with home schooling, it's more likely in the <br>
implementation of techniques rather than in home schooling itself. <br>
Some of the kindest,skilled, and well-rounded friends I have were home<br>
schooled at young ages.  I have seen families brought into the church<br>
as a result of contacts our church has with home schoolers.<br>
<p>
By the same token, I have seen churches split over the the issue of home<br>
schooling, and I have seen children emotionally scarred for life by such<br>
experiences.  The problem exists in that there is a certain class<br>
of emotionally misadjusted parents who are more likely to home school <br>
their children when the best thing for the kid would be to get away <br>
from the house.<br>
<p>
(The same category applies to some parents who choose to start their <br>
children late to school.)<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<p>
<p>
(To be fair, we have to say that Jesus himself was home-schooled.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
