<i>&gt;........... stuff deleted .........</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;  3) I find it interesting that EGW acknowledges that we will be judged</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;by our works.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Through selective quoting of EGW you can prove any position from legalism</i><br>
<i>&gt;to antinomianism.  Can you give me a page reference so I can check the</i><br>
<i>&gt;specific reference you refer to?  A judgment by works is indeed referred</i><br>
<i>&gt;to in EGW and the Bible but no one would pass that judgement save for</i><br>
<i>&gt;the grace and forgiveness of Christ.</i><br>
<p>
  Yup, and by selective quoting you can 'prove' that the Book of Mormon<br>
teaches polygny is a sin :).<br>
<p>
  I, and my church, agree that without Christ our good works are for<br>
naught.  And I and my church agree with EGW (or, in chronological order,<br>
EGW agrees with my church and I agree with them) that faith without<br>
works is dead.<br>
<p>
  Here are some snipets from Steps to Christ (1981 addition, interesting<br>
note, in the forward by the 'trustees of the EGW publications' she is<br>
listed as a 'religious speaker and writer');<br>
<p>
page 21, last full paragraph;<br>
  "Oh, let us comtemplate the amazing sacrifice that has been made for<br>
us!  Let us try to appreciate the labor and energy that Heaven is<br>
expending to recalaim the lost, and bring them back to the Father's<br>
house.  Motives stronger, and agencies more powerful, could never be<br>
brought into operation; the exceeding rewards to right-doing, the<br>
enjoyment of heaven, the society of the angels, the communion and love<br>
of God and His Son, the elevation and extension of all our powers<br>
throughout eternal ages--are these not mighty incentives and<br>
encouragements to urge us to give the heart's loving service to our<br>
Creator and Redeemer?"<br>
<p>
pg 60, first full paragraph, and then pg 61 second paragraph;<br>
  "The opposite and no less dangerous error is that belief in Christ<br>
releases men from keeping the law of God; that since by faith alone we<br>
become partakers of the grace of Christ, our works have nothing to do<br>
with our redemption."<br>
<p>
  "That so-called faith in Christ which professes to release men from<br>
the obligation of obedience to God, is not faith, but presumption.  'By<br>
grace are ye saved through faith.' But 'faith, if it hath not works, is<br>
dead.'"<br>
<p>
pg 80, last part of second paragraph on over to pg 81;<br>
  "Those who thus devote themselves to unselfish effort for the good of<br>
others are most surely working out their own salvation.<br>
<p>
  The only way to grow in grace is to be disinterestedly doing the very<br>
work which Christ has enjoined upon us--to engage, to the extent of our<br>
ability, in helping and blessing those who need the help we can give<br>
them.  Strength comes by exercise;<br>
<p>
  ...........  Some not typed, I am getting tired ..........<br>
<p>
  Thus the Christian who will not exercise his God-given powers not only<br>
fails to grow up into Christ, but he loses the strength that he already<br>
had."<br>
<p>
pg 122, part of second full paragraph;<br>
  "Do all you can on your part to bring about favorable results.  Jesus<br>
has promised His aid, but not apart from our effort.  When, relying upon<br>
our Helper, you have done all you can, accept the result cheerfully."<br>
<p>
  Well, did I get it out of context?<br>
<p>
  Thanks for the books R!<br>
