<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Subject: Home schooling and the Moores</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I have not read Dr. Moore's book on home schooling, so I am out of step in </i><br>
<i>&gt;questioning the utility of his work.  I retract my statement.</i><br>
<p>
I thank you for doing this.  My wife and I are home schooling our two <br>
pre-schoolers.  We examined the various home school offerings and found<br>
the Moores to follow closer to the Spirit of Prophecy recommendations<br>
than anyone else.<br>
<p>
I do hope that this network can avoid character assassination because of<br>
what someone has heard or thought they have heard.  There is enough of <br>
this going on in the church and outside the church.  We do not, as good<br>
disciples of Christ, follow in the world's footsteps.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;If there is any problem with home schooling, it's more likely in the </i><br>
<i>&gt;implementation of techniques rather than in home schooling itself. </i><br>
<i>&gt;Some of the kindest,skilled, and well-rounded friends I have were home</i><br>
<i>&gt;schooled at young ages.  I have seen families brought into the church</i><br>
<i>&gt;as a result of contacts our church has with home schoolers.</i><br>
<p>
It really does depend a lot on the curriculum offered and the dedication of<br>
the parents.  If the dedication is not there, the absolute willingness to<br>
devote the time to your children, DO NOT HOME SCHOOL.  This is a sacrifice of<br>
time and effort for both parents.  It means actually coming to know and<br>
experience your children's lives.  This is not easy with most of our<br>
upbringing today.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;By the same token, I have seen churches split over the the issue of home</i><br>
<i>&gt;schooling, and I have seen children emotionally scarred for life by such</i><br>
<i>&gt;experiences.  The problem exists in that there is a certain class</i><br>
<i>&gt;of emotionally misadjusted parents who are more likely to home school </i><br>
<i>&gt;their children when the best thing for the kid would be to get away </i><br>
<i>&gt;from the house.</i><br>
<p>
While you may have seen a few who are emotionally scarred, I would daresay<br>
that quite often our own schools don't do much better.  While the problem<br>
exists of certain parents who should not home-school, it really is a question<br>
of parenting and our desire to control.  I could also talk about teachers<br>
who could very easily leave scars on students.  Branding them "trouble-makers"<br>
or teaching them with such a STRICT discipline that they believe all people<br>
are like this.<br>
<p>
It is easy to talk about the exceptions.  Especially without the numbers or<br>
personal experience (not saying you don't have it Steve, just making note..:)<br>
with either type of schooling.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;(The same category applies to some parents who choose to start their </i><br>
<i>&gt;children late to school.)</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;(To be fair, we have to say that Jesus himself was home-schooled.  SCT]</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
Yes, we actually do.  Quite a few of our leaders in this country were home<br>
or self schooled.  :-)<br>
<p>
Russell Grau<br>
