<title>Apr_1992: Re: Anyone have a bio on EGW?</title>
<h1>Re: Anyone have a bio on EGW?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 20 Apr 1992 11:14:11 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#44">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#44">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#44">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#44">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Steve Hix: "Re:  Home schooling and the Moores"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Russell Grau: "Re:  Home schooling and the Moores"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0041.html">Scott Mattes: "Anyone have a bio on EGW?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0058.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Anyone have a bio on EGW?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In quick response to Scott's questions:<br>
Ellen White born as Ellen Harmon 1827, Portland, Maine,  died 1915<br>
Married James White, 1845.  Had four sons, two died in childhood.<br>
Shortly after "Great Disappointment" of Millerites in 1844, she <br>
received her first vision.  <br>
<p>
A small portion of Millerites believed that the sanctuary of Daniel 8:14<br>
that was to be cleansed was not this earth, but the heavenly sanctuary.<br>
This group met across New England for a series of Bible conferences in the <br>
next few years, forming the core set of beliefs which form Adventism today.<br>
The doctrines were discovered through hard Bible study, and then often Ellen<br>
would be shown a vision confirming the truth <br>
They came to realize that the door of mercy was not closed to those who <br>
had not believed in 1844, and started publishing a missionary paper.<br>
In the mid-1850's they moved west to Battle Creek, Michigan, and opened <br>
a new press.  The name "Seventh-day Adventists" was chosen in 1860,<br>
and the General Conference was organized in 1863.<br>
<p>
Ellen White's background was as a Methodist, as was John Byington, first<br>
church president.  James White had been a preacher in the Christian<br>
Connection before he became involved in the Millerite movement.<br>
During the Millerite movement many of them were disfellowshipped from the <br>
mainstream denominations which rejected it, and others left voluntarily.<br>
<p>
After the organization of the church, Ellen White's vision turned to <br>
giving guidance for the growing church in matters of publishing, health<br>
reform, and education.  Her husband died in 1881, after which she traveled<br>
to Europe and Australia in missionary work, working all the time on her <br>
writings.  Her later works focus more on devotional topics and the life of <br>
Christ, and the theme of the controversy between Christ and Satan.<br>
<p>
As to what Ellen White claimed for herself, and what others claimed for her,<br>
that's a discussion we have never had directly on SDAnet but probably should.<br>
I'll say more on that in another post.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
