<title>Apr_1992: Home Schooling</title>
<h1>Home Schooling</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 20 Apr 92 13:38:43 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#47">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#47">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#47">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#47">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0046.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: The real good news!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
We did home schooling one year.  Should give my wife credit for carrying<br>
the brunt of it.  She was not completely satisfied with what any single<br>
home school program offered.  So, she gleaned text books and ideas from<br>
all of them.  She has no formal teacher training.  Yet, where our boys<br>
had been mediocre before, they returned to school the following year<br>
to quickly find themselves at the top of their respective classes.  And<br>
to top that there was some serious consideration of having them skip<br>
a grade as they were running circles around their peers.  PS, our<br>
neighbor was the principle of the local public school.  It was soon<br>
enough obvious we were home schooling.  No problems from him.  But we<br>
did have a retired pastor who objected vigorously.  He claimed EGW<br>
basis for his objections (bogus).  I think his un-announced agenda was<br>
that it resulted in less support for the church's elementary school.<br>
We were being less than loyal to one of the church's programs.<br>
<p>
On the radio I heard of a case where the local public school objected<br>
to a certain girl being home schooled.  I think she was in the 4th<br>
grade.  The public school insisted on testing her, threatening that<br>
if she was deficient in any areas, she would have to go to public<br>
school.  After the testing they insisted she was performing at the<br>
6th grade level and that the family would have to send their daughter<br>
to public school so she could be put on an acceleration program to get<br>
her to the 6th grade, instead of leaving her to languish at the 4th<br>
grade level.  Fortunately the public school lost the argument.<br>
<p>
Another family home schooled their children through 12th grade, sending<br>
them to college "to get accreditation for what they had learned".  The<br>
biggest problem each of them had in college was that it was way too<br>
easy and not enough of a challenge.  All too often I hear of students<br>
who did very well in high school who come close to flunking out when<br>
the find college too tough for them.<br>
<p>
My experience -- when parents take home schooling<br>
seriously, their children benefit over what they would have in school.<br>
And of course there are horror stories of negligent parents and<br>
probably of over bearing dictatorial autocrats.<br>
<p>
One author of a home schooling book being interviewed on the radio<br>
as I was driving along said that teachers in public have such an<br>
overhead of large classes and volumes of busywork paper work that there<br>
is no way that even the best of teachers can do an adequate job.  They<br>
are simply too bogged down in administrivia to be able to really<br>
attend to their students.  Hence, the chances that a parent(s) can<br>
outperform even the best of elementary school teachers is really<br>
very good.<br>
<p>
If you have the time and energy to do home schooling, I highly recommend<br>
it.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
