<title>Apr_1992: Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit</title>
<h1>Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 21 Apr 92 13:07:41 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#48">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#48">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#48">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#48">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0049.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: More Good News and Happy Things"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Dave Buxton: "Home Schooling"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0028.html">Eric Snyder: "After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0057.html">Bob Moynihan: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi All<br>
<p>
Eric writes:<br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<i>&gt;        I have to admit.  I have thought a lot about this issue and have</i><br>
<i>&gt;      come to some conclusions.  Our Church, would not teach annialationism.</i><br>
<i>&gt;      As far as there being a Soul/Spirit that survives death, I believe the</i><br>
<i>&gt;      honest SDA or Evangelical would need to admit that there are</i><br>
<i>&gt;      Scriptures supporting both positions.  What about the Luke 16 parable</i><br>
<i>&gt;      about Lazurus and the Rich man.  Yes I realize that it was a parable,</i><br>
<p>
Well Eric I don't believe that the Parable of rich man and Lazarus <br>
contributes anything at all to our understanding about what happens at <br>
death because the entire thing is clearly metaphorical. These are my reasons :<br>
<p>
<p>
This is one of a series of parables: Mustard seed, leaven (Luke 13). <br>
Great supper,<br>
salt with no savor, (Luke 14). Lost sheep, piece of silver, prodigal son<br>
(Luke 15) Unjust stewart, rich man an Lazarus (Luke 16)<br>
<p>
It can not be a literal description of the condition of man after<br>
death because :<br>
<p>
        "Abraham's bosom" is figurative, not literal.<br>
        "One drop of water" is not enough to cool man in hell.<br>
        "People talk back and forth - heaven and hell are not so near.<br>
        Sinners are not punished until the day of judgment :<br>
<p>
<p>
2 Pet 2:9 The Lord knoweth how to deliver the godly out of temptations, and to<br>
          reserve the unjust unto the day of judgment to be punished: (KJV)<br>
<p>
The righteous are not rewarded until the resurrection at the <br>
second coming of Christ:<br>
        <br>
John 5:28 Marvel not at this: for the hour is coming, in the which all that<br>
          are in the graves shall hear his voice, (KJV)<br>
John 5:29 And shall come forth; they that have done good, unto the<br>
          resurrection of life; and they that have done evil, unto the<br>
          resurrection of damnation. (KJV)<br>
Rev 22:12 And, behold, I come quickly; and my reward is with me, to give every<br>
          man according as his work shall be. (KJV)<br>
<p>
 The dead are not conscious :<br>
<p>
Ps 146:3 Put not your trust in princes, nor in the son of man, in whom there<br>
         is no help. (KJV)<br>
Ps 146:4 His breath goeth forth, he returneth to his earth; in that very day<br>
         his thoughts perish. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Ecc 9:5 For the living know that they shall die: but the dead know not any<br>
        thing, neither have they any more a reward; for the memory of them is<br>
        forgotten. (KJV)<br>
Ecc 9:6 Also their love, and their hatred, and their envy, is now perished;<br>
        neither have they any more a portion for ever in any thing that is<br>
        done under the sun. (KJV)<br>
Ecc 9:10 Whatsoever thy hand findeth to do, do it with thy might; for there is<br>
         no work, nor device, nor knowledge, nor wisdom, in the grave, whither<br>
         thou goest. (KJV)<br>
<p>
The teaching of the parable is that in this life we settle our eternal destiny<br>
AFter death, the great gulf is fixed. No man is valued merely for his <br>
possessions.<br>
<p>
So If you wish to accept that this parable actually teaches us regarding the<br>
state of the dead you must also accept that each one of those 4 figurative<br>
statements I presented at the beginning to be also literally true. This<br>
can not be because hold them to be true violates various clear teachings<br>
with regard to the reward of the righteous.<br>
<p>
I don't know if you are aware Eric but many of the reformers did not <br>
believe in a consious state after death. For example we have <br>
<p>
<p>
William Tyndale (1484-1536), English Bible translator and Martyr.<br>
John Frith (1503-33), associate of Tyndale and fellow martyr.<br>
Martin Luther (1493-1546) German reformer and Bible Translator.<br>
George Wishart (1500-1546), Greek scholar, friend of Latimer, tutor of<br>
		John Knox, and martyr.<br>
Samuel Richardson (1633-1658) pastor, First Particular Baptist Church<br>
		of London<br>
John Milton (1608-1674), "Greatest of the Sacred Poets"; <br>
<p>
just to name a few.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;      but would Jesus use an untruthful example to teach ?  Also, Paul states</i><br>
<p>
Well does, the parable of the 10 virgins teach us that polygamy is acceptable ?<br>
I believe that Jesus method was similar in both these occasions He used<br>
examples which the people could identify with at the time and used them<br>
not as being central to the teaching but as an aid, the parable about the <br>
10 virgins teaches us nothing about marrige but it does teach us about<br>
the Lords coming. The concept of consiousness after death was a very commonly<br>
accepted idea at the time, thanks to the Hellenistic influences at work<br>
at the time in Israel, Hellenism or Greek paganism holds as a central tennet<br>
the immortality of the soul.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;      that to be absent from the body is to be with the Lord.  Do you not get</i><br>
<i>&gt;      a sense that Paul considers his body like a "shell"?  </i><br>
<p>
I believe this refers to Pauls experience when He was "out of his body" and<br>
in the third heaven in vision with God seeing and hearing things unlawful for<br>
a man to utter. A bit like when John the Revelator was taken in vision<br>
to heaven, his body remained here but he was not in his body he was in heaven<br>
being shown the mysteries of God. For both of these men these out of body<br>
experiences occured during there lives, not after their deaths. <br>
<p>
The concept of the body being a only shell comes from Greek Paganism, and <br>
Plato, which taught this concept very clearly and not from the bible.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;I have also spent</i><br>
<i>&gt;      time discussing the Luke 23:43 passage with the Jehovah's Witnesses.</i><br>
<i>&gt;      The difference is the placement of the comma, of which I believe in the</i><br>
<i>&gt;      original Greek was not present.  If the comma is before the word today</i><br>
<i>&gt;      than, Jesus is telling the thief that even though he is about to die,</i><br>
<i>&gt;      the thief will see Jesus that day in a much better place called paradise.</i><br>
<i>&gt;      On the other hand, if you place the comma "after" the word "today", it</i><br>
<i>&gt;      means that Jesus is emphasizing His point by stating that he is telling</i><br>
<i>&gt;      the thief on that day.</i><br>
<p>
Well the problem that arrises with this interpretation (there is no punctuation<br>
in Greek) is that then Jesus must have also been in heaven with the theif<br>
however we know for a fact because Jesus told us himself that He was not <br>
to be in heaven but in the tomb for 3 days, after the three days Jesus<br>
himself announced to Mary that He HAD NOT ascended up to His father<br>
( in paradise obviously ) yet and that He was to do so, this day was Sunday.<br>
So Jesus must have been lying to the thief because Jesus was definitively not<br>
in heaven until 3 days after He had promised the thief (according to this<br>
interpretation) that He would be there. So that It cannot be that Jesus<br>
promised the thief that he would be together with Jesus in paradise on the <br>
Friday because he wasn't. Only the other interpretation is viable.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;          There are many other passages that I believe that could be used to</i><br>
<i>&gt;      argue both sides.....I am certainly open to discuss this with anyone</i><br>
<i>&gt;      further......</i><br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<p>
yes, I would be willing to do so however you like, either on SDAnet or via<br>
email if you or Steve think this most appropriate.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
