<title>Apr_1992: Re: Pharisees' Guide</title>
<h1>Re: Pharisees' Guide</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 21 Apr 92 11:57:36 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#51">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#51">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#51">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#51">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0050.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0024.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Pharisees' Guide"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0065.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Pharisees' Guide"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
Steve writes :<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Nancy's mention of Pharisees brings to mind a Jewish tradition I once </i><br>
<i>&gt; heard.  It seems that the Pharisees believed that if one Sabbath was</i><br>
<i>&gt; kept perfectly in Israel, the Messiah would come.  Has anyone else </i><br>
<i>&gt; ever run across this tradition?</i><br>
<p>
Yes I have heard it as well but I can't add any more details about the <br>
tradition.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Along the same line, we hear the I.K.I.I.E.G.W.S.* statement "When the </i><br>
<i>&gt; character of Christ is fully reproduced in His people, then He will come </i><br>
<i>&gt; to claim them as his own."  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; *I Know It's In EGW Somewhere</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Yep I have read it and many more like it. I can give you an exact reference <br>
to it if you like.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What I have trouble with is the idea that we can control God by our actions.</i><br>
<i>&gt; There exist reasons why Christ has chosen not to come.  There exist no </i><br>
<i>&gt; barriers that would stop Him from coming at any second He chose.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Instead of pulling the blame on ourselves for it, or pushing it at others,</i><br>
<i>&gt; we need to view God as the God who is in control and ready to help us</i><br>
<i>&gt; finish the work that needs to be done.</i><br>
<p>
Yes it seems we are trying to work our way to heaven. It really worries me<br>
when I hear statements like "Jesus is waiting for us to do enough missionary<br>
work to convert the whole world and then He will come." Some even say that He <br>
will come in his own good time, when He feels like it.<br>
<p>
However EGW wrote back in the 1890's that Jesus would have already come if<br>
his people had been ready to receive Him and then she wrote that we too<br>
like the Israelites would have to return to wander in the desert some more <br>
years because we had rejected the loud cry message (1888) which was<br>
to prepare us for His coming.<br>
<p>
Jesus is not waiting for us to complete the work of spreading the gospel <br>
because He can finish the works in a matter of weeks, (with the power of<br>
the latter rain)<br>
the problem is that we are not ready to receive Him. God will give us the<br>
loud cry spirit and message when we are prepared to accept it, when we realise <br>
that we too are Laodicean and in need of an experience which we are<br>
too indolent to obtain. When we seek for God with all our hearts, when we cry<br>
for him whom we have pierced as one cries for his only son. When we realise<br>
like Peter that maybe we have been decieving ourselves all along and that it <br>
isn't good enough just to know Christ intellectually but that we must be <br>
prepared to sacrifice all with and for Christ, and when we realise like him <br>
that not matter how saved we feel ourselves to be, that there is yet a deeper <br>
work to be done in our souls, a work of unmasking our true natures and pleading<br>
with God to do a work in our hearts which we are of ourselves unable to do.<br>
And that this must be done or there will never be a Pentecost.<br>
<p>
When we permit God to work in us, to hew us by His Spirit, to cut away sin<br>
from our lives. Then the world will see Christ in you (the hope of Glory) and <br>
"ten men shall take hold out of all languages of the nations, even shall take <br>
hold of the skirt of him that is a Jew, saying. We will go with you: for we <br>
have heard that God is with you" Zech 8:23 When we are prepared to accept the <br>
message of the loud cry no matter how unpopular or contrary to our inclinations<br>
then the Lord will work in us and through us, His message will be proclaimed<br>
not through the machinations of man but through the powerful working of His<br>
Spirit and then He will come to claim us as His own.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
