<title>Apr_1992: Death/Afterlife</title>
<h1>Death/Afterlife</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 21 Apr 92 12:45 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Dave Buxton: "Moores and Home School"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
      Quick note to Paul, Paul..that book about False Authority sounds<br>
      very good.  Is the author an Adventist?<br>
 <br>
      To Rueben,<br>
 <br>
           One thing that I feel I need to express is this.  This issue<br>
       about Soul-Sleep vs the Soul/Spirit survivng death is not a major<br>
       issue for me.  There could in fact be some in our church who may<br>
       hold to the Soul/Sleep position but I'm not sure.  I guess what I'm<br>
       saying is this: It is not a make or break issue for someone's<br>
       salvation.  As for me, I'm not exaclty sure, which in some sense<br>
       gives me a bit more freedom to examine it with as much objectivity<br>
       as I can muster.  I don't necessarily feel any inclination to prove<br>
       either side, but simply desire to examine the Biblical evidence and<br>
       perhaps come to a conclusion.  I also need to express a slight<br>
       frustration I have.  Many times i have discussed the doctrine of the<br>
       Trinity with the JWs.  They  frequently state that the idea of a<br>
       "Trinity" comes from pagen influence and can not be found in the<br>
       Bible anywhere.  I believe they are guilty of arguing their point<br>
       without being honest to the Scriptures.  The Trinitarian doctrine was<br>
       pounded out for centuries by men committed to the Scriptures. They<br>
       didn't use any of Plato's material...just the Biblical evidence.  I<br>
       kind of feel the same about this issue.  I'm more than willing to<br>
       take an "honest" look at the Biblical evidence.  Dig into the Hebrew<br>
       and Greek meanings of words and compare Scripture with Scripture.<br>
       Perhaps I will be convinced, that at death, the entire person ceases<br>
       to exist until the Resurrection.  But to state that there is "no"<br>
       Biblical passages that "seem" to support the position, that the person<br>
       experiences consciousness after death, is not being truly honest to the<br>
       Scriptures.  If you tell me that after much prayerful study, you have<br>
       concluded that the Soul/sleep position is correct, I think thats fine.<br>
       But there are many passages that also lean towards the other position.<br>
       What about Revelation 6:9<br>
           And when He broke the fifth seal, I saw underneath the alter<br>
           the souls of those who had been slain because of the word of<br>
           God, and because of the testimony which they maintained.<br>
                                                NASB<br>
 <br>
       Thanks for your response Rueben<br>
 <br>
       Eric<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
