<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Well Eric I don't believe that the Parable of rich man and Lazarus</i><br>
<i>&gt;contributes anything at all to our understanding about what happens at</i><br>
<i>&gt;death because the entire thing is clearly metaphorical. These are my reasons :</i><br>
<p>
  Could someone explain to me why this parable is metaphorical?  All the<br>
other parables of Jesus seem to use real life things that people know<br>
happen or that are.  Why isn't this parable the same?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt;      but would Jesus use an untruthful example to teach ?  Also, Paul states</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Well does, the parable of the 10 virgins teach us that polygamy is acceptable ?</i><br>
  What has polygny to do with that parable?  And no this parable doesn't<br>
teach that, but there are other OT references that teach that for some<br>
men in some times polygyny was from God.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt;      than, Jesus is telling the thief that even though he is about to die,</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;      the thief will see Jesus that day in a much better place called</i><br>
<i>&gt;paradise.</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;      On the other hand, if you place the comma "after" the word "today", it</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;      means that Jesus is emphasizing His point by stating that he is telling</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;      the thief on that day.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;in Greek) is that then Jesus must have also been in heaven with the theif</i><br>
<i>&gt;however we know for a fact because Jesus told us himself that He was not</i><br>
<i>&gt;to be in heaven but in the tomb for 3 days, after the three days Jesus</i><br>
<i>&gt;himself announced to Mary that He HAD NOT ascended up to His father</i><br>
<i>&gt;( in paradise obviously ) yet and that He was to do so, this day was Sunday.</i><br>
<i>&gt;So Jesus must have been lying to the thief because Jesus was definitively not</i><br>
<i>&gt;in heaven until 3 days after He had promised the thief (according to this</i><br>
<i>&gt;interpretation) that He would be there. So that It cannot be that Jesus</i><br>
<i>&gt;promised the thief that he would be together with Jesus in paradise on the</i><br>
<i>&gt;Friday because he wasn't. Only the other interpretation is viable.</i><br>
<p>
  Excuse me, but I don't wanna (as opposed to can't) control myself<br>
here:<br>
<p>
  Why is it that Jesus, on some occasions only, talks so funny?  Was he<br>
delirous when he said, in effect, 'look today, that is, I am telling you<br>
this today and not yesterday or tomorrow, that you will be with me in<br>
heaven'?  And why, if he meant heaven, didn't he utter the word heaven<br>
instead of another hardly ever used word?<br>
<p>
  I mean, other than the reason that if he said what he meant (paradise<br>
today after we die and me in heaven after 3 days and nites) then there<br>
is a place that our spirits go after death and before heaven (after the<br>
judgement)?<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
