<title>Apr_1992: Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works</title>
<h1>Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works</h1>
Bill Oblitey (<i>OBLITEY@grove.iup.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 22 Apr 1992 09:43 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#56">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#56">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#56">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#56">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Bob Moynihan: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Sorry Dave, I beg to disagree.  Your illustrations are excellent but we<br>
are not saved by our works.  Our works demonstrate our appreciation for<br>
being saved.  The thief on the cross had no works - only faith.<br>
<p>
When we take the attitude that we are saved by our works, we will for sure<br>
have lots of questions for Jesus when we get to heaven in terms of some who<br>
have been saved and some who have not been saved.  I think it's up to Him<br>
who gets saved or not.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
