<!-- id="9204221329.AA13139@xuucp.ch.apollo.hp.com" -->
<!-- inreplyto="After Death - Soul/Spirit" -->
<title>Apr_1992: Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit</title>
<h1>Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 22 Apr 92 08:40:54 EDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#57">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#57">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#57">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#57">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0058.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Anyone have a bio on EGW?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0056.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0028.html">Eric Snyder: "After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0060.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Why is it that Jesus, on some occasions only, talks so funny?  Was he</i><br>
<i>&gt; delirous when he said, in effect, 'look today, that is, I am telling you</i><br>
<i>&gt; this today and not yesterday or tomorrow, that you will be with me in</i><br>
<i>&gt; heaven'?  And why, if he meant heaven, didn't he utter the word heaven</i><br>
<i>&gt; instead of another hardly ever used word?</i><br>
<p>
Scott, no one is saying that Jesus was talking funny.  What was put forward<br>
is the idea that in translating the Gospel from the original (punctuationless)<br>
Greek, a comma was placed, perhaps incorrectly.<br>
<p>
Jesus' words were "...assuredly I say to you this day you will be with me in <br>
Heaven".  <br>
<p>
Our Bibles have it punctuated as, "...assuredly I say to you, this day you will <br>
be with me in Heaven,"  which would mean that Jesus was telling the thief that<br>
on that day, He and the thief would both be in Heaven.  Numerous Scripture<br>
quotations recently sent out on this list indicate that death is like sleep and<br>
that -no one- ascends to Heaven until the day He returns for us.  Also, as was<br>
also stated, if the comma is placed that way, Jesus would have lied to the thief,<br>
as He assuredly -didn't- ascend to heaven for several days after His death.<br>
<p>
If the punctuation was set up this way, however, "...assuredly I say to you this <br>
day, you will be with me in Heaven," He would be saying this in today's english:<br>
<p>
"...believe me, because I'm telling you now, you'll be with me in Heaven." <br>
<p>
A pretty simple statement, if you ask me...<br>
<p>
Bob Moynihan                        Disclaimer:  I speak only for myself, not for<br>
moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com                         Hewlett-Packard Company, not for<br>
                                                 The Seventh-day Adventist Church.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
