<title>Apr_1992: Trinity Etc -- Was Death/Afterlife</title>
<h1>Trinity Etc -- Was Death/Afterlife</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 22 Apr 92 07:20:17 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#59">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#59">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#59">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#59">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0058.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Anyone have a bio on EGW?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Eric,<br>
<p>
You raised the question of the Trinity relative to your dialog with JWs.<br>
They insist this doctrine comes only from paganism and is not Biblical.<br>
<p>
When the pioneers of the SDA church were researching and establishing<br>
the doctrines of the church they were especially cautious of theology<br>
that came into prominence in the early hundreds because that is a period<br>
of church history when many pagan practices were popularized into the<br>
Roman Catholic Church.  At the time of Jesus and the Apostles, Imperial<br>
Rome had its seat of office in the city of Rome.  But this was later<br>
moved to another city and the rule of Rome was handed over to the<br>
church.  Suddenly it became expedient to be a Christian if you had any<br>
political ambitions and hence a large influx of pagans into the<br>
Christianity of Rome and its church politics.  And so much melting<br>
together of pagan and Christian belief and practice into a mixture<br>
that was claimed to be Christian.<br>
<p>
The Protestant Reformation cast off many of the more blatant practices<br>
and beliefs.  But Luther, for example, held back the pace of the<br>
Reformation, being concerned that too much change too quickly and the<br>
peasant folks would simply not keep up and perhaps fall back into the<br>
clutches of Romanism.  Luther, at least for a time, saw the Reformation<br>
as progressing on and on with its reforms into the future.  But what<br>
happened all too often was the development of each religion around the<br>
established theology of a particular reformer followed by the<br>
liberalising of that system of theology over the years.  All too often<br>
the work of a reformer was the high water mark for that particular<br>
church.  Lutherans, for example, still subscribe to infant baptism.<br>
<p>
Another example, Luther taught "soul sleep", as did most reformers.  But<br>
the Annabaptists were pressing for reforms that went beyond what Luther<br>
and others were ready for.  The Annabaptists, for example insisting<br>
that infant baptism meant nothing; that proper adult baptism was called<br>
for.  The Annabaptists became a thorn in the side of the Reformation<br>
churches which by then were becoming state churches.  There was a need<br>
for unity against the Annabaptists.  And so it was decided that<br>
"soul sleep" was a doctrine that could be left to rest in peace for a<br>
time as that was a strong doctrine of the Annabaptists.  Luther and<br>
others did not reject "soul sleep", they simply fell silent on the<br>
subject, allowing Calvin to wax eloquent.<br>
<p>
Anyway, back to the early SDA church.  It was clear that the Protestant<br>
reformation had not reformed all the paganism that had entered the<br>
early church.  And so they were especially cautious of any doctrine<br>
whose history was associated with those early years of pagan influx.<br>
The doctrine of the Trinity was one that had to be very closely<br>
and carefully examined.  Their finding was that the Trinity is clearly a<br>
Biblical doctrine and so it came to be accepted with enthusiasm.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
