[Email reporting this to be a Morris Vendon Philosophy]<br>
<i>&gt; An apple doesn't worry about whether or not it's going to produce apples.</i><br>
<i>&gt; It doesn't strain to produce them. The apples are a byproduct of its being </i><br>
<i>&gt; an apple tree (it being hard to grow cherries or kumquats on an apple tree).  </i><br>
<i>&gt; Their quantity and quality are dependent on the condition of the tree.</i><br>
<p>
Hi #####,<br>
<p>
I guess I have to take issue with this.  I believe this philosophy is<br>
what shorts out so many Christian batteries and drains off the power<br>
of the Gospel.  I hear people say in various ways -- I guess God has<br>
not decided to give me the victory yet on this matter, in His own good<br>
time He will get around to it.  -- Let us be clear, the power and the<br>
ability and the energy to be victorious comes from Him.  To fear and to<br>
withdraw from a mighty effort against sin in our lives is what so many<br>
Christians are being taught is Christianity.  How many Christians today<br>
would struggle all night for the victory as did Jacob?  In the end he<br>
was given the assurance that he would be safe from Esau.  It was not<br>
his victory, it was God's assurance.  But that came after a night of<br>
struggle and prayer.  Christians today are being taught to put the<br>
car in neutral and to let the breeses blow them where ever they will.<br>
What ever happened to the stout hearted Christianity of our pioneers?<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
