<title>Apr_1992: Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit</title>
<h1>Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 22 Apr 1992 11:16:02 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0060.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0074.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My thoughts on the parable of the Rich Man and Lazarus<br>
<p>
Let's suppose for a second that this parable is literally true.<br>
"The beggar died and was carried by the angels into Abraham's bosom."<br>
<p>
This doesn't mean that the beggar went straight to heaven.<br>
<p>
"The rich man died, and was buried.  And in hell he lift up his eyes..."<br>
<p>
Nor does it say that the rich man went to hell immediately<br>
<p>
The communication which happens between Father Abraham and the rich man <br>
is not impossible in hell as we know it, because Abraham stresses <br>
There is a great gulf fixed.<br>
<p>
Finally, nothing says that the rich man doesn't eventually burn up.<br>
<p>
So I think SDA's really have nothing to fear from this parable or a need to <br>
explain it away.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
