<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Scott, no one is saying that Jesus was talking funny.  What was put forward</i><br>
<i>&gt;is the idea that in translating the Gospel from the original (punctuationless)</i><br>
<i>&gt;Greek, a comma was placed, perhaps incorrectly.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Jesus' words were "...assuredly I say to you this day you will be with me in</i><br>
<i>&gt;Heaven".</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Our Bibles have it punctuated as, "...assuredly I say to you, this day</i><br>
you will<br>
<i>&gt;be with me in Heaven,"  which would mean that Jesus was telling the thief that</i><br>
<i>&gt;on that day, He and the thief would both be in Heaven.  Numerous Scripture</i><br>
<i>&gt;quotations recently sent out on this list indicate that death is like</i><br>
sleep and<br>
<i>&gt;that -no one- ascends to Heaven until the day He returns for us.  Also, as was</i><br>
<i>&gt;also stated, if the comma is placed that way, Jesus would have lied to the</i><br>
<i>&gt;thief,</i><br>
<i>&gt;as He assuredly -didn't- ascend to heaven for several days after His death.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;If the punctuation was set up this way, however, "...assuredly I say to you</i><br>
<i>&gt;this</i><br>
<i>&gt;day, you will be with me in Heaven," He would be saying this in today's</i><br>
<i>&gt;english:</i><br>
<p>
  Are there any other instances in the Bible of Jesus qualifying what he<br>
is saying as having been said on the day that he said it?  That is what<br>
sounds so funny to me.<br>
