<title>Apr_1992: More Death/Afterlife</title>
<h1>More Death/Afterlife</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 22 Apr 92 13:07 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#66">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#66">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#66">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#66">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re:     Baptism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Pharisees' Guide"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
       When looking at the Luke 23:43 verse, it is true as stated<br>
    before, that in the original Greek, there wasn't the comma.<br>
    I do agree that the passage can make sense with the comma placed<br>
    before or after the word "today".  I also need to say that if I'm<br>
    correct, every current English translation that I've looked at<br>
    ( except for the JWs NWT ) places it before the word today.  That<br>
    list would include the King James, the New King James, the New<br>
    International Version and the New American Standard Version.  I<br>
    am not positive, but I also believe the Revised Standard version<br>
    would also have it before "today".  I realize that the translators<br>
    are only human and are capable of making mistakes, but when it<br>
    seems like the majority of them use the same syntax, it warrants<br>
    us to examine if that might not be the best and most natural way<br>
    to read the text.  The problem occurs if one is trying to prove<br>
    that there is no consciousness immediately after death, then<br>
    there isn't any option, but to state that the comma must be<br>
    placed "after" the word today.  If we try to stand back and just<br>
    read the passage without trying prove or disprove anything, does<br>
    it not tend to lean towards the comma being "before".  Could you<br>
    not imagine the joy the thief had experienced.  Even though he<br>
    had been hanging from the cross in pain,  Jesus assures him that<br>
    by the close of that very day, instead of hanging side by side on<br>
    crosses, he will be with him in a much better place.<br>
 <br>
        Yesterday, I used Revelation 6:9, which states:<br>
 <br>
           And when he had opened the fifth seal, I saw under<br>
           the alter the souls of them that were slain for the<br>
           word of God, and for the testimony which they held.<br>
                                                KJV<br>
     The word "souls" here in Rev. 6:9 is the Greek word "Psuche"<br>
     According to Dr. Robert Morey in his book "Death and the Afterlife"<br>
     he states that "in the KJV New Testament, "Psuche" is translated<br>
     as "Soul" 59 times, "Life" 39 times, "Mind" 3 times, "Heart" 2<br>
     times, "You" 1 time and "Us" 1 time" (page 55).  In Matthew 10:28<br>
     is another occurrence where "Psuche" is translated "Soul".  It says<br>
 <br>
          And fear not them which kill the body, but are not able to<br>
          kill the soul: but rather fear him which is able to destroy<br>
          both soul and body in hell.    KJV<br>
 <br>
     Though there are instances in the New Testament, where Soul ind-<br>
     icates simply a person, here are two cases, where it must mean<br>
     the immaterial aspect of a person.  I state this for these reasons:<br>
 <br>
     1.  In both passages, the soul is described as a separate part<br>
         from the body.  In the Matt. 10:28, it states that we should<br>
         not fear them who can kill the "body" but not the "soul".<br>
         Also in the Matt. 10:28, it uses the phrase "both" indicating<br>
         two separate things.<br>
 <br>
     2.  Both passages indicate that it is indeed possible to have<br>
         the body dead, but the soul not.  If you read the following<br>
         passage in Rev ( Rev. 6:10, ) it states that these souls who<br>
         were slain, cry out to the Lord.  They clearly are dead and the<br>
         Ressurrection has not yet occurred....<br>
         Have a good one<br>
         Eric<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
