<title>Apr_1992: Re: Let me see if I have this correct</title>
<h1>Re: Let me see if I have this correct</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 23 Apr 92 12:25:16 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#68">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#68">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#68">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#68">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0069.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Death/Afterlife"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re:     Baptism"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0026.html">Steven Timm: "Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0094.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all with regard to this discussion<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt;&gt;  I am reading The Great Contraversy and wanted to see if my impressions</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;&gt;on what EGW is saying are 'correct'.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;........... stuff deleted .........</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;&gt;  3) I find it interesting that EGW acknowledges that we will be judged</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;&gt;by our works.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Through selective quoting of EGW you can prove any position from legalism</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;to antinomianism.  Can you give me a page reference so I can check the</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;specific reference you refer to?  A judgment by works is indeed referred</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;to in EGW and the Bible but no one would pass that judgement save for</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;the grace and forgiveness of Christ.</i><br>
<p>
I really like the analogy that Dr Ralf Larson uses to illustrate the<br>
difference between works and grace. It goes something like this :<br>
<p>
No one can measure a force directly, we can only measure the amount of <br>
work done by that force. <br>
<p>
For example we can't measure kinetic energy (heat) directly so we need to <br>
measure how high the mercury climbs up the thermometer. This is measuring<br>
the amount of work produced by the force. The mercury does not rise<br>
unless there is heat to push it up.<br>
<p>
We can't measure acceleration directly so we need to measure the amount of<br>
distance travelled (or change in) in a unit of time, this is measuring the <br>
amount of work being performed by the force. Stationary objects do not move <br>
unless there is acceleration to move them.<br>
<p>
We can't measure gravity directly so we need to measure the distance an<br>
object travels (down) on a weigh scale, this is measuring the amount of<br>
work the force performs. The weight scales do not move down unless there<br>
is a gravitational force to push them.<br>
<p>
God's grace is a force that compels each of us, if grace is acting in our<br>
lives then that grace will perform work, that work is manifest in our<br>
actions. We can not measure God's grace directly but we can measure <br>
its presence byt observing the works produced. This is why we are judged<br>
or measured by our works, because they testify that God's saving grace has <br>
been present in our lives. We can not do any real good works <br>
(not talking superficially here) unless God's grace is present within us.<br>
<p>
This is why Jesus said to Nicodemous that the wind (God's grace) goes where<br>
it wants and no one knows where it comes from nor where it goes, we can not<br>
see it but we can hear it. We can hear it because that that is how we measure<br>
wind by hearing the work it does in rustling the leaves.  The same is with<br>
God's grace, we can't see it but for the work it produces. <br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
