Eric,<br>
<i>&gt;       perhaps come to a conclusion.  I also need to express a slight</i><br>
<i>&gt;       frustration I have.  Many times i have discussed the doctrine of the</i><br>
<i>&gt;       Trinity with the JWs.  They  frequently state that the idea of a</i><br>
<i>&gt;       "Trinity" comes from pagen influence and can not be found in the</i><br>
<i>&gt;       Bible anywhere.  I believe they are guilty of arguing their point</i><br>
<i>&gt;       without being honest to the Scriptures.  The Trinitarian doctrine was</i><br>
<i>&gt;       pounded out for centuries by men committed to the Scriptures. They</i><br>
<i>&gt;       didn't use any of Plato's material...just the Biblical evidence.  I</i><br>
<p>
  I think they (JWs) and my church have a problem with the 3 in 1, 1 in<br>
3 concept that some have as their idea of the trinity.  LDS agree that<br>
there is the Father, the Son and the Holy Ghost, but we believe that the<br>
Bible teaches that they are separate beings.<br>
<p>
  Just a thought.<br>
<p>
  Btw, I was wondering about the same scripture from Rev as you asked<br>
about.<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
