<title>Apr_1992: Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works</title>
<h1>Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 22 Apr 92 10:02:08 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#70">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#70">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#70">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#70">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0071.html">Fred Christiansen: "Introducing myself as a new member of SDAnet"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0069.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Death/Afterlife"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0052.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; The question is -- is it works that save us?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I think Jesus illustrated it well when He spoke of the true vine and</i><br>
<i>&gt; its branches.  Our works can be like apples on an apple tree.  But</i><br>
<i>&gt; who would care to eat a wax apple that has been tied in place upon</i><br>
<i>&gt; the same apple tree.  Or who would care to eat an apple that has</i><br>
<i>&gt; fallen from the apple tree, to lay upon the ground for a week or two.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; We are saved by our works, but clearly it is the apple tree that</i><br>
  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
Did you really mean this?  We are *judged* by our works ("my reward is<br>
with Me, to give every man according to his works").<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; deserves all the credit for growing the apples.  And that apple tree is</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christ Jesus who came to save us from our sins.  He can grow apples,</i><br>
<i>&gt; all we can do is sculpture wax into something that looks like an</i><br>
<i>&gt; apple from a distance.</i><br>
<p>
"By grace are ye saved thru faith, and that not of yourselves; it is the<br>
gift of God."  God's grace is the desire ("both to will") and the power<br>
("and to do His good pleasure") to live a Christ-like life of submission<br>
(the Lord really as Lord) and obedience (the reason why Paul uses the<br>
terms 'slave' and 'servant') to the expressed will of God ("nothing myself<br>
but the will of my Father who sent Me").  Faith is also a gift; it is the<br>
belief that God, even tho we've never met him, is Who He says He is and<br>
what He says in His Word is reliable, trustworthy, effectual, and<br>
incumbent upon us ("All Scripture is given by inspiration of God and<br>
is profitable for ...".  "Do we then make void the Law thru faith?<br>
God forbid; yea, we establish the law." see also Lev 20:7,8).<br>
<p>
Works are the outward demonstration of the inward transformation (new man,<br>
new heart of flesh, i.e., sanctification).  They are the "proof of the<br>
pudding", so to speak.  They bring glory to God because they reveal His<br>
character ("let your light so shine before men that they may see your<br>
good works and glorify your Father who is in heaven", "you are living<br>
epistles, known and read of all men") and demonstrate the man's<br>
character can be changed; that "Christ in you" makes a difference.<br>
We are not saved by our works; yet we cannot be saved without works.<br>
<p>
We make a decision to accept Jesus as our Savior, i.e., that He paid the<br>
penalty for our sins (atonement), that our sins are forgiven (justification),<br>
that we walk in newness of life, and that we have eternal life (IJn5:11-13).<br>
But if things do not progress from there, we're just a bunch of hot air,<br>
we're all flap and no throttle.  Indeed, if there's no growing in grace,<br>
it is because we are rejecting the promptings of the Holy Spirit.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola TSD (DW278), 2900 S. Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ  85282
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  For the Lord gives wisdom:  out of His mouth comes knowledge
    and understanding (Prov 2:6).
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
