On Wed, 22 Apr 1992 10:30:05 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<i>&gt;Hi Eric,</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;........ most deleted ........</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Anyway, back to the early SDA church.  It was clear that the Protestant</i><br>
<i>&gt;reformation had not reformed all the paganism that had entered the</i><br>
<i>&gt;early church.  And so they were especially cautious of any doctrine</i><br>
<i>&gt;whose history was associated with those early years of pagan influx.</i><br>
<i>&gt;The doctrine of the Trinity was one that had to be very closely</i><br>
<i>&gt;and carefully examined.  Their finding was that the Trinity is clearly a</i><br>
<i>&gt;Biblical doctrine and so it came to be accepted with enthusiasm.</i><br>
<p>
  Yes, but, I think what Eric might be asking is what is the SDA concept<br>
of the trinity?  Three distinct individuals with the same desires?<br>
Three manifestations of one being?  Etc?<br>
  As LDS we recognize that there are 3 distinct personages to the<br>
Godhead.  They are one in purpose.  Two have bodies, while the Holy<br>
Ghost does not.  Before I was Lutheran and was taught 3-in-1 (which to<br>
this day I don't quite know what was meant).  If I remember correctly<br>
they taught only Jesus had a body.  To me, now, that means they don't<br>
read the Bible too much.<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
