<title>Apr_1992: More Death/Afterlife</title>
<h1>More Death/Afterlife</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 23 Apr 92 12:53 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#76">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#76">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#76">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#76">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Trinity Etc -- Was Death/Afterlife"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
        I just wanted to add an additional note to the discussion<br>
     regarding Luke 23:43.  The passage in the KJV reads as follows:<br>
 <br>
           "And Jesus said unto him, Verily I say unto thee,  To day<br>
         shalt thou be with me in paradise."<br>
 <br>
     I have a Strong's concordance of the entire KJV Bible.  I looked<br>
     up the term "verily".  Many times throughout the gospels, Jesus<br>
     uses this phrase "Verily I say unto thee".  Each and every time<br>
     that I looked up, the comma is always after the "thee".  Then after<br>
     the comma, Jesus makes his statement.  The New American Standard<br>
     version uses "Truly" instead of "verily".  This pattern is consist-<br>
     ent for each occurrence that I've looked up.  Below are several<br>
     examples of this.<br>
 <br>
     Matthew 5:26<br>
          Truly I say you, you shall not come out of there, until<br>
          you have paid the last cent.<br>
 <br>
     Matthew 8:10<br>
          Now when Jesus heard this, He marveled, and said to those<br>
          who were following, "Truly I say to you, I have not found<br>
          such great faith with anyone in Isreal."<br>
 <br>
     Luke 4:24<br>
          And He said, "Truly I say to you, no prophet is welcome in<br>
          his home town."<br>
 <br>
       In each of the above passages, the comma is after the phrase<br>
       "Truly I say to you".  Then after the comma, Jesus makes His<br>
       point.  There must be more than 40 occurrences of this phrase<br>
       in the gospels, and using my concordance, I didn't find any<br>
       instances where Jesus used "Truly I say to you today".<br>
       I believe this is a consistant pattern and should be taken<br>
       into account when interpreting Luke 23:43.  If anyone knows of<br>
       any that I overlooked, could you let me know ?<br>
       Eric Snyder<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
