<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;&gt;Scott, no one is saying that Jesus was talking funny.  What was put forward</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;is the idea that in translating the Gospel from the original (punctuationless)</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;Greek, a comma was placed, perhaps incorrectly.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;  Are there any other instances in the Bible of Jesus qualifying what he</i><br>
<i>&gt;is saying as having been said on the day that he said it?  That is what</i><br>
<i>&gt;sounds so funny to me.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
Yes, there are other instances.  Read John 9:1 - 6.  Pay particular attention<br>
to the question in verse 2 and Jesus' answer in verses 3 and 4.  If you are<br>
nor careful with the punctuation, you will think that Jesus is saying that<br>
God made someone blind just so Jesus will have the opportunity to perform a<br>
miracle.  Now place a period after "parents" in verse 3, and start the "but"<br>
with an upper case "B", and you'll notice that Jesus is now implying that the<br>
question is not relevant but He MUST make God's work relevant in this person.<br>
<p>
I hope I been of some help.<br>
<p>
Bill Oblitey<br>
