<title>Apr_1992: Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works</title>
<h1>Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 23 Apr 92 10:43:40 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#78">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#78">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#78">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#78">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; [Email reporting this to be a Morris Vendon Philosophy]</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; An apple doesn't worry about whether or not it's going to produce apples.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; It doesn't strain to produce them. The apples are a byproduct of its being </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; an apple tree (it being hard to grow cherries or kumquats on an apple tree).  </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Their quantity and quality are dependent on the condition of the tree.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I guess I have to take issue with this.  I believe this philosophy is</i><br>
<i>&gt; what shorts out so many Christian batteries and drains off the power</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the Gospel.</i><br>
<p>
Nuts.  I see that I didn't get the point clearly across.  You have<br>
missed the point, therefore. Mea culpa.  Did you miss the last line<br>
of the preceding paragraph?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I hear people say in various ways -- I guess God has</i><br>
<i>&gt; not decided to give me the victory yet on this matter, in His own good</i><br>
<i>&gt; time He will get around to it.</i><br>
<p>
This has essentially nothing to do with the apple tree analogy given<br>
above.<br>
<p>
The fruit of the tree is your works.  Your works may be good or bad,<br>
but the fact that there is fruit is no more than a byproduct of mere<br>
existence.  Your works may be of faith, or they may not be of faith.<br>
<p>
The *quality* of the fruit is a reflection of the person's relationship<br>
with Christ.  A useful indicator of your condition (although the said<br>
fruit may be either profitable or damaging to others).  Just because<br>
there's an apple is no reason to be complacent, unless you *like*<br>
worms or hard, sour, dry lumps.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  -- Let us be clear, the power and the</i><br>
<i>&gt; ability and the energy to be victorious comes from Him.</i><br>
<p>
Of course.  That's implied in the above analogy.  The tree cannot<br>
live, much less bear fruit, without the sun, soil, and water that<br>
it requires for life.  Those things it receives outside of any<br>
efforts of its own.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Christians today are being taught to put the</i><br>
<i>&gt; car in neutral and to let the breeses blow them where ever they will.</i><br>
<p>
The which, while true, is not supported by Venden's parable.<br>
<p>
Some seem to figure on waiting until they've miraculously received the<br>
victory (over whatever)...this points out that waiting around for it<br>
to drop on your head is not just pointless, it is damaging: the fruit<br>
is being borne all the while.  But it's not good fruit, not profitable<br>
to anyone.<br>
<p>
If nothing else, the notion should give you more impetus to fix the<br>
broken connection, to develop that full, right relationship, before<br>
any more damage is done.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What ever happened to the stout hearted Christianity of our pioneers?</i><br>
<p>
It's still around, as is the limp, soggy failings of them, too.  :{<br>
Something that we have to deal with, just as they had to.<br>
<p>
Sorry about the confusion, it seemed quite clear to me.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
