<title>Apr_1992: Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?</title>
<h1>Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 23 Apr 1992 23:51 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#79">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#79">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#79">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#79">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0080.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
I was talking with a friend who lives in Loma Linda tonight.  He indicated<br>
that the Medical Center is having severe financial troubles.  The cost<br>
overruns on the proton project have been tremendous.  It will take decades<br>
of treatments to pay for it!  They have terminated 600 workers.  Since the<br>
insurance companies have set limits to the amount of money they will pay<br>
for treatments and surgeries, the physicians at LLUMC are refusing to accept<br>
patients whose insurance carriers impose limits to coverage.  The building<br>
of the Childrens Hospital is on indefinite hold.  And the financial stability<br>
of the institution is in serious question.  Can any of you out there<br>
confirm these facts?  Is Loma Linda going to going down in financial flames<br>
rather than the literal flames of Battle Creek?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
