<title>Apr_1992: The Trinity</title>
<h1>The Trinity</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 23 Apr 92 21:45 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#81">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#81">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#81">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#81">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0082.html">Scott Mattes: "Did Jesus talk 'strangely'?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0080.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
        When I referred to my encounters with the JWs and discussing<br>
     the Trinity, I was only using that as an example of what I believe<br>
     to be an improper technique to argue a point.  The JWs state that<br>
     the idea of the Trinity is foreign to the Bible and that it came<br>
     from pagen sources.  This is not a true statement.  There is "plenty"<br>
     of biblical evidence supporting the Trinity.  I was using that to<br>
     describe some frustration when someone states that the idea of a<br>
     person having a soul/spirit that survives death is completely foreign<br>
     to the Bible and is completely influenced by Greek philosphers.<br>
     I believe that to some point that in some circles, Greek philosophy<br>
     "has" influenced this topic, but at the same time, to be fair, there<br>
     are some committed Christians who hold the "soul/spirit survives<br>
     death" position and they base their conclusions only on the Bible.<br>
 <br>
     As far as the Trinity goes, it is a complex doctrine and to do it<br>
     justice, we would need to take a lot of time, but I believe that<br>
     our church would be in agreement with the SDA position.  I could<br>
     though quickly sum up how I believe many theologians have arrived<br>
     at it.  Both the Old and New Testaments teach that there is one<br>
     and only one true God.  The Jewish faith was/is a "monotheistic"<br>
     faith.  The Christian faith is also a "monotheistic" faith, only<br>
     believing in one God.  Within the New Testament, there are three<br>
     persons who are called God.  The Father is called God ( 2 Peter 1:17),<br>
     Jesus is called God ( John 1:1, 20:28) and the Holy Spirit is<br>
     called God (Acts 5:3,4).  Yet there is only one True God (1 Corinthians<br>
     8:4, John 17:3).  To avoid heresy, you have to walk a fine line.  If<br>
     you deny that Jesus or the Holy Spirit are God, you aren't being<br>
     true to Scripture.  If you say there are 2,3 or many gods, you're<br>
     also not being true to Scripture.  In order to be true to the Scriptures<br>
     you need to maintain that there is only one "True" God, and that three<br>
     persons are referred to as God.  Yes, I know there are instances of<br>
     where people are called "gods" (Psalm 82) and satin is called the god<br>
     of this world, but John 17:3 states that there is only one "true" god.<br>
     We can always discuss this in more depth at a later date.  I hope you<br>
     all have a wonderful weekend and a very pleasant Sabbath.  One thing<br>
     I know, whether the soul survives death or not is one thing,  knowing<br>
     that at sometime in the future, we will be with the King of Kings in<br>
     a place where there are no more tears is quite another.<br>
 <br>
     Eric Snyder<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
