On Thu, 23 Apr 1992 12:55:57 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<i>&gt;Yes, there are other instances.  Read John 9:1 - 6.  Pay particular attention</i><br>
<i>&gt;to the question in verse 2 and Jesus' answer in verses 3 and 4.  If you are</i><br>
<i>&gt;nor careful with the punctuation, you will think that Jesus is saying that</i><br>
<i>&gt;God made someone blind just so Jesus will have the opportunity to perform a</i><br>
<i>&gt;miracle.  Now place a period after "parents" in verse 3, and start the "but"</i><br>
<i>&gt;with an upper case "B", and you'll notice that Jesus is now implying that the</i><br>
<i>&gt;question is not relevant but He MUST make God's work relevant in this person.</i><br>
<p>
  To make your example complete in my KJV I had to change the period at<br>
the end of v3 into a comma (and didn't really have to make the other<br>
changes).  Since becoming LDS I have interpreted it the same way you<br>
suggest (an irrelivant question because bad things happen to good people<br>
through no fault of their own and that God does not punish person A<br>
because their family are bad people).<br>
<p>
  However, I don't see that this example applies to the question I had<br>
about Jesus stating that what he is saying on that day is in fact being<br>
said on that day.<br>
