<title>Apr_1992: Soul sleep</title>
<h1>Soul sleep</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 26 Apr 92 15:06:55 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#83">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#83">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#83">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#83">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Richard Guy: "Re: Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0082.html">Scott Mattes: "Did Jesus talk 'strangely'?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here are some more thoughts on the discussion of death as a sleep.<br>
<p>
	When Jesus said, ``Verily I say unto thee today thou shalt be<br>
with me in Paradise,'' the fact that he said it ``today'' is highly<br>
significant.  He is saying, Today, when I am hanging on a cross,<br>
today, when the crowd is mocking me, today, when it seems like all is<br>
lost, today, I am promising you that you will be with me in Paradise.<br>
Jesus knew that that was a very special day, the day on which he was<br>
purchasing the pardon for our sins.<br>
<p>
	The fact that other times that Jesus said ``Verily I say unto<br>
thee'' the comma occurs next, is interesting but not by itself<br>
conclusive.<br>
<p>
	We really need to be careful to take the entire Bible<br>
testimony on each topic.  The reason we have so many churches is that<br>
some people take a few verses here and there and base a doctrine on<br>
it.  Others take a different selection of verses and come to a<br>
different conclusion.  We need to look at the entire Bible testimony<br>
on each topic and make our decision based on that.<br>
<p>
	Instead of focusing on a few verses where it is possible to<br>
interpret them as referring to a heavenly reward at death, we need to<br>
keep in mind many other verses.  For example, in the story of Lazarus,<br>
Jesus said ``Lazarus is sleeping.''  Paul writes in 1 Cor 15 that ``we<br>
shall not all sleep, but we shall all be changed.''  He also says in<br>
verse 26, the last enemy to be destroyed is death.  Death is an enemy,<br>
not a friend that takes us to heaven.  In 1 Thess 4 Paul comforts the<br>
bereaved that they will see their loved ones when Jesus returns.  How<br>
many funeral sermons do you hear like that today?  Instead, the<br>
minister comforts us that the deceased is in heaven.  Daniel says,<br>
``Many that sleep in the dust of the earth shall awake.''  (Daniel<br>
12:2) If you think Jesus spoke funny to the thief on the cross -- what<br>
about what he said about Lazarus sleeping and many other similar Bible<br>
verses?  Wouldn't it be speaking funny in all these places if indeed<br>
there were an immortal soul that went to heaven or hell at death?<br>
<p>
	This doctrine of soul sleep took me a while to convince myself<br>
of when becoming an Adventist.  But I studied for myself and became<br>
convinced that it is most in line with the entire Bible testimony.  I<br>
invite others to do the same.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
