<title>Apr_1992: Re: Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?</title>
<h1>Re: Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?</h1>
Richard Guy (<i>guy@ficus.cs.ucla.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 25 Apr 92 06:45:44 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#84">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#84">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#84">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#84">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Dan Blake: "Questions about SDA"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0083.html">David Plaisted: "Soul sleep"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My understanding is that the fundamental problem (at least at one level)<br>
is a low census percentage--in the 50s and 60s for the last several months.<br>
This is quite a change from the high 80s and low 90s of a year or so ago, when<br>
most other hospitals in the area were struggling along with low 70s.<br>
The hospital has recently taken three steps in response to this situation:<br>
closing wards so as to change the basis for computing census percentages<br>
so they don't look so bad; terminating employees to bring down the payroll cost<br>
(clearly the larget expense the hospital incurs on a continuing basis); and<br>
placing a very large number of employees on forced one-day-a-week unpaid leave.<br>
<p>
At another level, it seems that the hospital recently hired a consulting<br>
firm to identify the source of the census drop.  The preliminary report was<br>
that a large number of internists (internal medicine specialists, not to be<br>
confused with interns (doctors in training)) had left the hospital's staff<br>
over that past three years--20% or more by some estimates, and that had a<br>
significant impact on patients admitted to the facility.  The was not the<br>
politically correct answer, so a different consulting firm has been<br>
retained.  It is interesting to note that there has not been an exodus of<br>
internists from the Loma Linda housing market; they all seem to have joined<br>
the staffs of a hospital or two down the road a couple of miles...<br>
<p>
<p>
The hospital/medical school have experienced extended dissent among the<br>
internists for several years now--the politically correct approach to this<br>
problem has been to fire the leaders of dissenting parties.  This in turn<br>
has caused further distress/distrust/dissent.<br>
<p>
Significant problems also exist within the faculty side, apart from how the<br>
physicans are "managed" at the hospital; Dr. Behrens leadership style is<br>
under sever attack from several angles.  Even though LLU's WASC<br>
accreditation status has been upgraded from probatinary to a three-year<br>
term, it is readily apparent that all is not well within.<br>
<p>
I don't know to what extent the proton project can be blamed for financial<br>
distress, other than as a part of the financial burden of building two new<br>
wings, one of which (the children's hospital) is a hollow shell above the<br>
proton accelerator.<br>
<p>
One wonders when the board of trustees of LLU/LLUMC will question the<br>
appropriateness of the leadership teams in place there...  for now, it<br>
appears theat they are convinced that no other leaders can save the place.<br>
<p>
This raises an interesting question for this forum:<br>
what is the Christian way (if there is one) of forcibly chaning<br>
leadership?  Give them a call to some other position, and hope they accept<br>
it is divine guidance? and if they don't see it that way?<br>
<p>
richard<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
