<title>Apr_1992: Re: Questions about SDA</title>
<h1>Re: Questions about SDA</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 26 Apr 1992 19:24 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#88">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#88">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#88">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#88">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Baptism"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0085.html">Dan Blake: "Questions about SDA"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt; dblake asked:  The Catholic church considers someone a member of the church</i><br>
due to being born of Catholic parents.  Do SDAs feel the<br>
same?  Can one be born into the SDA church?<br>
<p>
Yes, we can be born into an SDA home and raised on SDA principles, sent to<br>
SDA schools and colleges, and adopt the SDA culture.  However, technically<br>
one is not a member of the SDA church until he/she is formally baptized into<br>
the church.  I was baptized at the age of 10 at my own request. I believed<br>
and practiced the beliefs and doctrines of the SDA remaining a steadfast<br>
member until my 20s.  Then I rejected the church and withdrew from formal<br>
association with the SDA.  I was never formally "disfellowshipped" or<br>
"excommunicated" and was rebaptized into the SDA church in my late 20s<br>
following a severe auto accident that caused me to start thinking about<br>
eternal things.  My rebaptism was my way of identifying myself as a<br>
believing SDA once again.  However, there was no searching for truth or<br>
personal study about the SDA doctrines at that time.  Only a recommitment<br>
to live an SDA life consistent with what I had been taught and known all<br>
my life.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
