<title>Apr_1992: Re: Perseverance</title>
<h1>Re: Perseverance</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 28 Apr 92 8:15:48 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#90">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#90">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#90">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#90">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0086.html">Dan Blake: "One more question"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The only kind of "perseverance of the saints" in which SDAs believe is that<br>
taught by Jesus himself.  Matthew 24:13--"He who endures to the end will be<br>
saved."  Rev 2:10--"Be faithful unto death and I will give you the crown of<br>
life."<br>
<p>
The apostles were aware of the danger of falling.  Peter wrote: "You, there-<br>
fore, beloved, knowing this beforehand, beware lest you be carried away with the error of lawless men and lose your own stability" 2 Pet 3:17.  Paul even<br>
allowed for the possibility of his own fall!  1 Cor 9:27--"I pommel my body and<br>
subdue it, lest after preaching to others I myself should be disqualified."<br>
<p>
Having admitted the possibility of falling from grace, we can nevertheless,<br>
with Paul, be sure that "we are more than conquerors through him who loved<br>
us."  Nothing, neither death nor life, nor angels, nor principalities, nor <br>
things present, nor things to come, nor powers, nor height, nor depth, nor<br>
anything else in all creation, will be able to separate us from the love of<br>
God in Christ Jesus our Lord" Rom 8:37-39.   Nothing--except our own choice!<br>
We are God's as long as we choose to belong to him.  When we choose other-<br>
wise, we depart from perseverance and fall into condemnation.<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
