<title>Apr_1992: Death/Afterlife</title>
<h1>Death/Afterlife</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 28 Apr 1992 12:38:13 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#92">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#92">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#92">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#92">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0093.html">Gross: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct on saved by works"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: After Death - Soul/Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0104.html">Scott Mattes: "Disfellowship"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
         I have a question as to how much tolerance the SDA church<br>
    has of its members who might not hold to the soul-sleep position.<br>
 <br>
    What would happen if a good standing member in the SDA church<br>
    expressed some doubt in the soul sleep position ?  Would that<br>
    member possibly be in jeopardy of excommunication ?  Would they<br>
    be considered a heretic or would the church leaders just simply<br>
    reply that he/she was incorrect on this point and that they needed<br>
    to re-study the topic ?  I'm just trying to get a feel of how much<br>
    importance this teaching is in the eyes of the church, and if there<br>
    is any leeway?<br>
<p>
[I've never heard a case where anyone challenged this doctrine.  It's one <br>
of the least-debated doctrines within the church, which is why I'm glad<br>
we're studying it now.  Traditional Bible studies on the topic aren't<br>
answering the<br>
questions people are asking.  I would note that even such "heretics" as <br>
Walter Rea who openly challenged the authority of Ellen White were not<br>
stripped of their church membership.  Disfellowship for disbelieving <br>
doctrine is extremely rare.  SCT]<br>
 <br>
    Dave Plaisted writes:<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt;          Instead of focusing on a few verses where it is</i><br>
<i>&gt;      possible to interpret them as referring to a heavenly</i><br>
<i>&gt;      reward at death, we need to keep in mind many other</i><br>
<i>&gt;      verses.  For example, in the story of Lazarus, Jesus</i><br>
<i>&gt;      said ``Lazarus is sleeping.''</i><br>
 <br>
 <br>
       I have to admit, these passages that mention the verb "sleep"<br>
    when referring to the dead need to be addressed and in my opinion<br>
    are some of the strongest verses for the soul-sleep position.<br>
    The passage that Dave refers to does seem to indicate that death<br>
    is considered "sleep".  However, if we read the entire passage,<br>
    you read in Jesus states in verses 25 and 26:<br>
 <br>
    John 11<br>
    v25   Jesus said to her, "I am the resurrection and the life; he<br>
          who believes in Me shall live even if he dies,<br>
    v26   and everyone who lives and believes in Me shall never die.<br>
          Do you believe this ?"<br>
 <br>
       If you focus on verse 26, Jesus says that the person who lives<br>
    and believes in Him shall "never die".  If, when a believer dies,<br>
    he/she passes into non-existance, how can Jesus say that the person<br>
    has never died ?  Though Lazurus body was indeed dead and in the<br>
    tomb 4 days, the only way to explain that he "never died" would be<br>
    to conclude that though his body expired, his soul/spirit continued<br>
    to live.  Lets compare this thought with some of Paul's writings:<br>
 <br>
    Dave further writes:<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt;          Paul writes in 1 Cor 15 that ``we shall not all</i><br>
<i>&gt;      sleep, but we shall all be changed.'' He also says in</i><br>
<i>&gt;      verse 26, the last enemy to be destroyed is death.</i><br>
<i>&gt;      Death is an enemy, not a friend that takes us to</i><br>
<i>&gt;      heaven.</i><br>
 <br>
    Dave says that death is an enemy and not a freind, that takes us<br>
    to heaven.   Please compare Dave's statement with philippians 1:21<br>
 <br>
        "For to me, to live is Christ, and to die is gain."<br>
 <br>
    Paul says that to die is "gain".  Further, in verse 23 Pauls<br>
    states "But I am hard-pressed from both directions, having the<br>
    desire to depart and be with Christ, for that is very much<br>
    better."  Then verse 24 "yet to remain on in the flesh is more<br>
    necessary for your sake."<br>
 <br>
        From the above passage, is there any question that Paul sees<br>
    his death as "gain" so that he can be with Christ ?  In addition,<br>
    Paul speaks of "remaining in the flesh".  Do you not get a sense<br>
    that Paul considers his body, something which "he is in".  Compare<br>
    this with 2 Corinthians 5:8<br>
 <br>
         "we are of good courage, I say and prefer rather to be<br>
       absent from the body and to be at home with the Lord."<br>
 <br>
    The key phrase is "absent from the body".  If at Paul's death,<br>
    he would pass into non-existance, how could he be "absent from<br>
    the body".<br>
 <br>
 <br>
    Eric Snyder<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
