<title>Apr_1992: Today in Paradise</title>
<h1>Today in Paradise</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 27 Apr 92 12:41:10 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#95">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#95">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#95">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#95">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0094.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Those who know a lot more about cruxifixions than I do tell me that<br>
victims who have not been scourged can last for days on the cross.<br>
Those who have been scourged have their back muscles so ripped up<br>
that breathing becomes increasingly difficult such that surviving<br>
the day is not likely.<br>
<p>
The traditional pictures show Jesus nailed and the two thieves<br>
tied.  Also quite possible that while Jesus was scourged, the thieves<br>
were not.  If that be the case, then the two thieves may very well<br>
have survived the day.  Their legs were broken at the end of the<br>
day.  If the soldiers wanted them dead by sundown they would have<br>
speared them as they did Jesus.  If, as was so often their intent,<br>
the soldiers wanted a lingering death of several days, then breaking<br>
the legs insured the virtual imposibility of their escape during the<br>
night.  Breaking the legs would bring on death by suffocation if scourged.<br>
But not so if not scourged.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0094.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
