<title>Apr_1992: Response to some questions about Death/Afterlife</title>
<h1>Response to some questions about Death/Afterlife</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 29 Apr 92 14:17:36 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#97">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#97">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#97">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#97">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Steven Timm: "Free speech"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Loma Linda in severe financial trouble?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In response to Eric Snyder's questions:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;    v26   and everyone who lives and believes in Me shall never die.</i><br>
<i>&gt;          Do you believe this ?"</i><br>
<p>
To the Christian the first death is of little importance.  It is only<br>
a sleep, till Jesus comes.  The second death is what is spoken of here.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;philippians 1:21</i><br>
<i>&gt;        "For to me, to live is Christ, and to die is gain."</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;in verse 23 Paul</i><br>
<i>&gt;    states "But I am hard-pressed from both directions, having the</i><br>
<i>&gt;    desire to depart and be with Christ, for that is very much</i><br>
<i>&gt;    better."  Then verse 24 "yet to remain on in the flesh is more</i><br>
<i>&gt;    necessary for your sake."</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Compare this with 2 Corinthians 5:8</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;       "we are of good courage, I say and prefer rather to be</i><br>
<i>&gt;       absent from the body and to be at home with the Lord."</i><br>
<p>
When the Christian dies, he or she sleeps till Jesus comes.  The next<br>
thing he or she knows is Jesus coming.  So, for us, death is<br>
immediately followed by Christ's return and the heavenly reward, even<br>
though many years may intervene.<br>
<p>
I think many Christians would echo Paul's desire to be absent from the<br>
body and present with the Lord.  When Jesus returns we will receive a<br>
new body, without the sinful tendencies and desires of the present<br>
body.  Just think of it -- no more constant struggle with the old man,<br>
always trying to regain control!<br>
<p>
So, these verses are consistent with the Adventist position.  You<br>
might also note that the term ``immortal soul'' never appears in the<br>
Bible.  Rather, it says that God only has immortality.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
