<title>Apr_1992: Free speech</title>
<h1>Free speech</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+%ANDREW.CMU.EDU%CMU.EDU@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 30 Apr 1992 11:10:12 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#98">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#98">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#98">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#98">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0097.html">David Plaisted: "Response to some questions about Death/Afterlife"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think SDA-L should remain unmoderated.  Abuse of this network just hasn't<br>
been a problem.  As long as SDA-L stays away from heavy doctrinal<br>
discussion and discussion of touchy issues within the church, we'll be fine.<br>
In the past most SDA-L members indicated that they didn't want to get into<br>
those kind of wars, which are the most likely to generate flames.  In<br>
my opinion, these issues are best reserved for SDAnet with moderation.<br>
 <br>
But outside of these areas there is still plenty to talk about.  Maybe<br>
the best thing to do is to form a collective leadership for the list<br>
who can come up with ideas for constructive discussion.<br>
 <br>
Remember, to the extent that SDA-L is unmoderated, so also is SDAnet,<br>
because all messages from SDA-L get passed on to SDAnet without my clearance.<br>
 <br>
SDAnet members, if you receive two copies of this message send me mail<br>
and I can tell you how to avoid that.<br>
 <br>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
