<title>Apr_1992: Re: Soul sleep</title>
<h1>Re: Soul sleep</h1>
Scott Mattes (<i>COTRSSM@sea04vm.navsea.navy.mil</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 30 Apr 92 11:44:31 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#100">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#100">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#100">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#100">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0101.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Leadership of SDA-L in transition"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: Let me see if I have this correct"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Sun, 26 Apr 1992 17:21:29 -0400 (EDT) someone said:<br>
<i>&gt;Here are some more thoughts on the discussion of death as a sleep.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;        When Jesus said, ``Verily I say unto thee today thou shalt be</i><br>
<i>&gt;with me in Paradise,'' the fact that he said it ``today'' is highly</i><br>
<i>&gt;significant.  He is saying, Today, when I am hanging on a cross,</i><br>
<i>&gt;today, when the crowd is mocking me, today, when it seems like all is</i><br>
<i>&gt;lost, today, I am promising you that you will be with me in Paradise.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Jesus knew that that was a very special day, the day on which he was</i><br>
<i>&gt;purchasing the pardon for our sins.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;        The fact that other times that Jesus said ``Verily I say unto</i><br>
<i>&gt;thee'' the comma occurs next, is interesting but not by itself</i><br>
<i>&gt;conclusive.</i><br>
<p>
  This would make the Bible so much harder to understand, let alone<br>
believe, than I think God intended.  For this example we are asked to<br>
believe that after establishing a clear pattern of speech Jesus would<br>
alter that pattern just once and expect everyone to 'know' that he meant<br>
it another way.<br>
<p>
  Not taking what is written more literally is why some believe that<br>
believers don't have to get baptised, Jesus really didn't mean me when<br>
he said all those things.  Etc.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;        We really need to be careful to take the entire Bible</i><br>
<i>&gt;testimony on each topic.  The reason we have so many churches is that</i><br>
<i>&gt;some people take a few verses here and there and base a doctrine on</i><br>
<i>&gt;it.  Others take a different selection of verses and come to a</i><br>
<i>&gt;different conclusion.  We need to look at the entire Bible testimony</i><br>
<i>&gt;on each topic and make our decision based on that.</i><br>
<p>
  But, where there is cause to think two sources are saying different<br>
things, whose words should we put more weight behind?  Jesus and written<br>
testimony centurys/millenium newer than OT prophets or words that we are<br>
told were exactly copied throughout the ages without even one deviation?<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
