<!-- body="start" -->
On Tue, 28 Apr 1992 12:39:25 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<p>
don't know what this was in response to, but....<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;The traditional pictures show Jesus nailed and the two thieves</i><br>
<i>&gt;tied.  Also quite possible that while Jesus was scourged, the thieves</i><br>
<i>&gt;were not.  If that be the case, then the two thieves may very well</i><br>
<i>&gt;have survived the day.  Their legs were broken at the end of the</i><br>
<i>&gt;day.  If the soldiers wanted them dead by sundown they would have</i><br>
<i>&gt;speared them as they did Jesus.  If, as was so often their intent,</i><br>
<i>&gt;the soldiers wanted a lingering death of several days, then breaking</i><br>
<i>&gt;the legs insured the virtual imposibility of their escape during the</i><br>
<i>&gt;night.  Breaking the legs would bring on death by suffocation if scourged.</i><br>
<i>&gt;But not so if not scourged.</i><br>
<p>
  As the Bible says the Jews wanted the bodies, including the two<br>
theives, down before the start of the Sabbath.  As a young Lutheran I<br>
was taught that the reason Jesus was poked instead of broke was 1) to<br>
fulfill prophecy that not a bone would be broken and 2) to make sure he<br>
was dead (what came out the wound was not the blood of a perso alive,<br>
but one who had been dead awhile).<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
<p>
[Dave was suggesting here that the thieves may not have died that day<br>
and thus didn't go to paradise or anywhere.  I have heard commentators <br>
suggest both ways.  SCT]<br>
