<title>Apr_1993: Re: The real issues?</title>
<h1>Re: The real issues?</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 6 Apr 93 14:39:41 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#144">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#144">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#144">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#144">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0145.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: The real issue"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0143.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: The Sovereignty of God"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0132.html">Steven Timm: "The real issues?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0175.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The real issues?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; It is true that many Adventists now emphasize the fact that we are</i><br>
<i>&gt; born in a state of separation from God, and thus unable, on our own,</i><br>
<i>&gt; to choose to do right.  And it is only through faith in God that this</i><br>
<i>&gt; relationship can be restored:  "Everything not of faith is sin."</i><br>
<i>&gt; However, I do not know of a single Adventist that believes in original</i><br>
<i>&gt; sin or inherited guilt.  We are born with Adam's separation from God,</i><br>
<i>&gt; but not with Adam's guilt.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Does being born separate from God mean that one is born in a "lost" condition ?<br>
if so, then it means the same as original sin.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
