<title>Apr_1993: Re: SDA: advent</title>
<h1>Re: SDA: advent</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 6 Apr 93 14:24:40 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#142">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#142">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#142">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#142">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0143.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: The Sovereignty of God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0141.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  The Sovereignty of God"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0125.html">Sherman Cox: "SDA: advent"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;  1. Every 2000 years something big happens.  Creation - Flood - Christ - 2nd</i><br>
<i>&gt;     advent. </i><br>
<p>
Flood 1656 After Creation<br>
Christ 4000 A.C.<br>
2nd Coming .... 6000 A.C. (?)<br>
<p>
EGW suggests this world won't continue much more than 6000 years.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  2. A day equals a thousand years with God.  Creation is 7 days, therefore</i><br>
<i>&gt;     the world will last 6000 years plus a seventh day of rest.  Perhaps someone</i><br>
<i>&gt;     who teaches this could better explain this one.</i><br>
<p>
Not that I teach this one, but the idea behind this is that the bible says<br>
that 6 days shall man labour, ie do the works of man. the seventh is the day<br>
of rest. The millenium is the 7th figurative day when the earth and man rests <br>
from sin, which he has been laburing hard at for the preceeding 6 figurative <br>
days.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<i>&gt;  3. Ellen White said that the world would last 6000 years.  She said sin would</i><br>
<i>&gt;     reign for 6000 years.  I also saw whre she said the world was 6000 years old </i><br>
<i>&gt;     at her time.  I saw her say that the flood was 4000 years ago in her day.</i><br>
<i>&gt;     Does this mean that these dates are exactly true?  My faith in ellen White</i><br>
<i>&gt;     soes not stand or fall on a legalistic reading of a few numbers.</i><br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<p>
I have looked into EGW's use of dates and numbers and found that she uses<br>
them in a general sense and always rounds them off to the nearest hundred<br>
or thousand. Bascially she rounds up to the same order of magnitude. So<br>
we can't use her use of dates as the basis of any time setting.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  I must say I have heard these arguments many a time, I have even heard the</i><br>
<i>&gt;  year 1996 spoken specifically from the pulpit.</i><br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<p>
According to some variants of biblical chronology, the first Advent occured<br>
in 4 B.C. exactly 4000 years after creation. Adding 2000 years to that<br>
date to make 6000 years brings us to 1996, except of course for those<br>
who remember to skip year 0 because it didn't exsist in which case the<br>
date becomes 1997.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  If the year 2000 passes and Christ has not come, I will continue to sing,</i><br>
<i>&gt;  "I don't believe He brought me this far to leave me."</i><br>
<p>
Yep me too, but I enjoy digging around escatological things.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
