<title>Apr_1993: Waggoner and Jones</title>
<h1>Waggoner and Jones</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 28 Mar 1993 13:26:39 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#2">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#2">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#2">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#2">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Info (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Gary W Burdick: "Religious liberty? and Branch Davidians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The confused description of Waggoner and Jones given by our antagonist <br>
on the other net is just that--confused.  They were considered liberals<br>
in their time for advocating a nontraditional stand on the role of the law<br>
of God.  Now, it seems that most of the advocates of their position <br>
(that Christ's righteousness can and should be ours) are termed either <br>
conservatives or perfectionists.  This is because the dominant position<br>
of the church has shifted from the ultra-legalism that was espoused <br>
in the days of 1888 to a position that pays lip service to righteousness<br>
by faith but has no idea what that actually is.  Most Seventh-day Adventists<br>
think they agree with the 1888 message but have no idea what it is.<br>
Even more troublesome is that most Seventh-day Adventists also think <br>
they agree with the exact opposite of that position, and cannot tell the <br>
difference between the two.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
