<title>Apr_1993: SDA: Left &amp; right are relative</title>
<h1>SDA: Left &amp; right are relative</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>29 Mar 1993 09:16:38 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#4">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#4">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#4">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#4">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Steven Timm: "RE: Why the SDA church needs conservatives"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Info (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve's remarks about Waggoner &amp; Jones serve to illustrate the fact that<br>
we use the terms "conservative" and "liberal" in very much a relative way.<br>
<p>
I honestly think we have few, if any, true liberal theologians in the SDA<br>
church. Those whom we think of as liberal within our church are far from<br>
being liberal in the broader sense. Liberal theologians in general seem to<br>
give and take without restriction when it comes to Biblical authority and<br>
interpretation, far more than any SDA I know.<br>
<p>
Even in worship style the relativism thing holds. The "liberals" today <br>
would be considered "conservative" in any pentecostal/charismatic church,<br>
and may well have been considered conservative by some of the early SDAs.<br>
The "conservatives" would be considered "liberal" by some of the reformers,<br>
who were accustomed only to music without harmony, or to harmony without<br>
accompaniment, or whatever.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
