<title>Apr_1993: SDA--Spectrum</title>
<h1>SDA--Spectrum</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 29 Mar 1993 20:10:55 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#9">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#9">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#9">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#9">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Gary W Burdick: "Re: How to answer a CB (Was Christ's humanity)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0008.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Those three angels"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I want to add just a few more words to the discussion of _Spectrum_ (as<br>
a frequent contributor).  Like this list, it's a bit of fresh air in the<br>
church.  It was founded back in the late '60s (I have been a charter member<br>
of the Association of Adventist Forums, and have, I believe, a complete<br>
run of _Spectrum_).  It was founded by graduate students who wanted a<br>
freer, more academic forum to openly discuss topics of interest.  Even<br>
though it's now more journalistic, it still has an academic tone, and a<br>
commitment to academic free speech (though there are limits to what the<br>
editor will print).  For the church, I believe, it's been something of a<br>
case of can't live with it, can't live without it (something like the<br>
Seminary and Andrews University, but that's another topic entirely!).<br>
Because it has printed articles that the hierarchy doesn't like, not<br>
only the conservatives, but also many of the bureaucrats like to<br>
criticize it (for example, not wishing it to be indexed in the _SDA<br>
Periodical Index_) while at the same time surruptitiously (I didn't<br>
check the spelling of that) reading it.  In fact, I observed just last<br>
week a GC department head supplying his workers with copies of a<br>
particular article.  I have also observed none other than Mervyn Maxwell<br>
bring it to committee meeting and literally hide it under the table!<br>
<p>
I believe that most true liberals have left the church, feeling it not<br>
worth the effort to try to change, while the conservatives always seem<br>
to want to reform it in their image (and claim that they are the<br>
"mainstream").  Articles from a variety of viewpoints have been<br>
published in _Spectrum_, but most conservatives refuse to publish there<br>
so it does end up on the liberal end of the spectrum (pun intended).<br>
However, it also takes on something of the personal bias of the editor<br>
(and I may be getting myself in trouble here).  Many authors have noted<br>
that they open up the issue to read what they "wrote."  <br>
<p>
For those interested in joining AAF (and subscribing to _Spectrum_),<br>
it's $25 for 5 issues, $32 in countries other than the US, and right now<br>
$16.50 for students.  The address is Box 5330, Takoma Park, MD  20913.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
