<title>Apr_1993: RE: Why the SDA church needs conservatives</title>
<h1>RE: Why the SDA church needs conservatives</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 29 Mar 1993 23:08:52 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#5">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#5">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#5">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#5">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "What is AntiChrist ?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0004.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "SDA: Left &amp; right are relative"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[From Marcus Stringer]<br>
I'm a little confused on the turn in this thread.  I thought I was up-to-date,<br>
but I might have missed something along the way.  Please help.<br>
<p>
1.  What points of interpretation, true or false, are<br>
     "liberals" saying that our "faith" is not affected by?<br>
<p>
2.  What points of interpretation are "conservatives"<br>
     marching ahead, showing that they are true?<br>
<p>
marcuss@microsoft.com<br>
<p>
<p>
[For the liberal example I am indebted to a certain AU professor who <br>
said:  "The Book of Esther is generally considered to be myth"<br>
Q:  "Does that mean it's not true?"<br>
"No, of course it's true"  --the point being that even if the early <br>
parts of the Bible were total legend, we could still draw many of the <br>
same supports for our faith.<br>
<p>
For the conservative example, I was thinking about Ruben's recent posts<br>
on the NIV showing how most of the modern translations follow a different<br>
reading than the KJV, and providing documentation that I had no idea <br>
existed.  SCT]<br>
