<title>Apr_1993: Re: Those three angels</title>
<h1>Re: Those three angels</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 29 Mar 1993 23:25:46 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#11">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#11">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#11">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#11">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steven Timm: "SDA: **Tony's original subject line censored**"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Gary W Burdick: "Re: How to answer a CB (Was Christ's humanity)"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0008.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Those three angels"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
First, William Johnsson of the Adventist Review when asked in open forum<br>
about the Review logo claims that the three wavy lines in the "A" of <br>
Adventist Review are a stylized representation of the three angels.<br>
It has previously gone around about what apostasy some conservatives <br>
interpret this to mean.<br>
<p>
Now to the issue of the "Three Angels Messages"<br>
<p>
It is my feeling that the "Three Angels Messages" and the gospel are<br>
the same and inseparable.  If any part of the SDA message exists which <br>
is not part of the core gospel, then we can dispense with it.  The <br>
fiction that there exists a "just know Jesus" gospel has led to many<br>
fruitless discussions.<br>
<p>
Nevertheless, SDA's tend to draw converts from those who are already<br>
Christian, even in some developing countries.  I agree that it is high<br>
time to get on the front lines and reach our share of the unchurched.<br>
That's why I'm excited about the current series of meetings we are having<br>
in the Chicago suburbs.  The Hinsdale SDA church, host church for the<br>
meetings, is essentially redefining itself (at the cost of much pain)<br>
to better target and reach the unchurched.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
