<title>Apr_1993: SDA: **Tony's original subject line censored**</title>
<h1>SDA: **Tony's original subject line censored**</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 29 Mar 1993 23:29:19 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#12">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#12">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#12">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#12">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0013.html">Steven Timm: "RE:  Maxwell's letter"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Those three angels"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0025.html">Dan Blake: "SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[From Tony Dyson]<br>
For those of you who wonder *why* your scientist friends are a bit<br>
worried by (a) the creation science movement, and (b) having recent<br>
creationism as a test of orthodoxy, have a read of this. It is a post<br>
I picked up from the newsgroup talk.origins. <br>
<p>
If the perception of Christianity by the academic community continues<br>
to be influenced by the excesses of the Creation Science movement in<br>
general, then how will we reach that segment of society with the gospel?<br>
Our credibility will be seriously in doubt, and that makes witnessing for<br>
Christ a little difficult.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
[I'm letting this post through, but I censored Tony's subject line.<br>
Posts like this were exactly why I put the ban on creationism discussion<br>
on SDAnet.  This post came during an open discussion which I started,<br>
so I will accept it, but I will accept no other posts on creationism<br>
or evolution for a good long time.  If people want to read this stuff,<br>
they can read talk.origins.  Our debate is degenerating to the level<br>
of that sludge-pit.  Just for information, it's my understanding <br>
of SDA policy that we oppose the teaching of creationism in public <br>
schools because this would be establishment of religion.  If someone<br>
wants to continue the discussion on a religious liberty level, they <br>
are welcome to do so.  SCT]<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
Let's approach this from a different angle.  Suppose I tell you I have<br>
a scientific theory.  I'm not going to tell you what the theory is<br>
right now, but I am convinced it is true, and I would like to have you<br>
pass a law so that every high school student in the country will be<br>
taught my theory, and so that my theory will be given equal time with<br>
the standard theory.  I think this is only fair.<br>
<p>
Like I said, I'm not going to tell you what my theory is right now, but<br>
I will tell you some other things.  I will readily admit that 99.9<br>
percent of the world's scientists think my theory is pure garbage.  Not<br>
just wrong, understand, but trash.  I will also admit that of the small<br>
handful of scientists who do back my theory, most are non-productive<br>
nobodys with degrees in irrelevant fields, and who are by the way<br>
obligated to believe in my theory or else give up their religion.<br>
Nevertheless I want you to pass a law to force unwilling science<br>
teachers to teach my theory to high school students.<br>
<p>
Will you do it?  Does it matter even a little bit what the details<br>
of my theory are, or how good I am at convincing people who are not<br>
scientists?  Of course not!!!  High school students are just being<br>
introduced to science, and we teach them standard, non-controversial<br>
science, because that is all they are ready for.<br>
<p>
Why am I talking about the way we teach science to high school<br>
students?  "Scientific Creationism" is a deeply dishonest enterprise.<br>
Real scientists work to convince other scientists that their theorys<br>
are true, because only the other scientists can understand anyway.  If<br>
Einstein had been unable to convince other scientists of the truth of<br>
relativity, do you think he would have gone to the state legislature<br>
and tried to get them to pass a law and teach relativity in high<br>
school?  Such a thing would never occur to a real scientist.  But the<br>
Scientific Creationists make very little effort to convince the<br>
scientific community.  They would much rather have the matter decided<br>
by the lawyers and politicians, and that's where their arguments are<br>
directed, that's where their efforts go.  Their main goal is to have<br>
their transparently religous "theory" taught in our schools (or to<br>
surpress the teaching of evolution), and they are perfectly willing to<br>
bypass the scientific community to do so.  Arguments here as to the<br>
truth or falsity of their ideas are really rather irrelevant.  Until<br>
they can convince the scientific community that their ideas have merit,<br>
those ideas should not be taught as science in our schools!  And that's<br>
all the Creationists are after anyway.<br>
<p>
John Blake<br>
<p>
&lt;----<br>
