<title>Apr_1993: RE:  Maxwell's letter</title>
<h1>RE:  Maxwell's letter</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 29 Mar 1993 23:40:50 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#13">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#13">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#13">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#13">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: What is AntiChrist ?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steven Timm: "SDA: **Tony's original subject line censored**"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0022.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Maxwell's letter"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One of the gripes which is most often voiced by folks such as "Our Firm<br>
Foundation" is that Adventist sermons today don't contain enough doctrinal<br>
content, or else the wrong doctrinal content.  Maxwell was echoing that<br>
when he decried the lack of strong theological articles in the Review.<br>
<p>
I may be wrong about this, but I was not aware that the Review was ever<br>
intended to be either a theological paper or a missionary paper.  Nor<br>
is it obvious in the more than twenty years I have read it that the<br>
number of theological articles has declined; if anything it has<br>
increased over the last few years.  Those who would have more theology<br>
everywhere <br>
miss an important point:<br>
<p>
The church service is now a be-all and end-all for many church members<br>
who have not gone to church school, don't study a Sabbath School lesson, <br>
don't go to prayer meeting.  The pastor is forced to meet many more needs<br>
in less allotted time.  Theological expositions have had to give way to the <br>
more basic remedial work.  It's not uncommon for pastors to have to spend<br>
the first year of their three at a church in remedial work, healing disputes,<br>
convincing people that God even loves them.  During this time outreach <br>
is practically impossible.<br>
<p>
(Some, including me, would say that outreach is the only effective<br>
remedy.  But I digress).<br>
<p>
The theological renaissance of the SDA church can only come if we first<br>
have a renaissance in the home unit and place people in a position where<br>
they are emotionally ready to receive the gospel.  One of the chief problems<br>
that we face in the church today is that people relate to God exactly <br>
like they relate to their father, and both relationships are dysfunctional.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
