<title>Apr_1993: Re: Seeking a Sanctuary</title>
<h1>Re: Seeking a Sanctuary</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 30 Mar 1993 09:32:37 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#26">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#26">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#26">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#26">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Seeking a Sanctuary"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Dan Blake: "SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0017.html">Steven Timm: "Seeking a Sanctuary"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0027.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Seeking a Sanctuary"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; [From Drew Corrigan]</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Hi All,</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; A friend of mine recommended I find and read the book,</i><br>
<i>&gt;   "Seeking a Sanctuary"</i><br>
<i>&gt; by Lockhart and Bull, published by Harper&amp;Row.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The book is a discussion on changes in the SDA church over the years,</i><br>
<i>&gt; but my (and my friend's) interest is how these changes have presaged</i><br>
<i>&gt; similiar changes in the WCoG over more recent times.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Has anyone read this book, and if so, what were your impressions?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Thanks,</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Drew.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; [I read and enjoyed the book.  I would recommend it to any friend who is </i><br>
<i>&gt; interested in an objective view of SDA's. Unfortunately, I believe </i><br>
<i>&gt; it is now out of print.  SCT]</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
This is one of the best recent books on Seventh-day Adventism (along<br>
with Gary Land's Adventism in America), and really is a "must-read."  I<br>
would certainly recommend it to any library seeking a small but good<br>
collection on the subject.  If you can't find it locally where you are,<br>
check with your local library interlibrary loan department.  I see 206<br>
libraries listed on OCLC (our online "virtual library") that own this<br>
book.  I also see that our copy is currently available.  You should be<br>
able to find it somewhere.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
