<title>Apr_1993: SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins</title>
<h1>SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 30 Mar 93 11:04:24 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#25">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#25">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#25">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#25">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Seeking a Sanctuary"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Why the SDA Church needs Lukewarm Couch Potatoes"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0012.html">Steven Timm: "SDA: **Tony's original subject line censored**"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0034.html">Steven Timm: "Re: SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Just for information, it's my understanding </i><br>
<i>&gt; of SDA policy that we oppose the teaching of creationism in public </i><br>
<i>&gt; schools because this would be establishment of religion.  If someone</i><br>
<i>&gt; wants to continue the discussion on a religious liberty level, they </i><br>
<i>&gt; are welcome to do so.  SCT]</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
-----------------------------<br>
If I generalize the focus of your statement to the teaching<br>
of *origins* in public schools, would you still be concerned<br>
about the establishment of religion?<br>
<p>
If yes, do you also oppose the teaching of evolution as an<br>
explanation of the origins of all that is?<br>
<p>
If no, what is it about creationism (if not its view about<br>
origins) that raises the specter of the establishment of a<br>
religion?<br>
<p>
Please keep any answers at a very high level to ensure that<br>
this discussion remains focused on religious liberty and not<br>
creationism per se.<br>
<p>
Dan Blake<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
