<h1>Re: How to answer a CB (Was Christ's humanity)</h1>
Gary W Burdick (<i>burdick@hkuxa.hku.hk</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 30 Mar 93 11:45:20 WST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#10">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#10">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#10">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#10">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Those three angels"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Harvey Brenneise: "SDA--Spectrum"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tony writes:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I think those who say Christ had a "sinful nature" and those who say he</i><br>
<i>&gt; had a "sinless nature", at least in the SDA church, are agreed about what</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christ was. What is not agreed is what sin is.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; [...]</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; So my questions on "how to answer a cb" would include "what do you say to a</i><br>
<i>&gt; person who says that transgression of law is the only definition of sin".</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I agree that this is the fundamental divisive question.  If we cannot<br>
come to an agreement on the definition of sin, then it really is<br>
pointless to discuss many of the other divisive questions such as the<br>
nature of Christ.  This is a question that I have been struggling<br>
with for some time.  Unfortunately, judging from the lack of responses<br>
to Tony's question, no one else seems to have a good answer either.<br>
<p>
To me, sinful acts are merely symptoms of the truly devistating<br>
disease of sin.  No matter how successful we are in treating those<br>
symptoms, if we do not treat the underlying disease, it will keep<br>
cropping up in other areas of our lives and eventually, it will kill<br>
us.<br>
<p>
Thus, I believe Justification is not only the legal forgiveness for<br>
our sinful actions, it also provides a cure for the disease of sin.<br>
(A good definition for legalism is "a preoccupation with our legal<br>
standing before God.")  If the disease of sin is cured, we won't have<br>
to worry about the symptoms.<br>
<p>
I would like to see a response from some of the "concerned brethern"<br>
on the net.  Is any consensus possible?<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Gary W. Burdick (burdick@hkuxa.hku.hk)
Department of Physics, University of Hong Kong, Pokfulam Rd, HONG KONG
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
