<title>Apr_1993: RE:  Maxwell's letter</title>
<h1>RE:  Maxwell's letter</h1>
Russell Grau (<i>reg@ctshp.celtech.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 30 Mar 1993 11:53:57 -0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#33">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#33">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#33">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#33">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Steven Timm: "Re: SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0032.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: What is AntiChrist ?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve writes......<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;The church service is now a be-all and end-all for many church members</i><br>
<i>&gt;who have not gone to church school, don't study a Sabbath School lesson, </i><br>
<i>&gt;don't go to prayer meeting.  The pastor is forced to meet many more needs</i><br>
<i>&gt;in less allotted time.  Theological expositions have had to give way to the </i><br>
<i>&gt;more basic remedial work.  It's not uncommon for pastors to have to spend</i><br>
<i>&gt;the first year of their three at a church in remedial work, healing disputes,</i><br>
<i>&gt;convincing people that God even loves them.  During this time outreach </i><br>
<i>&gt;is practically impossible.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
This may be true.  The real question could be, "Why is it true?"  More or less,<br>
the chicken and the egg arguement.  "Which came first?  The lack of study by<br>
the membership or the lack of leadership by the local elder/minister team?"  <br>
<p>
(Not placing blame, just wondering out loud about what Steve and I have seen<br>
 in different parts of the country)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;(Some, including me, would say that outreach is the only effective</i><br>
<i>&gt;remedy.  But I digress).</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;The theological renaissance of the SDA church can only come if we first</i><br>
<i>&gt;have a renaissance in the home unit and place people in a position where</i><br>
<i>&gt;they are emotionally ready to receive the gospel.  One of the chief problems</i><br>
<i>&gt;that we face in the church today is that people relate to God exactly </i><br>
<i>&gt;like they relate to their father, and both relationships are dysfunctional.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Steve Timm</i><br>
<p>
It also must come from our leadership.  If our leadership refuses to trust the<br>
membership, dictates conditions of membership, does not believe that the members<br>
are competent to be part of major efforts, well, it's not going to happen.<br>
<p>
Sermons are to inspire AND teach.  We should want to be part of the "church<br>
invisible" and not just good bench warmers.  This is a dual problem for the<br>
SDA church.  The services need to be such that bench warming is no longer an<br>
option in our churches.  EVEN if the tithe is dropping like a rock.  By the <br>
same token, the leadership is going to be REQUIRED to provide meaningful<br>
opportunities to serve.<br>
<p>
This spring our church had an evangelistic series (didn't yours  :-)) and if<br>
there were not enough positions to serve physically, there was a prayer group<br>
that was going on in the back room, every night, every minute of the night<br>
during the meetings.<br>
<p>
We need, as members to demand that opportunities be made available.  If they <br>
cant be made available through the local church, then WE must make them.<br>
<p>
God and us may hold the leadership to a higher standard, but, does He not also<br>
hold you and I to a higher standard than other Christians?  On this network<br>
we can do much to share and encourage each other.  I would like to see more<br>
of that.<br>
<p>
I would also like to hear from others about their ideas for service.  What you<br>
are doing locally.  How it works, the problems that you have had.  After all,<br>
why re-invent the wheel in every church?  Also, why stay with the canned <br>
programs that haven't worked?<br>
<p>
Hmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmm????????????????<br>
<p>
All thoughts welcome and appreciated.<br>
<p>
