<title>Apr_1993: SDA: Maxwell</title>
<h1>SDA: Maxwell</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 30 Mar 93 14:54:26 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#23">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#23">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#23">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#23">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Why the SDA Church needs Lukewarm Couch Potatoes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Maxwell's letter"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It seems as though one of the main points of Maxwell's letter has<br>
gone by without comment.  What are some thoughts on Maxwell's claim that<br>
the attack on the independent ministries was really an attack on <br>
conservatism in general.  He saw this because there has not been a reprimand<br>
of some liberal ministries and individuals.  I do not believe he said this<br>
directly, but this is what I gleaned from his letter.<br>
<p>
I guess I should change the word attack to a less explosive word.<br>
<pre>
-- 
<p>
"All things are possible to him that believeth."
<p>
Sherman H. Cox, II       scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu
