<title>Apr_1993: Re: SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins</title>
<h1>Re: SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 31 Mar 1993 00:12:26 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#34">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#34">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#34">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#34">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "To be or not to be"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Russell Grau: "RE:  Maxwell's letter"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0025.html">Dan Blake: "SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dan Blake comments on my opposition to teaching creationism in public<br>
schools, and asks if I would ban any teaching on origins for the same<br>
reason.<br>
I do feel that people such as Carl Sagan ought to be muzzled from making <br>
epistemological statements, whilst claiming the authority of a scientist.<br>
Evolution as well as creation often transcends the realm of science<br>
in the claims that are made in the name of science.  I support the<br>
teaching of science that relates to the data at hand.  If there is<br>
evidence that supports a young earth, it ought not to be suppressed. <br>
<p>
It is, however, difficult to talk about Creation Science without<br>
referring to a Creator.  Without the Creator, creation science has no<br>
meaning  (neither does evolutionary science have any meaning without a<br>
creator).  Some sample curricula do exist for public schools to discuss<br>
creation evidence.  In some years the church school I went to used a<br>
creationist Biology textbook.  But the Biology teacher (a<br>
creation-believing SDA minister, I might add)<br>
abandoned this text for a more conventional one mainly because the<br>
textbook was not of as good a quality.  I can see how the creationist<br>
evidence<br>
can be covered effectively in a church school classroom, but I don't know<br>
how this could be done in a public school classroom.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
