<!-- body="start" -->
I've always understood the three angels' messages as a God-inspired call<br>
back to THE GOSPEL ... that is, the true Apostolic Gospel.  The imagery<br>
of the three angels in mid-heaven is designed to denote the urgency of the<br>
times, given that entrance has been made into the "time of the end" of<br>
Daniel 12 -- but the Gospel message remains unchanged -- Jesus Christ, the<br>
same yesterday, today, and forever.<br>
<p>
<p>
On 31 Mar 1993 PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Paul claimed to be preaching the gospel, in fact, the *only* gospel, yet he</i><br>
<i>&gt; had no knowledge of the three angels' messages, at least he didn't refer to</i><br>
<i>&gt; them. I have heard people say that they believe the three angels' messages</i><br>
<i>&gt; are part of the gospel, but I'm not sure that I feel comfortable with that</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the light of what Paul had to say. I'm just not sure whether we're not</i><br>
<i>&gt; redefining "gospel" to suit our own understanding of what the people should</i><br>
<i>&gt; hear.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Tony</i><br>
