<title>Apr_1993: re: SDA: Lukewarm worshippers</title>
<h1>re: SDA: Lukewarm worshippers</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 31 Mar 93 10:36:35 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#55">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#55">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#55">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#55">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0056.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Why the SDA Church needs Lukewarm Couch Potatoes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0054.html">94POLLOK%CUA.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Re: To the editor of this list"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0019.html">Steven Timm: "SDA: Lukewarm worshippers"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Dan Blake writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; I am forced to believe this is tongue-in-cheek humor.</i><br>
My conclusion also.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; believe what they are saying.</i><br>
Maybe...<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The stated conclusion is wrong: the church does not need lukewarm</i><br>
<i>&gt; worshippers and is better off without them (1John 2:19).</i><br>
<p>
Ultimately true; however, are there principles in Mat 13:24-30,36-43<br>
(which refers to the world) which apply to the church?   Granted, an<br>
application seems difficult, since the parable suggests that there are but<br>
wheat and tares.  However, I think the Scriptures indicates that some "tares"<br>
become "wheat" (Rom 5:10, Col 1:21) and the final and forever determination<br>
for those yet living occurs just before Christ's return (Rev 22:11).<br>
<p>
A good question is:  Per Rev 3:15, how can we encourage one another to<br>
become "hot", to quit straddling the fence, to stop being mugwumps,<br>
to purify our hearts and lives from double mindedness (James 1:8, 4:8)<br>
(trying to have it both ways, God's and the world's), to serve God with<br>
our whole hearts (Mark 12:33; 2 Chr 15:15; Ps 119:2,34; Jer 24:7),<br>
holding nothing back from full surrender (2 Chr 16:9a)?<br>
<p>
Oh so regretably, truth-bearers sometimes fail the standard of Eph 4:15,<br>
1 Pet 1:22, and 1 John 3:18.  But truth itself is not divisive among<br>
truth-lovers (John 16:13, 17:21); in the general body, it reveals those<br>
who are "hot" and those who are "cold" (Heb 4:12).  Sunshine (cf Rom 5:5)<br>
upon clay makes clay hard (cf Heb 3:8,15); sunshine upon wax melts it.<br>
Of what is your heart and mine?<br>
<p>
As the time of Christ's return nears, we need to examine our hearts<br>
(1 Cor 11:28a, 1 Pet 4:17), confess our stubborn, rebel heart (Ps 106:6,<br>
Dan 9:3-19), humble ourselves (2 Chr 7:14, 34:27; Prov 16:19; Isa 57:15;<br>
Luke 18:14; Col 3:12; James 4:6,10; 1 Pet 5:5,6), so that the things<br>
that break God's heart break ours also (Joel 2:13).<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
