<title>Apr_1993: RE: SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins</title>
<h1>RE: SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 31 Mar 93 10:53:34 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#52">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#52">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#52">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#52">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Steven Timm: "SDA-L:  Call for working group"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0051.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Why God could never be a successful scientist"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dan Blake writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;If I generalize the focus of your statement to the teaching</i><br>
<i>&gt;of *origins* in public schools, would you still be concerned</i><br>
<i>&gt;about the establishment of religion?</i><br>
<p>
	Yes there should always be a concern.  "Origins"<br>
(including creation) in a general sense _should_ be<br>
taught in public schools.  Zealots on both sides forget that there<br>
are more versions of our origin than one interpretation of creation.<br>
If the teaching is to be done right - in a *public school* setting - ALL<br>
variations of the theme should be taught, encouraging the students<br>
to develop and use critical thinking skills.  While we're at it, our<br>
religion based schools might benefit from presenting alternative<br>
views as well.  The heavens know we need at least one generation<br>
of critical thinkers in the Church. (notice "C")<br>
	In my opinion, there is nothing in the creation theory which<br>
should bar it from classrooms IF it is _just_ an *alternative* view and<br>
not taught as a gospel - the same goes for evolution, and other<br>
versions of origin.  This is the key question: "Are religious groups<br>
seeking to take over public domain with their teachings (to the<br>
exclusion of opposing, or alternative views)?"  Those who've sought to<br>
keep the teaching of creation out completely have been guilty of this<br>
censure- ship of alternative thought.<br>
	Check out your local public school boards.  Are there battles<br>
over teaching origins, sex education, who should be able to teach,<br>
what groups may meet in facilities, prayer in school, taxpayer money<br>
for vouchers to private schools?  If any of these have happened in the<br>
last year, you should know that religious and secular groups are fighting<br>
for "ownership" of public domain, and the training ground for the minds<br>
of this nation.<br>
<p>
MarcusS<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
