On Mar 29, 11:40pm, Steven Timm wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; The church service is now a be-all and end-all for many church members</i><br>
<i>&gt; who have not gone to church school, don't study a Sabbath School lesson,</i><br>
<i>&gt; don't go to prayer meeting.  The pastor is forced to meet many more needs</i><br>
<i>&gt; in less allotted time.  Theological expositions have had to give way to the</i><br>
<i>&gt; more basic remedial work.  It's not uncommon for pastors to have to spend</i><br>
<i>&gt; the first year of their three at a church in remedial work, healing disputes,</i><br>
<i>&gt; convincing people that God even loves them.  During this time outreach</i><br>
<i>&gt; is practically impossible.</i><br>
<p>
I have seen this very thing in our church and others and find it sad that church<br>
members can not get past their looking at each other and criticizing and fueding so<br>
that we can focus on our true mission as a church body.<br>
<p>
I also find it very sad that the church (conference) leadership can not see to it<br>
that the pastors be placed in a district for more than a couple years.  Studies have<br>
shown that a pastor's effectiveness begins after about 5 years, about the time that<br>
he is usually moved.<br>
<p>
Sometimes I wonder if having churches exist that cator to the thinking of groups of<br>
people in that the conservatives all go to one place, the liberals to another, the<br>
moderates to another, etc, may help this fueding.  But then the churches as a whole<br>
will probably fued between each other.  I know the Celebration churches sure take<br>
alot of criticism from the conservatives who are uncomfortable with their worship<br>
style.<br>
<p>
I wish there was an eash solution!<br>
<p>
