<title>Apr_1993: Why God could never be a successful scientist</title>
<h1>Why God could never be a successful scientist</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>31 Mar 1993 16:15:36 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#51">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#51">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#51">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#51">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0050.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Re: SDAnet -- 3 angels"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Thanks for the excellent posts on "why the church needs...". I for one<br>
appreciate a bit of tongue-in-cheek humor, especially if it provides<br>
another non-threatening self-analysis tool!<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Reasons why God never received tenure at the university:<br>
<p>
     1. He only published one manuscript.<br>
     2. And it was in Hebrew.<br>
     3. And it had no references.<br>
     4. It never appeared in a refereed journal.<br>
     5. Some people even question if He wrote it.<br>
     6. Even if He did create the Earth, what has He done/published since.<br>
     7. His collaborative efforts are minimal.<br>
     8. The scientific community has had a difficult time replicating His<br>
        results.<br>
<p>
anonymous<br>
<p>
posted to b.l.c. by Steven Klepzig<br>
shared with SDAnet by Tony &amp; Raylene<br>
