<!-- name="Harvey Brenneise" -->
<!-- email="brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- subject="SDA:  The GC and the Internet" -->
<!-- id="9303312151.AA08158@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Apr_1993: SDA:  The GC and the Internet</title>
<h1>SDA:  The GC and the Internet</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 31 Mar 1993 16:51:10 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "To be or not to be. (cont)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Bruce Holm: "RE:  Maxwell's letter"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0059.html">Trevor Tompkins: "Re: SDA: The GC and the Internet"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As I noted in a post I sent last week, I believe there are a number of<br>
intersting issues at stake involving a potential GC connection to the<br>
Internet.  As Steve correctly stated, one is cost.  Will Internet cost<br>
them less than ATTMail?  I think that it's important to remember that<br>
the Internet is far, far more than e-mail.  As a librarian, I see great<br>
value in telnet and ftp as well.  A commercial e-mail service seems<br>
terribly limiting to me.  I can envision providing information services<br>
here at Andrews that would be of value to the GC, but will only be<br>
available by direct dial or telnet.  I really think accessing SDA-Net<br>
(important as it is!) is really a fairly minor consideration for the GC<br>
in establishing Internet connectivity.  There appears to be a very low<br>
level of knowledge in the building about the Internet and what it is.<br>
The young man who is in charge of e-mail (I'm embarrassed to say I<br>
didn't get his name) didn't even know what it is.  Lowell Witz, who is<br>
in charge of that department, was away, but I understand is interested.<br>
<p>
It is my understanding that the GC currently pays about $1700 a month<br>
for ATTMail use.  That's a substantial cost.  It appears that it was<br>
originally designed primarily to allow the "men" (who are on the road a<br>
lot) to stay in touch with their secretaries (we wouldn't insult them by<br>
calling them "droids").  Obviously, this is a very limited use.  There<br>
are still people around (including the president of this university and<br>
at least one editor at the Review) who think computers are for<br>
secretaries and not for them.  We have a big educational job ahead of us<br>
to enlarge the horizons of the GC people.  I always get a fortress<br>
(defensive) feeling when in that building, and this could be a good tool<br>
for creating positive new networks.  There does tend to be something of<br>
a "them" and "us" mentality that I think could be lessened through this<br>
means.  The Internet tends to level the playing field.  There are many<br>
people there who I believe are willing to learn.  What we need is<br>
leadership.  This is an educational opportunity that I hope we don't<br>
miss.  Earlier there was discussion of the possibility of having a<br>
symposium on the church and the Internet.  The place to have the<br>
meeting, it seems to me, is right at the GC.  Unfortunately, each<br>
department of the GC seems to operate autonomously.  An obvious place to<br>
start is with their people in computing.  I believe we now have 2<br>
subscribers to this list from the GC.  I hope this number increases<br>
(particularly the computer people at this point).<br>
<p>
Alan points out that there are a number of avenues of getting into the<br>
Internet in the DC area.  These should be explored.  If the GC and CUC<br>
could do something cooperatively, so much the better (how about the<br>
hospitals in the area?).  The burden shouldn't fall on CUC, which<br>
appears to be in delicate financial help.  Working together, we can<br>
benefit all.<br>
<p>
When I orginally made my statement about the GC and the Internet, I was<br>
not primarily concerned about GC access to SDA-Net.  Again, we can<br>
invite them to join and I think everyone would benefit if some did.  I<br>
don't see it as a gripe session, but as an opportunity to communicate<br>
more effectively.  People will have to decide if they want to get their<br>
mailboxes "flooded" with SDA-Net mail or not.  When we post now to<br>
SDA-Net, I think we have to assume that it can go anywhere and to<br>
anyone.  This is not a secret organization.  I hope people wouldn't feel<br>
threatened by having more people at the GC "listening."  It needs to<br>
continue to be an open forum.  I was really sorry that DaveB's Sabbath<br>
School class feels "censored" by the church.  I'm happy that mine (a<br>
fairly liberal class in a fairly conservative church) does not.<br>
<p>
One final word on where SDA-Net fits in the "SDA Spectrum" (pun not<br>
intended).  Obviously we're not an official organization (and thus not<br>
listed in the _SDA Yearbook_ or conference directory).  We really don't<br>
fit with ASI either (which also publishes a directory, which<br>
unfortunately is only available to members) because we're not a<br>
business.  We fit, I believe, with those other "special interest" groups<br>
like the SDA professional and interest associations (Association of SDA<br>
Nurses or Adventist Horsemen's Association)--people with similar<br>
interests who are friendly toward the church and are generally<br>
supportive.  Currently there is no directory of such organizations that<br>
I am aware of.  Bill Johnsson at the _Review_ plans a special issue for<br>
the fall which will include information about such groups.  I hope we<br>
can get something in there.  I'm also working on a directory of SDA<br>
associations for publication there.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
