<title>Apr_1993: SDA: Verbal inspiratio vs dictation</title>
<h1>SDA: Verbal inspiratio vs dictation</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>31 Mar 1993 17:21:19 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#39">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#39">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#39">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#39">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: SDA: Maxwell"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: How to answer a CB"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0060.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: SDA: Verbal inspiratio vs dictation"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here is another paragraph taken from that book by Carson that I have<br>
quoted from previously here. This one is to do with verbal inspiration,<br>
and the reason I am posting it is that those opposed to verbal inspiration<br>
have tended to portray it as "dictation". If Carson's definition is indeed<br>
that held by the pro-verbal-inspiration people within the SDA church, then<br>
their position has been oversimplified by those wishing to discredit them.<br>
(A common and effective tactic used by everybody from salesmen and politicians<br>
right through.) Anyway, here it is.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
quote....<br>
<p>
It is extremely important to understand what is meant, and what is not meant,<br>
by saying that the Bible "as originally written...is verbally and plenarily<br>
inspired." &lt;Baptist articles of faith&gt;  "Plenarily" means "fully." "Verbally"<br>
means that the inspiration extends even to the words written. In passing, I<br>
should point out that "verbally" does not entail the conclusion that the <br>
Bible was dictated by God. Most of it, according to its own witness, was not<br>
given in so immediate a fashion. Hence it is possible to distinguish betweem\<br>
the writing style of, say, Paul, and that of John. However, the inclusion of<br>
the word "verbally" is designed to protect us from vague notions of inspiration<br>
that suggest the human authors "felt inspired" or were "inspired" as to the<br>
general drift but not in the detail, or that their writings witness to the<br>
inspiration of their authors. In fact, divine inspiration so operated that<br>
even where the human authors were hammering out their own deeply felt and<br>
very personal concerns (for example, II Cor 10-13), the result was<br>
theopneustos, God-breathed (II Tim 3:16) even to the detail of the words<br>
used.<br>
<p>
unquote...<br>
<p>
<p>
The other alternative is that this passage may be designed to allow Baptists<br>
to believe in "thought inspiration" without feeling that they have violated<br>
their articles of faith. Does this summarize the position of the SDAs who<br>
believe in verbal inspiration, do you think, or do they believe the <br>
scriptures were dictated?<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
