<title>Apr_1993: Re: How to answer a CB</title>
<h1>Re: How to answer a CB</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 31 Mar 93 18:52:54 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#38">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#38">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#38">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#38">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "SDA: Verbal inspiratio vs dictation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: 3 angels"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0074.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: How to answer a CB"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tony writes:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; So my questions on "how to answer a cb" would include "what do you say to a</i><br>
<i>&gt; person who says that transgression of law is the only definition of sin".</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Nothing really, I'd agree :^).<br>
<p>
Gary Writes :<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I agree that this is the fundamental divisive question.  If we cannot</i><br>
<i>&gt;come to an agreement on the definition of sin, then it really is</i><br>
<i>&gt;pointless to discuss many of the other divisive questions such as the</i><br>
<i>&gt;nature of Christ.  This is a question that I have been struggling</i><br>
<p>
How very true.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;with for some time.  Unfortunately, judging from the lack of responses</i><br>
<i>&gt;to Tony's question, no one else seems to have a good answer either.</i><br>
<p>
A good answer to counter a CB ? Well I might suggest some but then I'd <br>
have to resort to some other authority other than the bible (such as<br>
St. Augustine). In which case any self respecting CB would reject it outright.<br>
<p>
Of course I would have some good answers to go the other way, but I'm<br>
sure not very many would be interested in hearing them. They would'nt<br>
be as exciting as Anti-CB calibre material.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I would like to see a response from some of the "concerned brethern"</i><br>
<i>&gt;on the net.  Is any consensus possible?</i><br>
<p>
Where are they ? arn't they all supposed to be retired ministers ?<br>
I didn't know any of them had net access. I wonder who could be refered<br>
to here ? umm,..<br>
<p>
It seems to be plight of the CBs that they have learnt the hard way that many<br>
times it just isn't worth the effort, no body really takes any notice<br>
of them anyway (esp. over here), and when they do, its not to throw<br>
flowers at them either. <br>
<p>
Alas I don't particularly want to get involved in another protracted<br>
discussion at the moment so I'll keep quiet (and make many people happy).<br>
<p>
As for consensus, I can't see it on the horizon, you can't have it <br>
both ways you know. Your entire theology stands or falls on your definition<br>
of sin, if you chose one definition one would do well to see where it leads.<br>
In one case it leads to things such as the immaculate conception and child<br>
baptism etc. In the other it leads to victory over sin.<br>
<p>
How about we all sit down with ZERO presumptions and ask God to lead<br>
our study of His Word, to find out the truth, not to gather arguments<br>
but to really seek truth, with a willing mind to leave aside any cherished<br>
interpretation that is not clearly supported by scripture. God will lead<br>
and teach those who are willing to be taught of Him.<br>
<p>
In fact its even easier than that get out your EGW index and find what <br>
EGW says is the ONLY definition for sin. That is unless of course you might<br>
feel that this is one of those cultural matters. Or that in this instance<br>
EGW's level of inspiration wasn't quite 100%.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
