<title>Apr_1993: Re: Gentry's halos</title>
<h1>Re: Gentry's halos</h1>
<i>ronswen@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 31 Mar 93 23:26:26 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#261">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#261">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#261">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#261">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0262.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Terrible Lizards."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0260.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: Gentry's halos"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve:<br>
I could not help but reply to some of the comments made to suggesting that 1)<br>
the atmosphere had a higher oxygen content previously ("* Dinosaur<br>
cardiovascular system could not have supported much activity in our<br>
atmosphere.  Must have had X2+ density and more oxygen") and 2) that this<br>
promotes greater health and/or longer life ("* Hospitals today that have<br>
hyperbaric chambers -- X2+ pressure and higher oxygen -- result in much<br>
faster healing rates").<br>
<p>
Oxygen is necessary for aerobic metabolism but is a cellular toxin requiring<br>
special enzymes and mechanisms for dealing with it.  It is not a longevity<br>
agent nor can higher O2 levels promote health except in specific disease<br>
states where inadequate oxygen is present in the organism (such as lung<br>
disease).  When high levels of O2 are given, the risks include lung damage<br>
(due to oxygen free radical formation during reaction with cellular proteins)<br>
and, particularly in premature infants requiring long-term oxygen, blindness.<br>
 To suggest that a higher atmospheric O2 level would promote longer life or<br>
greater strength is simply not correct.  In general oxygen is a toxin to<br>
living organisms, necessary for aerobic metabolism only and carefully<br>
neutralized to prevent the rapid cellular damage uncontrolled oxygen can<br>
cause.<br>
<p>
I add my voice to Steve's asking that we Christians use our scientific data<br>
accurately regarding things such as Creation.  If we are ill-informed about<br>
our topic we risk sounding like the National Enquirer!<br>
<p>
Thanks for reading,<br>
Ron Swensen<br>
(ron swen@aol.com)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
