<title>Apr_1993: SDA-L:  Call for working group</title>
<h1>SDA-L:  Call for working group</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+%ANDREW.CMU.EDU%CMU.EDU@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>31 Mar 1993 23:27:20 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#53">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#53">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#53">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#53">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0054.html">94POLLOK%CUA.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Re: To the editor of this list"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: SDA: Religious liberty vs. teaching origins"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
La Sierra University is now well-networked, and Enoch Hwang (co-founder<br>
and soft-spoken listowner of this list) would like to move SDA-L<br>
there to orion.lasierra.edu, a machine for which he is directly responsible.<br>
This requires unix-based LISTSERV software.  Some people sent me a veritable<br>
cornucopia of info on this a few months back, unfortunately I was forced<br>
to delete it due to a disk space crunch.  If this information could be<br>
reproduced and sent to me (st0o@andrew.cmu.edu) or Enoch (UNCEHW@LLUVM.Bitnet<br>
or enoch@orion.lasierra.edu), we'd appreciate it much.<br>
<p>
SDAnet formed a small working board a while ago to discuss technical issues<br>
and list policy.  I think it would be good for SDA-L to do the same.  The<br>
time is almost right for a good special-niche list to start up.  If we<br>
can find that niche effectively and keep the traffic low, it would become<br>
a good place for people to land who drop SDAnet due to high traffic.<br>
Jerome Grimmer expressed his interest to help a while ago.  If Jerome<br>
is still interested, and if others are interested, they should let me know,<br>
or post to the list saying so.  I think that SDA-L board people should be<br>
subscribers to SDA-L in their own right and not just receiving the feed<br>
through SDAnet.  (of course any SDAnet person can join, set  NOMAIL, and<br>
fulfill that requirement.)  Also the SDA-L board shouldn't include any<br>
members of the current SDAnet board.<br>
<p>
What if SDA-L added to its current (very low traffic) menu of support and<br>
fellowship issues a feature of late-breaking SDA news?  (This is more<br>
appropriate for an unmoderated newsgroup than a bunched, moderated SDAnet).<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
