<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Several respondents have mentioned "the original gospel" as something</i><br>
<i>&gt; distinct from the SDA message without saying what this may be.  Care to</i><br>
<i>&gt; enlighten us?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
The original Gospel can be summed up in one word: <br>
<p>
Judaism<br>
<p>
Think about it.  They were first  to champion the Sabbath, connecting it<br>
with Creation, and upholding the<br>
primacy of a Creator (instead of the wannabe idols of the time).  Both<br>
Paul and James cite Abraham as the model for dealings between God and<br>
man.  Jesus went through all the Jewish rituals Himself, from<br>
circumcision to Passover (let's not forget that the Last Supper was<br>
really a Passover seder).  In fact Jesus made it quite clear, in the<br>
punchline to the parable of the Rich Man and Lazarus, that if someone<br>
doesn't pay attention to Moses and the Prophets not even the fact of<br>
someone coming back from the dead would phase them.<br>
<p>
Then again, I converted to Adventism because it was the most Jewish of<br>
the Christian religions I came across.<br>
<p>
One caveat: NO gospel, however original or eloquent, can save anyone.<br>
That's where grace comes in.  But that's another subject.<br>
<p>
Daniel J. Drazen<br>
Editor, SDA Periodical Index<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
