<!-- name="Bill Allen" -->
<!-- email="allen@polaris.lasierra.edu" -->
<!-- subject="SDA: Kushner: To Life" -->
<!-- id="Pine.3.05.9304010931.A11938-b100000@polaris.lasierra.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="sfauBrS00YUoR0AoUE@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<title>Apr_1993: SDA: Kushner: To Life</title>
<h1>SDA: Kushner: To Life</h1>
Bill Allen (<i>allen@polaris.lasierra.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 1 Apr 1993 09:04:32 -0700 (PDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Harvey Brenneise: "RE: SDA: Maxwell (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  To be or not to be"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I looking for someone who has read To Life by Harold Kushner or other<br>
works by Kushner and would like to talk about it.  For some reason I have<br>
always enjoyed Jewish authors such as Heschel, Potok and Kushner (don't<br>
tell on me, Kemmelman).  <br>
<p>
On page xi Kushner says, "The sages teach us that "in time to come,<br>
everyone will have to account for all the good things God created which he<br>
refused to enjoy."  I like that a lot better than what I was reared on,<br>
namely, that in the judgment one would have to account for every penny that<br>
came into our posession.<br>
<p>
Again on page 14 he plucks a responsive chord in me.  "Judaism is less<br>
about believing and more about belonging.  It is less about what we owe<br>
God and more about what we owe each other, because we believe God cares<br>
more about how we treat each other than He does about our theology."  I<br>
always considered myself to be a conservative SDA (perhaps a California<br>
born version of said animal) but then I spent three years on the campus of<br>
Southern College of SDAs as academic v.p.  I came away from the experience<br>
with the belief that if those conservatives treated people they way they<br>
did, their theology must be flawed.  Remember Peters and Waterman (In<br>
Search of Excellence)  if you find coffee stains on the airlines tray<br>
table you begin to wonder about engine maintenance.  <br>
<p>
I like his emphasis on the Jewish faith as family.  By this he means<br>
that even though they may be in complete disagreement, they can never be<br>
separated, because they are genetically family.  A rather nice model of God's<br>
commitment to humanity I would think. In contrast, in Christianity every<br>
time someone has a belief that is somehat different, a new denomination is<br>
created and community is strained if not broken.<br>
<p>
Have a great day.<br>
<p>
Bill Allen  &lt;allen@polaris.lasierra.edu&gt;<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
