Marcus said:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I don't know everything, (thank God), but I do think that there were </i><br>
<i>&gt; two liberal groups</i><br>
<i>&gt; which the General Conference took to court over using the name</i><br>
<i>&gt; "Seventh-day Adventist."  One was/is a church, and the other a support group.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; This seems to be a repremand in my thinking.  How many more "liberal" groups</i><br>
<i>&gt; would Maxwell like to see repremanded?</i><br>
<p>
The two groups that the GC sued for trademark infringement were SDA<br>
Kinship, a support group for SDA gays and lesbians, and an independent<br>
church in Hawaii.  Kinship could probably fall in the category "liberal"<br>
but I believe the Hawaiian church was at the other end of the spectrum.<br>
Neither of these was particularly related to theology specifically<br>
although it might be argued that the church is embarrassed by Kinship<br>
and thus wants to distance itself from them.  Maxwell stated his<br>
"enemy," the Association of Adventist Forums and its journal _Spectrum_.<br>
There really aren't that many organized groups on the left side of Adventism.<br>
<p>
Harvey<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
