<title>Apr_1993: Re: How to answer a CB</title>
<h1>Re: How to answer a CB</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 1 Apr 93 13:35:12 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#74">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#74">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#74">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#74">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: To be or not to be"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0073.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: To be or not to be. (cont)"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0038.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: How to answer a CB"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; As for consensus, I can't see it on the horizon, you can't have it </i><br>
<i>&gt; both ways you know. Your entire theology stands or falls on your definition</i><br>
<i>&gt; of sin, if you chose one definition one would do well to see where it leads.</i><br>
<i>&gt; In one case it leads to things such as the immaculate conception and child</i><br>
<i>&gt; baptism etc. In the other it leads to victory over sin.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I agree with Ruben.  A whole lot hinges on your definition of sin.  As Ruben<br>
has stated, the answer to this question can lead to very different paths.  If<br>
there is any chance of consensus, you would have to start there.<br>
<p>
Ruben talks about the transgression of the law being the only definition<br>
for sin.  Others talk about a condition of sin.  I heard one Oakwood College<br>
theological student say, "Our very being is a sin."  I don't believe Ruben<br>
would doubt that we were born into the world in a bad state.  We were born<br>
into the world apart from Christ which is the only way you can live without<br>
transgression.  We were born apart from our power.  This, however, is very<br>
different than being born guilty of Adams sin.  If being born apart from <br>
power to do what is right is being born into a condition of sin, I would <br>
agree.  If being guilty at birth for someone elses transgression is <br>
being born in a condition of sin, I would not.<br>
<p>
The reason this is important is that in the first case when power comes, so<br>
does obedience.  So victory is possible through the power, not your power.<br>
If the first case is true, victory is not possible, for your living is sin.<br>
<p>
In my second paragraph, I presumed to state what Ruben might believe.  I<br>
guess I shouldn't have.  My connection is slow so I don't want to go up<br>
and erase it.<br>
<p>
Of course this looking at obedience will seem like legalism to some, but<br>
some people think that 1844 is fiction and that the Sanctuary is a face<br>
saving device.  <br>
<p>
I don't know whether I am a  CB.  Perhaps someone could tell me.<br>
<p>
bye bye<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
"Competition is the law of the jungle.
 Cooperation is the law of civilization."  -  Eldridge Cleaver
<p>
Sherman H. Cox, II       scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
