<title>Apr_1993: Re: To be or not to be</title>
<h1>Re: To be or not to be</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 1 Apr 93 14:02:35 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#69">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#69">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#69">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#69">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0070.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Don't pester the pastor"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: SDA: The GC and the Internet"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0035.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "To be or not to be"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben quotes the charter for Soc.Religion.Christian.bible-study<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; d       The universal sinfulness and guilt of human nature since the </i><br>
<i>&gt;         fall, rendering man subject to God's wrath and condemnation.</i><br>
<p>
	Some of us would agree, but I do not believe in any guilt coming to<br>
	all of human nature as a result of the fall.  We all partake of the <br>
	fall when we sin, as all of us have done.  All of us except one<br>
	that is.  I should say we all take part of the guilt from the fall<br>
	when we sin.<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; f       Redemption from guilt, penalty and power of sin only through the </i><br>
<i>&gt;         sacrificial death once and for all time of our representative and </i><br>
<i>&gt;         substitute, Jesus Christ, the only mediator between God and man.</i><br>
	Redemed by his death, saved by his life.  Yeah he died once as our<br>
	substitute.  Yes he is our mediator.  Actually as mediator he is<br>
	our priest.  When we talk about priest we talk about the sancutary.<br>
	This is fine, although that "once for all time" might be used to <br>
	attack the sanctuary.  At face value it is all right.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; i       The indwelling of the Holy Spirit in all those thus regenerated, </i><br>
<i>&gt;         producing in them an increasing likeness to Christ in character and </i><br>
<i>&gt;         behaviour, and empowering them for their witness in the world.</i><br>
<p>
	Why is it legalism when a SDA says this, but if anyone else disagrees<br>
	with it he should not be considered evangilical.  This is fine.<br>
	I would probably change the regenerated to being regenerated.<br>
<p>
