<title>Apr_1993: Re: SDA:  The GC and the Internet</title>
<h1>Re: SDA:  The GC and the Internet</h1>
Malcolm Butler (<i>malb@boojum.ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 1 Apr 93 16:31:09 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#80">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#80">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#80">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#80">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0081.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: What is Sin?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Sherman Cox: "SDA: America"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0043.html">Harvey Brenneise: "SDA:  The GC and the Internet"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Harvey Brenneise writes:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;It is my understanding that the GC currently pays about $1700 a month</i><br>
<i>&gt;for ATTMail use.  That's a substantial cost.  It appears that it was</i><br>
<p>
Wow!  I just checked out how much it costs to connect to AARNet as an<br>
"affiliate member".  (AARNet is the Australian Academic and Research<br>
Network, the body which manages Internet connections in Australia.<br>
Non-academic institutions can gain access as affiliate members.)<br>
<p>
NB: All costs given below are in AUSTRALIAN dollars unless indicated.<br>
<p>
Mail-only access starts at $1000/year, stepping up to $4000/year if you<br>
are considered a "high volume user" (over 4Mbytes/month).<br>
<p>
Full Internet access depends on how you connect:<br>
<p>
$5,000 p.a.     dial in at 9.6Kbps or lower<br>
$8,000 p.a.     9.6Kbps capacity - leased line or permanent call<br>
$15,000 p.a.    19.2Kbps  capacity  -  leased  line or permanent call<br>
$25,000 p.a.    48Kbps capacity<br>
$30,000 p.a.    64Kbps capacity<br>
$45,000 p.a.    2Mb capacity<br>
<p>
This buys you the connection rights, you still would have to pay for<br>
your leased line and terminal equipment on top of this.  I'm not<br>
certain how much this would be, but it seems to me to be rather<br>
competitive with $US1700/month in terms of what you can get for your<br>
money.<br>
<p>
There are also at least two commercial email services in Australia, and<br>
a few public access bodies that provide some access.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;originally designed primarily to allow the "men" (who are on the road a</i><br>
<i>&gt;lot) to stay in touch with their secretaries (we wouldn't insult them by</i><br>
<i>&gt;calling them "droids").  </i><br>
<p>
Do I detect a gentle flame?  My step-mother happens to work at the<br>
South Pacific Division.  Her official job title is "secretary", but in<br>
actual fact, about 10% of her work involves what would be described as<br>
secretarial duties anywhere else.  Hence, we prefer to call her an<br>
executive consultant.  So I'm no stranger to the plight of secretaries<br>
in our institutions.<br>
<p>
I could also defend myself by saying that I was applying the term to<br>
White House staff, but I suspect that wouldn't help my case.  Regardless,<br>
I unreservedly apologise if anyone found the term insulting.<br>
<p>
<p>
Malcolm<br>
<pre>
-- 
Switched Networks Research Centre,               malb@ee.uts.edu.au
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia            +61 2 330 2344
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
