<!-- body="start" -->
Steve,<br>
<p>
I think the internet services provided by telnet/ftp/talk are important, quite<br>
above and beyond e-mail.  Joining the internet will be moderately expenisve,<br>
and Folkenberg, et al, need to see just what is happening with the schools,<br>
'cuz NREN is going to be a basis for most academies and colleges and even<br>
one-room schools to communicate...  The conferences need to be in on this,<br>
if for no other reason than education departments consume the vast majority<br>
of conference budget/time/etc. That in turn argues for union/division level<br>
commitment, etc.  Its also a good way to communicate/share globally.<br>
<p>
Thus my query as to whether CUC is really on the net, since the GC<br>
obviously isn't...  It would also help to get the MIS types from a large<br>
number of conferences/unions present, since many of them are supporting<br>
far-flung s/w empires, etc.<br>
<p>
Frankly, I'd guess we could get more than a hundred warm bodies together<br>
without trying very hard, even with the fiscal crises all around.<br>
<p>
<p>
[As mentioned here before, CUC's connection is a mail-only connection,<br>
even though they have a domain address.  SCT]<br>
