<title>Apr_1993: Long-term visitors</title>
<h1>Long-term visitors</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu,  1 Apr 1993 22:40:01 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#83">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#83">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#83">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#83">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: To be or not to be"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0082.html">CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0097.html">darrell tinker: "Re: Long-term visitors"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This phenomenon has always been with us, but in recent years it seems to be<br>
increasing in numbers.  I speak of people who are not members of the <br>
Seventh-day Adventist church, and yet attend church services regularly, more<br>
so than some of the members.  In many cases they are fully integrated into <br>
the social life, and sometimes even the ministry of the church.<br>
<p>
There are two major reasons I can discern that these people come to the SDA <br>
church.<br>
<p>
1)  Assent to the doctrine of the Sabbath but not to other parts of SDA <br>
teachings.  <br>
<p>
2)  Following a spouse and/or children that are members of the church.<br>
<p>
Are there others?  Does this phenomenon show that Adventists are starting <br>
to put more stress on *belong* and less on *believe* and *behave*?  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm <br>
----------------<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
