<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Are SDAs evangelical, without knowing it ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Should we all just be Seventh Day Baptists ?</i><br>
<p>
Well, i've seen the SDA church defined in a cyclopaedia as:<br>
<p>
Seventh-day Adventists: an evangelical Prostant denomination observing the<br>
divinely ordained Seventh-day Sabbath of the fourth commandment rather than<br>
the first day of the week, for which there is no Biblical authority, and<br>
ardently looking for the second comming of Christ to right all earth's<br>
wrongs.<br>
<p>
-Pears Cyclopaedia, 65th edition, page 679<br>
<p>
(I think that is a very good definition, especially coming from a non-SDA<br>
source) So i always thought we were evangelical Prostetants. Recently<br>
though, i've heard talk that we're not evangelicals and we're not<br>
Protestants (or Papists for that matter), but it doesn't really matter to<br>
me. I suppose it depends on what you take these words to mean. After all,<br>
God knows, we are what we are, no matter what we're called. The Methodists<br>
got that name because people called them names, and that was one of them,<br>
the quakers got called that because of their quaking, others got their names<br>
from their founders. What does it matter anyhow. Well, i hope we live up to<br>
our name.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
