<!-- body="start" -->
On: Wed, 31 Mar 93 18:52:54 EST, ruben@ee.uts.edu.au (Ruben Gonzalez) wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Tony writes:</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; So my questions on "how to answer a cb" would include "what do you say to a</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; person who says that transgression of law is the only definition of sin".</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Nothing really, I'd agree :^).</i><br>
<p>
Sorry, what is a CB ?  I forgot.<br>
Anyway, to that person, i'd say that there is seldom, if ever, only exactly<br>
one way to define something, especially a concept like sin. This is because<br>
different people see it from different perspectives and emphasize different<br>
facets of it. All the views might be correct, albeit they be views beheld<br>
from different angles, because the thing being defined is always there, the<br>
same thing.<br>
	So, sin is "the transgression of the law" but also, "whatsoever is<br>
not of faith is sin" and "The sting of death is sin" and "all wrongdoing<br>
(unrighteousness) is sin and there is sin not unto death" and "sin is a<br>
reproach to any people"<br>
	Actually, most definitions of things, if they are good ones, will not<br>
contradict each other, when properly understood.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;Gary Writes :</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;I agree that this is the fundamental divisive question.  If we cannot</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;come to an agreement on the definition of sin, then it really is</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;pointless to discuss many of the other divisive questions such as the</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;nature of Christ.  This is a question that I have been struggling</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;How very true.</i><br>
<p>
How true indeed. Ok then, what is sin?<br>
Is sin an act to be committed? Is it a state of being? On who does the blame<br>
for sin fall? Who is to be held accountable, and under what circumstances?<br>
<p>
These are quite important, as the idea of salvation depends on the idea of<br>
sin to be saved from.<br>
<p>
I'll leave you all to think about it.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
