<title>Apr_1993: Aron &amp; Hur Club</title>
<h1>Aron &amp; Hur Club</h1>
<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 02 Apr 93 08:38:54 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#95">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#95">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#95">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#95">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Reply to Bill Allen"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0094.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: SDA: Kushner: To Life"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0131.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Aaron &amp; Hur Club"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have not attended a Aron &amp; Hur club sermon yet.  Its sweeping through<br>
this conference.  The emphasis seems to be on Moses being the pastor<br>
and Aron and Hur the church members.  Club membership equates to<br>
supporting your local pastor (and conference).  And so its not<br>
appropriate for the pastor to preach the sermon.<br>
<p>
But, my wife has been studying the topic from EGW.<br>
<p>
 Moses -- the prophet with his arms reaching out to God.<br>
<p>
 Aron  -- the ordained ministry (priesthood).<br>
<p>
 Hur   -- the laymen of the church (one of the artisans).<br>
<p>
A big reason for starting up these clubs is to try and get people<br>
to quit complaining about the pastors no longer supporting EGW, or<br>
serious Bible truths.  The idea is that the pastor should be free<br>
to preach anything he wants without getting hassled.  But the real<br>
symbolism seems to be quite the opposite.<br>
<p>
Dave<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
