<!-- body="start" -->
On Thu, 1 Apr 1993, Sherman Cox wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I have a question regarding the place of the United States of America in</i><br>
<i>&gt; Prophecy.  Our present, traditional view holds that america is a lamb-like</i><br>
<i>&gt; beast who will talk like a dragon.  Would we say it is a Beast, or it will</i><br>
<i>&gt; become a beast.</i><br>
<p>
In my understanding of it, a beast in prophecy represents a world power,<br>
and therefore America is currently a "lamb-like beast" that, according to<br>
Revelation, is destined to become a dragon-like beast.  <br>
<p>
Interestingly, I read an article yesterday from a recent issue of Time<br>
magazine, which describes many of the emergency governance plans that the<br>
U.S. had prepared in case of a nuclear strike by the former Soviet Union. <br>
The plans called for measures that severely curtailed many of our<br>
dearly-held constitutional rights.  To me, the article was a striking<br>
reminder, despite the apparently solidity of our governmental<br>
institutions and our freedoms, of how precarious our rights as<br>
American citizens really are.<br>
<p>
In a time of "national emergency," the lamb becomes a dragon in a matter<br>
of hours and a "lifeboat" mentality kicks in.<br>
<p>
NOE.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
