<title>Apr_1993: Re: SDA: The GC and the Internet</title>
<h1>Re: SDA: The GC and the Internet</h1>
<i>hamstra@orion.cc.andrews.edu</i><br>
<i>Fri, 2 Apr 93 09:51:17 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#93">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#93">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#93">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#93">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0094.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: SDA: Kushner: To Life"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0092.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Info (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;I found very interesting Harvey's comments about the general lack of knowledge</i><br>
<i>&gt;about the Internet on the part of GC "men."  This corresponds with what I</i><br>
<i>&gt;have seen in the past ten years among SDAs in general -- that is, either a</i><br>
<i>&gt;distrust in or a lack of committment toward new computer technologies. </i><br>
.<br>
.<br>
<i>&gt;Have those of you on SDANet had similar experiences?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;NOE@TENET.EDU</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
I am the Microcomputer Services Manager at Andrews University.  We run a<br>
computer store and provide hardware and software support services on<br>
campus.  It has been my observation that students in the Seminary here tend<br>
to be far more computer literate than the graduate student population in<br>
general.  It is quite common to find MDiv students who own portable<br>
computers and cart them around along with their textbooks.  I cannot<br>
comment on what percentage of the Seminary student body this might amount<br>
to but I'm quite certain it's large relative to other student sub groups.<br>
<p>
I've also noticed a similar trend among Seminary faculty.  They seem to get<br>
further beyond the word processing stage than the faculty population in<br>
general, excepting of course Computer Science, Physical Sciences and others<br>
where computers are quite integral.<br>
<p>
The reason I point this out as regards the GC etc. is that I've noticed a<br>
large number GC officiary are Andrews alumni by virtue of the Seminary<br>
being here.  Assuming this trend will continue (perhaps an invalid<br>
assumption), I would say that in about 20 years the GC brass will be fairly<br>
computer literate.  This will probably be about 10 years after the top<br>
management at most major corporations is computer literate.  I suspect<br>
administrative aversion to technology will subside sometime before this<br>
time.  I believed it was mentioned earlier in this thread that the U.S.<br>
government (at least in the White House) also suffers from this problem.<br>
<p>
<p>
dan hamstra<br>
hamstra@andrews.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
