<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0108.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: What is AntiChrist ?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0106.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: SDA: America"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0110.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: SDA: America"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0184.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: The Generation That Forgot God."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The cover story in this week's TIME magazine (April 5, 1993, pp. 45-49)<br>
concerns the return to "religion" on the part of thousands of "Baby<br>
boomers," who, according to the article, had dropped out of church in the<br>
late 60s and on through to the 80s.  <br>
<p>
I read the article with great interest, since it certainly touches on<br>
trends and attitudes that are affecting the Seventh-day Adventist Church.<br>
<p>
The article notes that "increasing numbers of baby boomers who left the<br>
fold years ago are turning religious again, but many are traveling from<br>
church to church or faith to faith, sampling creeds, shopping for a<br>
custom-made God" (p. 45).<br>
<p>
The authors point out that as more and more churches put "marketing<br>
strategies" into effect aimed at luring these baby boomers into their fold<br>
the churches "are at risk of losing their heritage--and their souls" (p. 46).<br>
<p>
According to the article, the baby boomers are most often drawn back to<br>
church by one of two things: (1) having children, or (2) facing a mid-life<br>
personal or career crisis.<br>
<p>
Further, the authors mention that church membership rates between 1965 and<br>
1989 indicate that the "old-line Protestant churches" are rapidly losing<br>
members, whereas the "evangelical churches" (with which the SDAs are<br>
included) have gained considerably.  SDA membership has grown by 92% since<br>
1965, a growth rate exceeded only by the Assemblies of God (121%), the<br>
Mormons (133%), and the Church of God (183%).<br>
<p>
One final interesting quote from the article:  "Though strict, doctrinaire<br>
religion might seem to drive away the tolerance-minded boomers, liberalism<br>
fares even worse.  When the faith replaces firm claims to truth with a<br>
spongy, homemade folk religion, younger members seem to take it as an<br>
invitation to look elsewhere" (p. 47).  The authors conclude that although<br>
the boomers might want flexibility in their worship, they definitely also<br>
want some well-defined moral and religious boundaries.<br>
<p>
I find this last observation of special interest in view of some recent<br>
pressures for the SDA church to "relax" some of our standards in order to<br>
reach out to groups like the boomers.<br>
<p>
