<title>Apr_1993: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit</title>
<h1>Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit</h1>
<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>02 Apr 1993 11:51:52 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#82">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#82">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#82">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#82">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Steven Timm: "Long-term visitors"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0081.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: What is Sin?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0085.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;From: ruben@ee.uts.edu.au (Ruben Gonzalez)</i><br>
<i>&gt;Subject: RE: How to answer a CB</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Your entire theology stands or falls on your definition</i><br>
<i>&gt;of sin, if you chose one definition one would do well to see where it leads.</i><br>
<i>&gt;In one case it leads to things such as the immaculate conception and child</i><br>
<i>&gt;baptism etc. In the other it leads to victory over sin.</i><br>
<p>
I'm really not happy with this assumption that child baptism results from<br>
an understanding of sin. Were the SDA church to decide that sin was definately<br>
not "the transgression of the law" only but instead "a broken relationship<br>
with God"/"an internal state"/etc we would still _never_ end up having<br>
child baptism. So I feel I have to reject that statement outright.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;How about we all sit down with ZERO presumptions and ask God to lead</i><br>
<i>&gt;our study of His Word, to find out the truth, not to gather arguments</i><br>
<i>&gt;but to really seek truth, with a willing mind to leave aside any cherished</i><br>
<i>&gt;interpretation that is not clearly supported by scripture. God will lead</i><br>
<i>&gt;and teach those who are willing to be taught of Him.</i><br>
<p>
I had a Sabbath School teacher a few years ago who taught our youth class<br>
in no uncertain terms that the Holy Spirit would lead all people who studied<br>
the Bible to the truth. And regardless of how many people honestly studied <br>
the Bible, they would all come up with the same conclusions due to the leading<br>
of the Holy Spirit.<br>
But what if they don't?<br>
Well "obviously" someone is not being lead by the Holy Spirit!<br>
<p>
The reality of the situation is that there *are* differences in what <br>
people discover - and to the observer it seems impossible to distinguish<br>
WHICH of these people is lead by the Holy Spirit and WHICH is not! (The<br>
worst thing being when a group of people decide that anyone not of their<br>
exact persuasion is of Satan/or something equally terrible and start a<br>
cleansing campaign.) Suppose the Holy Spirit leads them both?<br>
<p>
How do we resolve this dilemma?<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
---*---<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
