<i>&gt;From: bruceh@wv.mentorg.com (Bruce Holm)</i><br>
<i>&gt;Subject: RE:  Maxwell's letter</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I also find it very sad that the church (conference) leadership can not see </i><br>
<i>&gt;to it</i><br>
<i>&gt;that the pastors be placed in a district for more than a couple years.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;Studies have</i><br>
<i>&gt;shown that a pastor's effectiveness begins after about 5 years, about the </i><br>
<i>&gt;time that</i><br>
<i>&gt;he is usually moved.</i><br>
<p>
I have an Uncle who has been in a church for &gt; 10 yrs and seems to be doing<br>
OK. He's built a new church and really progressed. I really do think it is<br>
a good idea for pastors to be in a place for a longer period - even for the<br>
development of social roots etc for their family.<br>
<p>
But we probably should be a bit careful to assess the affectiveness of our<br>
pastors periodically and say "great job" if doing well, sympathize if going<br>
through a hard patch, and "smarten up" if required. I heard that an<br>
independant review had to assess a number of churches over here recently.<br>
Lots of pastors had bought their houses and settled down planning for their<br>
retirement - and effectively retired from anything but maintaining the<br>
status quo in their churches. Now is that sad or what?<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
