<title>Apr_1993: Reply to Bill Allen</title>
<h1>Reply to Bill Allen</h1>
Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473 (<i>jwiley@law.usc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 2 Apr 93 14:17:28 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#96">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#96">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#96">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#96">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0097.html">darrell tinker: "Re: Long-term visitors"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0095.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Aron &amp; Hur Club"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	Perhaps I've been more fortunate than one should reasonably<br>
expect, but almost all of my experience in universities has approached<br>
the ideals of a community of scholars seeking after truth.  Indeed,<br>
I hold that ideal even higher for church-related institutions, and<br>
thus for the faculty, staff and students who are the institution.  <br>
This has always seemed logical to me for both the church and the<br>
university are institutions, associations of people, dedicated to<br>
the pursuit of truth.<br>
<p>
	For the foregoing reason, among others, I was terribly disapointed<br>
to receive a copy of electronic mail sent by "Bill Allen" (according to<br>
the EM address) was was disparaging of his faculty colleagues, as well<br>
as all of the rest of us who serve on the presidential search committee<br>
for La Sierra University.  <br>
<p>
	Without checking his <br>
"facts" with any mmeber of the committee, least of all with its chair-<br>
person, he complained about "secrecy" and asserted that the committee<br>
was on "a short leash and a muzzle."  The fact that the entire membership<br>
of the committee, which is composed of faculty, trustees, an administrator,<br>
and an alumnus, discussed the benefits and burdens of a "closed" process<br>
versus and "open" process as to the names of persons nominated and those<br>
who were willing to become candidates, and voted unanimously for the<br>
closed process as the better for a private SDA institution.  The process<br>
was and is absolutely open to anyone to make a nomination, and all 52<br>
persons nominated have been invited to become candidates by their<br>
choosing to submit resumes.  It is an inclusive process, but we have<br>
no desire to harm the work of people in their present positions by<br>
announcing either that they've been nominated or that they've become<br>
candidates for there can be only one president.  I'd go on, but I'm<br>
not trying to list all of the reasons for choosing the methodology we<br>
chose, rather to illustrate that if "Bill Allen" had been searching<br>
for truth he might have discovered that the committee has/had good<br>
reasons for choosing the process even if he disagreed with our decision.<br>
<p>
	As to the line "has been removed from the committee," the<br>
person in question resigned.<br>
<p>
	As a former newspaper person, I've always preferred named<br>
sources to "authoritative information coming from off campus," and<br>
in the educational setting this seems so out of the character of our<br>
enterprise.  His assertion is simply wrong.  He seems to believe<br>
that his faculty colleagues on the committee, the outside trustees<br>
(those of us who are not employed by the denomination), the alumnus,<br>
would all be puppets lending our names to a decision made by<br>
Big Brother (not likely Big Sister presently).  That is demeaning<br>
to the individuals involved, indeed, it is defamatory.  Anyone<br>
who believes women and men of goodwill, strong convictions, and<br>
lively intellect can be so easily either manipulated or muzzled<br>
misjudges badly both the people and how one gets the best from<br>
good people.  <br>
<p>
	Dr. Larry Geraty did visit LSU.  He has a marvelous c.v.,<br>
and excellent administrative experience.  He is an outstanding<br>
scholar who has managed to make the transition to administration<br>
while holding fast to his scholarly ideals.  The committee was<br>
pleased he wanted to visit the campus.  Somehow I think "Bill<br>
Allen" wants us to apologize for our invitation to Dr. Geraty.<br>
On the contrary, we think the invitation quite justifiable.<br>
<p>
	Thanks for reading, if you struggled thro' the typos<br>
and the long reply.  This mail package, which is temporary,<br>
doesn't brook editing.<br>
<p>
Jerry Wiley<br>
Vice Dean and Professor of Law<br>
University of Southern California<br>
Trustee and Chair of the Presidential<br>
Search Committee for La Sierra University<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
