<title>Apr_1993: Re: To be or not to be</title>
<h1>Re: To be or not to be</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 2 Apr 93 15:16:50 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#84">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#84">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#84">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#84">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Steven Timm: "Long-term visitors"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0058.html">Malachi Robertson: "To be or not to be"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0087.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: To be or not to be"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ok Now I'll tell you all what I think.<br>
<p>
Generally I found them quite good although a bit hazy in some areas, here <br>
are some particular comments<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; d       The universal sinfulness and guilt of human nature since the </i><br>
<i>&gt;         fall, rendering man subject to God's wrath and condemnation.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
This one is too hazy, does this mean guilt as a direct consequence <br>
of Adam's fall, or as an consequece of our sinful acts since the fall ?<br>
You can't have it both ways.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; e       The full deity of the Lord Jesus Christ, the incarnate Son of God; His</i><br>
<i>&gt;         virgin birth and His real and sinless humanity; His death on the </i><br>
<i>&gt;         cross, His bodily resurrection and His present reign in heaven and</i><br>
<i>&gt;         earth.</i><br>
<p>
But Jesus doesn't rein on this earth (ecept in our hearts ) that will only <br>
happen after the 2nd coming the prince of this world is Lucifer, thats why <br>
suffering and death abounds.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; f       Redemption from guilt, penalty and power of sin only through the </i><br>
<i>&gt;         sacrificial death once and for all time of our representative and </i><br>
<i>&gt;         substitute, Jesus Christ, the only mediator between God and man.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Redemptiomn from guild through His death, power over sin through<br>
His resurrection. No resurrection no redemption. Why do some only focus<br>
on His death, Its His life which makes His death of any value. Paul basically <br>
says no resurrection, no salvation.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; i       The indwelling of the Holy Spirit in all those thus regenerated, </i><br>
<i>&gt;         producing in them an increasing likeness to Christ in character and </i><br>
<i>&gt;         behaviour, and empowering them for their witness in the world.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Why is it when we say that we are labelled as legalistic CB's ?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; j       The one holy universal Church, which is the Body of Christ, and to </i><br>
<i>&gt;         which all true believers belong.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
It depends on what this exactly means, ok at face value.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Will all the evangelicals who believe the above be saved ? Yes or No (why)</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
The point about this last question is that believing all of the above<br>
of itself is useless, because I'm certain the devil believes all of that<br>
and much more. Some christians have the idea that belief is all thats<br>
required for salvation. Not so, the life must be in conformity with<br>
the beliefs otherwise the belief is of no effect.<br>
<p>
The question was not meant to be an excuse to sit back and self-righteously<br>
declare all nonSDAs "unclean". Rather it was a point of reflection about<br>
how we view salvation in terms of our belief system. Salvation is always<br>
at an individual level so the answer is NO, not ALL who believe the above<br>
will be saved, what about those who say Lord, Lord we have believed in you ?<br>
Only God knows who will be saved.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
