<title>Apr_1993: Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit</title>
<h1>Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 2 Apr 93 15:59:58 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#85">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#85">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#85">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#85">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0086.html">Steven Timm: "See you at Andrews tomorrow"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: To be or not to be"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0082.html">CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0089.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I'm really not happy with this assumption that child baptism results from</i><br>
<i>&gt; an understanding of sin. Were the SDA church to decide that sin was definately</i><br>
<i>&gt; not "the transgression of the law" only but instead "a broken relationship</i><br>
<i>&gt; with God"/"an internal state"/etc we would still _never_ end up having</i><br>
<i>&gt; child baptism. So I feel I have to reject that statement outright.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Well here's how it works, (for the RCC at least). You are born guilty<br>
of original sin / separate from God / internally at variance with God/ what<br>
ever you like. Now being in this state means that if you die before this<br>
guilt / rebellion / whatever is removed then you die guilty and condemned<br>
to destruction. Accordingly Baptism, which symbolises the removal of the<br>
severed relationship / guilt / you get the idea is a necessary component<br>
for salvation. In this case rather than let a baby die while still guilty<br>
it is better to baptise it and in that way remove the stain due to Adam's<br>
sin.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I had a Sabbath School teacher a few years ago who taught our youth class</i><br>
<i>&gt; in no uncertain terms that the Holy Spirit would lead all people who studied</i><br>
<i>&gt; the Bible to the truth. And regardless of how many people honestly studied </i><br>
<i>&gt; the Bible, they would all come up with the same conclusions due to the leading</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the Holy Spirit.</i><br>
<i>&gt; But what if they don't?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Well "obviously" someone is not being lead by the Holy Spirit!</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
It is one thing to study, and quite another thing to Study !<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The reality of the situation is that there *are* differences in what </i><br>
<i>&gt; people discover - and to the observer it seems impossible to distinguish</i><br>
<i>&gt; WHICH of these people is lead by the Holy Spirit and WHICH is not! (The</i><br>
<i>&gt; worst thing being when a group of people decide that anyone not of their</i><br>
<i>&gt; exact persuasion is of Satan/or something equally terrible and start a</i><br>
<i>&gt; cleansing campaign.) Suppose the Holy Spirit leads them both?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
The H.S leads you into truth and unity, it is impossible for the H.S. to lead<br>
two people to opposite conclusions, the scripture confirms this.<br>
<p>
The H.S may not reveal all the truth to everyone at the same time, He leads<br>
as each indivdual is able to bear, this accounts for some differences of<br>
opinion. It is not correct to say that the H.S. has lead to different <br>
conclusions though. Other differences arise due to placing the <br>
wisdom of man (in whatever context) before the Word of God.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; How do we resolve this dilemma?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
With much study, prayer and fasting, like our church founders did.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
