<i>&gt; the Bible, they would all come up with the same conclusions due to the leading</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the Holy Spirit.</i><br>
<i>&gt; But what if they don't?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Well "obviously" someone is not being lead by the Holy Spirit!</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
It is one thing to study, and quite another thing to Study !<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The reality of the situation is that there *are* differences in what </i><br>
<i>&gt; people discover - and to the observer it seems impossible to distinguish</i><br>
<i>&gt; WHICH of these people is lead by the Holy Spirit and WHICH is not! (The</i><br>
<i>&gt; worst thing being when a group of people decide that anyone not of their</i><br>
<i>&gt; exact persuasion is of Satan/or something equally terrible and start a</i><br>
<i>&gt; cleansing campaign.) Suppose the Holy Spirit leads them both?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
The H.S leads you into truth and unity, it is impossible for the H.S. to lead<br>
two people to opposite conclusions, the scripture confirms this.<br>
<p>
The H.S may not reveal all the truth to everyone at the same time, He leads<br>
as each indivdual is able to bear, this accounts for some differences of<br>
opinion. It is not correct to say that the H.S. has lead to different <br>
conclusions though. Other differences arise due to placing the <br>
wisdom of man (in whatever context) before the Word of God.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; How do we resolve this dilemma?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
With much study, prayer and fasting, like our church founders did.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
