<title>Apr_1993: Is that the question?</title>
<h1>Is that the question?</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>02 Apr 1993 16:08:10 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#88">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#88">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#88">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#88">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: To be or not to be"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
1.	I noticed at the top of the evangelical statement of beliefs the<br>
	word "including". After reading the statement of beliefs and not<br>
	particularly disagreeing with any of the points, I considered that<br>
	any SDA should be able to agree with that list subject to that<br>
	word "including" which was at the top. Most SDAs would wish to add<br>
	a couple of things to the list.<br>
<p>
2.	As Ruben said in a subsequent post, it is not what you believe in<br>
	itself that is sufficient for salvation, so that provides an easy<br>
	"no" to the question "will all ... who believe the above be saved."<br>
<p>
3.	I still believe that it is "relationship", not "doctrine" that<br>
        is the crux of Christianity. And no, this does *not* equate to<br>
	antinomianism or anything similar. The very act of confessing known<br>
	sins to God every day assists in the process of leaving those things<br>
	behind. I think it would be fair to say that any person who confesses<br>
	things to Jesus specifically, with honesty and frankness, will be<br>
	disappointed that they are not living up to His standards. Do we<br>
	believe that the Holy Spirit can transform an "unknown sin" into a<br>
	"known sin"?<br>
<p>
 From my understanding of SDA beliefs, it is the traumatic events immediately<br>
preceding Christ's return that will settle the matter of who is and who is<br>
not truly loyal to Him. It seems a little premature to be looking around now<br>
and asking who will and will not be saved. I firmly believe that there are<br>
many true disciples of Christ in all kinds of various situations, many of<br>
whom we may consider to be quite misled in some of their beliefs. Some of<br>
those people are currently performing a powerful ministry spreading the<br>
news about Christ, and they may be better off staying where they are.<br>
<p>
I don't think we SDAs should lose our distinctive beliefs or our sense of<br>
mission, but I do think our hostility towards other members of God's family<br>
could be toned down or even turned off. The more I read, the more people<br>
I talk to, and the longer I am on SDAnet, the more I am convinced that the<br>
differences within the SDA church are far more related to approach,<br>
attitude and priorities than anything else.<br>
<p>
I might explain further sometime, but this post is long enough already!<br>
btw, thank you all who have replied to my questions regarding the three<br>
angels' messages. All responses have been appreciated!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
