<title>Apr_1993: Definition of CB</title>
<h1>Definition of CB</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>02 Apr 1993 16:25:38 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#91">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#91">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#91">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#91">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0092.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Info (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0090.html">Steven Timm: "Re: SDA: America"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0123.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Definition of CB"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Most of us Aussies only use the term CB to refer to that group of ultra-<br>
conservative SDAs who are active in criticizing church leadership and<br>
church institutions in an aggressive and damaging way. There are many<br>
conservative SDAs here who have sympathies with, or even support, the<br>
various groups of CBs, but would not themselves attract that label.<br>
<p>
No, the label is by no means complimentary, but neither are the CBs a lot<br>
of the time. I think most of you would have met negative, critical conservative<br>
SDAs as well as positive, helpful and constructive conservative SDAs. <br>
<p>
I'm not sure what the label is for a negative, critical liberal SDA, but<br>
I've met some of those too!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
