Steve writes:<br>
<i>&gt; This phenomenon has always been with us, but in recent years it seems to be</i><br>
<i>&gt; increasing in numbers.  I speak of people who are not members of the </i><br>
<i>&gt; Seventh-day Adventist church, and yet attend church services regularly, more</i><br>
<i>&gt; so than some of the members.  In many cases they are fully integrated into </i><br>
<i>&gt; the social life, and sometimes even the ministry of the church.</i><br>
<p>
At my local congregation we have had the privilege of having a young couple<br>
worshiping with us who are from the Church of God, 7th Day.  They came to<br>
Austin because he is working on a PhD at the University of Texas and chose<br>
to worship with us because the local COG, 7th Day is a Spanish speaking<br>
group and they liked the friendly reception they recieved.  They have become<br>
involved in the music and social life of the church.<br>
<p>
I have known some other cases where spouses of members where so involved in<br>
church life, that when they finally decided to be baptized and become members<br>
some people were suprised that they were not already members.<br>
<p>
I don't know that this represents any shift in adventist culture, but I see<br>
it as something positive for both the members and the "visitors".<br>
<p>
-Darrell  darrellt@ross.com<br>
