<title>Apr_1993: end times</title>
<h1>end times</h1>
Gregg Wisdom (<i>gwisdom@hpdmd48.boi.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 2 Apr 93 18:15:56 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#98">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#98">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#98">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#98">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Steven Timm: "Re: end times"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0097.html">darrell tinker: "Re: Long-term visitors"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0099.html">Steven Timm: "Re: end times"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am relatively new to the SDA church.  I became interested in the SDA church<br>
because of its prophetic interpretations.  Over the last year I have read <br>
several books dealing with the SDA view of how the end times will unfold.<br>
The books I have read are:  The Crisis of the End Times--Marvin Moore, Count<br>
down to Showdown--Dwight Nelson, Day of the Dragon--Clifford Goldstein, and<br>
The Antichrist and the New World Order--Marvin Moore.  Although the authors<br>
do not say so explicitly, I get the impression from these books that they<br>
believe the second coming is very close.  When I say close, it is my impression<br>
that they believe it won't go on much longer than the year 2000.  All of these<br>
books attempt to fit trends which the authors have seen occurring in recent <br>
times into what Adventists believe will happen at the end of time (things like<br>
the rising political influence of the Papacy, the U.S. as the sole remaining<br>
superpower, the increase in strength of the religious right in the U.S., etc).<br>
<p>
    <br>
If I were to look back over the last 30 years at the books published by <br>
Adventists about the end times would I see attempts to fit the trends Adventistshave seen in the past to the Adventist end time scenario?  What I mean is, are<br>
these trends that these authors point to really something significant or are<br>
they just another of many attempts to fit current events into our prophetic<br>
scenario?  Maybe somebody who is aware of what we have published in the <br>
past on current events and the end times can enlighten me.<br>
<p>
I have another question.  I have noticed in talking with Adventist young<br>
adults about the end of times and prophecy that they (at least amoung those<br>
I have talked to) are not really all that interested in the topic.  They have<br>
told me that they have heard this stuff almost their entire life (I am talking<br>
about those young adult SDAs who grew up in the church) and they are tired of<br>
hearing about how imminent the second coming is.  Does anybody know if this<br>
feeling is widespread in the North American church?  Has the SDA church <br>
"gone to the well" one too many times with these people <br>
<p>
<p>
about the imminencey of the second coming?  I ask this question because I<br>
wonder if I have gotten caught up too much in second coming fever (with the<br>
approach of the year 2000)only to be disappointed when it doesn't happen <br>
as soon as I am getting the impression it will from reading these books.<br>
I must say that although I do get the impression that these authors believe<br>
the end of time is very close, no where did they set any times of any sort,<br>
so I may be reading more into what they say than was intened by the authors.<br>
<p>
<p>
that they<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
