<title>Apr_1993: The real issues?</title>
<h1>The real issues?</h1>
Noe Torres | ECISD (<i>noe@tenet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 3 Apr 1993 16:24:10 -0600 (CST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#104">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#104">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#104">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#104">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0105.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Strange imagery."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0103.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0120.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The real issues?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I received in the mail today an unsolicited pamphlet from Dr. Ralph Larson of<br>
the independent ministry known as "Steps to Life."  The pamphlet, entitled<br>
"Issues: The Real Issue, the Side Issues, and the Pseudo Issues," is a<br>
rebuttal to the NAD's recent publication, "Issues: The Seventh-day Adventist<br>
Church and Certain Private Organizations."<br>
<p>
I'm wondering how many of you on SDANet have read this publication and what<br>
your thoughts on it are?<br>
<p>
Specifically, how do you feel about Larson's charge that the following five<br>
"historic Adventist doctrines" are being "replaced" by Calvinistic teachings:<br>
<p>
QUOTING FROM THE PAMPHLET:<br>
<p>
1-- The doctrine that we receive weakness from Adam, but not guilt, now<br>
being replaced by the Calvinistic doctrine of original sin defined as<br>
inherited guilt.<br>
<p>
2-- The doctrine that our Lord came to this earth in the human nature of<br>
fallen man, now being replaced by the Calvinistic doctrine that Christ came<br>
to earth in the human nature of the unfallen Adam.<br>
<p>
3-- The doctrine of righteousness by faith, now being replaced by the<br>
Calvinistic doctrine of unrighteousness by presumption, salvation in sin.<br>
<p>
4-- The doctrine of the sanctuary, now being either denied or replaced by<br>
vague uncertainties.<br>
<p>
5-- Belief in the Spirit of Prophecy, now being denied because it supports<br>
all of the Adventist doctrines listed above and firmly rejects the Calvinistic<br>
doctrines.<br>
<p>
END OF QUOTE.<br>
<p>
My own opinion is such that I question many of Larson's assertions and<br>
methods.  I believe he is demanding that something be either black or white,<br>
when it may really be gray.  I believe he is introducing a spirit of<br>
divisiveness and criticism toward the denomination, instead of working to<br>
make positive change.<br>
<p>
I'd like to hear what some of your opinions are.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
