<title>Apr_1993: Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit</title>
<h1>Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit</h1>
Malcolm Butler (<i>malb@boojum.ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 3 Apr 93 23:27:19 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#103">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#103">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#103">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#103">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0104.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "The real issues?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0102.html">Fred Christiansen: "who does baptism preparation"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0089.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Sin and the leading of the Holy Spirit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben Gonzalez writes:<br>
[ about how the definition of sin affects one's belief in child baptism ]<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Well here's how it works, (for the RCC at least). You are born guilty</i><br>
<i>&gt;of original sin / separate from God / internally at variance with God/ what</i><br>
<i>&gt;ever you like. Now being in this state means that if you die before this</i><br>
<i>&gt;guilt / rebellion / whatever is removed then you die guilty and condemned</i><br>
<i>&gt;to destruction. Accordingly Baptism, which symbolises the removal of the</i><br>
<i>&gt;severed relationship / guilt / you get the idea is a necessary component</i><br>
<i>&gt;for salvation. In this case rather than let a baby die while still guilty</i><br>
<i>&gt;it is better to baptise it and in that way remove the stain due to Adam's</i><br>
<p>
There are two things required here: a belief in original sin AND the <br>
belief that the rite of baptism is essential for salvation.  The<br>
legalistic approach comes more from the second belief than from the<br>
first.<br>
<p>
Further, a belief that sin is a state of separation from God does not<br>
automatically imply original sin.  Just as you don't necessarily impute<br>
your parent's transgression of the law onto the children, you don't have<br>
to impute their "separation from God".  It's just easier.<br>
<p>
<p>
Malcolm<br>
<pre>
-- 
Switched Networks Research Centre,               malb@ee.uts.edu.au
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia            +61 2 330 2344
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
