<title>Apr_1993: Re: What is AntiChrist ?</title>
<h1>Re: What is AntiChrist ?</h1>
Malcolm Butler (<i>malb@boojum.ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 3 Apr 93 23:53:13 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#108">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#108">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#108">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#108">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0109.html">Steven Timm: "No SDAnet messages on Sabbath."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0107.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "The Generation That Forgot God."</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0062.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What is AntiChrist ?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0119.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: What is AntiChrist ?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;&gt; As Malcolm stated, where do you draw the line as to what is truth and</i><br>
<i>&gt;what isn't?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Well I always thought that God's Word was the test of truth.</i><br>
<p>
If you recall my example, people have difficulty in even agreeing what<br>
God's Word is, let alone how to understand it.  So how useful is this as<br>
a definition?<br>
<p>
The main problem I have with the line of reasoning Ruben is following<br>
is that when taken to its extreme, it reduces arguments to "I read the<br>
Bible and the Holy Spirit revealed &lt;such-and-such&gt; to me.  Someone else<br>
uses the same argument to come to a different conclusion.  I don't<br>
propose that they are both in some sense right, but it seems to me that<br>
there must be something lacking in the process if such a situation is<br>
possible.<br>
<p>
<p>
Malcolm<br>
<pre>
