<title>Apr_1993: Re: end times</title>
<h1>Re: end times</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun,  4 Apr 1993 01:33:40 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#99">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#99">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#99">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#99">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0100.html">Steven Timm: "Re: SDA: Library addresses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Gregg Wisdom: "end times"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0098.html">Gregg Wisdom: "end times"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0114.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  end times"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDA literature has always viewed the second coming as imminent.  During the <br>
first world war, lots of attention was paid to Daniel 11 and the possible<br>
fulfillments of prophecies with the Ottoman Empire as "the king of the north"<br>
The destruction of such empire forced people to re-evaluate.<br>
<p>
In the 1960's rhetoric would have focused on the Catholic president of the<br>
time, plus Vatican II.  The 70's had talk about energy crises forcing<br>
Sunday laws.  In the early 80's the Moral Majority was the favorite target,<br>
and would have been more so were it not for the preponderance of Republicans<br>
among the people who make these interpretations.<br>
<p>
But really, this is how it should be.  We should always feel the imminence<br>
of the 2nd coming and always be ready for it.  The one thing we know for sure<br>
is that every day will be one day closer to the end.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
