<title>Apr_1993: Re:  end times</title>
<h1>Re:  end times</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 4 Apr 93 17:39:35 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#114">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#114">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#114">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#114">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0115.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: SDA: America"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0113.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: 3 angels"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0098.html">Gregg Wisdom: "end times"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0172.html">Woody Baker: "Re:  end times"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;If I were to look back over the last 30 years at the books published by </i><br>
<i>&gt;Adventists about the end times would I see attempts to fit the trends Adventistshave seen in the past to the Adventist end time scenario?  What I mean is, are</i><br>
<i>&gt;these trends that these authors point to really something significant or are</i><br>
<i>&gt;they just another of many attempts to fit current events into our prophetic</i><br>
<i>&gt;scenario?  Maybe somebody who is aware of what we have published in the </i><br>
<i>&gt;past on current events and the end times can enlighten me.</i><br>
<p>
Well, some of it is and some of it isn't (fitting current events into<br>
prophecies) but i've noticed that our understanding of prophecy seems to<br>
be reflected in current world trends, and these were prophecies which<br>
we knew about before these trends became prominent. We may not know the<br>
exact details of, say, how the time of trouble and the great worldwide<br>
persecuition of God's people will come about, but current events seem to be<br>
setting the stage for these things to happen. There is the extreme moral<br>
degredation of many societies, which will prime them for moral backlashes,<br>
the great swings in the balence of power amongst the worldly powers, with<br>
America now as the only superpower, and i forgot where the saying came from,<br>
that "power corrupts and absolute power corrupts absolutely."<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I have another question.  I have noticed in talking with Adventist young</i><br>
<i>&gt;adults about the end of times and prophecy that they (at least amoung those</i><br>
<i>&gt;I have talked to) are not really all that interested in the topic.  They have</i><br>
<i>&gt;told me that they have heard this stuff almost their entire life (I am talking</i><br>
<i>&gt;about those young adult SDAs who grew up in the church) and they are tired of</i><br>
<i>&gt;hearing about how imminent the second coming is.  Does anybody know if this</i><br>
<i>&gt;feeling is widespread in the North American church?</i><br>
<p>
I don't know about the NAD churches, but i suspect that you can't generalize<br>
amongst them. Amongst the young people in my church, i don't think they're<br>
bored about the 2nd comming, although some are more interested than others.<br>
We've even done plays on the topic even, to try to bring across the urgency<br>
of the times to the rest of the congregation.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  Has the SDA church "gone to the well" one too many times with these</i><br>
<i>&gt; people about the imminencey of the second coming?  I ask this question</i><br>
<i>&gt; because I wonder if I have gotten caught up too much in second coming</i><br>
<i>&gt; fever (with the approach of the year 2000)only to be disappointed when</i><br>
<i>&gt; it doesn't happen as soon as I am getting the impression it will from</i><br>
<i>&gt; reading these books. I must say that although I do get the impression</i><br>
<i>&gt; that these authors believe the end of time is very close, no where did</i><br>
<i>&gt; they set any times of any sort, so I may be reading more into what they</i><br>
<i>&gt; say than was intened by the authors.</i><br>
<p>
Well, i guess the important thing about it is not just the 2nd comming per<br>
se, but that because Jesus is coming so soon, we need to get our act<br>
together and be as useful to Him as we can, in finishing the work, giving<br>
the last departure/arival call so that as many people as possible will have<br>
as good a chance as possible to know enough to decide which side they want<br>
to be on. The harvest is plentiful but the workers are few, let us work<br>
while it is day, the night cometh when no man can work. In these times,<br>
times that test men's souls, it is our job to help save souls, it is verily<br>
a question of life or death, do or die. We have to let people know: There's<br>
a WAR going on, which side are you on? You'd better make up your mind, 'cause<br>
there ain't much time.<br>
<p>
	As for date-setting, i heard an interesting song on BBC radio once,<br>
on something called the vintage chart show, it was number one in the secular<br>
pop charts of 19 July 1965 and it was "In the Year 2525" by Zager &amp; Evans<br>
, and after several stanzas about the progressive degeneration of the<br>
human race, which happen to be somewhat prophetic, with the benefit of<br>
hindsight, it went like this:<br>
<p>
	In the year 75 ten,<br>
	If God's a commin'<br>
	He oughtta make it by then,<br>
	Maybe He'll look around Himself and say:<br>
	"Guess its time for the judgement day"<br>
<p>
	In the year 8510,<br>
	God is gonna shake His mighty head,<br>
	He'll either say "I'm pleased where man has been"<br>
	Or tear it down, and start again.....<br>
<p>
Well, i don't know who Zager and Evans are, but they got me thinking: If God<br>
doesn't come back pretty soon, the way things are going, He may not have<br>
much left to come back to. But anyway, we know He's coming, so we should<br>
follow the Scout motto: "Be prepared."<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
