<!-- received="Sun Apr 05 10:22:08 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="05 Apr 1993 10:22:08 +1000" -->
<!-- name="PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- email="PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- subject="Re: The real issue" -->
<!-- id="01GWNC63FKM09LZKQZ@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- inreplyto="The real issue" -->
<title>Apr_1993: Re: The real issue</title>
<h1>Re: The real issue</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>05 Apr 1993 10:22:08 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#128">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#128">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#128">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#128">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0129.html">Steven Timm: "Prophecy about Bill Clinton"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0127.html">Steven Timm: "The Sovereignty of God"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0152.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: The real issue"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
----&gt;<br>
1-- The doctrine that we receive weakness from Adam, but not guilt, now<br>
being replaced by the Calvinistic doctrine of original sin defined as<br>
inherited guilt.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I think what is taught by many now is along the lines of "Sin is living<br>
your life independently of God in wilful rebellion against his authority."<br>
And the when a human is born, the default is that they are not in a proper<br>
relationship with God, and that this must be remedied. Contrast with the<br>
original situation, where humans would have been born in a proper relationship<br>
with God.So it's not so much "guilt" that is inherited from Adam, just the<br>
fact that humanity as a whole was separated from God. The visible signs of<br>
this come in the form of wilful rebellion, ie sinful acts and so on.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
2-- The doctrine that our Lord came to this earth in the human nature of<br>
fallen man, now being replaced by the Calvinistic doctrine that Christ came<br>
to earth in the human nature of the unfallen Adam.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I think what is taught by many now is that Christ inherited weakness from<br>
Adam, referred to in point 1, but that he was born without the separation<br>
from God that the rest of us inherit. The "human nature" of Christ <br>
is seen as the human mind and body, deteriorated from its original state<br>
due to thousands of years of living in rebellion. The "divine nature" is<br>
seen as the total relationship between Christ and his heavenly father, among<br>
other things.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
3-- The doctrine of righteousness by faith, now being replaced by the<br>
Calvinistic doctrine of unrighteousness by presumption, salvation in sin.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I have never heard anything like this myself in any church, although I<br>
believe some of the pentecostal/charismatic congregations teach this kind<br>
of thing. I think this is a misunderstanding on both sides. <br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
4-- The doctrine of the sanctuary, now being either denied or replaced by<br>
vague uncertainties.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I have heard SDAs say that Hebrews does not speak about the geography of<br>
heaven, although they do believe there is a heavenly sanctuary, and that<br>
the priestly role of Christ changed in 1844. Does this constitute a vague<br>
uncertainty? (not a rhetorical question btw)<br>
<p>
I personally know some SDAs who may not believe in the doctrine of the<br>
sanctuary and maybe not the investigative judgment, but I have never heard<br>
this mentioned inside an SDA church. Then again, perhaps the fact that I<br>
rarely hear the doctrine of the sanctuary is evidence for point 4. I don't<br>
really know. <br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
5-- Belief in the Spirit of Prophecy, now being denied because it supports<br>
all of the Adventist doctrines listed above and firmly rejects the Calvinistic<br>
doctrines.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I honestly don't know where many SDAs stand regarding their acceptance of<br>
E.G.White and her writings. I don't know any SDAs who don't believe in the<br>
Spirit of Prophecy, but it is certainly possible that some question whether<br>
EGW herself had this gift. I myself refuse to *equate* "Spirit of Prophecy"<br>
with "the testimonies of Ellen White" to the exclusion of other manifestations<br>
of the gift.<br>
<p>
One thing which is certainly needed is some open discussion about the role<br>
of EG White, both in the nineteenth century and today. There are certainly<br>
some problems with the way some have represented her writings and her role,<br>
and these problems exist on both sides of the issue. Anybody who brings up<br>
difficulties with the red books tends to be classed as a "critic", whereas<br>
to me it is important to face these difficulties and deal with them.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
I'd like to hear what some of your opinions are.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Well, there you are!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
