[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; [Tony writes} </i><br>
<i>&gt; We would say it is a Beast.  Yes, I think we definitely would.</i><br>
<p>
I may be reading something into Tony's tone that is not there, in fact,<br>
but I get the feeling that he may have meant Americans often act very<br>
"beastly" (and in my mind's ear, I'm recalling the connotation I get from<br>
hearing Brits use this word).  8-)  And since I'm Canadian 8-) ...<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; [This is interesting.  Is Tony suggesting that "USA in prophecy" type sermons</i><br>
<i>&gt; are just as common in Australia as they are here?  What about in some place</i><br>
<p>
FYI, in Arizona we only seem to get these sermons around July 4 and on<br>
Religious Liberty emphasis Sabbath.  Would not seem a "common" occurence.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; like Papua New Guinea, where the threat of not being able to buy or sell </i><br>
<i>&gt; means nothing to a tribesman who doesn't do so anyway?  Is the SDA church </i><br>
<i>&gt; American no matter what country we are in?  SCT]</i><br>
<p>
Undoubtedly Americanisms and American perspectives can creep into one's<br>
belief system.  However, given that we SDAs interpret the lamb-like beast of<br>
Revelation as representing the United States, and rightly so I would argue<br>
(cf. Great Controversy), it is definitely *not* inappropriate to preach that<br>
interpretation 'round the world.  It is the implications and consequences<br>
of this that will be "customized" by geographic circumstance, IMHO. <br>
<p>
I'm curious (not skeptical) re what (presumably unwarranted) Americanisms<br>
you all see present in SDA beliefs (as distinct from what a given individual<br>
might personally subscribe to).<br>
