<title>Apr_1993: Theories of inspiration</title>
<h1>Theories of inspiration</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>05 Apr 1993 10:46:51 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#116">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#116">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#116">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#116">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0117.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: SDA: America"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0115.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: SDA: America"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi, Ruben asked what other kinds of inspiration there could be besides<br>
verbal inspiration and thought inspiration. In his series of papers which<br>
appeared in the Journal of Adventist Education, V44, No. 1, 2 &amp; 3, Roger<br>
Coon listed three different theories. In my view, two of them were very<br>
much oversimplified, but then again Coon's aim was to affirm the<br>
truth of the plenary (thought) inspiration, not to objectively discuss all<br>
three. Here I have quoted one or two short paragraphs from each of his<br>
three descriptions.<br>
<p>
1. Theory of verbal inspiration<br>
<p>
...This view is rather a mechanical one, since it perceives the prophet's <br>
role as simply that of a stenographer who takes down the boss's dictation<br>
word for word. In this model the stenographer is not at liberty to change<br>
anything that has been given by the dictator: no synonyms may ever be<br>
employed; no failing to dot an "i" or to cross a "t" is permitted.<br>
<p>
This view seems to suggest that God, or the angel, puts a heavenly hand over<br>
the hand of the prophet and guides it - literally - so that every word,<br>
every syllable comes directly from God. The prophet, in this view, is not at<br>
liberty to change anything or to state the message in his own words. This<br>
mechanical view is strictly, stringently literalistic, with infallibility<br>
residing at the point of the written word.<br>
<p>
2. Theory of Plenary Inspiration<br>
<p>
In contrast with the view of verbal inspiration, the plenary theory of<br>
inspiration suggests that thoughts - rather than words - are inspired. The<br>
plenary view is not forced to grapple with the problems of the verbalist.<br>
For the SDA, this view has the added advantage of having been accepted and<br>
advocated by Ellen White.<br>
<p>
3. Theory of Encounter Inspiration<br>
<p>
(ref. Robertson and Dederin, in "The Challenge to God's Word", although it<br>
sounds like this is itself a discussion of the original material on<br>
Encounter Inspiration)<br>
<p>
As encounter theology sees it, revelation (or inspiration) is an experience<br>
that takes place in an "I-Thou" encounter between the prophet and God. It<br>
is then, primarily, and experience, with no exchange of information taking<br>
place.<br>
<p>
This view is based, at least in part, on the "I-Thou" concept of Philosopher<br>
(sic) Martin Buber. The three basic tenets or postulates will now be<br>
examined:<br>
<p>
	1. Inspiration is, by its very nature, inherently subjective rather<br>
	   than objective.<br>
<p>
	2. The Bible contains the word of God, but is not itself the word<br>
	   of God.<br>
<p>
	3. Inspiration is "quantitative, not qualitative".<br>
<p>
<p>
Coon's papers are quite interesting and informative, although as I said<br>
earlier, they're not very objective. I am now looking for more material on<br>
"Encounter Inspiration", because I would like to know more about what it is.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
