<i>&gt; God's Word is, let alone how to understand it.  So how useful is this as</i><br>
<i>&gt; a definition?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The main problem I have with the line of reasoning Ruben is following</i><br>
<i>&gt; is that when taken to its extreme, it reduces arguments to "I read the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Bible and the Holy Spirit revealed &lt;such-and-such&gt; to me.  Someone else</i><br>
<i>&gt; uses the same argument to come to a different conclusion.  I don't</i><br>
<i>&gt; propose that they are both in some sense right, but it seems to me that</i><br>
<i>&gt; there must be something lacking in the process if such a situation is</i><br>
<i>&gt; possible.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
<p>
Well If we can't trust the bible and the H.S then who do you propose we follow<br>
the majority or the traditions of our church leaders, or what ?<br>
<p>
Ruben. <br>
