<title>Apr_1993: Re: Aaron &amp; Hur Club</title>
<h1>Re: Aaron &amp; Hur Club</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 5 Apr 93 12:45:32 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#131">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#131">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#131">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#131">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0132.html">Steven Timm: "The real issues?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0130.html">Steven Timm: "Relationship theology"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0095.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Aron &amp; Hur Club"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm going to re-arrange the order of the text slightly ...<br>
<p>
[davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; [re lay sermons re Aaron &amp; Hur, from Ex 17]</i><br>
<p>
The idea for this appears to have been sparked by a fairly recent<br>
article in the Adventist Review (fyi, for those not receiving it).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  Moses -- the prophet with his arms reaching out to God.</i><br>
<i>&gt;  Aaron -- the ordained ministry (priesthood).</i><br>
<i>&gt;  Hur   -- the laymen of the church (one of the artisans).</i><br>
<p>
Since what we have in Ex 17 is neither parable nor prophecy but history,<br>
we may have some more leeway re what this story teaches us (1 Cor 10:11).<br>
I agree 100% that a direct application is that ministers and laymen should<br>
be fully supportive of God's prophet(ess).  (For instruction on what to<br>
do if this is not the case, we need to look elsewhere.)  However, I think<br>
it not untoward (cf 2 Pet 3:16) to also apply it to members' relation<br>
to pastors and others with leadership responsibility.  {Could someone<br>
check EGW refs (anyone got the CD-ROM?) to Aaron &amp; Hur to see if this<br>
latter application has precedent?  I'm thinking maybe ...}<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Club membership equates to supporting your local pastor (and conference).</i><br>
<p>
If we accept the second application as permissible, the next question is:<br>
How are we lay folk to support our pastors?  (I have some material at<br>
home re this that I can maybe post later.)  For starters, we have Gal 6:2,<br>
James 5:16, Ps 105:15; cf I Tim 2:1,2.  However, support should not be<br>
construed to mean unquestioned, unverified, untested acceptance (1 John 4:1;<br>
Acts 17:11) of every word.  Gal 6:1 specifically addresses instances wherein<br>
any member, pastor or layperson, is off-base (tho note its warning, similar<br>
to 1 Cor 10:12).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; A big reason for starting up these clubs is to try and get people</i><br>
<i>&gt; to quit complaining about the pastors no longer supporting EGW, or</i><br>
<i>&gt; serious Bible truths.  The idea is that the pastor should be free</i><br>
<i>&gt; to preach anything he wants without getting hassled.</i><br>
<p>
I think it exceedingly needful and timely for us to understand Scriptural<br>
methods of how to express concern or make an appeal.  Lack of true<br>
humility (Jam 4:6), a conscience not void of offense (Acts 24:16),<br>
using man's tactics (Is 55:8,9; Zec 4:6), inappropriate timing (Pro 27:14),<br>
impatience (Rom 15:5; 2 Cor 6:4; Col 1:11; 1 Ti 6:11; 2 Ti 2:2; Jam 5:10),<br>
etc, can all be impediments [*].  And if, despite following Scriptural<br>
methods, we are rejected in our appeal, we can find comfort in 1 Pet 2:19-24,<br>
3:14-17.  God is *still* in control (Ps 75:7; Dan 3:17, 4:35,37; John 19:11).<br>
{Btw, it was instructive to me just finding (!) these verses.}<br>
<p>
[*] I recall walking thru the church foyer some years back and passing by<br>
    the visiting speaker, a prior conference president, who had been<br>
    button-holed by another visitor.  The latter's face was livid, his<br>
    tone of voice sharp, punctuated by thumping a fist into the other hand.<br>
    I caught "...and if you don't, their blood will be upon your hands!"<br>
    However valid his point, it's questionable if it got across.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
