<title>Apr_1993: SDA Evangelical or not?</title>
<h1>SDA Evangelical or not?</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 5 Apr 1993 13:18:25 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#134">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#134">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#134">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#134">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0135.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: The real issues?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0133.html">lin collette: "Re: SDAnet Digest Mar 28-Apr 4 1993"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
After scanning the 160 odd pieces of email, most of it SDAnet,<br>
which I received in the last week and a half, I feel a bit of a speech<br>
coming on.<br>
<p>
Are we Evangelical, Protestant etc?<br>
<p>
This question no doubt has to do with our sense of identity. We like to<br>
think of ourselves being different, and that those differences are important.<br>
I would be the last to suggest that the differences are not important, but<br>
I am also concerned that sometimes we make wear those differences high on<br>
our sleeves when it would be best not to do so. Surely there is a lot<br>
of common ground between Catholics, Protestants, Evangelicals, Charasmatics<br>
and Seventh-day Adventists. I recall a discussion on Christianity I had with<br>
a Catholic Priest, whose kindness and love reflect a love of Jesus that we<br>
would all do well to emulate. In dealing with Christians of other faiths<br>
establishing a common ground in love leads to some informed discussion on<br>
the differences?<br>
<p>
I was once asked by an evangelical about the differences in the SDA church.<br>
(He had heard about the issues raised by Des Ford) I briefly summarised the<br>
problems and He shook his head and said "what a stupid thing to argue over."<br>
I asked him what the current situation was in the Uniting Church of Australia,<br>
and he laughed and said "They are much the same as in the Adventist Church."<br>
The discussion we had on Christain values in the face of internal conflicts<br>
in the church was a conversation I still value highly. Our differences<br>
were minimised, our experiences were shared and I felt better for it because<br>
some of my fears about the church were put aside.<br>
<p>
United States in Prophecy<br>
<p>
In Australia there is quite a broad spectrum of thought on USA in prophecy.<br>
Those who follow a traditional line would see very definite references and<br>
would like to hear more on that line of interpretation. In a Sabbath<br>
School class last year at Avondale College I ventured to suggest that we<br>
ought to adopt a more open approach to the question and I was immediatly<br>
taken to task by 2 theology students waving their Bibles in the air and<br>
declaring that I was abandoning the faith.<br>
<p>
I have no quarrel with the interpretation that USA fulfills a place in <br>
prophecy, but I hesitate to tie some prophecies to concrete organisations.<br>
I rather think sometimes that things like the media today are playing<br>
the role of the image of the beast, subtly changing our moral attitudes<br>
and bending our perception of good and evil. There is always the danger<br>
that we watch the wrong horse, while an outsider sneaks up on us unawares.<br>
<p>
In answer to the specific question "What do SDA's preach about USA in<br>
prophecy in other countries?" In Australia, I don't here many sermons about<br>
it. In fact I do not hear many sermons about prophecy and last day events<br>
full stop (period, for our American friends). That probably is a pity, but<br>
I think the sermons we are getting are relevent and challenging non-the-less. <br>
<p>
Maurice Ashton<br>
Avondale College<br>
mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au<br>
   .-_|\<br>
  /     \<br>
  \.--._/<br>
       V<br>
