<title>Apr_1993: SDA: advent</title>
<h1>SDA: advent</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 5 Apr 93 15:05:44 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#125">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#125">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#125">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#125">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0126.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: SDA: America"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0124.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: The real issues? (Dr. Ralph Larson)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0142.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: SDA: advent"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 Someone, I forget his name, posted about the possibility of putting our faith<br>
 in a date and ending up in bad shape if the date passes.  This reminded me of<br>
 the "prophecy" of the world ending in 2000 AD or close to it.  I have heard<br>
 a few arguments and I will summarize them.<br>
 <br>
 1. Every 2000 years something big happens.  Creation - Flood - Christ - 2nd<br>
    advent.  I have never heard a real precise definition of Big, but there<br>
    is no doubt these are big things.  One thing that is in doubt is 2000<br>
       years happening between each of these events.  I guess 2000 years<br>
       give or take a few hundred years.  But to give or take a few hundred<br>
       years you add a few hundred years past the supposed date 0of the <br>
       adfvent.<br>
 <br>
 2. A day equals a thousand years with God.  Creation is 7 days, therefore<br>
    the world will last 6000 years plus a seventh day of rest.  Perhaps someone<br>
    who teaches this could better explain this one.<br>
 <br>
 3. Ellen White said that the world would last 6000 years.  She said sin would<br>
    reign for 6000 years.  I also saw whre she said the world was 6000 years old <br>
    at her time.  I saw her say that the flood was 4000 years ago in her day.<br>
    Does this mean that these dates are exactly true?  My faith in ellen White<br>
    soes not stand or fall on a legalistic reading of a few numbers.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
 Then before the argument closes, whichever of the three they use, they say<br>
 Jesus said no one knows the day or the hour.  He did not say anything about<br>
 the year.<br>
 <br>
 I must say I have heard these arguments many a time, I have even heard the<br>
 year 1996 spoken specifically from the pulpit.<br>
 <br>
 Before I close, I want to make it clear that I am an Adventist meaning I<br>
 do look for the coming of Christ.  I hope and pray we will be ready for him<br>
 if the years is 1993 (The last movements will be rapid ones), 1996, or 2040.<br>
 <br>
 If the year 2000 passes and Christ has not come, I will continue to sing,<br>
 "I don't believe He brought me this far to leave me."<br>
 <br>
 <br>
 -- <br>
 "Competition is the law of the jungle.<br>
  Cooperation is the law of civilization."  -  Eldridge Cleaver<br>
 <br>
 Sherman H. Cox, II       scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu<br>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
