[PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Most of us Aussies only use the term CB to refer to that group of ultra-</i><br>
<i>&gt; conservative SDAs who are active in criticizing church leadership and</i><br>
<i>&gt; church institutions in an aggressive and damaging way.  There are many</i><br>
<i>&gt; conservative SDAs here who have sympathies with, or even support, the</i><br>
<i>&gt; various groups of CBs, but would not themselves attract that label.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; [..] as well as positive, helpful and constructive conservative SDAs. </i><br>
<p>
Something perhaps worthy of discussion is:  What distinguishes "helpful<br>
and constructive" comment from "damaging" comment?  When one is on<br>
the receiving end, it is often difficult to be objective.  Also, what<br>
distinguishes "criticism" from 'expressing concern' or 'making a<br>
heart-felt appeal'?  Since I think we are all willing to accept that<br>
conference and institution leaders can and do make mistakes, how should<br>
a concerned brother or sister relate? i.e., what characterizes a godly,<br>
Scripturally-based approach?<br>
