<!-- body="start" -->
[From Gary Burdick.  Just a note, Steps To Life was founded by the late <br>
Marshall Grosboll and is currently run by his brother John Grosboll.  <br>
If I mistake not both are former SDA pastors; a recent ordination at <br>
this organization caused no small stir.  Larson participated in that service,<br>
and they publish his works, but to my knowledge he himself has not been<br>
dropped from membership in the SDA church nor has he had his credentials<br>
revoked.   SCT]<br>
<p>
Noe writes: <br>
<i>&gt; I received in the mail today an unsolicited pamphlet from Dr. Ralph Larson of</i><br>
<i>&gt; the independent ministry known as "Steps to Life."  The pamphlet, entitled</i><br>
<i>&gt; "Issues: The Real Issue, the Side Issues, and the Pseudo Issues," is a</i><br>
<i>&gt; rebuttal to the NAD's recent publication, "Issues: The Seventh-day Adventist</i><br>
<i>&gt; Church and Certain Private Organizations."</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I'm wondering how many of you on SDANet have read this publication and what</i><br>
<i>&gt; your thoughts on it are?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Specifically, how do you feel about Larson's charge that the following five</i><br>
<i>&gt; "historic Adventist doctrines" are being "replaced" by Calvinistic teachings:</i><br>
<p>
I find the section on the five historic doctrines to be the only<br>
logical and arguably defensible part of the entire pamphlet.  I could<br>
not find a single instance where the book "Issues" actually says what<br>
Larson claims it said.  In my opinion, Larson is a real artist when it<br>
comes to taking quotes out of context and making others say what he<br>
wants them to say.  However, as the question raised above deals<br>
specifically with the five "Calvinistic teachings" I will refrain from<br>
expounding further on Larson's scholarship :-)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; QUOTING FROM THE PAMPHLET:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 1-- The doctrine that we receive weakness from Adam, but not guilt, now</i><br>
<i>&gt; being replaced by the Calvinistic doctrine of original sin defined as</i><br>
<i>&gt; inherited guilt.</i><br>
<p>
It is true that many Adventists now emphasize the fact that we are<br>
born in a state of separation from God, and thus unable, on our own,<br>
to choose to do right.  And it is only through faith in God that this<br>
relationship can be restored:  "Everything not of faith is sin."<br>
However, I do not know of a single Adventist that believes in original<br>
sin or inherited guilt.  We are born with Adam's separation from God,<br>
but not with Adam's guilt.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 2-- The doctrine that our Lord came to this earth in the human nature of</i><br>
<i>&gt; fallen man, now being replaced by the Calvinistic doctrine that Christ came</i><br>
<i>&gt; to earth in the human nature of the unfallen Adam.</i><br>
<p>
Once again, the emphasis has shifted in order to emphasize that Christ<br>
was born with an unbroken relationship to God, a relationship that we<br>
also may have through faith in Christ.  But this does not negate the<br>
fact that He was "tempted in all points like we are," that He came in<br>
the flesh with the possiblity of failure, or that we may overcome<br>
(through faith in Him) like Christ overcame.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 3-- The doctrine of righteousness by faith, now being replaced by the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Calvinistic doctrine of unrighteousness by presumption, salvation in sin.</i><br>
<p>
Our GC president emphasizes very strongly the "assurance of<br>
salvation."  But to consider this "salvation in sin" (and thus<br>
presumption) rather than "salvation from sin" is to totally<br>
misunderstand his message.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 4-- The doctrine of the sanctuary, now being either denied or replaced by</i><br>
<i>&gt; vague uncertainties.</i><br>
<p>
It is my understanding that at one time, most non-Adventists<br>
misunderstood our position on the sanctuary to mean that Christ was<br>
continually being sacrificed for us.  At the time of the writing of<br>
_Questions_on_Doctrine_, we changed the wording of our belief in order<br>
to clarify our true stand, that Christ was sacrificed once and for all<br>
on the cross, and Christ is presently applying that sacrifice to us.<br>
This rewording has been attacked as an evangelical compromise.<br>
However, I believe that our fundamental belief has not changed.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 5-- Belief in the Spirit of Prophecy, now being denied because it supports</i><br>
<i>&gt; all of the Adventist doctrines listed above and firmly rejects the</i><br>
Calvinistic<br>
<i>&gt; doctrines.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Many of us know what it feels like to be hit over the head with Mrs.<br>
White's writings--and are thus unwilling to treat others as harshly<br>
and unlovingly as we ourselves have been treated--but that does not<br>
mean that we have thrown out Ellen White.  Also, the fact that I<br>
reject Ralph Larson's interpretation of what Mrs. White says does not<br>
mean I reject what Mrs. White says. (There is a difference :-) )<br>
Personally, I believe that _Steps_to_Christ_ is the single best<br>
exposition on the gospel that has ever been written.<br>
<p>
But, all of this is just my opinion.  I do know people who believe<br>
that every word Ralph Larson has ever written is the gospel truth.<br>
And I cannot help but feel sorry for them.  It must be a miserable<br>
feeling to sincerely believe that everyone else in the church is in<br>
apostacy.  <br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Gary W. Burdick (burdick@hkuxa.hku.hk)
Department of Physics, University of Hong Kong, Pokfulam Rd, HONG KONG
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
