<title>Apr_1993: Relationship theology</title>
<h1>Relationship theology</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  5 Apr 1993 23:20:27 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#130">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#130">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#130">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#130">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0131.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Aaron &amp; Hur Club"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0129.html">Steven Timm: "Prophecy about Bill Clinton"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0151.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Relationship theology"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The talk of a "personal relationship with Christ", "accepting Him as <br>
your personal savior", and other such clauses are fairly recent, as far<br>
as I can tell.  Certainly no such clauses appear in the Bible, and that<br>
worries <br>
me somewhat.<br>
<p>
The definition of sin and the process of salvation are quite connected.  <br>
I remember when I was in fifth and sixth grade I was quite worried about<br>
this, thinking that the verses "To him that knoweth to do good and doeth<br>
it not, to him it is sin,", "Sin is the transgression of the law", and<br>
"all <br>
have sinned and come short of the glory of God"  were all in contradiction<br>
with each other.  I was taught a very legalistic view of religion in<br>
general, and I would sometimes have nightmares about being outside of<br>
heaven, particularly because I wasn't baptized at the time.  Yet I<br>
resisted the <br>
"baptismal mill" that the rest of the fifth graders at my church school<br>
were put through.<br>
<p>
Later, in seventh grade, my Bible teacher explained the idea in a 3-tiered<br>
relationship plan.  The first tier was knowing God and having a<br>
relationship, which would lead to right thoughts and attitudes, and thus<br>
to right actions.<br>
The opposite would be a broken relationship with God, which would lead to <br>
wrong thoughts and attitudes and thus to wrong actions.  All three of<br>
these levels would be sin, but it was all curable through a restoration<br>
of the relationship with God.<br>
<p>
So I don't want to tear down this idea, it was and continues to be one<br>
of the central organizing principles of my life.  It would, however, be<br>
nice to find<br>
more scriptural support for it than I'm aware exists now.  It provides a<br>
valuable counterpoint to the narrow definition of sin that claims it is<br>
only actions as opposed to sinful thoughts or broken relationship with<br>
God.<br>
At the end, the gospel is not whether I know Christ, but whether He knows me.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
