<title>Apr_1993: The real issues?</title>
<h1>The real issues?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  5 Apr 1993 23:35:02 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#132">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#132">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#132">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#132">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0133.html">lin collette: "Re: SDAnet Digest Mar 28-Apr 4 1993"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0131.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Aaron &amp; Hur Club"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0144.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: The real issues?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My comments on the pamphlet<br>
<i>&gt;1-- The doctrine that we receive weakness from Adam, but not guilt, now</i><br>
<i>&gt;being replaced by the Calvinistic doctrine of original sin defined as</i><br>
<i>&gt;inherited guilt.</i><br>
<p>
Although I agree that a hatchet job on this doctrine was done in Questions<br>
On Doctrine, (also #2), it doesn't seem to have penetrated to other areas<br>
such as the Fundamental Beliefs.  Inherited guilt is a moot point in <br>
any case because by now all humans have sinned whether we start out that<br>
way or not.  Rom. 3:23<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;2-- The doctrine that our Lord came to this earth in the human nature of</i><br>
<i>&gt;fallen man, now being replaced by the Calvinistic doctrine that Christ came</i><br>
<i>&gt;to earth in the human nature of the unfallen Adam.</i><br>
<p>
Larson seems unwilling to admit that Christ was in any way advantaged<br>
over His fellow humans.  This makes it hard for him to show why it was <br>
necessary for Christ to be divine, or why a savior ought to be divine.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;3-- The doctrine of righteousness by faith, now being replaced by the</i><br>
<i>&gt;Calvinistic doctrine of unrighteousness by presumption, salvation in sin.</i><br>
<p>
You can scarcely call the current mix Calvinistic, because Calvinists<br>
are predestinarians, which no SDA's of any flavor are.  Nevertheless<br>
there is antinomianism in the SDA church and Larson is right to call it<br>
to task.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;4-- The doctrine of the sanctuary, now being either denied or replaced by</i><br>
<i>&gt;vague uncertainties.</i><br>
<p>
Besides those on the far left in SDA colonies, and Desmond Ford's crowd,<br>
I have not seen a wholesale rejection of the sanctuary doctrine.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;5-- Belief in the Spirit of Prophecy, now being denied because it supports</i><br>
<i>&gt;all of the Adventist doctrines listed above and firmly rejects the</i><br>
<i>&gt;Calvinistic doctrines.</i><br>
<p>
The position being denied is that of various Review editors after the<br>
death of Ellen G. White who built up the doctrine of verbal inspiration<br>
in contradiction to her writings.  Perhaps this re-examination would not<br>
have <br>
taken place had not the Walter Rea controversy occured.  But I think <br>
the re-examination is good for the church.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;END OF QUOTE.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;My own opinion is such that I question many of Larson's assertions and</i><br>
<i>&gt;methods.  I believe he is demanding that something be either black or white,</i><br>
<i>&gt;when it may really be gray.  I believe he is introducing a spirit of</i><br>
<i>&gt;divisiveness and criticism toward the denomination, instead of working to</i><br>
<i>&gt;make positive change.</i><br>
<p>
If a gray position is a compromise between the black and white position<br>
(both of which are often wrong), then I want no part of it.  A compromise<br>
between two wrong opinions is still wrong.  If we can give up the dependence<br>
on binary logic and see that sometimes both opinions can be right and other<br>
times both can be wrong, we'd get a lot farther faster.  Larson is not<br>
introducing a spirit of criticism and dissension into the denomination--<br>
it's been with us from the beginning.  His discourses are in the best<br>
of time-honored SDA tradition.  That's the only way he knows how to<br>
communicate, and we ought not to fault him for that.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
