<title>Apr_1993: Gospel, etc.</title>
<h1>Gospel, etc.</h1>
David E. Johnson (<i>71172.2044@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>06 Apr 93 02:21:44 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#149">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#149">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#149">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#149">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0150.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "messianic Jews"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0148.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Visions of...what?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As I have just waded through this weeks 240k of SDAnet "Digest", may I <br>
reemphasize a plea from others:  Please, PLEASE reduce the volume of qouted <br>
and requoted text!<br>
<p>
I have three responses so far...<br>
<p>
RE: Tony's question "Christians are ... called to preach the gospel. [Any] <br>
mandate for preaching three angels message...?<br>
<p>
Well, when I read Rev. 14.6, I find an angel with the "eternal Gospel to <br>
proclaim..." and what I really have to evaluate is, How is the gospel of <br>
Revelation 14 the same gospel of Galatians 1, Romans 1, etc, etc...<br>
<p>
Paul says his gospel was received "by revelation from Jesus Christ" (Gal <br>
1:12), and that what "is no gospel at all" is one confused and perverted, <br>
in the larger context, by those (Judaizers) who wished to bind the church <br>
with Old Testament ceremony.<br>
Paul's gospel (Rom 1:16)  is "the power of God for salvation ... a <br>
righteousness from God ... a righteousness by faith from first to last".<br>
<p>
Now, if a message to put God first and only; that a mixed, adulterated <br>
religion [one that says Christ AND --- (insert ANYTHING here)] is fallen; <br>
and that judgment is a call to remain faithful to Jesus is NOT the gospel, <br>
what, pray tell, is?<br>
<p>
****************<br>
RE: SDA E-Mail directory<br>
<p>
The GC has mapped the first six digits of all SDA institutions, including <br>
local churches, to an ATT Email address. The "master list" has recently <br>
appeared in documentation regarding the processing of SDA service <br>
(employment) records. Southeastern California Conference's (where I work) <br>
is "ANPM11", but since you don't find this code in Harvey's list, you would <br>
correctly assume that SECC is *not* a subscriber to ATT Email.<br>
 <br>
Which brings me to a third subject,<br>
************<br>
RE: Ned Torres, distrust ... toward computer tech ... among SDA's<br>
<p>
Here at SECC, the problem isn't as much a *fear* of technology as it is (1) <br>
a serious lack of funds to do *big* things, (2) haziness among <br>
administrators as to the value of WAN technology, and (3) a lack of <br>
communication - human networking - among the diaspora of computer literates <br>
and professionals among the official church.<br>
<p>
An evolutionary, perhaps conspiratory, sometimes underground, and <br>
definitely cheap, strategy is the rule here.<br>
<p>
We started small - a PC-XT compatible a few years back - and have migrated <br>
most to the 386/486 level. The XT's went to directors and then schools, <br>
etc.  Today, many of our directors &amp; administrators carry notebooks, laser <br>
printers are everywhere, and everyone but the gardener has a PC on the <br>
desk. Larger departments are interconnected on two Novell/Ethernet LANs, <br>
and our camp (Pine Springs) is currently using Lantastic/Ethernet. (We'd <br>
like FDDI, but ...)<br>
<p>
My guess is that these people will first have to see the results of Local <br>
Email (they're still getting used to voice mail after a year!) and other <br>
networking goodies before they will jump for ATT Email, much less Internet. <br>
Perhaps as our LAN's enlarge, a critical mass will demand wider services.<br>
<p>
There are, of course, many other issues. For one, we at SECC still don't <br>
know why the GC chose ATT, but we do know that the discussions which took <br>
place several *years* ago didn't include us, or to our knowledge any local <br>
conference in the Pacific Union. The question now is, are we going to be <br>
locked into the ATT world by the GC? and what (cheap) mechanisms would get <br>
us into Internet? Did the GC ever consider *distributed* Internet <br>
addressing schemes?  Our local schools, and the elementary/secondary system <br>
at large seems captivated by Prodigy. Well, it is cheap.<br>
<p>
If nothing else you have provoked this SDAnetter to a few more serious <br>
conversations with local and union administrators, as well as some of the <br>
GC techies.<br>
<p>
Until next sunday's digest,<br>
<p>
David Johnson<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
