<title>Apr_1993: Re: Aaron &amp; Hur Club (SoP refs)</title>
<h1>Re: Aaron &amp; Hur Club (SoP refs)</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 6 Apr 93 10:33:16 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#155">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#155">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#155">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#155">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0156.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: What is AntiChrist ?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0154.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: SDA: America"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[fredch writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; {Could someone</i><br>
<i>&gt; check EGW refs (anyone got the CD-ROM?) to Aaron &amp; Hur to see if this</i><br>
<i>&gt; latter application has precedent?  I'm thinking maybe ...}</i><br>
<p>
Answering my own question 8-) ...:  PP299, 1T527, 2T108, 3T296, 4T531, 5T162.<br>
<p>
If memory serves ...  3T296 and PP299 read almost identically and speak of<br>
Aaron and Hur as being examples for how Israel should regard Moses.  1T527<br>
refers to evil surmisers in the church who would do better to follow<br>
Aaron &amp; Hur's example.  The remaining three are exhortations to serious<br>
intercessory prayer on behalf of pastors/leaders/burden bearers.  I found<br>
the latter two quite winsome, and will partially quote 4T531:<br>
<p>
{Joshua leading the army .. Moses "reaching his hands toward heaven and<br>
interceding in their behalf" .. "takes the whole matter to God in<br>
prayer" .. "pleading with the Lord" ..}<br>
"That prayer which comes forth from an earnest, believing heart is the<br>
effectual, fervent prayer that availeth much.  God does not always answer<br>
our prayers as we expect, for we may not ask what would be for our highest<br>
good; but in His infinite love and wisdom He will give us those things<br>
which we most need.  Happy the minister who has a faithful Aaron and Hur<br>
to strengthen his hands when they become weary and to hold them up by<br>
faith and prayer.  Such support is a powerful aid to the servant of Christ<br>
in his work and will often make the cause of truth to triumph gloriously."<br>
<p>
I think this answers the question as to whether the Aaron &amp; Hur metaphor<br>
applies to members supporting their pastor by prayer, etc.  I submit<br>
that we should pray earnestly for our pastors.  I see many attacks from<br>
Satan upon shepherds (Mt 26:31, a remarkable application of Zec 13:7).<br>
They need our intercessory prayers so that the dark clouds of confusion<br>
can be beaten back (note the struggle reported in Dan 10:11,12), so that<br>
they may have wisdom, understand truth, preach truth, and live the truth<br>
in purity and holiness (Ps 24:3,4; Eph 4:24, 1 Thess 4:7).<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
