</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; [ (1) ..] Contrast with the</i><br>
<i>&gt; original situation, where humans would have been born in a proper relationship</i><br>
<i>&gt; with God. [..]</i><br>
<i>&gt; [ (2) ..]</i><br>
<i>&gt; I think what is taught by many now is that Christ inherited weakness from</i><br>
<i>&gt; Adam, referred to in point 1, but that he was born without the separation</i><br>
<i>&gt; from God that the rest of us inherit.</i><br>
<p>
"Desire of Ages" makes some fairly specific statements about what sort of<br>
physical and moral-tendencies nature Christ inherited, based upon several<br>
texts of Scripture.  It also makes statements about His divine nature, such<br>
as He did not make use of it in battling temptation or even to perform<br>
miracles; that all victories/miracles were a manifestation of God's power,<br>
such as we also may benefit from.  I'm having difficulty matching what<br>
I've learned therein with "he was born without the separation from God<br>
that the rest of us inherit" (which would, in that respect, be identical<br>
to Adam pre-fall).  Perhaps I've overlooked something [*].  What is the<br>
Scriptural basis (fortified, presumably, with SoP material) for this claim?<br>
<p>
[*]  My wife and I were amazed in recently re-reading Patriarch's &amp; Prophets'<br>
     chapter "Seth and Enoch" that we had previously failed to grasp<br>
     several important principles of life.  I highly recommend a reading<br>
     of this during your next devotional time.<br>
<pre>
