<title>Apr_1993: Expressing concern</title>
<h1>Expressing concern</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>06 Apr 1993 12:23:36 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#121">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#121">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#121">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#121">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0122.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: SDA: The GC and the Internet"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The real issues?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Fred's remarks are very pertinent. What expressions of concern equate<br>
to "damaging criticism" and what are constructive? Clearly there is a large<br>
grey area, and as Fred stated, those on the receiving end often feel<br>
hurt and criticized anyway.<br>
<p>
Still, there are some things going on around the place which are unquestionably<br>
damaging. One example is the publication and distribution of tracts and<br>
videos aimed specifically at destroying a person or institution's reputation.<br>
I was given a booklet last year, upon asking what it was the reply was "it's<br>
the truth, just read it". The booklet used quotations from the Bible and<br>
Ellen White to pointedly say that the SDA church organization is Babylon,<br>
and to come out of her. It was a harsh, damning indictment, no holds barred,<br>
and I could not see how it was constructive in any way.<br>
<p>
For another example, I'll quote from a letter I received this morning from<br>
my mother-in-law in Melbourne.<br>
<p>
"Some of these CBs go a bit over the top. Apparently there was an<br>
advertisement in the paper at Mildura that the person taking the church<br>
service on Sabbath (Eric Winter) was responsible for introducing<br>
hypnotism into the Adventist church in Australia, and to not attend that<br>
day. Dr. Salom got a mention too. They had obviously bought several<br>
newspapers, cut the advertisements out, and then when people went to Church<br>
Sabbath morning, they found these advertisements stuck over the doors and<br>
windows etc. Not a very impressive thing to do. Not very impressive either<br>
to publicize these matters. And dishonest. There is NOT hypnotism in the<br>
SDA church!"  etc. etc.<br>
<p>
It takes a fair bit to make my mother-in-law mad, but that surely did!<br>
Church leaders are publicly criticized for running seminars on improving your<br>
self-esteem, because Ellen White said that self-esteem is "a poisonous weed,<br>
to be rooted out." Another minister attends a seminar on outreach techniques,<br>
and is subsequently labelled a hypnotist.Conservative congregations are<br>
afraid to look the minister in the eye while he is preaching, just in case<br>
they are mesmerized, because that's what the trouble-makers have told them<br>
will happen.<br>
<p>
A third thing is the Osborn videos on celebration which were circulated here.<br>
 From what I've heard, these videos had scenes from SDA churches mixed in with<br>
scenes from over-the-top charismatic churches, and other such deceptive tricks.<br>
I'm afraid that such things really don't help their cause in my eyes.<br>
<p>
So yes, there are valid questions to be answered regarding what is and is not<br>
a suitable way to express concern, but at the same time there are some things<br>
going on which seem definitely unsuitable!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
