<title>Apr_1993: missions and missionaries</title>
<h1>missions and missionaries</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 6 Apr 93 13:19:01 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#164">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#164">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#164">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#164">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0165.html">Ray Mialki: "Re: The Sovereignty of God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0163.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Dillema... What to do in this situation!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Pre WWII, many Japanese worshipped their emperor as a god (one of several).<br>
After the defeat of Japan, Chrisitians there reported a great interest in<br>
Christianity.  Many people groups of old viewed defeat or victory in battle<br>
as indicating the failure or success of their god in battle with their<br>
foes' god (cf 1 Sam chs 4,5).  Evidently the attitude of many Japanese was<br>
very similar.  Who was this God of the West?  Pleas were made to the<br>
American Bible Study for several million Bibles and hundreds of<br>
missionaries.  Alas!, no one in the West was prepared for this and the<br>
pleas went largely  unanswered.  Instead, Japan learned Western culture<br>
and materialism.  {adapted from an IBLP publication; the writer's father<br>
was, if memory serves, chairman (or something like that) of the ABS at<br>
that time}<br>
<p>
Many formerly closed countries are opening up to the Gospel (and for how<br>
long?).  The number of gospel workers needed far exceeds the supply<br>
(Mt 9:37,38; John 4:35; Rev 14:15).<br>
<p>
I am reminded of the prayer fragment that Eric B Hare's mother taught<br>
him, roughly "I want to be a servant of God's, even to the four corners of<br>
the earth."  Prompted me to examine whether I'm teaching my children to<br>
be self-serving or self-denying.<br>
<p>
My kids are all book-worms, but I guess they come by it naturally.  I would<br>
like to have our library contain many inspiring books of great Christians,<br>
great missionaries.  Anyone have good titles on folk like Hudson Taylor,<br>
William Carey, Adoniram Judson (I have the Jr Guide issues from years<br>
ago but no book), David Livingstone, Mary Slessor, Robert Moffatt,<br>
John Paton, Jim Elliot, the founders of Solusi, etc? If you share the<br>
interest, here are two (of many) that we really like:<br>
    Treasures from the Haunted Pagoda, by Eric B Hare<br>
    Fulton's Footsteps in Fiji, by Eric B Hare<br>
<p>
Finally, I'd like to plug Adventist Frontier Missions (church planting<br>
in unentered areas).  These missionaries seem to live a lot closer to<br>
the level of the local people, altho perhaps not totally akin to folk<br>
with Wycliffe Bible Translators.  I count important.  My wife and I<br>
spent some time in Zaire, fresh from college, newly married, with little<br>
to our names by Western standards.  Yet we appeared quite well-to-do<br>
in the eyes of Zairians, and that was an impediment.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
