<title>Apr_1993: Re: What is AntiChrist ?</title>
<h1>Re: What is AntiChrist ?</h1>
Malcolm Butler (<i>malb@boojum.ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 6 Apr 93 14:22:13 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#156">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#156">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#156">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#156">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0157.html">Steven Timm: "What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0155.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Aaron &amp; Hur Club (SoP refs)"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0119.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: What is AntiChrist ?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben Gonzalez writes:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Well If we can't trust the bible and the H.S then who do you propose we follow</i><br>
<i>&gt;the majority or the traditions of our church leaders, or what ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
It seems rather paradoxical, but I don't think we CAN do better than to<br>
trust the Bible and the H.S., and make the best decisions that we are<br>
able to come to.  But I'm rather concerned about how the position this<br>
places us in, as far as making pronouncements about right and wrong,<br>
since there are very clear examples where groups of people have tried<br>
this, presumably in good faith, and come into direct conflict with each<br>
other.<br>
<p>
How to resolve the paradox?  The most common way is for each person to<br>
assume that s/he is right, and the other person is wrong.  After all,<br>
if you can't trust yourself, who can you trust?  The other way is NOT<br>
to trust yourself, but to be fair, you can't trust the other person<br>
either.  So what are you left with?  Well, not to coin a phrase, "you<br>
only know what you know".  (Are you reading this, Mazz?)  If you can't<br>
see the other person's point of view, and can't make them see yours,<br>
you just have to agree to disagree.  Just hope that their belief isn't<br>
that it is God's will that they have to kill you.<br>
<p>
To tie this in to the thread on America, I just happened to see part of<br>
one of the Sunday morning religious programs on the weekend.  (In case<br>
you're wondering how I managed to drag myself up at that hour on a<br>
Sunday, I'd actually been up all night, and just flicked it on out of<br>
idle curiosity.  And no, I had NOT been out on the town, it was real<br>
work.)  It happened to be Norman Schwarzkopf (sp?) talking about his<br>
experiences in Vietnam and the Gulf war.  He said that the best<br>
experience of his life was his first tour in Vietnam, because it was so<br>
wonderful to be fighting on the side of right.  Similarly, during the<br>
Gulf War, he said the feeling among the troups was that even if the<br>
Iraqis had had all their high-tech equipment and numerical advantages,<br>
they would still have won, because God was on their side.<br>
<p>
I'll resist commenting on the America-in-prophecy thread here, though<br>
it is no doubt relevant, but this sort of thing scares me silly,<br>
because, at least from listening to him for five minutes, there seems<br>
no doubt that this is what he really believes.  If you asked Saddam<br>
Hussein, I am sure he would be equally fervent in proclaiming his<br>
belief in his own divine appointment.  It's all well and good to say<br>
that at least one (or even both) are completely and utterly deluded,<br>
but they really and truly believe they are right.  So can we do any<br>
better than to draw OUR own conclusions, and trust OUR own judgement<br>
(which is presumably what they are doing)?  Of course, we study the<br>
Bible and ask the H.S. for guidance (which they have not necessarily<br>
done), but in the end, you make the decision for yourself.  We can say<br>
that they are deluded, but how do I know for sure that it is not me<br>
that is deluded?  It seems impossible to get entirely away from the<br>
interpreting process.<br>
<p>
<p>
Malcolm<br>
<pre>
-- 
Switched Networks Research Centre,               malb@ee.uts.edu.au
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia            +61 2 330 2344
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
