<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I think what is taught by many now is along the lines of "Sin is living</i><br>
<i>&gt; your life independently of God in wilful rebellion against his authority."</i><br>
<i>&gt; And the when a human is born, the default is that they are not in a proper</i><br>
<i>&gt; relationship with God, and that this must be remedied. Contrast with the</i><br>
<i>&gt; original situation, where humans would have been born in a proper relationship</i><br>
<i>&gt; with God.</i><br>
<p>
Huh ? I was never aware of the original situation being as you express it.<br>
The original situation was the relationship of the child was dependant of the<br>
relationship of the parents with God.<br>
<p>
We can also be born with a fully intact relationship with God,<br>
<p>
What does God say regarding this matter ?<br>
<p>
Look at Luke 1:13-15,  Isa 59:2 and<br>
 <br>
Jeremiah 1:5 "Before I formed thee in the belly I knew thee; and before thou camest forth out of the womb I sanctified thee, .."<br>
<p>
NOT all are born separated from God.<br>
 <br>
What is it that separates us from God ?<br>
<p>
 "But your iniquities have separated between you and your God, and your sins<br>
    have hid His face from you, that He will not hear." Isa 59:2<br>
<p>
So if you say we are born separate from God it can only be because of original <br>
sin.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I have heard SDAs say that Hebrews does not speak about the geography of</i><br>
<i>&gt; heaven, although they do believe there is a heavenly sanctuary, and that</i><br>
<i>&gt; the priestly role of Christ changed in 1844. Does this constitute a vague</i><br>
<i>&gt; uncertainty? (not a rhetorical question btw)</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
I have heard ministers categorically deny that anything happened in 1844<br>
and that Jesus never went into the Most Holy Place at all and if He did<br>
it was at His ascention.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
