<title>Apr_1993: Re: Definition of CB</title>
<h1>Re: Definition of CB</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 6 Apr 93 15:24:49 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#146">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#146">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#146">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#146">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0147.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  The Sovereignty of God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0145.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: The real issue"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0091.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Definition of CB"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0168.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Definition of CB"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Something perhaps worthy of discussion is:  What distinguishes "helpful</i><br>
<i>&gt; and constructive" comment from "damaging" comment?  When one is on</i><br>
<i>&gt; the receiving end, it is often difficult to be objective.  Also, what</i><br>
<i>&gt; distinguishes "criticism" from 'expressing concern' or 'making a</i><br>
<i>&gt; heart-felt appeal'?  Since I think we are all willing to accept that</i><br>
<i>&gt; conference and institution leaders can and do make mistakes, how should</i><br>
<i>&gt; a concerned brother or sister relate? i.e., what characterizes a godly,</i><br>
<i>&gt; Scripturally-based approach?</i><br>
<i>&gt; -- </i><br>
<p>
 It seems to me that all of the prophets and especially Jerimiah would have<br>
been prime candidates for CB-manship. <br>
<p>
You see Jerimiah was sooo critical of the leadership and the church that<br>
they decided to get rid of him. He was accusing them of every type of sin<br>
you could name, and worse than tht he was publishing evil reports about the <br>
church, that it would fall, they were very unhappy with the critical, divisive, <br>
and combative spirit that Jerimiah exhibited that they decided to <br>
disfellowshsip him.<br>
But that didn't work and so they decided to really rub him out, in the<br>
end the best they could do was to silence him up by sticking down a well.<br>
<p>
Talk about making damaging and destructive comments, Jerimiah was telling<br>
the church members to completely ignore the leadership because they were ALL<br>
apostates and telling them to stop supporting them. They did not like this<br>
one bit, talk about Ralf Larson, he is a kitty purring compared to Jerimiah's<br>
roaring. Jeremiah was making them look bad not only in the church but even<br>
to the outside world, What an unchristian man he was !!<br>
<p>
Jeremiah is the arch-CB, a role model for all contemporary CB's !:^) <br>
<p>
(how about we all go and read the story again some time ?)<br>
<p>
A bit like Elijah I would say (maybe he was the arch-CB), I mean even the <br>
conference president (who was trying to locate him for disfellowshipping)<br>
when he finally found him said "boy are you a trouble maker, look at all the<br>
divisivenes and lack of confidence in the leadership that you have brought<br>
into the church" Well in good CB combative spirit Elijah turns around and<br>
says "Not me, But YOU and the leadership, have brought this trouble upon<br>
yourselves" Take ThaT !!! And boy did the Gen. conference president like<br>
that, he was more determined than ever to get him. But anyway Elijah decided<br>
he wanted to call a show down. He was into those sort of things, you know<br>
expose it all into the open and really ridicule the apostates. Nothing<br>
like a bit of excitement to get the youth interested !!!<br>
<p>
Jesus says "Blessed are ye when men shall hate you and when they shall separate<br>
you from their company, and shall reproach you and shall cast out your name as <br>
evil, for the Son of Man's sake. Rejoice ye in that day and leap for joy for<br>
behold your reward is great in heaven, for in like manner did their fathers<br>
unto the prophets."<br>
<p>
Notice of whom Jesus is speaking in these verses, it is not the world, but<br>
the church who did likewise unto the prophets.<br>
<p>
-----<br>
<p>
This little reality break, has been brought to you, to say that before we<br>
start jumping up and down like some did in the past when men arise saying<br>
things we don't like, that we should listen very carfully to see if there<br>
is any truth, however unpaletable in the message that they bring.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
