<title>Apr_1993: Re: The real issues?</title>
<h1>Re: The real issues?</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 6 Apr 93 17:06:08 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#159">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#159">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#159">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#159">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0160.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Relationship theology"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0158.html">Steven Timm: "Relationships and sin"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0132.html">Steven Timm: "The real issues?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Larson seems unwilling to admit that Christ was in any way advantaged</i><br>
<i>&gt;over His fellow humans.  This makes it hard for him to show why it was </i><br>
<i>&gt;necessary for Christ to be divine, or why a savior ought to be divine.</i><br>
<p>
EGW categorically states that Jesus had NO advantage over us. So I can't <br>
see that as any major problem with Larsons understanding.<br>
<p>
Tell me what reason would you supply as a requirement for Jesus to be divine ?<br>
Remember that if it has soley to do with superior relationships any angel<br>
could have done the job as well. Jesus didn't use any power we don't have at<br>
our displosal in even greater quantities that He had.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; You can scarcely call the current mix Calvinistic, because Calvinists</i><br>
<i>&gt; are predestinarians, which no SDA's of any flavor are.  Nevertheless</i><br>
<i>&gt; there is antinomianism in the SDA church and Larson is right to call it</i><br>
<i>&gt; to task.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
When Larson refers to Calvinism he does not refer to Calvinism as understood<br>
in todays sense of the word. I once heard (read) somewhere his explaination<br>
of his usage the term Calvinistic. I think his thrust was that original<br>
Calvinism was rather different from todays version of it and was one of<br>
the two basic views of the gospel back in reformation days. You could choose<br>
from either the Calvinistic or the Armenian view point. Calvinism taught<br>
that one could never gain the victory over sin and so one must be saved in<br>
sin rather than from it. This of course also implied that Jesus could not<br>
have been like us and that in turn defined the nature of sin etc.<br>
The Armenian (ie from Armenius) view point was that one could obtain the <br>
victory over sin in the same way Jesus did. Therefore flowed the teaching<br>
that Jesus was in effect like us in all things which implied that sin<br>
is what de do not what we are.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Besides those on the far left in SDA colonies, and Desmond Ford's crowd,</i><br>
<i>&gt; I have not seen a wholesale rejection of the sanctuary doctrine.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
No and the evangelicals don't reject it wholesale either they just think<br>
the whole thing is not particularly relevant and does'nt really have<br>
very many practical applications. I've never had any evangelical reject<br>
the doctrine of a heavenly sanctuary to me. That doesn't make them SDAs.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The position being denied is that of various Review editors after the</i><br>
<i>&gt; death of Ellen G. White who built up the doctrine of verbal inspiration</i><br>
<i>&gt; in contradiction to her writings.  Perhaps this re-examination would not</i><br>
<i>&gt; have </i><br>
<i>&gt; taken place had not the Walter Rea controversy occured.  But I think </i><br>
<i>&gt; the re-examination is good for the church.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Q. What of the three levels of inspiration presented by Tony which would<br>
you suggest should be applied in EGW's case, plenary or encounter inspiration ?<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
