<title>Apr_1993: What I think everyone agrees on</title>
<h1>What I think everyone agrees on</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  6 Apr 1993 23:55:49 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#157">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#157">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#157">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#157">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0158.html">Steven Timm: "Relationships and sin"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0156.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: What is AntiChrist ?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0166.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Human nature of Christ:<br>
Christ was born with the same type of physical infirmities and inherited <br>
tendencies that anyone at the time he lived would have.<br>
<p>
Christ overcame sin with the same power from God that is available to <br>
every believer for the asking.<br>
<p>
Human nature of people:<br>
It is observed, that, original sin or no, every human that has ever lived<br>
has sinned, and that fairly soon after birth.  So the question of<br>
imputed guilt is moot, whether sin be relationship-breaking or action,<br>
everyone has done it except Jesus Christ himself  (Rom 3:23).<br>
<p>
Human nature of Christ:<br>
It is obvious that Christ did not do so, but nevertheless was capable of<br>
doing so (what does this mean to those who say that God cannot sin?).<br>
<p>
The gospel: <br>
Christ is willing to make the power that was available to Him available<br>
to all of us, so victory over sin can be ours.<br>
<p>
We see that independent of any possible differences in nature, there is<br>
certainly a difference in behavior between Christ and any other human<br>
being that has ever lived.  So we ask:  What made this difference?<br>
<p>
1)  Was Christ born with what we are not--an unbroken relationship with God?<br>
Did he have from the beginning what we acquire only once we are born again?<br>
Was that which becomes second nature for us first nature for Him?  <br>
<p>
I believe so, and believe such a view is consistent with all the points <br>
of agreement above.<br>
<p>
But there are at least two other options:<br>
<p>
2)  Christ was born with the same broken relationship as the rest of us<br>
and by some miracle was able to be "born again" before the natural "gimme"<br>
reflexes of infancy began to manifest themselves.<br>
<p>
3)  Everyone is born with an intact relationship with God, just Christ was<br>
the only one not to blow it.<br>
<p>
The difficulty I have relating to the positions presented here is that<br>
most of those who are telling me that Christ was human enough to be my<br>
example<br>
aren't explaining how He is divine enough to be my Savior.  I think we're<br>
getting somewhere with this discussion--let's keep it up.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
