<title>Apr_1993: Relationships and sin</title>
<h1>Relationships and sin</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  7 Apr 1993 00:01:25 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#158">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#158">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#158">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#158">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0159.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: The real issues?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0157.html">Steven Timm: "What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0170.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Relationships and sin"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben points out that Adam is one who began with a perfect relationship<br>
to God.  He quotes the text "iniquities have separated you from God."<br>
However, let's examine it closely.  Adam's sin didn't begin with eating<br>
the fruit.  The first sin Adam made was to doubt God, and as soon as this<br>
happened, his relationship with God was not in working order.  The <br>
sin of action followed.  So the iniquity did indeed separate Adam from God,<br>
but the separation happened well before the fruit was munched.  Read<br>
Patriarchs and Prophets with regard to this.   I would, but my library<br>
is trapped in Pittsburgh.  (I'll get there next weekend.)<br>
<p>
As to whether Adam sinned again or not, we have no record of that.  Any<br>
statement on that account is mere speculation.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
