As quoted from the previous post, "The authors conclude that although the<br>
boomers might want flexibility in their worship, they definitely also want<br>
some well-defined moral and religious boundaries."<br>
<p>
"I find this last observation of special interest in view of some recent<br>
pressures for the SDA church to "relax" some of our standards in order to<br>
reach out to groups like the boomers."<br>
<p>
This looks like an excellent topic for discussion.  What are the "standards"<br>
which define us as a people.  Should we have behavioral standards which are<br>
required as tests of fellowhip?  (Non-smoking for example.)  If so, why,<br>
considering the crowd of "sinners", tax collectors, prostitutes and societal<br>
dropouts that Jesus ran around with.  If not, why not considering the advice<br>
of Jesus in Matthew 18 about how to deal with those who are sinners and the<br>
advice of Paul (see for example his vigorous comments in Corinthians 5:<br>
9-13).  <br>
<p>
I look forward to your comments,<br>
<p>
Ron Swensen<br>
ron swen@aol.com<br>
