<!-- name="Noe Torres | ECISD" -->
<!-- email="noe@tenet.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Re: What I think everyone agrees on" -->
<!-- id="Pine.3.03.9304071420.A26265-c100000@Joyce-Perkins.tenet.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="kfkZ35S00YUo9QIH5m@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<title>Apr_1993: Re: What I think everyone agrees on</title>
<h1>Re: What I think everyone agrees on</h1>
Noe Torres | ECISD (<i>noe@tenet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 7 Apr 1993 14:44:21 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#167">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#167">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#167">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#167">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0168.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Definition of CB"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0166.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0157.html">Steven Timm: "What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0178.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It's not that I don't agree with what Steven cites as things everyone<br>
agrees on....  It's just that I have questions:<br>
<p>
On Tue, 6 Apr 1993, Steven Timm wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Human nature of Christ:</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christ was born with the same type of physical infirmities and inherited </i><br>
<i>&gt; tendencies that anyone at the time he lived would have.</i><br>
<p>
I am in full agreement with this statement, based on my reading of<br>
Scripture and Mrs. White's commentaries.  But alas, it's not the physical<br>
or genetic attributes that we are mainly concerned about -- it's Christ's<br>
spiritual standing.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Christ overcame sin with the same power from God that is available to </i><br>
<i>&gt; every believer for the asking.</i><br>
<p>
OK, but I have these very innocent questions:  Does this mean that we too<br>
can "tap" into this "power" and overcome exactly as Christ overcame?  And<br>
if so, what was the point of the Atonement?  And if so, why couldn't Adam<br>
have "tapped" into it sufficient to prevent the Fall or to remedy the Fall?<br>
What about Lucifer and his access to this "power"?  And what power is it,<br>
anyway, and what relationship does this power have to the Atonement?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Human nature of people:</i><br>
<i>&gt; It is observed, that, original sin or no, every human that has ever lived</i><br>
<i>&gt; has sinned, and that fairly soon after birth.  So the question of</i><br>
<i>&gt; imputed guilt is moot, whether sin be relationship-breaking or action,</i><br>
<i>&gt; everyone has done it except Jesus Christ himself  (Rom 3:23).</i><br>
<p>
Humbly, I ask: if there is no "imputed sin" then each of us has the<br>
potential to become our own "savior," is this not so?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Human nature of Christ:</i><br>
<i>&gt; It is obvious that Christ did not do so, but nevertheless was capable of</i><br>
<i>&gt; doing so (what does this mean to those who say that God cannot sin?).</i><br>
<p>
I would say that He placed Himself in the same position as Adam before the<br>
Fall (spiritually-speaking) and was "capable" of sin, but was not<br>
naturally inclined or disposed toward sin as we are.  Thus, Christ is<br>
referred to in the NT as the Second Adam.  He proved that Adam need not<br>
have fallen -- is this not correct?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The gospel: </i><br>
<i>&gt; Christ is willing to make the power that was available to Him available</i><br>
<i>&gt; to all of us, so victory over sin can be ours.</i><br>
<p>
Is not the power to have victory over sin DERIVED from Christ's own<br>
victory over sin?  Isn't it because of Christ's perfect life and atoning<br>
death that He qualifies to grant us by grace His perfection to take the<br>
place of our own "filthiness"?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; We see that independent of any possible differences in nature, there is</i><br>
<i>&gt; certainly a difference in behavior between Christ and any other human</i><br>
<i>&gt; being that has ever lived.  So we ask:  What made this difference?</i><br>
<p>
I have been of the opinion that Christ's "difference" was simply that He<br>
did not suffer the same "propensity" toward sin (as per the famous Baker<br>
letter statement) that developed post-fall.  I don't feel He could have<br>
and yet been the spotless Lamb who did not need to be sacificed for His<br>
own sin but rather who gave his pure life as a sacrifice "without spot and<br>
without blemish."<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; most of those who are telling me that Christ was human enough to be my</i><br>
<i>&gt; example</i><br>
<i>&gt; aren't explaining how He is divine enough to be my Savior.  I think we're</i><br>
<i>&gt; getting somewhere with this discussion--let's keep it up.</i><br>
<p>
I sense a danger in making Christ "altogether one as ourselves."  Yes, He<br>
was fully human.  Yes, he suffered in all things as we suffer.  He felt<br>
our pain and our sin laid upon Him who knew no sin.  <br>
<p>
I also see a problem with attributing Christ's victory to an external<br>
force and then suggesting that any human, by tapping into this external<br>
force, can win out their victory.  I believe we are saved by accepting<br>
Christ's victory on our behalf by faith -- not by trying to tap into a<br>
"power" that will "help" us to reproduce His accomplishments.<br>
<p>
But please, I am a student....  Let me hear your thoughts.<br>
<p>
NOE&gt;<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
