<title>Apr_1993: Re: Definition of CB</title>
<h1>Re: Definition of CB</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 7 Apr 93 15:04:00 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#168">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#168">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#168">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#168">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0169.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: The real issue"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0167.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0091.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Definition of CB"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Will the real CB please stand up !<br>
----------------------------------<br>
<p>
The expression CB is generally used to describe a large segment<br>
of historic Adventists. Due to the noncomplimentary way in which<br>
the expression is used toa label people some say that it applies<br>
only to those SDAs which are critical and negative about the church<br>
organisation. In many cases it is used to tar all conservatives with<br>
the same brush.<br>
<p>
Where did the expression originate from ? During the mid '70s when<br>
Dr Des Ford was in his element at Avondale College certain leading<br>
ministers called the attention of the division to the distorted<br>
doctrines which Ford was openly teaching. The division chose to cover<br>
up the issue and make certain underhanded moves in order to do so. Many <br>
leading ministers some of which were retired wrote a letter of <br>
protest to the division regarding the way in which the matter was being <br>
handled. They signed their names following the expression "the concerned <br>
bretheren".  It was only latter that any action was taken regarding Ford.<br>
I have personally read the letter and know which are the ministers who<br>
signed the letter, these men were very well respected and leading ministers<br>
at all levels of the organisation. They were not negative or critical<br>
but wanted truth to be brought out into the open and dealt with.<br>
<p>
Now we are told that CB's refers to the extreme radical elements in the church.<br>
I'm not sure how these men, the original CB's would appreciate the usage of <br>
label. It is true that there are some radical and extreme elements in<br>
the church but these have very little in common with the principles and<br>
actions cherished by the true concerned bretheren.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
