<title>Apr_1993: Re: What I think everyone agrees on</title>
<h1>Re: What I think everyone agrees on</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 7 Apr 93 16:14:19 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#187">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#187">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#187">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#187">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0188.html">Steven Timm: "Iniquities and separation from God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0186.html">Steven Timm: "Distinctive features"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0166.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0167.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Sherman Cox writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm Writes:</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Christ overcame sin with the same power from God that is available to </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; every believer for the asking.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Does everyone or I should say a vast majority of adventists believe in the</i><br>
<i>&gt; complete overcoming of all sin in this life thorugh the power of God?</i><br>
<p>
My reading of Scripture and SoP indicates it is possible and indeed<br>
desirable and should be our aim.  Witness the lives of Enoch, Moses,<br>
and Elijah.  Would it be valid to claim:<br>
  Only those who, from the Fall until the close of probation, have removed<br>
  all sin from their lives will be saved?<br>
I hesitate on that one (have not studied this out thoroughly, weighing<br>
all refs in their contexts); one will not know for sure (I'm thinking<br>
of EGW's description of folk during the time of Jacob's trouble).  Would<br>
it be valid to claim:<br>
  All those who, from the Fall until the close of probation, in the eyes<br>
  of God, are earnestly seeking to overcome all sin in their lives and<br>
  in whom the trend is victory rather than defeat, will be saved? (cf<br>
  John 16:8; 1 Pet 4:17; Lam 3:40; esp Ps 139:23,24 for some add'l tho'ts)<br>
<p>
I'm more comfortable with the latter at this point.  Regardless, I submit<br>
that overcoming sin by the blood of the Lamb is one characteristic of those<br>
who love His appearing (1 Tim 4:8), who desire His character (actions,<br>
attitudes, motives (Jer 17:10), methods, words, thoughts (2 Cor 10:5;<br>
Phil 2:5), etc) to be fully reflected in theirs, who thirst after<br>
righteousness, who accept His Lordship, who hold nothing back, who<br>
want a new heart (Rom 2:15; 2 Cor 3:3; Heb 8:10, 10:16,22; Jer 31:33),<br>
who humble themselves under God's hand, who fear the Lord, who behold<br>
Jesus only, who abide in Christ, whose hearts are teachable; those in whom<br>
the Holy Spirit dwells.<br>
<p>
I note a recurring theme in Scripture (e.g., Ps chs 18, 24) re clean hands<br>
and pure heart, echoed in SoP (e.g., Testimonies to Ministers and Gospel<br>
Workers).  Also themes re the Day of Atonement, esp as were are living<br>
in the antitypical (Lev 16, Dan 8:14).  Themes on holiness and<br>
overcoming also abound.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
