<title>Apr_1993: other beings</title>
<h1>other beings</h1>
Clayton Alves (<i>alvescv@vuse.vanderbilt.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 7 Apr 93 16:41:34 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#185">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#185">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#185">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#185">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0186.html">Steven Timm: "Distinctive features"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0184.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: The Generation That Forgot God."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0190.html">Woody Baker: "Re: other beings"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
If you have read the first two chapters of Job in conjunction with the<br>
sabbath school lesson, you may have notice the phrase "the sons of God".<br>
In my sabbath school class my teacher went off on a tangent and asked if<br>
we thought the sons of God like we do. After all, Adam was a son of God.<br>
I answered no, just as I believe that angels may not look as we portray them<br>
(men with wings). After class I was asked by a visiting adventist what would<br>
be the purpose of creating other beings in an image different from God's.<br>
Of course I have no answer for that question, but I still beleive that the <br>
being (sons of God) on other planets do not have to look like us. Plus we<br>
have been changed because of sin. So, when we recieve new bodies, we may not<br>
look exactly like we do now.<br>
<p>
Let here your thoughts on the matter.<br>
<p>
Clayton Alves<br>
Vanderbilt University<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
