<title>Apr_1993: Re: Relationship theology</title>
<h1>Re: Relationship theology</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 7 Apr 93 16:59:31 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#183">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#183">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#183">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#183">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0184.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: The Generation That Forgot God."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0182.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: The real issues? (Dr. Ralph Larson)"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0130.html">Steven Timm: "Relationship theology"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0199.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: Relationship theology"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Apr 6,  4:40pm, Ruben Gonzalez wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re: Relationship theology</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; The opposite would be a broken relationship with God, which would lead to</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; wrong thoughts and attitudes and thus to wrong actions.  All three of</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; these levels would be sin, but it was all curable through a restoration</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; of the relationship with God.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Did Adam have a right relationship with God ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Did Adam sin ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Was it a broken relationship that lead him to sin ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; What did break Adam's relationship ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; "But your iniquities have separated between you and your God, and your sins</i><br>
<i>&gt;     have hid His face from you, that He will not hear." Isa 59:2</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; No Adam did not sin because he had a bad relationship, it was his sin that</i><br>
<i>&gt; broke a good relationship.</i><br>
<p>
What was his "sin", in this case?<br>
<p>
A relationship does not cause sin but can indicate how susceptible you might be to<br>
sin.  A weak relationship with God can certainly lead to sin but a healthy<br>
relationship can help prevent alot of falling down.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Did Adam's broken relationship now mean he kept on sinning ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; No Adam did not keep on sinning, he fixed the relationship and did not sin</i><br>
<i>&gt; again after that.</i><br>
<p>
Do we know for a fact that Adam did not keep on sinning?<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
