<!-- body="start" -->
[From Noe Torres]<br>
I too am having difficulty making the distinction between "Adam's<br>
separation from God" and "Adam's guilt."  Isn't sin, by definition, a<br>
separation from God -- a breach in trust?  How else could Adam have been<br>
separated from God?  I've always believed in "original sin," meaning that<br>
from conception we are born under the effects of the transgression of our<br>
first parents.  Subsequently we add our own transgressions (plural) to the<br>
"original" transgression to which we are all subject.  If this were not<br>
the case, then every human being would be "without sin" until such time as<br>
he/she deliberately and willfully committed a sin, and thus every human<br>
being would have the potential to become his/her own saviour.  Alas,<br>
Christ need not have died....<br>
<p>
NOE.<br>
<p>
[The text he included from Ruben's post is deleted.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
