<title>Apr_1993: Distinctive features</title>
<h1>Distinctive features</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  7 Apr 1993 22:50:07 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#186">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#186">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#186">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#186">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0187.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0185.html">Clayton Alves: "other beings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tony asked:  What should be the distinctive features of the SDA church?<br>
I answer:  The same as those of the church in Acts.  Acts 4:13 "...they were<br>
marveling, and began to recognize them as having been with Jesus."<br>
<p>
Note that many other signs also characterized the NT church.  These<br>
included manifestations of all the gifts of the Spirit, but more<br>
important, unity <br>
of mind and purpose.  Also a phenomenal spiritual authority exercised<br>
by the apostles--Sapphira lies and is immediately struck down dead.<br>
There were also standards:  Abstain from fornication, from things<br>
offered to idols, from things strangled, and from blood.  But I think<br>
these all derived<br>
from the first distinctive, knowing and spending time with Jesus.<br>
<p>
Keith Green once said  "Going to church doesn't make you a Christian<br>
any more than going to McDonald's makes you a hamburger."  The traditional <br>
distinctives that have set SDA's apart are necessary, but they are good only<br>
if once people look at us, the distinctive people, they see a reflection<br>
of Christ.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
