<title>Apr_1993: What is "Historic Adventism"?</title>
<h1>What is "Historic Adventism"?</h1>
James Jackman (<i>71221.3506@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>08 Apr 93 01:01:38 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#191">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#191">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#191">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#191">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0192.html">Ray Mialki: "Re: Relationships and sin"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0190.html">Woody Baker: "Re: other beings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0213.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: What is "Historic Adventism"?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The ongoing discussion of defining "conservatives," "liberals," "concerned <br>
brethren," etc., has left me with a new label to ponder. I have been a member <br>
of the SDA church for close to twenty years. I attended SDA schools from the <br>
7th grade through college, but had never heard the term "Historic Adventism" <br>
until several months ago when our congregation was searching for a new pastor.<br>
What is "Historic Adventism?" How does this differ from, what I must assume is<br>
the opposite, "Modern Adventism?" <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
