<title>Apr_1993: Complete overcoming</title>
<h1>Complete overcoming</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>08 Apr 1993 09:54:59 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#179">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#179">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#179">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#179">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0180.html">Malachi Robertson: "Missions and the Bible"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0178.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Through God all things are possible, a very well-known text, so I would<br>
say that yes, a vast majority of Adventists do believe that it is possible<br>
for a complete overcoming of all sin in this life through the power of God.<br>
(I think I know what was meant by "all sin" in this question.)<br>
<p>
Do they believe that it can happen for them as individuals? Deep down I <br>
think a lot of us have instinctive doubts, even if the beliefs we have<br>
chosen to adopt tell us otherwise.<br>
<p>
Do they believe it *will* come about? Do they believe it *should*? Do they<br>
believe it absolutely *has to* or they cannot be rescued from this world?<br>
Do they believe others have overcome sin (through Christ's power) in the<br>
past?<br>
<p>
Belief and practice...if only the two were more synonymous, more easily.<br>
Even some who claim to believe in this salvation by faith (from sin, not ini<br>
it) seem very preoccupied by all kinds of little things, and let this<br>
"overcoming" take precedence even over other aspects of their Christian<br>
witness.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
