<!-- inreplyto="wfksh0m00YUo8RTMxC@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<title>Apr_1993: Re: The real issues?</title>
<h1>Re: The real issues?</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 8 Apr 93 17:22:49 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#193">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#193">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#193">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#193">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0194.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Re: The real issues? (Dr. Ralph Larson)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0192.html">Ray Mialki: "Re: Relationships and sin"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0175.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The real issues?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0198.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: The real issues?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Noe Wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I too am having difficulty making the distinction between "Adam's</i><br>
<i>&gt; separation from God" and "Adam's guilt."  Isn't sin, by definition, a</i><br>
<i>&gt; separation from God -- a breach in trust?  How else could Adam have been</i><br>
<p>
Once again our definition of sin will make a difference in our theology<br>
tremendously<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; separated from God?  I've always believed in "original sin," meaning that</i><br>
<i>&gt; from conception we are born under the effects of the transgression of our</i><br>
<i>&gt; first parents.  Subsequently we add our own transgressions (plural) to the</i><br>
<i>&gt; "original" transgression to which we are all subject.  If this were not</i><br>
<i>&gt; the case, then every human being would be "without sin" until such time as</i><br>
<i>&gt; he/she deliberately and willfully committed a sin, and thus every human</i><br>
<i>&gt; being would have the potential to become his/her own saviour.  Alas,</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christ need not have died....</i><br>
<p>
This argument is not clear for you assume that an individual who does not <br>
commit a sin needs a saviour.  Rather that person would be his own saviour <br>
or Christ would be his saviour.  That assumption I would like to see proven,<br>
I do not deny it I just want to see it proven.  Of course we all have sinned<br>
so potential or not we are all guilty of some sin.  The qeustion<br>
is is some of this guilt passed to us as a result of Adam's transgression.<br>
<p>
Next if someone does not commit a sin, he fulfilled the law from birth you <br>
say that he would be guilty anyway.  This is only telling us the definition<br>
of original sin.<br>
<p>
So what you are saying is original sin is true because original sin is true.<br>
In other words you are saying that there is an original transgression (Adam's)<br>
of which<br>
we are guilty,  because if we were to live our life without sin we would still<br>
have Adam's transgression counted against us.  That is circular reasoning.<br>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
"Competition is the law of the jungle.
 Cooperation is the law of civilization."  -  Eldridge Cleaver
<p>
Sherman H. Cox, II       scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
