<title>Apr_1993: Re: Relationships and sin</title>
<h1>Re: Relationships and sin</h1>
Ray Mialki (<i>rm1g+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu,  8 Apr 1993 18:28:56 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#192">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#192">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#192">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#192">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0193.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: The real issues?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0191.html">James Jackman: "What is "Historic Adventism"?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0170.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Relationships and sin"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0202.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Relationships and sin"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am sorry, but I find it hard to believe that Adam was without sin<br>
after the initial fall.  It is mere speculation to believe otherwise. <br>
Take a close look at the passage, and you will see that there were other<br>
occasions of sin around that same episode.<br>
<p>
Adam was with Eve throughout the entire episode.  Yet he allowed Eve to<br>
be the spokesperson about the things of God, abdicating his role as<br>
spiritual head over the family.  He allowed Eve to eat the fruit, while<br>
he stood right by her.  Then he ate some of the fruit himnself.<br>
<p>
Then confrontation time.  When God confronts Adam, he first blames the<br>
woman for his sin, and then finally blames God for putting the woman<br>
there in the first place.  This does not sound like a man who is<br>
repentant.  And since Scripture says that if we train up a child in the<br>
way that he should go, he will not depart from it when older, take a<br>
look at Cain.  If Adam no longer sinned after the fall, where did Cain<br>
get such an example to live his life by?  <br>
<p>
Ray the kop<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
