<title>Apr_1993: Re: What is "Historic Adventism"?</title>
<h1>Re: What is "Historic Adventism"?</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 9 Apr 93 7:48:44 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#213">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#213">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#213">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#213">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0214.html">Steven Timm: "Immunity to the Gospel?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0212.html">Dan Gill: "dinosaurs"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0191.html">James Jackman: "What is "Historic Adventism"?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; What is "Historic Adventism?" How does this differ from, what I must assume is</i><br>
<i>&gt; the opposite, "Modern Adventism?" </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
 From my understanding, Historic Adventism is the term those people who believe<br>
that the church is giving up some of the fundamental doctrines of our past <br>
call themsleves.  They believe taht the teachers of this "New Theology" are<br>
giving up the doctrines that made this church great.  I believe "New Theology"<br>
is used to describe them not necessarily "Modern Adventism".  <br>
<p>
One thing about Histoiric Adventism though, the name sounds almost stale and<br>
, in other words it sounds as though no new truth is needed or accepted.  This<br>
is from my experience with so-called "Historical Adventists."  I hope we never<br>
get to the position or place wherre we can not or will not consider "new light."<br>
<p>
But once again, this is my perception.  Perhaps others may have better definitions.<br>
<p>
<p>
