<title>Apr_1993: Center Stage ...</title>
<h1>Center Stage ...</h1>
Dave Thomas (<i>umsfdtho@deimos.oscs.montana.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 9 Apr 93 08:34:10 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#211">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#211">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#211">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#211">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0212.html">Dan Gill: "dinosaurs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0210.html">TANG BENG YONG: "being different"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0222.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  Center Stage ..."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
All this talk about the nature of Christ, the nature of man, <br>
whether or not we can live perfect lives while waiting for<br>
the return of Christ ... it seems to place argumentation itself<br>
at center stage of the great controversy ... as if our salvation<br>
is somehow dependent on us thrashing out the answers to <br>
questions that have been unanswered for thousands of years.  That<br>
places far too high a value on what we THINK and far too little<br>
emphasis on what Christ had DONE.  He saved us while we are still<br>
ignorant savages.  No degree in theology is required, not that<br>
such degrees offer much practical help to sin damaged souls.  <br>
<p>
The real battle is not between us and Satan.  It isn't between us<br>
and God.  It's between Christ and Satan and the outcome has already<br>
been decided.  Placing our own silly thoughts at center stage of<br>
this controversy is both egotistical and dangerous.  What we thinks<br>
is important, but not as important as Who we love and trust.<br>
<p>
Dave Thomas<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
