<title>Apr_1993: being different</title>
<h1>being different</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix3.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 9 Apr 93 13:24:23 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#210">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#210">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#210">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#210">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0211.html">Dave Thomas: "Center Stage ..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0209.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Original sin"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Maurice George Ashton writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;This question no doubt has to do with our sense of identity. We like to</i><br>
<i>&gt;think of ourselves being different, and that those differences are important.</i><br>
<i>&gt;I would be the last to suggest that the differences are not important, but</i><br>
<i>&gt;I am also concerned that sometimes we make wear those differences high on</i><br>
<i>&gt;our sleeves when it would be best not to do so.</i><br>
<p>
Well, we are differnet, but the fact that we are is, to me, incidental,<br>
and not of any importance in itself.  The important thing is that we are<br>
following the all truth revealed to us by God.  If, because of that, we<br>
are different, than so be it, if we are the same, than so be it too.  We<br>
should not try to conform to be "one of the crowd" just for the sake of<br>
conformity, neither should we try to be different just to be different.<br>
We should just follow where God leads and be whatever He wants us to be,<br>
and not worry too much about it.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Surely there is a lot of common ground between Catholics, Protestants,</i><br>
<i>&gt;Evangelicals, Charasmatics and Seventh-day Adventists. I recall a discussion</i><br>
<i>&gt;on Christianity I had with a Catholic Priest, whose kindness and love</i><br>
<i>&gt;reflect a love of Jesus that we would all do well to emulate. In dealing</i><br>
<i>&gt;with Christians of other faiths establishing a common ground in love leads</i><br>
<i>&gt;to some informed discussion on the differences?</i><br>
<p>
It is good to at first talk with others about subjects upon which we can<br>
both agree, so that prejudice will be broken down and they will be more<br>
receptive to other things too, and both us and them will be brought closer to<br>
God.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;In answer to the specific question "What do SDA's preach about USA in</i><br>
<i>&gt;prophecy in other countries?" In Australia, I don't here many sermons about</i><br>
<i>&gt;it. In fact I do not hear many sermons about prophecy and last day events</i><br>
<i>&gt;full stop (period, for our American friends). That probably is a pity, but</i><br>
<i>&gt;I think the sermons we are getting are relevent and challenging non-the-less. </i><br>
<p>
I think you might find this quote interesting:<br>
"The message of truth is new and startling to the people of this country<br>
[Austraila]. The bible doctrines presented are as a new revelation, and they<br>
really look upon the sentiments advanced as infidelity. In presenting the<br>
Sunday question, or the union of church and state, handle it carefully. It<br>
will not answer to present the strong positions that have been and will of<br>
necessity be presented in America." -- Evangelism page 227<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<p>
E-mail address:   med10014@nusunix1.nus.sg<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
