<title>Apr_1993: God still heals</title>
<h1>God still heals</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 10 Apr 93 22:57:20 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#203">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#203">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#203">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#203">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0204.html">Fritz Guy: "Re: "Baker letter""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0202.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Relationships and sin"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
A couple of years ago or so, I received a letter from a friend who I had met <br>
at Walla Walla College.  He had graduated with his civil engineering degree<br>
and returned to West Africa (Ivory Coast) with the hope of his skills as a<br>
blessing to his fellow Africans.  <br>
<p>
Things did not turn out as he had planned, however.  He found that people <br>
were jealous of his opportunity to study in the States and had little use for<br>
his talents.  He could not find work in his line of expertise.  He told me in <br>
this letter that he considered returning to Africa to be the biggest mistake <br>
of his life.  <br>
<p>
I really felt sorry for him.  I had purchased a calculator for him while he<br>
was still in the States so that he could take it with him when he returned to <br>
Africa.  He was so happy about it.  I can still remember seeing his big<br>
grin when I bumped into him unexpectedly at WWC during a return visit to<br>
campus.<br>
<p>
Sometime later I received another letter from him informing me that he had<br>
contracted tuberculosis and was unable to walk.  He included a picture of<br>
himself in a hospital bed.  I thought, "What a waste!"  The prognosis<br>
looked bleak for him.  The physicians thought he might die from the disease,<br>
or at least be crippled, but his condition began to improve.  I received <br>
more letters from him indicating that God was healing him.<br>
<p>
Yesterday's mail brought another letter, including a photo of him STANDING <br>
beside a wheelchair and a walker.  Praise the Lord!  His faith is strong <br>
also.  He asked me to share his experience with those I know, so I will quote <br>
from his letter.<br>
<p>
QUOTE...(grammatical mistakes uncorrected)<br>
<p>
Doctors and many people thought I would definitely have to die or at the best<br>
have my legs crippled!  I had sores with visible bones all over my body.  But<br>
like a miracle, my health improved and gradually I found my health back.  <br>
This left many people amazed.  The miracles of our Lord were the yesterday, <br>
today and tomorrow.  Please tell my story to your other friend to strengthen<br>
their faith in all situations.  Please read John 11:40.<br>
<p>
END OF QUOTE<br>
<p>
Here is John 11:40 from the NIV (context = raising of Lazarus):<br>
  Then Jesus said, "Did I not tell you that if you believed, you would see <br>
  the glory God?"<br>
<p>
Well, this story has strengthened my faith.  I hope it has yours as well.<br>
<p>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
