<title>Apr_1993: Cassette Evangelism</title>
<h1>Cassette Evangelism</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 10 Apr 93 23:46:02 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#200">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#200">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#200">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#200">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0201.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Mark Martin in Arizona"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0199.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: Relationship theology"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
A few months ago our congregation held a Revelation seminar, with our pastor<br>
as the speaker.  The first night's attendance was quite good (approximately<br>
80-100 non-SDAs I would estimate).  On the second night, we had about half<br>
as many non-SDAs and it soon tapered off to a faithful few (about 20).<br>
<p>
It so happens that our pastor had previously produced a series of 24 cassettes <br>
covering basically the same topics as those addressed during a Revelation <br>
seminar.  This has proved to be a successful program.  He has commented that in<br>
the past when he gave a seminar and people would miss a night or drop out due <br>
to time conflicts he simply had to tell them to come back to a future seminar <br>
or direct them to some outside reading.  At this seminar, he was able to give<br>
them the cassette corresponding to the night they missed.  We have also been<br>
able to make use of the many names of those who registered for the series<br>
but who never came or dropped out very early.  Many of the people he has <br>
called after the seminar have desired to receive the cassettes, which are<br>
delivered one-per-week by our members.<br>
<p>
The seminar ended in November and for the approximately $10,000 spent on it<br>
we have, as yet,had only one baptism directly attributable to the lectures.  <br>
However, this cassette program has yielded one baptism and three more have <br>
chosen to be baptised next month.  So the two methods are complementing each <br>
other.  In the past, the names garnered from the expensive mass-mailing of <br>
Revelation seminar handbills would not be used if they didn't show up at the <br>
seminar.  Now we can capitalize on these interests even if they don't come to <br>
the meetings.<br>
<p>
When I first heard our pastor promoting his tape program, I was uncertain<br>
what to think, since there is very little person-to-person contact in it <br>
unless the student indicates a desire for it.  You simply leave the next tape <br>
with them and pick up the previous one each week.  They fill out a very short<br>
quiz on the tape they have listened to and are asked to make incremental<br>
commitments each week.  People seem to prefer this to bringing you into their <br>
home.<br>
<p>
One basic assumption behind it is that people are not reading much these<br>
days, and are therefore less likely to study through a set of written Bible<br>
studies than they are to play a cassette.  Another assumption is that people<br>
are very busy and are not likely to want to set up a regular schedule<br>
for you to visit and study with them.<br>
<p>
This tape program is working for our church, and is being used in about 100<br>
other churches, our pastor says.  If you are interested, let me know, and I <br>
will give him your name.  This is a sales pitch I know; but, hey, why not?<br>
<p>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
