<title>Apr_1993: Re: "Baker letter"</title>
<h1>Re: "Baker letter"</h1>
Fritz Guy (<i>fguy@polaris.lasierra.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Apr 1993 05:34:32 -0600 (PDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#204">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#204">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#204">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#204">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0205.html">David Plaisted: "Humanity of Christ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0203.html">Tim Swensen: "God still heals"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The so-called "Baker letter" is known officially as EGW Letter 8, 1895,<br>
although it was probably written in February 1896. It was addressed to<br>
W.T.H. Baker and his wife, who had just completed a disappointing series <br>
of evangelistic meetings in Tasmania. Most of the letter is available from<br>
the White Estate as Ms. Release #414. <br>
<p>
The letter is lengthy--requiring some 19 pages of double-spaced typescript<br>
(the released portion is 14 pages long). Embedded in the midst of advice<br>
on various subjects related to evangelism are five paragraphs on talking<br>
(publicly) about the nature of Christ. These are published in the SDA Bible<br>
<p>
"Be careful, exceedingly careful as to how you dwell upon the human nature<br>
of Christ. Do not set Him before the people as a man with the propensities<br>
of sin. He is the second Adam. The first Adam was created a pure, sinless<br>
being, without a taint of sin upon him; he was in the image of God. He<br>
could fall, and he did fall through transgressing. Because of sin, his<br>
posterity was born with inherent propensities of disobedience. But Jesus<br>
Christ was the only begotten Son of God. He took upon Himself human<br>
nature, and was tempted in all points as human nature is tempted. He could<br>
have sinned; He could have fallen, but not for one moment was there in Him<br>
an evil propensity. He was assailed with temptations in the wilderness, as<br>
Adam was assailed with temptations in Eden."<br>
<p>
Fritz Guy<br>
fguy@polaris.lasierra.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
