<title>Apr_1993: Mark Martin in Arizona</title>
<h1>Mark Martin in Arizona</h1>
<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>11 Apr 1993 12:14:32 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#201">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#201">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#201">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#201">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0202.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Relationships and sin"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0200.html">Tim Swensen: "Cassette Evangelism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
We recently received in the mail a set of 6 tapes from Mark Martin, of<br>
Calvary Community Church in Phoenix, Arizona.  We had not requested the<br>
tapes, so I don't know if he bought an mailing list or someone else had<br>
them sent to us.  We listened to three and are throwing the rest away.<br>
Apparently he is a PUC graduate and former assistant pastor of the Glendale<br>
AZ church, who became disaffected with Adventism over 1844 and the sanctuary,<br>
and now is not keeping Sabbath anymore either because he sees it as the<br>
sign and seal of the Old Testament covenant.  Because we are now under<br>
grace rather than the law, he sees no need to keep the old Sabbath.  We<br>
found him to be a bit insulting about the denomination, saying that SDAs<br>
cultic and that you couldn't be a true Christian and remain in the church.<br>
He also made statements such as non-vegetarians could not be elders or<br>
deacons in the church, which might be true for some very conservative<br>
local congregations, but is definitely not true for the church at large.<br>
Two of the tapes we heard were radio interviews, while one seemed to be<br>
part of a sermon.<br>
<p>
Anyone know more about this guy?  How did he get our address?  It came<br>
to our old address, from which we moved last summer, so whatever list<br>
he's got, it isn't up to date.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
