<title>Apr_1993: Immunity to the Gospel?</title>
<h1>Immunity to the Gospel?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Apr 1993 13:48:22 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#214">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#214">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#214">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#214">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0215.html">Steven Timm: "Am I a hypocrite?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0213.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: What is "Historic Adventism"?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Over the past two weekends I have, along with my primary-aged<br>
puppeteers, been helping with the children's program at the Questions<br>
Before Midnight<br>
meetings currently going at the SDA church in Hinsdale, IL.  There are few<br>
thrills more satisfying than seeing the eager eyes of those young children<br>
who have always been interested in the things of God, and each time they hear<br>
the story they listen with an enthusiasm as if they are hearing it for<br>
the first time.  For the few that are hearing it the first time, it is<br>
even better.<br>
<p>
But I have also seen a troublesome trend in our group this time that<br>
I've not seen before.  Even in children of eight and nine years old, I<br>
see in some of them a hardness--they are not willing to hear or listen. <br>
I can only guess that they are so TV-saturated that even with a fast<br>
paced program of Christian magic, puppets, games, songs in addition to<br>
solid Biblical teaching, they do not have the attention span or the<br>
discernment to respond.<br>
Is this too black of a thought to even be speakable on Easter?  Are our<br>
kids so conditioned to entertainment that the content of that<br>
entertainment does not affect them anymore?  We face the dual dilemma: <br>
1)  The only reality these kids know is the television set.  2)  If we<br>
communicate Jesus to them <br>
within this reality, we run the risk of reducing Jesus to a movie star.<br>
<p>
I suppose the best I can hope for this group is to teach them that Easter is <br>
not a day where we honor the unselfish bunny who rises from his burrow and <br>
gives us all eggs and candy. (And if he sees his shadow, we have six<br>
more weeks of winter, isn't that right?  It's been a while since I heard<br>
this legend).  <br>
<p>
Happy Easter, everybody.  I've got to go eat some chocolate so I can keep <br>
up with this crowd tonight.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
