<title>Apr_1993: Am I a hypocrite?</title>
<h1>Am I a hypocrite?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Apr 1993 14:05:18 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#215">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#215">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#215">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#215">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0216.html">David Plaisted: "Baker letter"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0214.html">Steven Timm: "Immunity to the Gospel?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0227.html">Ray Mialki: "Re: Am I a hypocrite?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Some of you may know that about once a month I play organ for our local<br>
church services.  Recently our church was "blessed" by the arrival of a<br>
rich semi-retired doctor and his wife.  Shortly after they drove their<br>
Lexus into <br>
the parking lot, he took over the duties of director of music.  He is a<br>
fairly accomplished pianist and vocalist.  She is a well-trained<br>
vocalist.<br>
He claims to be an organist as well but has proved otherwise on several<br>
occasions.  It's all I can do to keep from grinding my teeth while he<br>
plays.<br>
<p>
The good doctor has decided that our church needs a new organ (which we do,<br>
the old one is gradually breaking down stop by stop.)  He has a strong ally<br>
in the person who has been head organist for the last several years.  A<br>
Wurlitzer electronic organ was duly rented for our 25th anniversary. <br>
The salesman offered to leave the organ at our church for a couple extra<br>
weeks, hoping we would decide to buy this organ which "lists for $26000<br>
but can be ours for a limited time at the price of $19995."<br>
<p>
Now, I think the church board of our church is skeptical and conservative <br>
enough that this probably won't pass.  (There's at least one of our board<br>
members on the net.)  But even a few weeks ago when it looked like they<br>
might be able to steamroll it through, I was pretty much quiet, partly<br>
because I didn't wish to get shut out of playing the organ, and partly<br>
because I want a <br>
new organ just as much as anyone else, and  although I know there are much <br>
better organs than this one, we probably couldn't afford them.  Is being<br>
quiet in this situation a sign of hypocrisy?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
