<title>Apr_1993: Baker letter</title>
<h1>Baker letter</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Apr 93 15:00:12 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#216">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#216">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#216">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#216">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0217.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Baker letter"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0215.html">Steven Timm: "Am I a hypocrite?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0217.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Baker letter"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ralph Larson argues that the Baker letter was a refutation of<br>
adoptionism.  This is the belief that Christ was born just as we are,<br>
that is, a human but not divine.  Then at some stage He was adopted<br>
because of his efforts to achieve holiness, and became divine as well<br>
as human.  Ellen White wanted to make it clear that Christ had a<br>
divine as well as a human nature, and thus was not one altogether as<br>
ourselves.  And certainly the thought of One who is absolutely pure is<br>
an awesome thought.<br>
<p>
Yet there are also a great many other statements of Ellen White (and<br>
the Bible) that assert that Christ had a humanity like ours.  For<br>
example,<br>
<p>
``He took upon Him our sinful nature.''  RH 12/15/96<br>
<p>
``He took upon Himself fallen suffering human nature, degraded and<br>
defiled by sin.''  Youth Instructor 12/20/1900<br>
<p>
``Wherefore in all things it behooved him to be made like unto his<br>
brethren, that he might be a merciful and faithful high priest in<br>
things pertaining to God, to make reconciliation for the sins of the<br>
people.  For in that he himself hath suffered being tempted, he is<br>
able to succor them that are tempted.''  Hebrews 2:17,18<br>
<p>
And 1 John 4:1 - 3 emphasizes the importance of the humanity of Christ<br>
as a test between true and false spirits.  I would also mention that<br>
Roman Catholicism teaches that Christ had a superior humanity, as did<br>
His mother Mary.<br>
<p>
The doctrine that Christ had a superior human nature is considered to<br>
be part of the New Theology, with the claimed consequence that we<br>
cannot have victory over sin.  This is one doctrine that the<br>
denominational book ``Issues'' calls a ``moot theological issue.''<br>
But I can testify that it was not moot for me and some of my friends;<br>
the knowledge that Christ had a humanity like mine was a great<br>
liberator and opened the possibility of a new level of obedience to<br>
us.<br>
<p>
However I would like to caution that the theoretical knowledge is less<br>
important than the practical experience in one's life.  We are not<br>
saved by knowing the truth about the humanity of Christ, though I<br>
believe this truth is important to know.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
