<title>Apr_1993: Humanity of Christ</title>
<h1>Humanity of Christ</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Apr 1993 15:07:50 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#230">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#230">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#230">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#230">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0231.html">Steven Timm: "... The Power Of a Old Seing!!!"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0229.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Spiritual head of the family"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yes, it is tremendously important to recognize that Christ was fully human.<br>
I know of no Adventist that would deny that.  My question is whether one<br>
can determine from the evidence what KIND of human nature he had and whether<br>
this determination is vital to salvation or the mission of the church.<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
