<!-- body="start" -->
Steve,<br>
	If your board is wise, it will explore more than one option. At<br>
your suggestion the members can visit churches (preferrably, but showrooms<br>
as well) to view and listen to Allen and Rogers electronic organs. Also, in<br>
the classifieds of _The American Organist_ (American Guild of Organists'<br>
official publication at your library), churches who are upgrading to larger<br>
electronic organs and pipe organs advertise their instruments.<br>
	Wurlitzers have a reputation for being an entertainment/show<br>
organ and are not known for church repertoire. Allen and Rogers organs (and<br>
perhaps other less well-known ones, but be careful) can be purchased which<br>
offer an electronic likeness to the sounds of a pipe organ at a more affordable<br>
price. There are models available for most church budgets. Perhaps you could<br>
call the representatives for Rogers and Allen and get prices and literature<br>
to bring to the board meeting. The choice of an organ to support the best<br>
worship music is an important one. Don't be silent.<br>
<p>
Pam Harris<br>
Harrisp@utkvx.utk.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
