<title>Apr_1993: Re: Humanity of Christ</title>
<h1>Re: Humanity of Christ</h1>
Noe Torres | ECISD (<i>noe@tenet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Apr 1993 20:18:21 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#220">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#220">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#220">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#220">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0221.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Helath and Christianity"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0219.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  dinosaurs"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0205.html">David Plaisted: "Humanity of Christ"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Thus we are faced with a dilemna.  Given that:<br>
<p>
* It is impossible for post-Fall man, on his own, to keep God's law perfectly.<br>
<p>
* If we break the least of the commandments, we are guilty of breaking<br>
them all.<br>
<p>
* God seems to expect perfect commandment-keeping of his people, as<br>
pointed out in the EGW statements quoted by David Plaisted.<br>
<p>
So my question is: How can we obtain the perfect commandment-keeping that<br>
qualifies us for heaven?<br>
<p>
The answer, in my humble opinion, is that we obtain as a grace gift from<br>
God the perfect commandment-keeping of Christ Himself.  By His grace we<br>
are saved, through faith, and that NOT OF OURSELVES.  <br>
<p>
Christ's perfect righteousness then clothes our unrighteousness and we are<br>
accounted as if we had never sinned.  Does that transaction then make void<br>
our need of keeping God's law any further?  No, for we walk by faith not<br>
by the flesh, and we will seek to do God's will to the best of this<br>
sinful-natured shell in which we are trapped until the Second Coming.  Notice:<br>
<p>
"Nothing but the righteousness of Christ can entitle us to one of the<br>
blessings of the covenant of grace.  There are many who have long desired<br>
and tried to obtain these blessings, but have not received them, because<br>
they have cherished the idea that they could do something to make<br>
themselves worthy of them.  They have not looked away from self,<br>
believing that Jesus is an all-sufficient Saviour.....  Let none look to<br>
self, as though they had the power to save themselves.  Jesus died for us<br>
because were were helpless to do this.  In Him is our hope, our<br>
justification, our righteousness."  (Patriarchs and Prophets, p. 431).<br>
<p>
"The law demands righteousness, and this the sinner owes to the law; but<br>
he is incapable of rendering it.  The only way in which he can attain to<br>
righteousness is through faith.  By faith he can bring to God the merits<br>
of Christ, and the Lord places the obedience of His Son to the sinner's<br>
account.... and the pardoned soul goes on from grace to grace, from light<br>
to greater light."  (Selected Messages, Vol. 1, p. 367).<br>
<p>
"...Jesus Our Advocate presents an effectual plea in behalf of all who by<br>
repentance and faith have committed the keeping of their souls to Him.  He<br>
pleads their cause and vanquishes their accuser by the mighty arguments of<br>
Calvary.  His perfect obedience to God's law, even unto the death of the<br>
cross, has given Him all power in heaven and in earth, and He claims of His<br>
Father mercy and reconciliation for guilty man."  (Testimonies, v. 5, p. 491).<br>
<p>
"We cannot say, I am sinless, till this vile body is changed and fashioned<br>
like unto His glorious body."  (Special Testimony, 3/23/1888).<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
