<title>Apr_1993: Re:  Center Stage ...</title>
<h1>Re:  Center Stage ...</h1>
Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473 (<i>jwiley@law.usc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 12 Apr 93 07:37:21 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#222">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#222">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#222">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#222">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0223.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Immunity to the Gospel?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0221.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Helath and Christianity"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0211.html">Dave Thomas: "Center Stage ..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave's EM reminds me that I came to the SDA church because of the<br>
cognitive, but have remained because of the affective.  That is, I<br>
once thought that doctrine was central until I recognized that Christ<br>
[as portrayed in the gospels] had very little to say about dorctrine,<br>
but a lot to say about relationships.  Our denomination puts such<br>
emphasis on "getting it right" [doctrine] that it appears we believe<br>
salavation is "won" by doing well on a qualifying examination the<br>
substance of which is doctrine.  This is, of course, nonsense in<br>
a number of ways. For example, as Dave points out, the chances of our<br>
"getting it right" are remote.  Secondly, salavation is Gods' [yes,<br>
I really meant plural possessive although the singular possessive<br>
will work as well] gift to his beloved humans -- to us.  As a matter<br>
of "law" a gift only requires two things 1)the offer, and 2)the acceptance<br>
of the offer.<br>
<p>
Our preoccupation on occasion with whether something happened in the<br>
heavenly sanctuary in 1844 [I don't want to tackle all the assumptions<br>
that question makes] or what of the ceremonial law survives in the<br>
New Testament is about who we are, not about who God is.  That self-<br>
centeredness is probably dnagerous to our spiritual health.<br>
<p>
Sorry -- this is longer than I intended, and I've "only just begun."<br>
<p>
--Jerry Wiley<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
