<title>Apr_1993: DINOSAURS</title>
<h1>DINOSAURS</h1>
ELAINE KENNEDY (<i>GRIMKE%LLUVM.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>12 Apr 1993 08:21:25 -0800 (PST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#224">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#224">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#224">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#224">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0225.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Job and the GC"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0223.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Immunity to the Gospel?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0257.html">Bill Allen: "Re: DINOSAURS"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hello,<br>
<p>
Since mail from LLU is running about 2 weeks late this may arrive long after<br>
interest in this topic has died but I thought I might add just a bit:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;What do all of you believe happened to the dinosaurs?</i><br>
<i>&gt;Were they destroyed in the flood?</i><br>
<p>
I'm not sure we can determine exactly what did happen to the dinos.  Certainly<br>
Noah's flood is one of the best explanations proposed for their extinction.<br>
One of the big problems with the asteroid impact is explaining the selectivity<br>
of the survivors.  The big question for me is Did some of them survive the<br>
flood?  It has been estimated that about 1/2 of the dinos were the size of a<br>
turkey or German shepherd.  So I think it is probable that some of the dinos<br>
were included on the ark.   Some ask how the big ones could have been included<br>
on the ark; I don't think the text excludes juveniles or eggs.  Certainly the<br>
three layers of Cretaceous dino nests in Montana (and nests elsewhere) suggest<br>
that either things were getting pretty frantic during the flood or that these<br>
are post-flood nesting sites.  If they are post-flood, then the ultimate ex-<br>
tinction of the dinos was probably due to their inability to survive in the<br>
post-flood world as is true of many other organisms.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Did they really exist?</i><br>
<p>
There is a lot of excellent evidence that they did indeed exist.  Many complete<br>
skeletons exist, not just adults but juveniles as well.  Skin impressions have<br>
been found and recently, preserved skin! nests, eggs that have been x-rayed and<br>
contain embryos, hatchlings, dung, trackways, all indicate the dinos were real<br>
and very much alive.  I'm not sure where SDAs get the idea that the dinos never<br>
lived and the bones were made by Satan to confuse us.<br>
<p>
[More accessible material: National Geographic v. 183, no. 1, January, 1993;<br>
Discover special issue, January, 1993; Earth Science, summer, 1989; Geology<br>
Today Nov-Dec, 1992, 206-209, 211-212.  Less accessible materials: Jour Paleon-<br>
tology 53(3)566-577; Geology 20:1068-1070; Contrib to Geology, Univ WY 29(2):<br>
81-96; Geological Society of America, Abstracts with Program, 1991:A457.  In<br>
addition, there are a number of good books out that are available through the<br>
public libraries.  Get the most recent books, some of Jack Horner's stuff has<br>
been recently revised.]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Was it a million years ago?</i><br>
<p>
If you accept the geologic time scale, dinos lived between 250 m.y. and 65 m.y.<br>
b.p.  If you accept the biblical chronology, dinos were pre-flood and possibly<br>
post-flood.  If you accept the dragon legends as reliable accounts of dino<br>
sightings, then dinos were alive in more recent times and their demise is due<br>
to human intervention.  I am comfortable with the biblical chronology.  The<br>
geologic explanations have a number of problems:  the remains are all water<br>
laid and in some cases have marine shark remains associated with them  (this is<br>
a strange mixture of environments), there is no evidence for a break in the<br>
food chain but on the other hand, the deposits of some  dinos seem to   lack<br>
adequate vegetation for the herbivorous dino herds, the asteroid impact and sub<br>
sequent "nulear winter" scenario invoked to explain the dino destruction cannot<br>
explain the survival of reptiles of similar size and habitat, the sudden extinc<br>
tion appears to some to have been very gradual over the approximately 200 m.y.<br>
period that dinos supposedly existed i.e., Triassic dino populations are<br>
different from Jurassic dino pop. and both are different from Cretaceous dino<br>
pop., there are big arguments with regard to the survival of dinos past the K/T<br>
(Cretaceous/Tertiary) boundary (so far all of the post K/T deposits I have seen<br>
are reworked sediments and cannot be used to prove post K/T survival).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Were they a product of the antediluvians fiddling around with genetics?</i><br>
<p>
I'm going to jump to a big conclusion here and assume this question is prompted<br>
by EGWs statements with regard to God's destruction of amalgamated species. (At<br>
least that is the context in which I always hear this question.)  When she<br>
writes about the analgamated species she says they caused confusion.  As far as<br>
I can tell there is no confusion with respect to the dinos; they are reptiles.<br>
There are other fossils that in my mind fit her description much better such as<br>
mammal-like reptiles.  By the way, her comments on the large beasts should not<br>
be applied exclusively to dinos either; almost all of the large mammals are<br>
gone as well as many gigantic marine organisms.  So to answer the question, no<br>
I don't think the antediluvians had much to do with the dinos.<br>
<p>
To shift the topic just a tad, I was told recently (last Sabbath) that our<br>
scientists are to the point or almost to the point where they can write genes.<br>
Is this true?  Apparently, once a new gene is written and introduced there is<br>
no way to remove it from the population (you can make it recessive but you can<br>
not eliminate it).  Are we going to have gene hackers like the computer people<br>
that introduce computer viruses?  It is also my understanding that new genes<br>
are required for evolution to occur and that is why geneticists are not too<br>
keen on evolution or argue that there has not been enough time for evolution to<br>
occur if mutation is the only source for new genes.  Any insight on this?  Oops<br>
this is not intended as an evolution question per se but rather as a genetics<br>
issue. (I'm just curious, Steve, and if you want to edit that last part it's OK<br>
by me.)<br>
<p>
I have a few things on dinos lying around my office.  If some of you would like<br>
some of the material, send me your snail mail address and I'll be glad to send<br>
it out.  My e-mail address:  GRIMKE@LLUVM.BITNET.<br>
<p>
Elaine<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
