<title>Apr_1993: Job and the GC</title>
<h1>Job and the GC</h1>
<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>12 Apr 1993 15:29:24 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#225">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#225">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#225">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#225">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0226.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Job and Great Controversy"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0224.html">ELAINE KENNEDY: "DINOSAURS"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
That's GC as in Great Controversy, not General Conference!  I got some<br>
replies personally to my queries about Job, the gist of which is<br>
summarized by saying Job (as we all are) was caught up in the Great<br>
Controversy between Christ and Satan.  I have no problem with the idea<br>
that Satan plays dirty tricks on humans in his role of troubler of Zion,<br>
I even can take the idea that God allows this to go on in a broad, general<br>
sense.  It is the specificity with which it occurs in the story of Job<br>
that is so difficult for me.<br>
<p>
To bring it to modern times, I was reading Newsweek about the Bosnians<br>
who were fleeing in trucks from one awful place to a slightly less<br>
awful place.  One grandmother had gotten separated from all her family<br>
except a teenage granddaughter, but that granddaughter was killed in the<br>
crush on the trucks.  At the destination, the grandmother was curled<br>
up on a mat, not taking food, but simply crying over and over, "I have<br>
no one."  If I believed that God and Satan had discussed in detail just<br>
what was going to happen to this woman and God had said, "OK, go ahead<br>
and take away all her family, kill her granddaughter, let her starve<br>
to death," then my conception of God would be completely different than<br>
it is now.  Do you see my point at all?  I can take the global awfulness<br>
that is a result of sin and Satan's actions, and I can accept that God<br>
allows the consequences of sin to play out; but I have major trouble<br>
with the idea that God somehow initials Satan's plans on a case by case<br>
basis.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
