<title>Apr_1993: Re: Baker letter</title>
<h1>Re: Baker letter</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 12 Apr 1993 23:14:50 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#217">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#217">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#217">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#217">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0218.html">HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU: "New organ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0216.html">David Plaisted: "Baker letter"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0216.html">David Plaisted: "Baker letter"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0240.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Baker letter"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Well, it's clear what we shall have to do on the first evening of the <br>
SDAnet symposium, whenever it happens (not before my dissertation is written).<br>
<p>
We will organize a viewing of the movie "The Last Temptation of Christ"<br>
This should make the case well for one point or the other as has been <br>
discussed here.  (I have never seen this movie so I don't know beforehand <br>
which.)  Then we can spend an evening in live and animated discussion.<br>
<p>
All seriousness aside, I think all that we can conclude from the various<br>
quotes in the Baker Letter and elsewhere is that "nature" and "propensities"<br>
mean something different, because one was sinful and the other is not.<br>
We would all do well to continue to study the life of Christ.  That which<br>
Ellen White referred to as a mystery is something where speculation may <br>
prove either misleading or fruitless.  My posts have included as much<br>
speculation  as any others in this series.<br>
<p>
Dr. Larson's main lesson that he draws from the nature of Christ seems <br>
to be that it is possible for us to overcome sin through the same power<br>
of God that Christ accessed.  There are some SDA's who would dispute that,<br>
including possibly the late authors of Questions on Doctrine.  But as<br>
far as I read the Fundamental Beliefs, this doctrine is on quite firm<br>
standing<br>
and included as part of the twenty-seven.  If there is any dispute,<br>
it's just whether or not every text and every EGW quote that Dr. Larson <br>
claims points to this doctrine, and his conception of how Christ had to<br>
be to make this doctrine true, have anything to do with the actual truth<br>
of the situation. <br>
<p>
The question of "Historical Adventism" should have little to do with it.<br>
Fortunately Ellen White did not worry about "historical Methodism", nor<br>
did Martin Luther worry about "historical Catholicism."  Present truth<br>
must stand in the present, not on the foundation of historical precedent.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
