<title>Apr_1993: Humanity of Christ</title>
<h1>Humanity of Christ</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>12 Apr 93 23:16:14 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#236">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#236">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#236">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#236">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0237.html">HEALY, TAMMY R: "Last Temptation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0235.html">Paul Gates: "Job, other beings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0249.html">HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU: "Re: Humanity of Christ"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve, on your quote of COL 331 I would have felt better if you had <br>
included a sentence in that same paragraph:  "The real difficulty arises <br>
from the corruption of an unsanctified heart,  AND AN UNWILLINGNESS TO <br>
SUBMIT TO THE CONTROL OF GOD." At least in one sense I believe reflecting <br>
God's character is impossible without the control of God in our lives. I am <br>
sure you agree! Correct?<br>
<p>
On the nature of Christ, I have some strong convictions. I think that we <br>
could probably support both views -- sinless verses sinful nature from the <br>
SOP. Martin Weber made the remark a few weeks ago in our Sabbath School <br>
class at Grasonville that Christ did have an advantage that we do not have! <br>
He could have called down the powers of heaven! In case someone retorts <br>
with Desire Of Ages, I will say now that I know DA mentions that Christ had <br>
no power that we cannot have. However, I have not been able to call fire <br>
down from heaven lately! &lt;&lt;smile!!&gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
Further, I would say, that we spend entirely too much time trying to figure <br>
out Christ's nature when we could be giving the gospel to someone that <br>
doesn't know about it.<br>
<p>
In retrospect, I am not trying to solicit messages from the net but I do <br>
believe that Christ had a sinless nature. Also I think a lot of us over <br>
react on this question. I think it is good to let "dead dogs lie." It is <br>
not going to affect my relationship with Christ -- with me it is not a <br>
matter that I must know one way or the other in regard to Christ's nature.<br>
<p>
Just voicing a personal opinion!<br>
<p>
.......Paul<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
