<title>Apr_1993: Re: Job and Great Controversy</title>
<h1>Re: Job and Great Controversy</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 12 Apr 1993 23:31:58 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#226">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#226">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#226">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#226">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0227.html">Ray Mialki: "Re: Am I a hypocrite?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0225.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Job and the GC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0272.html">Fritz Guy: "Re: "Historic Adventism""</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Lola says that she has trouble believing that God initials Satan's plans<br>
on a case by case basis.  Well first of all, we should point out that<br>
this was the only place Satan was nice enough to ask God about it. <br>
Nevertheless,<br>
the idea follows quite naturally:<br>
<p>
1)  God is omnipotent<br>
2)  God knows all Satan's plans before they are ever carried out.<br>
3)  Therefore God could intervene and keep any evil from happening<br>
     to anyone.<br>
4)  He chooses not to in many cases.<br>
<p>
This follows along with Jesus' words to Pilate "thou couldst have no <br>
power against me except it were given thee from above."<br>
<p>
To me the idea that "God doesn't cause such-and-such, He just allows it <br>
to happen" is a swindle.  It points to a helpless God.  The truth is that <br>
God is sovereign and is responsible for everything that happens on this <br>
earth.  The sacred writings between Genesis 3 and 1 Chronicles dispense<br>
with the devil as a cause for suffering altogether, because God was intent<br>
on revealing Himself as the only Sovereign being, not wanting to make an <br>
identifiable evil figure such as existed in the pantheon of most other<br>
religions at the time.<br>
<p>
If we recognize that God is the key figure in the suffering that happens<br>
to us, and the first one to help us repair whatever damage was done, we<br>
can <br>
have a greater picture of His power.<br>
<p>
(Sorry, longtime SDAnet readers, for repeating myself on this one.  SCT)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
