<!-- body="start" -->
David,<br>
If you qualify your emphasis that Christ was born on earth in the same<br>
"sinful, degraded" human nature that we have with a statement that in His<br>
humanity He was "yet without sin,"  then I agree with you fully.  Though<br>
He was tempted in every point, yet He was without sin, else He would not<br>
have been the Sinless One, the spotless Lamb.<br>
<p>
Whatever the circumstances behind the writing of the Baker later, the<br>
admonition contained therein seems genuine and applicable in addressing any<br>
attempt to make Christ appear to be completely like one of us in every<br>
respect.  Christ was a Special Creation, "that holy thing."  In my<br>
opinion, His spiritual condition could be likened to that of Adam before<br>
the Fall, and I have several EGW statements to that effect.  The<br>
difference being that his physical nature and attributes were post-Fall.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
