<title>Apr_1993: Re: Historic Adventism</title>
<h1>Re: Historic Adventism</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>13 Apr 1993 10:13:44 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#228">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#228">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#228">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#228">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0229.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Spiritual head of the family"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0227.html">Ray Mialki: "Re: Am I a hypocrite?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Sherman's description of "historic Adventism" is pretty much what I<br>
understand the term to mean.<br>
<p>
It is a more precise term than "conservative". All "historic Adventists"<br>
are conservative, but not all who are conservative are historic Adventists.<br>
A conservative person places importance on holding on to values and ideals<br>
which have been passed down by previous generations, but is not opposed to<br>
thinking about new ideas, and will adopt those new ideas should they prove<br>
worthwhile. This could not be said for most who claim the label "historic<br>
Adventist".<br>
<p>
As for "modern Adventism", yes, the historic Adventists differentiate between<br>
themselves and others by labelling the other beliefs as "New Theology". They<br>
coined this phrase themselves, so the best description of what it entails is<br>
probably Larson's description, given here on the net a few days ago. Whether<br>
or not Larson is correctly portraying the beliefs of modern Adventism is<br>
debatable. (As evidenced by the subsequent posts, Re: The real issue, which<br>
followed up the original one.)<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
