<!-- body="start" -->
On Apr 13, 10:05am, PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Spiritual head of the family</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;From a message about Adam &amp; sin:</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Where does the idea come from that Adam was the spiritual head over the</i><br>
<i>&gt; family even before sin? I would have thought that Eve's "connection" with</i><br>
<i>&gt; God was equal to Adam's, and that the concept of a "spiritual head" is</i><br>
<i>&gt; only needed under the rule of sin.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Tony</i><br>
<p>
I don't disagree that Eve had a good "connection" with God just as Adam did.  But I<br>
think there can be only one head of a household and since Adam was given dominion<br>
over the animals he was thereby placed in a position of leadership.  To me, as I look<br>
at the way children look up to there dad's as representative of God (in their eyes),<br>
it only makes sense that the father be the spiritual leader of the household.  This<br>
is not to belittle the very important spiritual role that the mother plays in the<br>
home, but ideally, the father should be initiating the spiritual leading in the home.<br>
<p>
Just as you run into trouble in a house where you have two heads of the house in<br>
other areas, I believe that you will have trouble if you have two spiritual leaders,<br>
particularly if the two spouses don't see eye to eye on things.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
