<title>Apr_1993: Jeremiah, and comparisons of prophets &amp; present critics</title>
<h1>Jeremiah, and comparisons of prophets &amp; present critics</h1>
<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>13 Apr 1993 12:43:57 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#234">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#234">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#234">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#234">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0235.html">Paul Gates: "Job, other beings"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0233.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Humanistic judaism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben Gonzalez said:<br>
<i>&gt; It seems to me that all of the prophets and especially Jerimiah would have</i><br>
<i>&gt;been prime candidates for CB-manship. </i><br>
<p>
I thought this comparison of present day unacceptance of those who criticise<br>
and the prophets of old very clever, and it is this same question that often<br>
gets me really confused over who is really right and who isn't. <br>
<p>
I have also recently been reading about Jeremiah and other prophets in the <br>
surrounding periods of the history of Israel and Judah. It is a fascinating <br>
story and you bring up a good point that the prophets did not mince words when <br>
it came to criticizing the erring Kings (and priests etc) of God's people. <br>
<p>
But at the same time three points come to mind:<br>
<p>
1. Jeremiah was a *prophet*. <br>
<p>
Jeremiah was chosen by God to be a prophet. That meant that in a time when<br>
the people were ignoring God, and God was planning their punishment for<br>
breaking their covenant, Jeremiah was one of the people chosen to record the<br>
messages of God so that a record of God's attempts to rescue his people would<br>
exist. Jeremiah had an exceedingly tough task.<br>
<p>
I think that many of us would also agree, despite the fact that EGW never<br>
claimed the title for herself, that she was a prophet or messenger from God<br>
for a more recent time. Part of her job was to encourage the Church, as part<br>
of Jeremiah's job was, but it also had to involve reproof - or criticism <br>
(which is painful to receive).<br>
<p>
The question I ask is are-there/will-there-be any more prophets? Are these<br>
people (some of these people) who criticise the church prophets? If they are<br>
then we should accept their criticism. If they aren't then maybe a comparison<br>
of their criticism with the criticism of Jeremiah or Elijah isn't such a good<br>
one.<br>
<p>
2. The sins of the people.<br>
<p>
Israel before its fall, then Judah in the times of Jeremiah really were <br>
involved in some horrible sins. The worship of pagan deities involved<br>
fertility rites which included homosexual and heterosexual activities. Child<br>
sacrifice was also practiced. These things really are uncivilized stuff, and<br>
very disturbing considering the value God has always placed on marriage and<br>
on human life. Our secular society would really be up in arms about such<br>
activities today. So why should we be surprised that God's prophets spoke<br>
so strongly about the harlotry of Israel and Judah?<br>
<p>
3. The attitudes of the prophets.<br>
<p>
The thing I like the most about these prophets is that while their messages<br>
were stern, and often condemnatory, they didn't enjoy giving them. God always<br>
chose people as his messengers who had a great burden for those to whom the<br>
message must go. It caused them great pain to give God's messages, and they<br>
frequently wept or became ill as a result. It seems that God told Jeremiah<br>
to stop praying for Judah because it was no use but Jeremiah couldn't help<br>
himself and prayed for Judah anyway, and Moses likewise often plead for God's<br>
people.<br>
<p>
I don't know about the private prayer lives of those who criticise the Church<br>
today, but if their criticism comes just from the bitterness of human nature<br>
rather than through the pain of having to deliver a message from God to people<br>
they love then ... <br>
<p>
Just a few thoughts hey. What do you guys think?<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
