<title>Apr_1993: Power for victory</title>
<h1>Power for victory</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Apr 93 13:05:12 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#248">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#248">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#248">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#248">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0249.html">HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU: "Re: Humanity of Christ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0247.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Spiritual head of the family"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0251.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Power for victory"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In response to Noe Torres, I believe that without Christ's atonement<br>
we would be cut off from God and not have access to power for<br>
victory over sin.  But Christ, coming to this world, still had<br>
a connection with God by virtue of His own Deity.  Now that<br>
Christ has offered Himself for us, we have access to the same<br>
power in Him that He had in God.  Before Christ died, there was<br>
still power for victory available, but it was apparently more<br>
limited, depending on a future atonement.  Since Pentecost the<br>
Holy Spirit has been poured out in fuller measure.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
