<!-- body="start" -->
David,<br>
I am continuing this thread not for the sake of argumentation, but rather<br>
in the spirit of legitimate inquiry:<br>
<p>
<p>
On Tue, 13 Apr 1993, David Plaisted wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I believe that without Christ's atonement</i><br>
<i>&gt; we would be cut off from God and not have access to power for</i><br>
<i>&gt; victory over sin.</i><br>
<p>
Good, but here's my point: Isn't "victory over sin" assured by the Cross? <br>
Doesn't "It is finished" mean that Christ's mission was successful and<br>
that, had it not been successful, the sin problem would not have had a<br>
successful resolution?  Isn't the "power for victory over sin" completely<br>
wrapped up in Christ and His ministry of atonement?  Remember that NO ONE<br>
was found worthy in heaven or earth to open the seal but the Lamb that was<br>
slain from the foundation of the world.  I don't believe there is another<br>
power over sin other than that which resides in Christ.  <br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  But Christ, coming to this world, still had</i><br>
<i>&gt;  a connection with God by virtue of His own Deity.</i><br>
<p>
This speaks to my previous point.  Christ maintained a His connection with<br>
Deity in a way that differs from all others who have ever lived.  He was<br>
"the holy One."  He COULD have exercised the powers of the Universe on His<br>
behalf, yet chose not to so that His mission could be fulfilled.  EGW says<br>
that Christ COULD have drawn strength from His divine nature but did not. <br>
He remained fully diety while being fully man -- this is the great mystery.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  Now that</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christ has offered Himself for us, we have access to the same</i><br>
<i>&gt; power in Him that He had in God.</i><br>
<p>
Christ is much more than just the offering.  He is the Creator of the<br>
Universe.  He is the High Priest.  He is the Coming King of Glory.  He is<br>
our justification, our sanctification, and our righteousness.  The power<br>
of God that Christ had was His own by virtue of His co-equal status with<br>
the Father and the Spirit.  He did not go outside Himself to another to<br>
work out our redemption.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  Before Christ died, there was</i><br>
<i>&gt; still power for victory available, but it was apparently more</i><br>
<i>&gt; limited, depending on a future atonement.</i><br>
<p>
Depending on the Atonement.... exactly.  Everything depends and revolves<br>
around Christ and Him Crucified.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
