<title>Apr_1993: The dreaded pendulum</title>
<h1>The dreaded pendulum</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>13 Apr 1993 14:17:18 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#238">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#238">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#238">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#238">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0239.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Marriage hints &amp; tips file"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0237.html">HEALY, TAMMY R: "Last Temptation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I said recently that I thought the differences between the various SDA<br>
factions are largely based on approach and priorities. Now I am going to<br>
try and explain what I mean by that. I hope what I have said here is<br>
clear enough to be understood!! (NB this is around 95 lines worth)<br>
<p>
<p>
====================================================<br>
<p>
THOUGHTS PERTAINING TO DISPUTE WITHIN ADVENTISM<br>
^^^^^^^^---------------------------------------<br>
<p>
It's mostly caused by poor communication, knee-jerk reactions and the<br>
eternal pendulum-swinging phenomenon.<br>
<p>
Take the perceived role of Ellen White. From the 20s through 50s the church<br>
leaders and writers portrayed a somewhat "fundamentalist" approach to the<br>
writings of Ellen White, with some of them teaching verbal inspiration and<br>
infallibility of the written word, and so on. Hence when Rea and Numbers<br>
came up with their material, it was a major shock to a large proportion of<br>
grass-roots SDAs. The two extreme reactions tended to be (1) ignore the<br>
problem and blame Rea and Numbers for bringing it up, and (2) abandon Ellen<br>
White completely.<br>
<p>
The legacy of that situation is what we face today. As soon as someone appears<br>
to question even an application of Ellen White's writings, letalone question<br>
the interpretation or content, the right wing immediately assumes that said<br>
someone has adopted reaction (2), and starts preaching about doubting the<br>
"Spirit of Prophecy". And dare to actually quote from Ellen White to help<br>
resolve questions of Scriptural interpretation, or to help determine <br>
worthwhile lifestyle principles, and the left wing assumes that reaction (1)<br>
has been adopted and starts preaching "sola scriptura" and "principle, not<br>
policy".<br>
<p>
Take the other debate, involving sin, the nature of Christ, and righteousness<br>
by faith. Mention a commandment, victory over sin, or a lifestyle issue, and<br>
straight away those on the left start in with charges of legalism, <br>
perfectionism and "righteousness by works". Speak of social issues, God's love,<br>
or relationships, and from the right will come accusations of Calvinism, "once<br>
saved, always saved", antinomianism, and New Theology.<br>
<p>
It's gotten to the point where some discussion/sermon topics are "safe" and<br>
others are not. Certain important aspects of Christianity are being avoided<br>
because people are concerned about being labelled one way or the other, or<br>
maybe even being weighed and found wanting by both sides.<br>
<p>
Even on SDAnet (!) there have been times where this has occurred. I could be<br>
wrong, but I think that those who post long messages about overcoming sin<br>
and the nature of Christ do so because they think their readers believe that<br>
God requires nothing of them, and that Christ's sacrifice is wholly to allow<br>
God to ignore a person's sinful living. They insist that God *requires* this<br>
and *requires* that, to counter the perceived belief that God really doesn't<br>
mind one way or the other since all he sees is Jesus.<br>
<p>
Those who respond do so because they see legalism and a focus on actions,<br>
with no mention of the reciprocal love between Christ and the Christian. These<br>
insist that nothing is *required* except to accept Jesus as our substitute,<br>
to counter the perceived belief that a Christian will not be accepted by<br>
God unless he/she has no sin or sinful propensity.<br>
<p>
In actual fact, it is safe to say that the perceptions are wrong in almost<br>
every case.<br>
<p>
The complete right-wing package is probably not too different to the complete<br>
left-wing package, theologically at least. It is just the emphasis that is<br>
different, and it seems to me that this emphasis is largely there to counter<br>
the other side's emphasis (get that??). Hence the problem is self-propagating.<br>
<p>
An example: Christ said "If you love me, keep my commandments".<br>
<p>
He didn't say, "If you love me, that's just great!",<br>
<p>
or just        "Keep my commandments, o human race!"<br>
<p>
Surely all agree that the entire sentence is important, and that both aspects<br>
are essential for a full understanding of the gospel. If it seems that part<br>
of the text is being ignored, it is only natural that the other part will<br>
be emphasized in order to restore the balance.<br>
<p>
If I'm right, then I find that a little encouraging. But that still doesn't<br>
provide a solution to the problem. Any solution would necessarily involve<br>
open discussion, with both sides agreeing not to threaten or intimidate, and<br>
both also agreeing not to become defensive at the mere hint of difference.<br>
Often such hints are misunderstood. <br>
<p>
=============================================<br>
<p>
Well, I never realized an oversimplification could constitute so many lines<br>
of text!<br>
<p>
By the way, I'm still waiting for hints on how literally to interpret Ellen<br>
White's visions. Personal e-mail would be fine if you don't want to "brave"<br>
publicly airing your own filter technique!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
