<title>Apr_1993: Power for victory</title>
<h1>Power for victory</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Apr 93 14:59:42 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#259">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#259">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#259">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#259">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0260.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: Gentry's halos"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0258.html">Clayton Alves: "re:Job and other beings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0254.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Power for victory"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In response to Noe Torres' message:<br>
<p>
You raise the point -- Christ ``did not go outside Himself to another<br>
to work out our redemption.''<br>
<p>
But what about statements like John 5:19:<br>
<p>
``The Son can do nothing of Himself, but only what He seeth the Father<br>
do: for what things soever He doeth, these also doeth the Son<br>
likewise.''<br>
<p>
The trinity is a great mystery.  But the Bible presents the<br>
relationship of Jesus to the Father in terms of Christ depending on a<br>
power outside of Himself, namely, that of the Father.  And Ellen White<br>
speaks of this in the same way.  Of course, since Christ and the<br>
Father are one, in another sense Christ is depending on His own power.<br>
But I think that the Bible and Ellen White try to present this subject<br>
to us in terms of dependence on an outside power.  This is the best<br>
way for us to understand the subject.  Consider John 6:57:<br>
<p>
``As the living Father hath sent Me, and I live by the Father: so he<br>
that eateth Me, even he shall live by Me.''<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
