<title>Apr_1993: Re: Power for victory</title>
<h1>Re: Power for victory</h1>
Noe Torres | ECISD (<i>noe@tenet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Apr 1993 16:19:09 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#254">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#254">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#254">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#254">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0255.html">Steven Timm: "Can we all get along?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0253.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: What I think everyone agrees on"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0259.html">David Plaisted: "Power for victory"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0278.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Power for victory"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Tue, 13 Apr 1993, David Plaisted wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; In response to Noe Torres' message:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; You raise the point -- Christ ``did not go outside Himself to another</i><br>
<i>&gt; to work out our redemption.''</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; But what about statements like John 5:19:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; ``The Son can do nothing of Himself, but only what He seeth the Father</i><br>
<i>&gt; do: for what things soever He doeth, these also doeth the Son</i><br>
<i>&gt; likewise.''</i><br>
<p>
The humanity of Christ, with which He clothed Himself in order to carry<br>
out the great mission, did rely on faith in and strengthening from the<br>
Father.  You are correct.  Because Christ voluntarily DENIED HIMSELF<br>
ACCESS to His rightful Divine prerogatives, He did not draw from His<br>
divinity to sustain His humanity.  He COULD have, but He did not.<br>
<p>
This does not make Christ a "lesser God," as some teach.  Our church has<br>
always taught that Christ is fully equal to the Father.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
