<title>Apr_1993: SDANET:   DINOSAUR Genetics</title>
<h1>SDANET:   DINOSAUR Genetics</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Apr 1993 23:41:23 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#243">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#243">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#243">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#243">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0244.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Baker letter"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0242.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Baker letter"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Elaine Writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; To shift the topic just a tad, I was told recently (last Sabbath) that our</i><br>
<i>&gt; scientists are to the point or almost to the point where they can</i><br>
write genes.<br>
<i>&gt; Is this true?  Apparently, once a new gene is written and introduced there is</i><br>
<i>&gt; no way to remove it from the population (you can make it recessive but</i><br>
you can<br>
<i>&gt; not eliminate it).  Are we going to have gene hackers like the</i><br>
computer people<br>
<i>&gt; that introduce computer viruses? </i><br>
<p>
Although I am not a PhD in Genetic Engineering, I do know that at the present<br>
time, we should not be worrying about gene hackers creating new genes.  We can<br>
indeed read the human genetic code (i.e. the human genome project underway), <br>
but the results of this project are simply a sequence of nucleic acids.  What<br>
does a sequence such as ATGTAGTGCGTAGT mean?  Who knows!  We can identify the<br>
sequences that make up some specific proteins, but we have no clue how the <br>
structure of the body is encoded.<br>
<p>
As far as writing genes goes, we can write specific nucleic acids in sequence.<br>
But here again, we don't know what they do.  We just don't know enough to go<br>
off creating a new creature.  We do know some specifics, but trying to create<br>
a new gene from scratch would be like trying to create a new computer by <br>
scratching the disk drive with a pin.  <br>
<p>
Brian Hartman<br>
Biology and Bioengineering<br>
Walla Walla College<br>
<p>
[Real life may not have made it yet, but cloned dinosaurs are scheduled <br>
to hit the movies in _Jurassic Park_ this summer.  More comments in the next<br>
post.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
