<title>Apr_1993: Re: "Historic Adventism"</title>
<h1>Re: "Historic Adventism"</h1>
Fritz Guy (<i>fguy@polaris.lasierra.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Apr 1993 23:50:50 -0600 (PDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#272">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#272">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#272">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#272">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0273.html">Steven Timm: "RE: The Last Gap"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0271.html">Ademir P. Soares: "Re: SDA Bibel for PC"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0226.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Job and Great Controversy"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
When people claim to be proponents of "historic Adventism," a crucial (and<br>
usually unasked) question is: WHICH "historic Adventism"? The Adventism of<br>
1844? Of 1863? Of 1888? Of 1901? Of 1915? Of 1952? of 1980? <br>
<p>
Adventism is (and always has been) a living, dynamic religious community,<br>
and it is both foolish and futile to expect otherwise. Like individual<br>
believers, when a religion stops changing, it is dead. If this sounds too<br>
"liberal" or "progressive" to some, they may with profit recall some words<br>
of Ellen White: <br>
<p>
	"There is no excuse for anyone in taking the position that there<br>
is no more truth to be revealed, and that all our expositions of Scripture<br>
are without an error. The fact that certain doctrines have been held as<br>
truth for many years by our people is not a proof that our ideas are<br>
infallible. Age will not make error into truth, and truth can afford to be<br>
fair. No true doctrine will lose anything by close investigation."<br>
["Review and Herald," December 20, 1892]<br>
<p>
	"We have many lessons to learn, and many, many to unlearn. God and<br>
heaven alone are infallible. Those who think that they will never have to<br>
give up a cherished view, never have occasion to change an opinion, will<br>
be disappointed." ["Review and Herald," July 26, 1892]<br>
<p>
	"Whenever the people of God are growing in grace, they will be<br>
constantly obtaining a clearer understanding of His Word. They will<br>
discern new light and beauty in its sacred truths. This has been true in<br>
the history of the church in all ages, and thus it will continue to the<br>
end. But as real spiritual life declines, it has ever been the tendency to<br>
cease to advance in the knowledge of the truth. Men rest satisfied with<br>
the light already received from God's Word, and discourage any further<br>
investigation of the Scriptures. They become conservative, and seek to<br>
avoid discussion." ["Testimonies for the Church," vol.5, pp. 706-7]<br>
<p>
None of this means that we should be disrespectful of our theological<br>
heritage. Indeed, we should take it very seriously--but not absolutely. It<br>
is a foundation on which to build, not a corral in which to be confined.<br>
<p>
Fritz Guy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
