<!-- received="Tue Apr 13 23:52:52 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Tue, 13 Apr 1993 23:52:52 -0400 (EDT)" -->
<!-- name="Steven Timm" -->
<!-- email="st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- subject="The last gap" -->
<!-- id="EfmseIO00YUoI5q7I1@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Apr_1993: The last gap</title>
<h1>The last gap</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Apr 1993 23:52:52 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#245">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#245">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#245">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#245">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0246.html">Dan Blake: "Job's thoughts about his plight"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0244.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Baker letter"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0284.html">Danny Kumamoto: "Re:  The last gap"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Most creation-believing scientists, including myself, point out that <br>
a strong argument against the evolution scenario, is that abiogenesis<br>
(creation of life by some means other than reproduction) has not been <br>
observed to occur.  But what would happen to such an argument<br>
if scientists were to someday start with basic alcohols and inorganic<br>
reagents and proceed to synthesize a living cell from scratch?<br>
<p>
Before the moon landing, SDA preachers were preaching that God would never<br>
allow sinful men to land on the moon and spread sin elsewhere.  But it<br>
happened.  <br>
<p>
It is easy to hide behind the "God of the Gaps" theory and postulate God<br>
as the moving force behind all that is unknown.  But then God must<br>
necessarily shrink as scientific knowledge grows, until as Laplace said<br>
"I have no need of that hypothesis."<br>
<p>
I would propose that we spend more time in emphasizing the role of God<br>
in that which we do understand.  I don't know how God creates a cell,<br>
but I have a pretty good understanding about how He does a photon or<br>
an electron, and hopefully before my thesis is done I'll have a handle<br>
on the Sigma-minus particle as well.  A miracle that is understood <br>
is no less of a miracle.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
