<!-- body="start" -->
On Tue, 13 Apr 1993, David Plaisted wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The trinity is a great mystery.  But the Bible presents the</i><br>
<i>&gt; relationship of Jesus to the Father in terms of Christ depending on a</i><br>
<i>&gt; power outside of Himself, namely, that of the Father.  And Ellen White</i><br>
<i>&gt; speaks of this in the same way.  Of course, since Christ and the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Father are one, in another sense Christ is depending on His own power.</i><br>
<p>
I somehow feel the key to this is that Christ's human nature, which was<br>
denied access to power from His divine nature for use on Himself, relied<br>
on faith and trust in the Father.  The Father, through the Spirit and the<br>
ministering angels, worked to strengthen the human nature of Christ.  I<br>
have an EGW statement at home that I'll post later that hits this point<br>
right on the head.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
