<title>Apr_1993: Terrible Lizards.</title>
<h1>Terrible Lizards.</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 14 Apr 93 13:00:56 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#262">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#262">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#262">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#262">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0263.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: Spiritual head of the family"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0261.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: Gentry's halos"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Brian Hartman writes:<br>
<i>&gt;As far as writing genes goes, we can write specific nucleic acids in sequence.</i><br>
<i>&gt;But here again, we don't know what they do.  We just don't know enough to go</i><br>
<i>&gt;off creating a new creature.  We do know some specifics, but trying to create</i><br>
<i>&gt;a new gene from scratch would be like trying to create a new computer by </i><br>
<i>&gt;scratching the disk drive with a pin.</i><br>
<p>
We may not know how to create from scratch, but we can play around with some<br>
of the jumper switches. We can genetically engineer cells like yeast, to<br>
produce human antibodies and pharmaceutical chemicals, and we can mix genes,<br>
like when they implanted a firefly gene in a tobacco plant, or like the<br>
mouse which they wanted to copyright because they put some human genes in it<br>
or something, and we can alter the way genes express or make cells with<br>
abnormal numbers of chromosomes (like some plants we can cause to grow to<br>
Cannanite proportions by making them polyploid). Perhaps that was how the<br>
ante diluveans made their confusing amalgamations.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;[Real life may not have made it yet, but cloned dinosaurs are scheduled </i><br>
<i>&gt;to hit the movies in _Jurassic Park_ this summer.  More comments in the next</i><br>
<i>&gt;post.  SCT]</i><br>
<p>
It might be possible soon, to clone a dinosaur from dinosaur DNA, if we can<br>
find it. A more likely subject for cloning are preserved wolly mammoths<br>
though.<br>
<p>
-Beng Tang<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
