Steve Timm writes:<br>
<i>&gt; But what would happen to such an argument</i><br>
<i>&gt; if scientists were to someday start with basic alcohols and inorganic</i><br>
<i>&gt; reagents and proceed to synthesize a living cell from scratch?</i><br>
<p>
This wouldn't be a problem, as a creationist, since it would only<br>
prove that it takes "intelligence" to make life from scratch.  Unless<br>
scientists can show that life can come about without any intervention<br>
by man -- or other animals -- creationists can rest at ease.<br>
<p>
(The same rule applies to language.  So far, scientists have yet to<br>
show that language can come about without any intervention by another<br>
language-user.  All the animal research studies are naught, since, so<br>
far, they have been accomplished by direct intervention by<br>
language-users, i.e.  research scientists.  They have only shown that<br>
it takes a helping hand from a language-user to become another<br>
language-user -- something linguists have been saying for the last 30<br>
years or so.  At least, the non-creationist-linguists have smartened<br>
up by no longer discussing the origin of language -- since the only<br>
possible source of the original language is either extra-terrestrial<br>
beings or -- gasp! -- God.)<br>
<p>
Danny<br>
