<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Steve,<br>
<p>
I don't mean to start a creation-evolution discussion here, and anyway,<br>
there are no evolutionists to argue with me here, but the fact of God's<br>
creatorship (see 1st angel's message and 2Pe 3:3-7) and how the work of God,<br>
like the Word of God, speaks volumes about Him (Ps 19:1-3, Rom 1:20) are<br>
things of great interest to SDAs, or so i think.<br>
[Evolutionists are here, but they keep their mouth shut.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;observed to occur.  But what would happen to such an argument</i><br>
<i>&gt;if scientists were to someday start with basic alcohols and inorganic</i><br>
<i>&gt;reagents and proceed to synthesize a living cell from scratch?</i><br>
<p>
Well, we are yet far removed from that possibility. I don't think they can<br>
even bring a dead cell, with all its parts in place, back to life, let alone<br>
make a new one from scratch. They used to think, in the early days of<br>
evolutionary theory, that the cell was just a buble of fluid with some fats,<br>
proteins and so on, and if you shake some organic soup up in a reducing<br>
atmosphere with some lightning and UV radiation and do other elaborate<br>
things to it, you just might eventually get a cell. But with the advent of<br>
the electron microscope and other modern methods of investigation, we know<br>
know that even the smallest unit of living matter is fearfully and<br>
wonderfully made. I mean, looking at electron micrographs of cell<br>
ultrastructure, i wonder how anyone in their right mind can imagine that all<br>
that happened by small doses of increadibly good luck over eons. Although<br>
intelligent human beings using complex processes and devices, have been<br>
shown to be able to synthesize simple biological molecules and polymers, the<br>
reverse has not been demonstrated, that given time, simple biological<br>
molecules can arrange themselves into intelligent human beings.<br>
	This same combination of unimaginable complexity and despite that,<br>
the increadible harmony and well-designed, for want of a better word, way<br>
in which natural systems operate, is seen in the biochemistry and physiology<br>
of plants and animals. How, for example, their enzymes work under precisely<br>
the right conditions and in precisely the right way, how the half-lives of<br>
hormones are tuned to the systems they regulate, how physiological<br>
parameters and biochemical pathways are so exactly regulated, at precisely<br>
the best places in order to achieve optimum efficiency and performance, how<br>
cells and even molecules, respond in just the right way to changes in their<br>
environments, in order to fulfill their functions, the list goes on. Praise<br>
be to God, for all His works, in wisdom are they all made!<br>
	Of course, only a Christian can fully appreciate the things of<br>
nature, for he can discern the character his master in the work of His<br>
mouth.  Evolutionists would ascribe all the marvels of nature to<br>
unintelligent and meaningless chance that has less than a one in a million<br>
probability of happening in a million years. Its amazing what some people<br>
will believe.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Before the moon landing, SDA preachers were preaching that God would never</i><br>
<i>&gt;allow sinful men to land on the moon and spread sin elsewhere.  But it</i><br>
<i>&gt;happened.  </i><br>
<p>
Well, thats what comes of preaching things not found in the bible.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;It is easy to hide behind the "God of the Gaps" theory and postulate God</i><br>
<i>&gt;as the moving force behind all that is unknown.  But then God must</i><br>
<i>&gt;necessarily shrink as scientific knowledge grows, until as Laplace said</i><br>
<i>&gt;"I have no need of that hypothesis."</i><br>
<p>
True enough. A regular atheist contributor to the religion conference in<br>
my University's bulletin board put it thus:<br>
	"All I can say is: God ought to put in more effort [to make Himself<br>
known to man]. Because so far, all He has succeded in doing is to produce a<br>
Universe which looks exactly as it would if He didn't exist." Although<br>
i don't agree with him, i can understand what he means.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I would propose that we spend more time in emphasizing the role of God</i><br>
<i>&gt;in that which we do understand.  I don't know how God creates a cell,</i><br>
<i>&gt;but I have a pretty good understanding about how He does a photon or</i><br>
<i>&gt;an electron, and hopefully before my thesis is done I'll have a handle</i><br>
<i>&gt;on the Sigma-minus particle as well.  A miracle that is understood </i><br>
<i>&gt;is no less of a miracle.</i><br>
<p>
True enough and well said. May God help you in your hunt for exotic<br>
particles!<br>
	Steve, do you know a guy called Weng Kee Leong? He is now lecturing<br>
Physics and Chemistry at Southeast Asia Union College, and attends my church,<br>
and he said he knows you. If you know him, it will be the second time i've<br>
met someone on SDAnet who knows someone else i know.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
[I believe he was at Andrews during the same time I was.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
