<title>Apr_1993: Re: Could you define some terms?</title>
<h1>Re: Could you define some terms?</h1>
Noe Torres | ECISD (<i>noe@tenet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 15 Apr 1993 08:20:11 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#287">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#287">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#287">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#287">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0288.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Re: The last gap"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0286.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: Bible for PC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dan,<br>
The Atonement to me is the one, ultimate, defining act of God for<br>
eternity.  It is the act of God that, through love, establishes forever<br>
His authority and character.  It is the "at-one-ment," meaning that the<br>
universe is healed and made "one" again when, as a direct result of<br>
Christ's sacrifice on Calvary, final judgment descends upon Satan and his<br>
followers and the universe is cleansed forever of the cancer of sin. <br>
Affliction shall not arise a second time, the Bible says.<br>
<p>
The Atonement was conceived in the council of peace before our world was<br>
created, it was set into motion after the rebellion of Adam and Eve, its<br>
climax came in the perfect life and atoning death of the God-man Jesus<br>
Christ, and there remains just a "short span" until the plan of redemption<br>
concludes.<br>
<p>
We don't understand the full implications of the Atonement.  It is an<br>
event more glorious than words can describe.  Aspects of it will remain a<br>
mystery for all eternity.  Few statements I've ever read speak to the<br>
glory of the Atonement as well as the one that follows:<br>
<p>
<p>
"The angels ascribe honor and glory to Christ, for even they are not<br>
secure except by looking to the sufferings of the Son of God.  It is<br>
through the efficacy of the cross that the angels of heaven are guarded<br>
from apostasy.  Without the cross they would be no more secure against<br>
evil than were the angels before the fall of Satan.  Angelic perfection<br>
failed in heaven.  Human perfection failed in Eden, the paradise of bliss.<br>
 All who wish for security in earth or heaven must look to the Lamb of God.<br>
<p>
"The plan of savation, making manifest the justice and love of God,<br>
provides an eternal safeguard against defection in unfallen worlds, as<br>
well as among those who shall be redeemed by the blood of the Lamb."<br>
(5BC 1132).<br>
<p>
My apologies for any 50-cent words I may have used....<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
