<title>Apr_1993: Spiritual Headship</title>
<h1>Spiritual Headship</h1>
Ray Mialki (<i>rm1g+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 15 Apr 1993 13:09:58 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#280">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#280">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#280">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#280">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0281.html">Susan Harrington: "Re: Spiritual head of the family"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0279.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "RE: Power for victory"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In reply to Pam Harris's comment on Adam's headship.<br>
<p>
Yes, both Eve and Adam were responsible for their own sin.  Adam was<br>
guilty of abdicating his spiritual headship over Eve, his wife.  But Eve<br>
was also responsible for her part in the sin.<br>
<p>
If you look at how things transpire when God confronts Adam, Eve, and<br>
even the serpent, you see that God first confronts Adam.  Eve was the<br>
first to take a bite of the fruit, but God holds Adam first responsible.<br>
 Then Adam goes and puts the blame on God, for producing the woman.<br>
<p>
Then God confronts Eve, but she puts the blame on the serpent.  All<br>
three were guilty of sin.  All threee were confronted by God.  And all<br>
three recieved a curse from God.<br>
<p>
Think about it, what wrong did the serpent really do?  Adam and Eve<br>
didn't have to listen to it.  But the serpent still was found guilty.  <br>
<p>
If Adam tried to stop Eve, and Eve continued, then Adam would have been<br>
free from guilt.  But Adam chose not to do this, so he is guilty.  <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
