<i>&gt;&gt;The Holy One created us all to have an individual relationship with Her.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;This is new to me. Are you suggesting that God is female? All along, i had</i><br>
<i>&gt;the impression that if God has gender, then God must be male, because the</i><br>
<i>&gt;bible always uses "He" and "His" and so on, to refer to God. The only place</i><br>
<p>
Jesus speaks of himself not only as a hen wishing to gather her chicks under<br>
her wings but also as a woman searching her house in search of a lost coin.<br>
And it strikes me as effective that God should use the "mother" scenario<br>
to describe himself as well as the "father" one since the mother has<br>
traditionally been more strongly involved (both in general and emotional <br>
terms) in the rearing and caring for children.<br>
<p>
And if God was female anyway - why would s/he admit it to an ancient society<br>
so strongly gripped by male domination?<br>
<p>
But also remember... God made man (generic) in his own image - male and<br>
female. Is God both male and female? Neither male or female? Surely he couldn't<br>
be just male or just female if both are his image?<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
