<title>Apr_1993: Proof</title>
<h1>Proof</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>16 Apr 1993 12:05:29 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#291">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#291">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#291">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#291">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0292.html">Steve Hix: "Re: The last gap"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0290.html">CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Spiritual Head of the Family"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I feel like being picky today...<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
<i>&gt; But what would happen to such an argument</i><br>
<i>&gt; if scientists were to someday start with basic alcohols and inorganic</i><br>
<i>&gt; reagents and proceed to synthesize a living cell from scratch?</i><br>
<p>
This wouldn't be a problem, as a creationist, since it would only<br>
prove that it takes "intelligence" to make life from scratch.  Unless<br>
scientists can show that life can come about without any intervention<br>
by man -- or other animals -- creationists can rest at ease.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I watched "Ancient Secrets of the Bible" the other day, and noticed that<br>
many of the Biblical accounts were claimed to have been "proven correct" <br>
by scientists, anthropologists and archaeologists. The problem is that<br>
evidence in favour of something doesn't constitute the eradication of all<br>
doubt. Even in court there is a difference between "found guilty" and<br>
"proven guilty".<br>
<p>
If scientists eventually succeed in copying a living cell, or even <br>
inventing one, that will only "prove" that intelligent beings are<br>
capable of creating life. It won't prove that intelligent beings are<br>
necessary for this to occur. I think moderation of language used in<br>
such claims would even help people like myself, letalone those who<br>
don't agree at all with our position to start with!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
