<title>Apr_1993: Iron &amp; vegetarians</title>
<h1>Iron &amp; vegetarians</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>16 Apr 1993 12:11:33 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#302">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#302">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#302">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#302">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0303.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Distinctives"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0301.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Can we all get along?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0306.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Iron &amp; vegetarians"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On our TV news a couple of nights ago was a report urging caution to <br>
various groups of people regarding adequate iron and calcium intake.<br>
One of the groups specifically mentioned was vegetarians. Something <br>
about how the iron in vegetables and grains isn't as easily absorbed<br>
by the body as iron in meat.<br>
<p>
Now I know that broccoli is supposed to be a good iron source. What<br>
other types of food are important to maintain adequate iron intake?<br>
I have at least one friend who suffers fatigue due to iron deficiency,<br>
and she is strictly vegetarian. I follow a vegetarian diet 99% of the<br>
time, so the normal advice "eat more red meat, or if you don't want<br>
to do that, eat dark coloured fish or chicken" is useless to me.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
