<title>Apr_1993: RE: The Last Gap</title>
<h1>RE: The Last Gap</h1>
Rick Cook (<i>rlcook@erenj.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 16 Apr 93 14:13:49 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#299">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#299">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#299">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#299">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0300.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Can we all get along?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0298.html">McCluskey G: "Project Gutenberg"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
       In Steve's essay, he suggests the possibility of one of the critical<br>
gaps in evolutionary theory may be overturned by future scientific<br>
research:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;observed to occur.  But what would happen to such an argument</i><br>
<i>&gt;if scientists were to someday start with basic alcohols and inorganic</i><br>
<i>&gt;reagents and proceed to synthesize a living cell from scratch?</i><br>
<p>
        In the debate over the possibility of artificially creating cells,<br>
the replies thus far have been centered around disproving that this is a<br>
scientific possibility.  Whether or not this particular "discovery" is<br>
likely to occur, Steve's point that creationists tend to point to the "gaps<br>
in science" as proof of God and/or His activity in creation is well taken.<br>
        There is a fundamental problem in using the inability of science to<br>
present a complete picture as evidence for the need of a god.  Most<br>
scientists will admit that scientific theory is fluid, liable to change at<br>
any time to reflect new data and evidence.  However, most Adventists would<br>
contend that there is an absoluteness about their theological theories;<br>
i.e., God does not change with time.  One cannot expect any arguments for<br>
theology to pass the test of time if they are based on temporally unstable<br>
scientific understanding.  This is certainly the case with "man cannot make<br>
a cell therefore God did."<br>
	       I guess I have seen so much evidence of "convincing arguments"<br>
being destroyed when a gap is filled that I simply cannot buy the<br>
abiogenesis argument.  Launching attacks on abiogenesis evolution does not<br>
prove creation--you cannot prove one theory by disproving another without<br>
committing a serious logical fallacy.<br>
	       Another big problem with the "gap" mentality is that it makes<br>
Christians very suspicious of scientists.  This is because the scientists'<br>
quest to fill in the gap with a natural explanation is viewed by the<br>
Christian as an attempt to disprove God.  This suspicion is also fueled, I<br>
believe, by a general misunderstand of the difference between scientific<br>
and theological methodology.<br>
	       It is the role of the Christian to point out the miracle of life,<br>
the role God plays in life.  God does work in logical ways, it should not<br>
discourage the Christian to discover that God's methods are being uncovered<br>
by science.<br>
<p>
-Rick Cook<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
