<title>Apr_1993: Re: Can we all get along?</title>
<h1>Re: Can we all get along?</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 16 Apr 93 15:14:20 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#300">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#300">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#300">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#300">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0301.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Can we all get along?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0299.html">Rick Cook: "RE: The Last Gap"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0255.html">Steven Timm: "Can we all get along?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0301.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Can we all get along?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As a church we still have the racial problems.  The segregated church services<br>
in america help to shield these things from us.  Just like in the world, the<br>
Black and the White adventist are very much different economically.  Black<br>
adventists in america usually are from the lower end of the economic ladder.<br>
Black and White adventists grow up in entirely different worlds.  I would bet<br>
that most White american Adventists are Republican, while mose Black American<br>
Adventists are Democratic.  <br>
<p>
A lot of young black Adventists are getting caught up in the Black Awakening<br>
that is going on.  A feeling of pride in blackness seems to be going around<br>
America and Blacks in the Church also are feeling this.  I would guess that <br>
the White american Church would see this black Awakening as racist.  Which<br>
shows that the church, at least on race issues, mirrors the world.<br>
<p>
Some of our difficulties stem from our detatchment from one another.  I do<br>
know where the White church is and the conference office and I even know <br>
people in the White church, but I do not feel as though I am in one of my<br>
churches when I go to it.  <br>
<p>
I hate to say it, but I feel more at home in a black "non-adventist" church<br>
than white "adventist"  churches.  There is no question that part of this is<br>
me.  I could be more open to my brothers and sisters in the "other" church.<br>
Part of this is my brothers and sisters in the "other" church.  They could<br>
be a little more open to me.  Part of this is just blacks sticking together.<br>
<p>
At work I am closer to the black people than the white people, as a rule.<br>
There are exceptions.  I guess part of it is we believe it is us against<br>
the world.  THere is usually not that many of us, so we stick together.<br>
<p>
I must say that I do not hesitate to go to any adventist church, but I do <br>
prefer "Black" churches.  The question that Rodney King asked, "Can we<br>
all get along?" can be answered Yes if we have talks like this.  If we<br>
tell each other what we are thinking.  I  would be interested to hear from<br>
Adventists in america from the "White" churches.  I  do not wish to exclude<br>
foreigners, but I do not know if their situation is the same.  It may be.<br>
<p>
bye<br>
<pre>
-- 
"Competition is the law of the jungle.
 Cooperation is the law of civilization."  -  Eldridge Cleaver
<p>
Sherman H. Cox, II       scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
