Sherman Cox writes:<br>
<p>
[About "race" in the Seventh-day Adventist Church]<br>
<p>
I find your statement - that the Church "reflects the world" in this<br>
matter - to fit with suspicions I've had.<br>
<p>
Church members are members of, and effected by what happens outside<br>
the church walls.  So the economic difference doesn't shock me.  The silence<br>
of the Church regarding it enrages me.  By God's grace S/He helps me<br>
channel that rage so that it is constructive, and doesn't consume me.<br>
Like Sherman, I too am curious about foreigners, and their perspective.<br>
<p>
For the past year I've attend a "white" church in suburban Seattle, which is<br>
probably somewhat different from the same thing in suburban Huntsville,<br>
*Alabama* (I've visited some of those churches).  But even we aren't<br>
immune to issues of race.  At the beginning of my attendance, some people<br>
made such a show of acknowledging me, that I felt self-conscious and out of<br>
place.  I experienced others who *seemed* to be suspicious of my motives for<br>
attending there church.  There are still a few who seem to not trust me <br>
for some<br>
reason.  But there would be people in a black church who might not like me for<br>
different reasons other than race.<br>
<p>
I suspect that silence about this on SDA-net will be deafening, as in other<br>
areas of SDA-world.  Maybe "netland" will prove me wrong - - I'll welcome it.<br>
<p>
Marcus Stringer<br>
