<title>Apr_1993: dietary iron</title>
<h1>dietary iron</h1>
<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>17 Apr 1993 15:59:20 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#310">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#310">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#310">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#310">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0311.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "more things"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0309.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Distinctives"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It's true that the iron in mrat is absorbed through a different<br>
mechanism than is iron from other sources.  In general, only 10% of<br>
the iron you eat is absorbed, unless you are deficient in iron, in<br>
which case the efficiency of absorption my double or even triple.<br>
Lots of factors have an impact on iron absorption -- too many to go<br>
into here.  One easy way to help enhance iron absorption from plant<br>
sources is to get enough vitamin C, which helps reduce ferric iron to<br>
the more absorbable ferrous form.<br>
<p>
Good sources of iron for vegetarians:<br>
  Prune juice -- 10.5 mg per cup!!!<br>
  Beans -- depending on the kind of bean, 5-8 mg per cup of cooked beans<br>
  Green leafy veges, fresh peas -- 2-4 mg per cup cooked<br>
  dried fruit (peaches, raisins, dates, prunes) -- 2-4 mg<br>
       from 5 peach halves, or 1/2 cup raisins, or 10 dates, or 5 prunes<br>
  Blackstrap molasses -- 3.2 mg per tablespoon<br>
<p>
Another way to up iron consumption is to cook acidic foods in cast iron<br>
cookware.<br>
If you cook spaghetti sauce in an iron pot for three hours, you increase<br>
its iron content 29 times!  You can get twice as much iron from scrambled<br>
eggs or 14 times as much from gravy that has cooked for 45 minutes in iron<br>
cookware (the eggs only have to be in the pot three minutes).<br>
<p>
Hope this helps.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
