<title>Apr_1993: Re:  Iron &amp; vegetarians</title>
<h1>Re:  Iron &amp; vegetarians</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 18 Apr 93 02:36:28 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#306">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#306">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#306">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#306">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0307.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Vitamin B12 and vegetarians"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0305.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: Can we all get along?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0302.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Iron &amp; vegetarians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tony writes:<br>
<i>&gt;One of the groups specifically mentioned was vegetarians. Something </i><br>
<i>&gt;about how the iron in vegetables and grains isn't as easily absorbed</i><br>
<i>&gt;by the body as iron in meat.</i><br>
<p>
This was postulated from animal experiments, if i'm not wrong, and if so, i<br>
wonder at their validity in humans. Anyway, the thing they think is that<br>
iron 2+ (ferrous iron), found in haem prosthetic groups on haemoglobin and<br>
myoglobin molecules (found in blood and muscle respectively) is much more<br>
readily absorbed in the intestine, than iron 3+ (ferric iron), the more<br>
oxidised form of iron, which is the predominant form in our diet and in<br>
grains and vegetables.<br>
	In the stomach, the acid dissolves the iron and allows it to form<br>
soluble complexes with substances which reduce it to the ferrous (2+) form<br>
and keep it reduced. The most notable of these reducing agents is vitamin C,<br>
which is found in quantity only in fruits and vegetables (and not in meat).<br>
Thus, i would think that it is good to get iron from these sources. There<br>
are many other factors in iron absorbtion in the gastro-intestinal tract,<br>
but in individuals with a normal healthy GIT, iron deficiency is not really<br>
something to worry about, not in vegetarians either, although phytic acid in<br>
cereals and oxalates in some leafy vegetables bind iron in an insoluble<br>
compound and render it unavailable for absorbtion. Still, there is enough<br>
iron in a vegetarian diet. Nothing to worry about.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Now I know that broccoli is supposed to be a good iron source. What</i><br>
<i>&gt;other types of food are important to maintain adequate iron intake?</i><br>
<p>
Apples turn brown because the iron 2+ (ferrous) gets oxidised to brown rust<br>
(iron 3+, ferric iron), so i guess they have quite a bit of iron. Egg yolk<br>
also has a lot of iron, but also has loads of cholesterol. Some breakfast<br>
cereal or bread manufacturers add iron to their products. Milk has iron.<br>
Leafy vegetables also have iron, but i wonder at the oxalic acid in spinnach<br>
etc. (see above) and another source also contributes to dietary iron: iron<br>
cooking utensils! Actually, iron deficiency normally results from some<br>
problem with the GIT or from bleeding (eg. ulcers) rather than a dietary<br>
deficiency, as long as we take a varied diet, and the body has a remarkable<br>
mechanism for regulating iron absorbtion to adjust to iron needs, so when<br>
more iron is needed, more is absorbed.<br>
	Even if vegetarians get less iron than "meatarians", that may not be<br>
such a bad thing, recent research has suggested that high levels of iron in<br>
the blood, are associated with most types of cancer and with heart disease,<br>
both of which are the main killers of modern urban man, so much so that some<br>
even recommend blood donation as a way to keep the body's iron stores low.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
Internet:	med10014@nusunix1.us.sg<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
