<title>Apr_1993: Vitamin B12 and vegetarians</title>
<h1>Vitamin B12 and vegetarians</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 18 Apr 93 04:18:18 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#307">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#307">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#307">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#307">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0308.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Sabbath-keeping Ethiopeans"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0306.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Iron &amp; vegetarians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0326.html">Michael Merginio: "Re: Vitamin B12 and vegetarians"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi again,<br>
	another thing you'll hear is that vegetarians lack Vitamin B12 in<br>
their diet and so are prone to pernicious anaemia.<br>
	Vitamin B12 (cyanocobalamin) is not produced by either plants or<br>
animals. Its sole natural source, as far as is known, is bacteria which<br>
synthesize it. Meat is thus a secondary source of the vitamin, the animals<br>
from which the meat is derived having obtained their B12 from bacterial<br>
action in their guts or on the food they eat or in the water they drink.<br>
Thus, animal products, meat, eggs, milk and particularly bivalve shellfish,<br>
are considered good sources of the vitamin, and some people say that<br>
vegetarians will thus lack B12.<br>
	However, B12 is often found in stream and well water, and on<br>
vegetables, and especially root vegetables, contaminated by soil bacteria<br>
that produce it (so it doesn't pay to be too hygenic eh?). It is also<br>
produced by symbiotic bacteria in the root nodules of legumes like peanuts<br>
or soybeans etc, which makes me wonder if peanuts are a good source ot it,<br>
them being underground and all.<br>
	In humans, it is produced in appreciable amounts in the large<br>
intestine, by bacteria that live there, but this is below the region where<br>
it can be actively absorbed (there are receptors for it in the small<br>
intestine) and so very little of it is obtained here.<br>
	However, i recently read an article in Nature magazine, which should<br>
be of interest to veggies. CMC in Vellore, India, did a survey of the<br>
intestinal flora in the small intestines of South Indians, and found at<br>
least 2 strains of bacteria there (Pseudomonas and Kleisignella... i think i<br>
spelt that wrong) which produced Vitamin B12 or B12-like substances, and<br>
suggested that that was why B12 deficiency was rare, even among vegetarians,<br>
in South India; whereas is was more common amongst South Indian vegetarians<br>
who migrated to Western countries, although their diet was the same, because<br>
standards of hygene are such that their intestinal flora becomes<br>
impovrished.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<p>
Internet: med10014@nusunix1.nus.sg<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
