<title>Apr_1993: Sabbath in Ethiopia</title>
<h1>Sabbath in Ethiopia</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 18 Apr 1993 14:55:55 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#323">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#323">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#323">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#323">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0324.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0322.html">HEALY, TAMMY R: "Re: Union"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It is difficult to know what kind of Sabbath-keepers in Ethiopia were<br>
referred to in the magazine.  Two items of interest:  The seventh-day<br>
Sabbath was kept in Ethiopia as a regular day of rest until the 16th<br>
century.  Conflict with Roman Catholics changed the custom.<br>
Saturday is considered the appropriate day of worship, with Coptic <br>
meetings taking place in the afternoon.  However, Sunday is also a<br>
day to worship.  This is what we observed on a brief visit there in<br>
1989.<br>
On the historical aspect of Sabbath in Ethiopia, see the chapter in<br>
Sabbath in Scripture and History.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
