We who live in Southern California now know no majority culture.  We<br>
are all minorities searching for a way to create the New Testament<br>
church when we are buffeted from and about the multitude of cultures<br>
and races around us.  I believe that in time all of the United States<br>
will have to come to the realization that there is no majority race<br>
(culture), and I we hope that those of us who've gotten to that point<br>
early will have a model or multiple models of how to live together and<br>
to achieve our true vocation -- advancing the gospel.  Indeed, if<br>
we do offer models we will have advanced the gospel.<br>
<p>
My home church, Alhambra, CA, is classified by the conference as an<br>
Anglo (white) church, but some members' skins reflect a great deal of<br>
the ambiant light and others absorb most of it.  There are those<br>
who speak English as their first language, adn thos who speak Talagu,<br>
Spanish, Portuguese, Korean, Mandrin, Romanian, Japanese, and<br>
some other European languages I'm sure I've omitted.  We get along<br>
together marvelously for we have a truly inclusive body of believers.<br>
We cherish our diversity while striving for the same goals.  We are<br>
working now to make sure that we are also sensitive to age-inclusiveness<br>
as well as race (culture) and gender.  We've been idea tolerant for<br>
decades.  <br>
<p>
--Jerry Wiley<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
