<title>Apr_1993: iron</title>
<h1>iron</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 19 Apr 93 11:16:23 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#317">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#317">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#317">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#317">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0318.html">Ray Mialki: "Jack in the Box Lies"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0316.html">Steven Timm: "Background on Ruben's post"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here's something I posted to another group a while back.<br>
<p>
Bottom line summary might be:<br>
<p>
	- men often get too much iron<br>
<p>
	- women often don't get enough (I've heard reports of 25%<br>
	rates of deficiency for women), partly because of greater<br>
	losses and partly because they tend to eat lighter foods like<br>
	salads<br>
<p>
	- just because a plant diet was right in the Garden of Eden<br>
	(and still right in my view) doesn't automatically mean that<br>
	one can get enough iron from plant foods;  it's rare, for<br>
	example, for someone with bad eyes to refuse glasses with the<br>
	argument that "it's not natural" or "they didn't wear glasses<br>
	in the Garden of Eden"<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<p>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
*From: glenm (Glen McCluskey)<br>
*Subject: iron - more than you want to know<br>
*Date: Tue, 10 Dec 91 22:02:49 EST<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I read yesterday that iron can be better assimilated from plant</i><br>
<i>&gt; sources if more vitamin C is consumed at the same time.  So, I</i><br>
<i>&gt; suppose iron from plants is better assimilated if it is eaten</i><br>
<i>&gt; fresh and with other fresh vegetables?!</i><br>
<p>
I have my copy of the 1980 "Recommended Dietary Allowances" handy and<br>
thought I would summarize more completely what it says about iron.  As<br>
far as I know nothing has changed in the last 10 years.<br>
<p>
1.  Anemia is not necessarily a very sensitive indicator of iron<br>
depletion, because iron is stored in the body and the stores are<br>
depleted before the hemoglobin concentration begins to drop.<br>
<p>
2.  Iron metabolism is not regulated by increased or decreased<br>
excretion, as is the the case for other minerals.<br>
<p>
3.  The average iron loss in the healthy adult male is about 1.0mg a<br>
day.<br>
<p>
4.  For adult females, there is an additional loss of 0.5mg a day, the<br>
amount of iron in the menstrual blood flow averaged over a month.<br>
<p>
5.  There is wide variation in #4, and about 5% of females have been<br>
observed to lose over 1.4mg a day, making the total loss 2.4mg a day.<br>
<p>
6.  Pregnancy increases the requirement to 3.5mg a day.<br>
<p>
7.  Children and adolescents need about 1.8mg a day.<br>
<p>
8.  Intestinal absorption is regulated in a way that tends to keep<br>
body iron constant.  In the event of iron deficiency, the rate of<br>
absorption increases by a factor of 2-3, but this is not necessarily<br>
sufficient to prevent anemia.<br>
<p>
9.  The above requirements are combined with an estimated 10%<br>
availability of food iron to get the recommended daily allowances.<br>
So, for example, an adult female may excrete 1.5-2.4mg per day,<br>
meaning that she needs 15-24mg of iron in the diet.<br>
<p>
10. A more precise estimate of iron availability in food can be<br>
obtained by considering "heme" and "nonheme" iron.  All iron from<br>
vegetable sources is nonheme, while 40% of iron from animal sources is<br>
heme and 60% nonheme.<br>
<p>
11. Given the types of iron, availability can be calculated as<br>
follows:<br>
<p>
        type of meal            nonheme absorption      heme absorption<br>
        ------------            ------------------      ---------------<br>
<p>
        &lt;30g meat                       3                       23<br>
        &lt;25mg vitamin C<br>
<p>
        30-90g meat                     5                       23<br>
        or 25-75mg vitamin C<br>
<p>
<i>        &gt;90g meat                       8                       23</i><br>
        or &gt;75mg vitamin C<br>
        or 30-90g meat<br>
        plus 25-75mg vitamin C<br>
<p>
12. Various dietary and medicinal substances decrease iron absorption,<br>
such as calcium and phosphate salts, phytates, tannic acid in tea, and<br>
antacids.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
