SDAnetters,<br>
<p>
On Sun, 18 Apr 1993, TANG BENG YONG wrote: (edited for space)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 	Vitamin B12 (cyanocobalamin) is not produced by either plants or</i><br>
<i>&gt; animals. Its sole natural source, as far as is known, is bacteria...</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	In humans, it is produced in appreciable amounts in the large</i><br>
<i>&gt; intestine, by bacteria that live there, but this is below the region where</i><br>
<i>&gt; it can be actively absorbed (there are receptors for it in the small</i><br>
<i>&gt; intestine) and so very little of it is obtained here.</i><br>
<i>&gt; -beng</i><br>
<p>
Actually another good source of B12 is soy sauce.  Even though it may be<br>
fermented, and moderately high in sodium.  But considering, you can<br>
replace your MSG or normal table salt with it, it's not so bad a trade.<br>
