<title>Apr_1993: more things</title>
<h1>more things</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 19 Apr 93 17:03:06 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#311">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#311">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#311">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#311">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0312.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0310.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "dietary iron"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Sorry to strum this chord again, especially to those who would<br>
much rather I wouldn't. However some of you are interested in this<br>
material so I will post it. Those of you not interested should just skip<br>
this message and ignore it.<br>
<p>
Following are some verses which if accepted as truth strike directly against<br>
the Adventist position, because they are key texts. I am not suggesting <br>
that the SDA position relies solely on "island texts" for support but<br>
obscuring the clearly obvious texts doesn't help.  <br>
<p>
The question is, how would you answer someone who came with a different version <br>
regarding these key doctrines ? And after having explained these translations<br>
away, how would you then handle the assertion that the bible was contradictory,<br>
or unreliable in the light of the twisting and summersalting necessary to<br>
straighten out these distorted texts ?<br>
<p>
Even though I am only comparing the NIV to the KJV, I do it because the NIV<br>
is representative of just about if not all modern translations and in fact<br>
it is also fairly representative of the Catholic Reims version and the Jesuit <br>
bible of 1582. I could just about as well included the ASV or RSV or you name<br>
it instead of the NIV, just that the NIV is handiest, and of course I don't<br>
want to waste too much bandwidth listing all the translations :^)<br>
<p>
-----------------------------------------------------<br>
2 Pet 2:9 <br>
<p>
KJV	The Lord knoweth how to deliver the godly out of temptations, and to<br>
	reserve the unjust unto the day of judgment to be punished: <br>
<p>
NIV	if this is so, then the Lord knows how to rescue godly men from<br>
	trials and to hold the unrighteous for the day of judgment, while<br>
	continuing their punishment. <br>
<p>
in this case the NIV as well as many of the newer versions teach the doctrine <br>
of ongoing suffering in purgatory.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Exo 20:8-10<br>
<p>
KJV	Remember the sabbath day, to keep it holy.  <br>
	Six days shalt thou labour, and do all thy work:	<br>
	But the seventh day is the sabbath of the LORD thy God: in it thou<br>
	shalt not do any work, thou, nor thy son, nor thy daughter, thy<br>
	manservant, nor thy maidservant, nor thy cattle, nor thy stranger<br>
	that is within thy gates: 	<br>
<p>
ASV 	Remember the sabbath day, to keep it holy. 	<br>
	Six days shalt thou labor, and do all thy work; 	<br>
	but the seventh day is a sabbath unto Jehovah thy God: (in it) thou<br>
	shalt not do any work, thou, nor thy son, nor thy daughter, thy<br>
	man-servant, nor thy maid-servant, nor thy cattle, nor thy stranger<br>
	that is within thy gates: 	<br>
<p>
NIV	"Remember the Sabbath day by keeping it holy. 	<br>
	Six days you shall labor and do all your work,	<br>
	but the seventh day is a Sabbath to the LORD your God. On it you<br>
	shall not do any work, neither you, nor your son or daughter, nor<br>
	your manservant or maidservant, nor your animals, nor the alien<br>
	within your gates. 	<br>
<p>
Now what is it to be, just "a" Sabbath, anyday you wish, one of many, <br>
or is it to be THE Sabbath of God? We know what the evangelicals think.<br>
<p>
--------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Dan 8:14 <br>
<p>
KJV	And he said unto me, Unto two thousand and three hundred days; then<br>
	shall the sanctuary be cleansed. 	<br>
<p>
NIV	He said to me, "It will take 2,300 evenings and mornings; then the<br>
	sanctuary will be reconsecrated." 	<br>
<p>
This reading plainly obliterates the doctrine of the cleansing of <br>
the Sancutary. Well, was it cleansed in 1844 or not ? What does it mean<br>
to be reconsecrated? Definitively not even remotely the same as cleansed.<br>
 <br>
----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
As before I won't be entering any discussion as to the whys, wherefores<br>
and whatnots of bible translations and manuscripts.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
