<title>Apr_1993: Jack in the Box Lies</title>
<h1>Jack in the Box Lies</h1>
Ray Mialki (<i>rm1g+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 19 Apr 1993 19:37:49 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#318">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#318">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#318">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#318">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0319.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re: Can we all get along?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0317.html">McCluskey G: "iron"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
If you recall the disaster in Washington State regarding Jack in the Box<br>
Resturants and e coli contamination, I have some information that makes<br>
me think that we have been lied to regarding the REAL reason e coli was<br>
in those burgers.<br>
<p>
Some years past, I did a research paper for my college English class<br>
that was on modern meat.  It turns out that in recent studies, nearly<br>
two thirds of samples of ground beef exceeded federal standards for e<br>
coli contamination, and about one fourth of those exceeded the standards<br>
by 100 times.<br>
<p>
 From my waste water engineering class several years back, I learned that<br>
e coli is a so-called "indicator organism" that is measured to see if a<br>
treated waste water sample is free of pathogens.  <br>
<p>
E coli live naturally in the human intestines.  It is a natural<br>
component of municipal sewage.  The elimination of this organism in<br>
treated waste water shows that other harder to trace pathogens have been<br>
eliminated.<br>
<p>
As far as I can determine, untreated sewage should be the only way this<br>
organism could enter the food supply.  How this gets into ground beef, I<br>
don't even want to try to guess.  <br>
<p>
I really don't believe that the reason this organism entered the food<br>
supply was due to undercooking of the hamburger meat.  You mean to tell<br>
me over the decades and the billions of hamburgers sold in this country,<br>
it is only now that this contamination came forth?  In all those<br>
resturants, they all happened to undercook their burgers over the same<br>
short period of time?  <br>
<p>
The point in all of this is that our meat supply is definitely not safe.<br>
 You don't really need a religious reason to consider vegetarianism.<br>
<p>
Ray the kop<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
