<title>Apr_1993: Re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?</title>
<h1>Re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?</h1>
Noe Torres | ECISD (<i>noe@tenet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 20 Apr 1993 07:42:51 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#334">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#334">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#334">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#334">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0335.html">Steven Timm: "What is sin part 1"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0333.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0312.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0347.html">Juha Helminen: "Re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Sun, 18 Apr 1993, Kwong-hoon Andrew Park wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; "Therefore do not let anyone judge you by what you eat or drink, or with</i><br>
<i>&gt; regard to a religious festival, a New Moon celebration or a SABBATH DAY."</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	- Col 2:16</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; This text is has been used by many sunday keeping church pastors to </i><br>
<i>&gt; keep their people from becoming an adventist.  And when a person gets </i><br>
<i>&gt; sabbath message they always question with this one.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Any one have good answers for this one?</i><br>
<p>
There are two reasonable-sounding explanations that I've heard concerning<br>
this text:<br>
<p>
1) The Hebrews observed several "sabbath days" other than THE seventh-day<br>
Sabbath of the fourth commandment.  I don't have the Scriptural support<br>
here at hand for this, but I know it to be true that other feast/festival<br>
days were referred to as "sabbaths."    The seventh-day Sabbath would not<br>
be just "a sabbath day" -- it would be THE Sabbath, and Paul would assume<br>
that his audience would make the distinction in their minds.  The context<br>
seems to bear this out, as it speaks of "festivals" and "new moons," and<br>
does not refer to other of the ten commandments.<br>
<p>
2) Even if this were a reference to the seventh-day Sabbath, Paul is<br>
correct in stating that we should not "judge" anyone concerning their<br>
keeping of these festivals or ceremonies.  It has not been appointed to us<br>
to judge, and we all know the dangers of judging fellow believers.  All<br>
judgment ultimately belongs to God.  We can teach; we can encourage; we<br>
can support; but, I don't feel, we can judge or condemn.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
