<title>Apr_1993: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce</title>
<h1>Vitamin B12 in Soysauce</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 20 Apr 93 13:28:19 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#342">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#342">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#342">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#342">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0343.html">Steven Timm: "What is sin part 3"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0341.html">Maurice George Ashton: "SDA-   Plants and Music"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0350.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Michael Merginio writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Actually another good source of B12 is soy sauce.  Even though it may be</i><br>
<i>&gt;fermented, and moderately high in sodium.  But considering, you can</i><br>
<i>&gt;replace your MSG or normal table salt with it, it's not so bad a trade.</i><br>
<p>
I didn't know that. Thanks for the info. Well, Chinese (i am one) use a lot<br>
of soy sauce in their cooking, there are 2 varieties, a "light" brown watery<br>
type which has a different taste from just salt, and a darker less watery<br>
type which tastes more like plain salt. They have different uses. There is<br>
also a thick sweet type of soysauce.<br>
<p>
Although it is fermented, i do not think it has any alcohol in it, at least<br>
i can't smell any. It doesn't smell fermented at all, come to that.<br>
<p>
The indians (not red indians) have a kind of soybean food called Tempei,<br>
which is fermented soybeans, fried in batter, and i hear that it is also<br>
high in B12.<br>
<p>
I wonder why fermented soybean products have B12. Perhaps they get<br>
contaminated by symbiotic bacteria from the soybean roots (pseudomonas?)<br>
which grow when fermentation takes place, and make the vitamin.<br>
<p>
Besides B12, soybean products (bean curds etc) is a very good source of<br>
protein, and essential amino acids, of which it lacks only one, which is<br>
obtainable from grain protein.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
